<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>First Stop: Merging of an Existing Depository Institution into a Savings Bank</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#004080" LINK="#004080" VLINK="#0080C0" ALINK="#0080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/fs/fslogosm.gif" alt="First Stop Logo" width=171 height=120 align=left>
<h3 align=center>Department of Commerce & Community Affairs
<hr>
First Stop Business Information Center<br>
Business Requirement
</h3>
<hr>
<br clear=all>

<H3>I.	Business Requirement:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Merging of an Existing Depository Institution into a Savings Bank
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>II.	Agency:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Office of the Commissioner of Savings & Residential Finance<BR>
Thrift Corporate Affairs Division<BR>
205 West Randolph, Suite 1900<BR>
Chicago, Illinois 60606-1811<BR>
(312) 793-1450<BR>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>III.	Statute:</H3>
<DL><DD>
205 Illinois Compiled Statutes 205\8004 (Savings Bank Act)  
</DD></DL>
<H3>Regulation:</H3>
<DL><DD>
38 Illinois Administrative Code 1075
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>IV.	Requirement Description:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Any depository institution (a commercial or savings bank, a savings / loan association, trust company, homestead, building and loan association, cooperative bank, industrial bank or a credit union) may merge into a savings bank. Merging is perpetually valid. Violations of this Act would initiate supervisory action to re-establish compliance. Failure to comply could result in revocation of the charter, criminal or civil penalties.<P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>V.	Approval Process:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Applicants must submit to the Commissioner of Savings & Residential Finance (the Commissioner) the plan for merging after they have been approved by the Boards of Directors of all depository institutions. The plan should include the names of each merging institution; the name of the continuing savings bank; location of the business and branch offices; provisions stating the method, terms and conditions of the merge. In regard to the resulting savings bank, information must be submitted on the amount of capital, surplus and reserve for operating expenses, the classes and number of shares of stock and their par value, the charter and bylaws and a detailed financial statement showing the assets and liabilities after the proposed merger. Applicants must submit certified copies of the Boards of Directors' approval. The Commissioner then examines the affairs of each merging institution applicant, their affiliates and subsidiaries. Applications are usually processed within 4-6 weeks. Applications may be denied if the applicants do not meet necessary requirements, if the same conditions do not exist with respect to the new resulting savings bank that would be required for the organization of a new savings bank, or if the merger agreement is unfair. If an application is denied, the applicant may amend and resubmit the plan.  <P>   
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VI.	Pre-Requisites, Co-Requisites, Post-Requisites:</H3>
<DL><DD>
<EM>Pre-Requisite:</EM> The Board of Directors for each merging depository institution must adopt the plan of merger.<P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VII.	Fees:</H3>
<DL><DD>
The application processing fee is $1000.
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<STRONG>| <a href="/dcca/home.htm">DCCA Home Page</a> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/fsm1.htm">First Stop</a> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/fsbr.htm">Business Requirements</a> |</STRONG>

