<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>First Stop: Permit to Organize a Savings Bank</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#004080" LINK="#004080" VLINK="#0080C0" ALINK="#0080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/fs/fslogosm.gif" alt="First Stop Logo" width=171 height=120 align=left>
<h3 align=center>Department of Commerce & Community Affairs
<hr>
First Stop Business Information Center<br>
Business Requirement
</h3>
<hr>
<br clear=all>


<H3>I.	Business Requirement Profile:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Permit to Organize a Savings Bank
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>II.	Agency:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Office of the Commissioner of Savings & Residential Finance<BR>
Thrift Corporate Affairs Divisions<BR>
205 West Randolph, Suite 1900<BR>
Chicago, Illinois 60606-1811<BR>
(312) 793-1450<BR>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>III.  	Statute:</H3>
<DL><DD>
205 Illinois Compiled Statutes 205\3001 - 3007 (Savings Bank Act )
</DD></DL>
<H3>Regulation:</H3>
<DL><DD>
38 Illinois Administrative Code 1075
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>IV.	Requirement Description:</H3>
<DL><DD>
No fewer than 5 nor more than 20 persons may organize  a savings bank. The Commissioner of Savings and Residential Finance (The Commissioner) determines the minimum required capital which is at least the minimum required to obtain insurance of accounts and must include additional amounts as the Commissioner may find necessary. <P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>V.	Approval Process:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Applicants must submit to the Commissioner an application which includes information on the applicants, an audited financial statement, the proposed articles of incorporation and bylaws, and all information on stocks. Upon receipt, the Commissioner performs an investigation which can include subpoenaing books and records, taking public testimony and conducting hearings. All information gathered is then evaluated to see that requirements are met, application information is correct, the business plan and capitalization will serve the needs of the community and that the accounts are insured. Applications may be denied if there are deficiencies. Denied applications may be corrected and resubmitted. Applications are usually processed within 4-6 weeks. If the information submitted is satisfactory, applicants may temporarily organize the savings bank. Applicants will elect officers and directors, secure subscriptions for capital in the form of pledges to purchase stock, prepare articles of incorporation and bylaws, apply for insurance of accounts and submit the names / addresses of investors who have purchased stock. When all information is completed and submitted, the Commissioner issues a certificate of "Complete Organization". Certification is replaced by issuance of a charter when the newly created savings bank secures federally sponsored insurance of its accounts.  <P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VI.	Pre-Requisites, Co-Requisites & Post-Requisites:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Accounts must be insured prior to issuance of a charter.<P>

<EM>Post-Requisites:</EM>  Charter recipients must comply with supervisory letters if requested and file and annual audit and quarterly report.   <P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VII.	Fees:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Application processing fee is $1000.<P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<STRONG>| <a href="/dcca/home.htm">DCCA Home Page</a> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/fsm1.htm">First Stop</a> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/fsbr.htm">Business Requirements</a> |</STRONG>

</BODY>
