<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>First Stop: Savings and Loan Association Merging</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#004080" LINK="#004080" VLINK="#0080C0" ALINK="#0080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/fs/fslogosm.gif" alt="First Stop Logo" width=171 height=120 align=left>
<h3 align=center>Department of Commerce & Community Affairs
<hr>
First Stop Business Information Center<br>
Business Requirement
</h3>
<hr>
<br clear=all>

<H3>I.	Business Requirement:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Savings and Loan Association Merging
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>II.	Agency:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Office of the Commissioner of Savings & Residential Finance<BR>
Thrift Corporate Affairs Divisions<BR>
205 West Randolph, Suite 1900<BR>
Chicago, Illinois 60606-1811<BR>
(312) 793-1450<BR>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>III.	Statute:</H3>
<DL><DD>
205 Illinois Compiled Statutes 105\6-4 to 6-9 Illinois Savings and Loan Act 
</DD></DL>
<H3>Regulation:</H3>
<DL><DD>
38 Illinois Administrative Code 400.110
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>IV.	Requirement Description:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Two or more associations (depository institutions), any association (not meeting its net worth requirements) and a federal association, or any association and an eligible insured bank may merge to become one savings and loan association. Permits are usually perpetually valid. The Commissioner determines the minimum initial capital an association must have, this may not be less than what would be required to obtain insurance of accounts by the Federal Savings & Loan Insurance Corporation.<P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>V.	Approval Process:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Upon approval by the Boards of each merging association, the plans for merging, a certified copy of the authorizing resolution and an "Application for Permit to Merge" must be submitted to the Commissioner of Savings & Residential Finance (the Commissioner). An examination of the affairs of each merging association/eligible insured bank may be required by the Commissioner. Applications are usually processed in 4-6 weeks. If the plans are denied, applicants may amend the plan and resubmit it. If denied, the Commissioner may require that the plan be submitted to the members of the merging associations for approval. If a plan is approved, the Commissioner issues a Certificate of Merger. The merger is effective when the Certificate is recorded in each county where the merging associations/eligible insured banks were located and in the county of the continuing association.<P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VI.	Pre-Requisites, Co-Requisites, Post-Requisites:</H3>
<DL><DD>
<EM>Pre-Requisite:</EM> The Board of Directors from each merging association must approve a resolution to merge. This resolution must include information on the names of each merging association/eligible insured bank, the name of the continuing association and the location of its business office; amount of capital, reserves and undivided profits and kinds of shares and other types of capital to be issued; articles of incorporation for the continuing association; detailed "pro forma" financial statement of assets and liabilities of continuing association; manner and basis of converting capital of each merging association/eligible insured bank into capital of the continuing association, and; terms and conditions of merger and the methods for doing so.<P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VII.	Fees:</H3>
<DL><DD>
The application processing fee is $1000.<P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<STRONG>| <a href="/dcca/home.htm">DCCA Home Page</a> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/fsm1.htm">First Stop</a> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/fsbr.htm">Business Requirements</a> |</STRONG>

</BODY>
</HTML>
