<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>First Stop: Commercial Drivers License (CDL)</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#004080" LINK="#004080" VLINK="#0080C0" ALINK="#0080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/fs/fslogosm.gif" alt="First Stop Logo" width=171 height=120 align=left>
<h3 align=center>Department of Commerce & Community Affairs
<hr>
First Stop Business Information Center<br>
Business Requirement
</h3>
<hr>
<br clear=all>

<H3>I.	Business Requirement Profile:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Commercial Drivers License (CDL)
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>II.	Agency:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Illinois Secretary of State<BR>
Driver Services Department<BR>
2701 South Dirksen Parkway<BR>
Springfield, IL 62723<BR>
(217) 782-7044<BR>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>III.	Statute:</H3>
<DL><DD>
625 Illinois Compiled Statutes  Act 5/Section 6-101 through 6-102(7).
</DD></DL>
<H3>Regulation:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Title 92, Illinois Administrative Code, Part 448.
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>IV.	Requirement Description:</H3>
<DL><DD>
A Commercial Driver's License is required to operate any of the following vehicles:  <P>
<DL><DD>
	(1) Any combination of vehicles with a GCWR* of 26,001 lbs. or more, providing the GVWR** of the vehicle being towed is in excess of 10,000 lbs.  <P>

	(2) Any single vehicle with a (GVWR) of 26,001 lbs. or more, or any such vehicle towing another not in excess of 10,000 lbs.  <P>

	(3) Any vehicle, regardless of size, designed to transport 16 or more persons, including the driver.<P>

	(4) Any vehicle required by federal regulations to be placarded while transporting hazardous materials.<P>
</DD></DL>
The purpose of commercial drivers license requirements is insure that commercial drivers are qualified to operate their vehicles safely.  Under this program, there are nationally uniform testing procedures, and strict reporting, alcohol, and disqualification provisions.  <P>

Commercial drivers licenses are valid for 4 years.<P>

* (GCWR)  means the value specified by the manufacturer as the (GVWR) of the power unit plus the (GVWR) of the towed unit or units, or the combined registered weight of the power unit plus the towed unit(s), whichever is greater.<P>

**GVWR means the value specified by the manufacturer as the maximum loaded weight of a single vehicle or combination of vehicles, or the registered gross weight, whichever is greater.<P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>V.	Approval Process:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Applicants must complete an application, available at the SOS Drivers License Facilities, and provide prove of identity, age, Illinois residency, a signature and social security number.  Applicants must take a vision test and pass a written test (and may be required to pass a road skills test).  The written and road skill CDL tests are available at all driver services facilities except those located in Cook, DuPage, Kane, Lake, McHenry and Will counties.  These counties are served by four special CDL facilities.  <P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VI.	Pre-Requisites, Co-Requisites & Post-Requisites:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Applicants must be at least 21 to drive a commercial motor vehicle across state lines, carry hazardous materials or transport passengers.  Applicants must certify that they do not have more than one drivers license, and that their driving privileges are not suspended, revoked, canceled or disqualified.<P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VII.	Fees:</H3>
<DL><DD>
<STRONG><EM>License fee:</EM></STRONG>  $40.  (This includes $10 for the basic drivers license, $24 for the CDL, 	and $6 to cover the cost of the new national commercial drivers license information system.)  A $5 fee will be charged to CDL holders who wish to change classifications or endorsements.
</DD></DL>


<HR>
