<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>First Stop: Illinois Driver's License</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#004080" LINK="#004080" VLINK="#0080C0" ALINK="#0080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/fs/fslogosm.gif" alt="First Stop Logo" width=171 height=120 align=left>
<h3 align=center>Department of Commerce & Community Affairs
<hr>
First Stop Business Information Center<br>
Business Requirement
</h3>
<hr>
<br clear=all>

<H3>I.	Business Requirement Profile:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Illinois Driver's License
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>II.	Agency:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Illinois Secretary of State<BR>
Driver Services Department<BR>
2701 South Dirksen Parkway<BR>
Springfield, Illinois 62723<BR>
(217) 782-7044<BR>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>III.	Statute:</H3>
<DL><DD>
625 Illinois Compiled Statutes 5/6-101, 102
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>IV.	Eligibility Criteria:</H3>
<DL><DD>
A license or permit is required to drive a motor vehicle on a highway in Illinois. Some exemptions apply. A non-resident who becomes a resident of this State may, for a period of the first 90 days of residence in Illinois, operate a motor vehicle for which he/she was qualified or licensed to drive by his home state or country, so long as he/she has in his/her possession a valid and current license issued by that home state or country.  After the 90 day period, the new resident must comply with the provisions of this Act and apply for an Illinois license or permit.<P>

Licenses issued to drivers under 21 expire three months after their 21st birthday.<P>

Licenses issued to drivers between 21 and 80 are valid for four years, and expire on the driver's birthday.<P>

Licenses issued to drivers between 81 and 86 are valid for two years.<P>

Licenses issued to drivers 87 and older must be renewed each year.<P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>V.	Approval Process:</H3>
<DL><DD>
To receive an Illinois driver's license, applicants must provide a minimum of 3 acceptable forms of identification to prove name, date of birth, Illinois residency, social security number and signature for comparison. One of these forms should be a certified birth certificate.<P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VI.	Pre-Requisites, Co-Requisites, Post-Requisites:</H3>
<DL><DD>
When applying for an Illinois driver's license, the applicant will be asked questions regarding their general health and will take vision, written and driving tests. An individual is allowed 3 attempts to pass each of these tests within 1 year from the date the individual paid his/her application fee.<P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VII.	Fees: </H3>
<DL><DD>
	<STRONG><EM>Original Instruction Permit:</EM></STRONG>	$20<BR>
	<STRONG><EM>Basic Driver's License:	</EM></STRONG>$10<BR>
	<STRONG><EM>Commercial Driver's License:	</EM></STRONG>$40<BR>
	<STRONG><EM>Driver's license for persons age 18-20</EM></STRONG>	$  5<BR>
	<STRONG><EM>Driver's license for persons age 69-80</EM></STRONG>	$  5<BR>
	<STRONG><EM>Driver's license for persons age 81-86</EM></STRONG>	$  2<BR>
	<STRONG><EM>Driver's license for persons age 87 and older</EM></STRONG>	Free<BR>
	<STRONG><EM>Duplicate license/permit for persons age 60 and 	above whose license has been stolen:</EM></STRONG>	Free<BR>
	<STRONG><EM>New classification added, not at time of renewal (except CDL):</EM></STRONG>	$ 5<BR>
</DD></DL>


<HR>
