<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<font size=+3>1996 News Releases</font>
<br clear=right>
<hr>
<h3 align=center>
November 6, 1996<p>
Governor Announces Auto Part Company will Locate New Plant in Lawrenceville; State Helps to Create About 125 Jobs
</h3>

<strong>LAWRENCEVILLE, ILL</strong> -- Gov. Jim Edgar today announced Trim Masers, Inc., an automobile parts manufacturing company, will locate a new plant in Lawrenceville with assistance for the state. <p> 

"I am delighted that Trim masters has joined many, many other companies that have decided to invest in Illinois and create jobs here because of our excellent business climate and quality workforce, " the Governor said.<p>

"More than 360,000 new jobs have been created in our state in just the last four years, reflecting our retooled and re-energized efforts to make Illinois a place where businesses want to expand and locate," Edgar said.<p>

Kentucky-based Trim master will employ about 125 and invests as much as $12 million in the 100,000 square-foot facility at Lawrenceville.  At least two other states were competing for the plant.  Construction will begin next May and is expected to be complete in December 1997.  Trim Masters manufactures seat trim covers, door trim and complete seats for automobiles.<p>

The state, through the Department of Commerce and Community Affairs, will provide $187,000 in job-training funds and $500,000 in infrastructure assistance to help fund water and wastewater projects.  The City of Lawrenceville will donate the plant site.<p>

Lt. Gov. Bob Kustra, the Governor's senior adviser for economic development, said the state worked with Lawrenceville area officials to make the project a reality.<p>

"This project was a team effort," said Kustra.  "Assistance at the state and local level was needed to bring Trim masters to Lawrenceville, and we are pleased to see much-needed jobs come to this community."<p>

Lawrenceville Mayor Jerry Harper said residents are excited about the jobs that will be created.<p>

"This announcement gives Lawrenceville an economic shot in the arm," Harper said.  "We wouldn't have been able to land this project without the assistance of the State of Illinois.  The help provided by the Illinois Department of Commerce and Community Affairs clinched the deal to bring Trim Masters here, and we are very appreciative."<p>

Philip Ashcraft, Senior Vice President and General Manager of Trim Master, said the company is looking forward to working with the community.<p>

"The enthusiasm of the people in Lawrenceville area was one of the reasons we chose to locate here," said Ashcraft.  "that local support, combined with an excellent labor pool and the incentives offered by the State of Illinois, helped to make locating in Lawrenceville an easy decision for Trim Masters."<p>

<center><strong>###</strong></center>
	 
