<h3 align=center>
October 11, 1996<p>
Governor Announces Grant to Boost Economic Development in Red Bud
</h3>

<strong>RED BUD, Ill.</strong> -- Gov. Jim Edgar today announced a $500,000 grant that will aid a business development in Red Bud, creating at least 15 new jobs and retaining more than 50.<p>  

"Red Bud is poised for economic growth," the Governor said.  "This Community Development Assistance Program grant is expected to help the city retain one of its most important employers and create exciting opportunities for new businesses to locate in Red Bud." <p>

The $500,000 grant through the Department of Commerce and Community Affairs (DCCA) will go to the City of Red Bud.  The city will loan the money to TPC Properties, L.L.C., to purchase the building that houses Total Process Corp., a manufacturer of structural steel, piping and electrical components.  Two Red Bud banks will lend TPC Properties $1.3 million to complete the purchase.  The city of Red Bud will loan TPC an additional $200,000 at no interest to renovate the building.<p>

After acquisition and improvements are completed, Total Process Corp. will sign a long-term lease with TPC Properties and other tenants will be actively recruited for remaining space in the building, now owned by Inter-City Products.<p>

"There is tremendous economic development potential in small communities throughout Illinois," Edgar said.  "My administration is committed to helping small towns and cities realize that potential."<p>

Red Bud Mayor Clement L. Esker said the project will renew optimism in the community's future.<p>

"Red Bud is turning around," Esker said.  "We appreciate the efforts of the Edgar administration to help put our community on the comeback trail.  Red Bud is ready to move on to a brighter future with new growth and job opportunities for our citizens."<p>

Lt. Gov. Bob Kustra, the Governor's senior adviser for economic development, called the project an excellent example of public-private cooperation.<p>

"The Edgar administration is a partner in economic development with local governments and the private sector," Kustra said.  "All of us must work together to accomplish our common goal of improving the quality of life for citizens across Illinois."<p>


<center><strong>###</strong></center>
	 
