<h3>
Department of Commerce & Community Affairs<p>
</h3>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<font size=+3>1996 News Releases</font>
<br clear=right>
<hr>
<h3 align=center>
September 11, 1996<p>
Governor To Lead Trade Mission to Japan, South Korea, China and Hong Kong
</h3>

<strong>SPRINGFIELD, Ill.</strong> -- Gov. Jim Edgar today announced he will lead a trade mission to Japan, South Korea, China and Hong Kong in an effort to solidify relations and expand markets for Illinois firms.<p>

The Governor, First Lady Brenda Edgar and representatives from more than two dozen Illinois businesses, trade organizations and labor groups will meet with business and government leaders in the four countries.<p>

Becky Doyle, Director of the Illinois Department of Agriculture, and Norman Sims, Executive Deputy Director of the Department of Commerce and Community Affairs, also will be among those accompanying the Governor.<p>

"This mission represents an excellent opportunity for Illinois firms -- large and small -- to explore new market opportunities," the Governor said.  "The countries we'll be visiting are particularly interested in Illinois products and technological assistance in a variety of industrial areas, including our state's number one industry, agriculture."<p>

In each country, the delegation will meet with industrial leaders whose firms have facilities or subsidiaries in Illinois, or who seek to expand trade with Illinois firms.<p>

The delegation leaves for Japan on September 15.  The Japan visit includes a tour and address on the campus of Southern Illinois University - Nakajo campus.  SIU President Ted Sanders will host the Governor's visit there.<p>

Edgar and the Governor of Niigata, Japan, are expected to reaffirm the Niigata-Illinois Educational and Economic Development Council agreement that was signed during the 1980s.  <p>

The slate of industrial meetings in Japan includes talks with leaders of Koito, parent company to Illinois-based North American Lighting, and of Mitsubishi Motors, which oversees several Illinois-based facilities.<p>

In South Korea, the Governor will meet with Prime Minister Soo Sung Lee, and with U.S. Ambassador James Laney.<p>

In South Korea, the mission also will meet with the chairman of Samsung, which recently announced a distribution center in Bolingbrook, and with the chairman of Lucky Goldstar, which owns controlling shares in Zenith Corporation, a Chicago-based firm.<p>

The trip to China includes meetings with the Ministry of Agriculture, the Ministry of Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation, and a Chinese vice premier.<p>

In China, the delegation's schedule includes visits with officials from Motorola, Deere & Co., and Ameritech.<p>

In Hong Kong, Edgar will meet with Gov. Chris Patten, and British Trade Commissioner Francis Cornish.<p>

The delegation also has meetings scheduled with the Hong Kong Trade Development Council, and China Aerospace International Holdings.  Edgar also will witness the signing of an agreement between DCCA and the Hong Kong Metal Merchants Association.<p>

The delegation is scheduled to return to Illinois September 28.<p>

"We expect this trip, like our previous trade missions to Mexico, Europe and the Middle East, to broaden our export horizons, a long standing priority of our administration," Edgar said.<p>  

"We were pleased to be invited by leaders of each of the countries we'll be visiting.  As we improve our business relations abroad, Illinois' export industry should grow.  That means a stronger Illinois economy, and more good-paying jobs for Illinoisans right here at home."<p>

	 
