<HEAD><TITLE>DCCA: News Release -- August 22, 1996</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#8080C0" ALINK="#8080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/logosm.jpg" alt="DCCA Logo" width=165 height=82 align=left>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<h3>
Department of Commerce & Community Affairs<p>
</h3>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<font size=+3>1996 News Releases</font>
<br clear=right>
<hr>
<h3 align=center>
September 5, 1996<p>
Edgar Administration Announces Grants to Aid Small Manufacturers in Illinois
</h3>

<strong>SPRINGFIELD, Ill.</strong> -- The Edgar administration announced today that a $2.67 million grant from the National Institute for Standards and Technology, coupled with $1.2 million in state grants, will enable the Illinois Manufacturing Extension Center to expand and improve its technical assistance for small- and mid-sized manufacturers throughout Illinois.<p>
 
IMEC provides a range of technical services to firms, including manufacturing assessment, engineering assistance, modernization demonstrations, support in product and network development, and referrals for services provided by other private firms.<p>

The grants mean greater access and more comprehensive support for all of the nearly 9,700 small and medium-sized manufacturers in Illinois outside the Chicago metropolitan area that are not currently served by the federal government.  The federal grants supplement existing state programs that serve all 24,000 industrial firms in Illinois.<p>

"The manufacturing sector in Illinois is of critical importance to the future of the state's economy," said Dennis Whetstone, director of the Illinois Department of Commerce and Community Affairs, which will provide $600,000 of the state's commitment.  "At the same time, small and medium-sized manufacturers employ large numbers of Illinois workers.  By providing greater support for this crucial segment of our manufacturing base, we will both improve the state's economy and increase the number of good jobs available to Illinois workers."<p>

"The state of Illinois with support form NIST, has invested for more than three years in developing the state's manufacturing service system," said Bob Weinstein, interim executive director for IMEC.  "These investments and the grants announced today will let IMEC be established as an independent, not-for-profit corporation to provide substantive assistance to Illinois manufacturers."<p>

The $2.67 million NIST grant, through the U.S. Department of Commerce, can be awarded annually for up to six years.<p>

The balance of the $1.2 million commitment from the Edgar administration comes through the Illinois Board of Higher Education.  The center also gets about $200,000 in cash grants and fees from private firms, along with about $1.3 million through in-kind contributions from private firms.<p>

The total $2.7 million in state and local support represents the matching funds needed to qualify the center for the $2.67 million federal grant announced today.<p>

The president of the Illinois State Chamber of Commerce, Sally Jackson, applauded the public-private partnership that resulted in the center's expansion.  "I commend Governor Edgar for his strong leadership in forging innovative public-private alliances that will assure continued economic expansion in Illinois," Jackson said.<p>

Bradley University President John Brazil commended the cooperative effort among Illinois businesses, institutions of higher education and the state and federal governments that led to the establishment of IMEC.  "Bradley is proud to have been able to play a facilitating role in the creation of the IMEC," Brazil said.  "We are committed to the success of IMEC and pledge our full cooperation and continuing support for the fulfillment of its mission."<p>

IMEC will be based in Peoria, with sub-centers on the campuses of Bradley University in Peoria, Rock Valley College in Rockford, and Southern Illinois University at Carbondale.  Field extension offices are located in the Quad Cities, Joliet, LaSalle-Peru, Bloomington-Normal, Springfield, and Edwardsville.<p>

The federal grant announced today doubles the center's annual budget.  It will help the center expand its offerings in existing offices and add four new field extension offices.  Areas under consideration for the new offices include Champaign-Urbana, Decatur, Effingham and Quincy.<p>

The expansion means that more than 80 percent of the state's small- and medium-sized manufacturers outside the Chicago area will be within 40 miles of an IMEC office.<p>

"In the first year, we expect to reach at least 1,000 manufacturers in providing some level of service," Weinstein said.  "We expect to link with all the state's small- and medium-sized manufacturers at some point.<p>

"Being part of the national network with NIST allows us to meet the specific needs of our area's smaller manufacturers while leveraging national resources that previously had not been available to us.  In addition to these national resources, the establishment of IMEC brings together a partnership of Illinois higher education institutions, research laboratories, business assistance centers, employer and trade associations and private sector companies who are committed to the continued growth and vitality of Illinois manufacturing," Weinstein said.<p>

<center><strong>###</strong></center>
	 
