<h3 align=center>
August 8, 1996<p>
GRANTS AVAILABLE TO ENCOURAGE YOUTH VOLUNTEERISM IN ILLINOIS
</h3>




<STRONG>SPRINGFIELD, Ill.</STRONG> -- Not-for-profit organizations may receive financial assistance to help them create opportunities for young people to assist with community service work, under a grant program being administered by the Illinois Department of Commerce and Community Affairs (DCCA).<P>

The Learn and Serve Program grants, awarded to DCCA through the Corporation for National Service, encourage youths to volunteer their services, while helping to improve a community's public safety and increasing young peoples' knowledge of health and wellness issues.<P>

DCCA has received $64,792 to fund the grants, which will pay for activities conducted during the fall and winter months.       "Volunteers are the foundations of our communities," said Dennis R. Whetstone, DCCA Director.  "Service learning programs like this one link academic learning with volunteer community service.  In doing so, we help to instill in our young people an understanding and appreciation of their communities and help them increase their self-esteem and develop the skills they need to become future leaders."<P>

Not-for-profit (IRS 501(c)(3)) organizations are eligible to apply for the grants.  Eligible applicants must partner with a school (K-12) and a for-profit business to ensure community-wide support.  Selected programs are expected to meet a community need by raising safety awareness, decreasing the opportunity for criminal activity, or increasing the knowledge and participation in health and wellness activities in the community.  <P>

The average grant award will range from $2,000 to $7,000.  Eligible applicants must provide a cash or in-kind match of 10 percent.<P>

Applications are due August 30, 1996.  Programs will operate between October 1, 1996 and March 15, 1997.<P>

To apply, or for further information, contact the Illinois Commission on Community Service at DCCA, James R. Thompson Center, 100 W. Randolph St., Suite 3-400, Chicago, IL 60601, phone 800/592-9896 (TDD users call 800/419-0667).<P>





