<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<font size=+3>1996 News Releases</font>
<br clear=right>
<hr>
<h3 align=center>
August 7, 1996<p>
GOVERNOR ANNOUNCES CREATION OF SMALL BUSINESS ADVISORY COUNCIL
</h3>

<STRONG>CHICAGO, ILL.</STRONG> --  Gov. Jim Edgar today announced the creation of the Illinois Small Business 100, a council of small business owners who reflect the unique diversity of the 617,000 small businesses in Illinois.<P>

"Small businesses are the backbone of the state's economy," the Governor said.  "They play vital roles as job creators, employing millions of Illinois citizens, and they provide tremendous opportunities for those who have the determination to work hard and succeed.  And we are seeing some of the most dramatic growth in small businesses owned by women and minorities.	<P>

"Through this council, my administration is forging an even stronger relationship with small business--one that is designed to foster a better understanding of the ongoing issues and challenges facing this important segment of our economy.  We will work together to promote business growth and expansion in a low-tax, common-sense climate that does not choke economic growth."   <P>

Lt. Gov. Bob Kustra, the Governor's senior advisor for economic development, said the small business council will have the ability to communicate the most pressing concerns of small business directly to state government.<P>

"The Illinois Department of Commerce and Community Affairs (DCCA) will develop a site on the World Wide Web for the council that will include links to the members' E-mail, business pages, chambers of commerce and trade organizations," Kustra said.  "Members will be regularly polled on regulatory and small business issues, creating a sounding board for sound economic development policies."<P>

In conjunction with announcing the creation of the council,  the Governor also today presented the first Governor's Illinois Business Leadership award to Campagna Turano Bakeries, Inc. of Berwyn.  <P>

In the nearly half century since it was founded, Turano has grown from a small family business into a nationally known company, servicing accounts ranging from fast food outlets to fine dining establishments and from small neighborhood grocery stores to the largest supermarket chains.<P>




