<h3>
Department of Commerce & Community Affairs<p>
</h3>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<font size=+3>1996 News Releases</font>
<br clear=right>
<hr>
<h3 align=center>
July 17, 1996<p>
                    
</h3>

<H3 align=center>GRANTS HELP LOCAL GOVERNMENTS
REMOVE ARCHITECTURAL BARRIERS</H3>

<STRONG>SPRINGFIELD, Ill. </STRONG>-- Gov. Jim Edgar today announced grants totaling $1 million to help 15 Illinois communities renovate public buildings to accommodate the needs of people with disabilities.<P>

"Many small communities face financial hardships in renovating public buildings to comply with the requirements of the Americans with Disabilities Act," the Governor said.  "These grants provide local governments with the funds they need to proceed with the necessary renovations.  We want to ensure that regardless of their disabilities, all citizens may access public services."<P>

The grants are made available through the Removal of Architectural Barriers component of the Community Development Assistance Program (CDAP).  <P>

Projects to renovate the Tuscola Public Library and the Joy Village Hall are examples.  <P>

Tuscola's library was built in 1903 with funds from the Carnegie Foundation.  The historic building is a two-story structure accessible only by stairs, with floors connected by narrow, steep stairways.  The City of Tuscola will receive a $145,000 CDAP grant to assist with the costs of installing an elevator, accessible restrooms, and constructing an accessible parking area.  <P>

Joy's village hall is the location for village board meetings and is the office of the village clerk and president, police department, and maintenance superintendent.  Citizens also pay village utility bills in the building.  The village will receive a $15,000 CDAP grant to install an entrance ramp and handrails, renovate the restroom to make it accessible, and install accessible parking.<P>

"CDAP grants are one of Illinois' most important tools to help small communities meet the needs of their citizens," said Lt. Gov. Bob Kustra, the Governor's senior adviser for economic development.  "This component was developed to ensure that even in small communities, public buildings comply with the provisions under the Americans with Disabilities Act."<P>

The Community Development Assistance Program (CDAP) is administered by the Department of Commerce and Community Affairs (DCCA).  Applications for ADA grant funding were awarded following a competitive review that looked at a community's justification of project need, financial need, and eligibility of the activities outlined in the project implementation plans. <P>

Funded with federal block grant funds from the U.S. Department of Housing and Urban Development (HUD), CDAP grants are awarded by DCCA to units of local government with populations of 50,000 or less that are not located within one of the seven large urban counties that receive funds directly from HUD.  The maximum grant available under this component is $150,000.  <P>	

A list of communities receiving CDAP Removal of Architectural Barriers grants is attached.<P>
                             

