<HEAD><TITLE>DCCA: News Release -- June 26, 1996</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#8080C0" ALINK="#8080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/logosm.jpg" alt="DCCA Logo" width=165 height=82 align=left>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<h3>
Department of Commerce & Community Affairs<p>
</h3>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<font size=+3>1996 News Releases</font>
<br clear=right>
<hr>
<h3 align=center>
June 28, 1996<p>
Governor Announces Grant to Help Displaced Coal Miners
</h3>

<strong>SPRINGFIELD, Ill.</strong> -- Gov. Jim Edgar today announced the U.S. Department of Labor has approved his request for $5.7 million in federal job training assistance to help more than 400 workers dislocated by the closings of five Southern Illinois coal mines.<p>

"Although we agree that a clean environment is important, the federal Clean Air Act Amendments of 1990 have had a devastating effect on the Illinois coal industry," Edgar said.  "We are working diligently to find new markets and explore clean coal technologies that will enable us to regain our market share.  In the meantime, we must ensure that miners who have lost their jobs can receive the training and other services they need to continue to be productive workers."<p>

The $5,755,360 grant was approved by U.S. Secretary of Labor Robert Reich and was allocated from Clean Air-related national reserve funds under Title III of the Job Training Partnership Act (JTPA).  <p>

The grant is expected to provide services to approximately 416 miners dislocated from the Zeigler Coal Company's Old Ben Mine #24 near Benton and #26 near Sesser, Arch of Illinois' Captain Mine in Percy, Freeman United Coal Company's Orient Mine #6 in Waltonville, and Consolidated Coal Company's Rend Lake Mine near Sesser.<p>  

Job skill assessment, career counseling, job search assistance, relocation assistance, vocational/occupational skills training, on-the-job training, and supportive services such as child care and transportation assistance will be available to dislocated workers.  Because the dislocation was related to the Clean Air Act Amendments of 1990, eligible workers also will receive needs-related payments.  <p>

These payments enable dislocated workers enrolled in training or education programs who have exhausted their unemployment insurance (UI) benefits to continue receiving an amount approximately equal to the UI benefit or the poverty level, whichever is higher.<p>

Training will be administered through the Management, Training and Consulting Corporation (MAN-TRA-CON) Service Delivery Area #25 in Zeigler.<p>


