<h3>
Department of Commerce & Community Affairs<p>
</h3>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<font size=+3>1996 News Releases</font>
<br clear=right>
<hr>
<h3 align=center>
June 25, 1996<p>
Governor Approves Sales Tax Break for Oil Drilling, Exploration Equipment
</h3>

<strong>MT. VERNON, Ill.</strong> -- Gov. Jim Edgar today signed legislation eliminating the sales tax on equipment costing less than $250 used for oil field exploration, drilling and production. <p> 
 
"This legislation will save companies involved in Illinois oil-drilling about $1 million a year, giving them new funds to maintain and expand their investments in Illinois," the Governor said.  "It gives this industry the same tax benefits other industries in Illinois already enjoy."<p>

The legislation, similar to a bill the Governor signed on Monday for the coal industry, eliminates the sales tax on equipment in the oil exploration industry costing less than $250, the same tax advantage given to manufacturers and farmers during the 1980s.  Equipment costing more than $250 already was exempt from the sales tax.<p>

Chief sponsors of the measure, House Bill 2703, were Reps. John Jones (R-Mt. Vernon), Terry Deering (D-DuBois), Mike Bost (R-Murphysboro), Ron Stephens (R-Troy), Gwenn Klingler (R-Springfield) and Thomas Holbrook (D-Belleville) and Sens. Harry "Babe" Woodyard (R-Chrisman) and William O'Daniel (D-Mt. Vernon).<p>

It is effective immediately.<p>



