<h3>
Department of Commerce & Community Affairs<p>
</h3>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<font size=+3>1996 News Releases</font>
<br clear=right>
<hr>
<h3 align=center>
June 14, 1996<p>
Governor Congratulates Illinois Company for Largest Stamping Press Built in North America
</h3>

<strong>CHICAGO, ILL. </strong>- Gov. Jim Edgar today congratulaed Chicago-based Allied Products Corporation on the production of the largest automotive production presses ever built in North America, an order that added 100 jobs to the company's payroll.<p>

Three of the giant "A"-sized presses will be manufactured by Allied's Verson Division on Chicago's southeast side, two for shipment to a Chrysler production plant in Mexico and the third for use at Chrysler's Belvidere plant in northern Illinois.<p>

"The critics of the North American Free Trade Agreement argued it would cause the United States to export jobs across the border," the Governor said.  "Today is proof that NAFTA is creating good jobs for Illinois workers.  We are producing the goods that are necessary to produce goods throughout the world."<p>

"Illinois is an international powerhouse in the production of industrial machinery," Edgar said.  "Allied has made a tremendous contribution to our global reputation by being the first North American manufacturer of the "A"-size press, the largest machine tool made."<p>

Stamping presses make parts, such as fenders and hoods, from flat sheets of metal, usually steel.  The size and weight of 12 railroad locomotives, the presses are used primarily to make large body parts for automobiles and trucks.<p>

"We are also proud that Chrysler plans to use one of these presses at the Belvidere plant right here in Illinois and that two Illinois-made presses will be shipped to Mexico," Edgar said.   "This is a significant example of how the lowering of trade bariers is creating economic opportunity for Illinois companies and their workers."<p>

In 1995, the export of industrial machinery by Illinois companies reached $8.3 billion dollars, a 15 percent increase over 1994.<p>

Allied Products CEO Richard A. Drexler said the quality of the Illinois workforce has been a leading factor in the company's success.<p>

"Allied Products has been headquartered in Illinois for more than 30 years," Drexler said.  "The superb teamwork of our employees and our suppliers, coupled with the support of state and local governments, has enabled us to attain this milestone."<p>

The Verson Division of Allied Products Corporation is the only remaining American-owned-and-operated builder of heavy metal-forming presses.  Approximately 650 people are employed at the company's Chicago headquarters and manufacturing facility.<p>


