<HEAD><TITLE>DCCA: News Release -- June 13, 1996</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#8080C0" ALINK="#8080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/logosm.jpg" alt="DCCA Logo" width=165 height=82 align=left>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<h3>
Department of Commerce & Community Affairs<p>
</h3>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<font size=+3>1996 News Releases</font>
<br clear=right>
<hr>
<h3 align=center>
June 13, 1996<p>
Hometown Awards Honor Contributions of Local Volunteers
</h3>

<strong>SPRINGFIELD, ILL.</strong> --  Gov. Jim Edgar tonight congratulated winners in the 15th annual Governor's Home Town Awards, which recognize volunteer efforts that better the quality of life in Illinois communities.<p>

"Illinoisans have a strong sense of community," the Governor said.  "If there is a problem to be solved, or work to be done, we accept the challenge of changing things for the better.  Even the simplest project can make a difference in the lives of our fellow citizens. The volunteers honored with these awards have planted gardens, tutored students, sponsored plays and festivals, and built libraries, shelters and police stations.  They are an inspiration to us all, and this is our opportunity to show our appreciation for their efforts."<p>

The Governor's Cup, a traveling silver trophy, was awarded to Woodford County for its "Heart House" project, selected as this year's project most representative of the spirit of volunteerism in Illinois.<p>

Four years ago, a group of concerned citizens representing various religions came together to discuss establishing a homeless shelter in Woodford County.  Funded with donations, Heart House was opened in a former fraternity house near the Eureka College campus.<p>

When the fraternity decided to reactivate its chapter, the Heart House board decided to build a new shelter.  Hundreds of volunteers, including civic groups, labor unions and school groups, donated funds and assisted with the construction of the new facility, performing tasks from painting to carpentry.  The result is a homeless shelter valued at more than twice its cost that provides needed services totally without tax support.<p>

In all, the Governor presented awards to 73 projects.  In addition, a special award was presented to Palos Hills, which has received an award every year since the program's inception.<p>

The Governor's Hometown Awards competition is administered by the Illinois Department of Commerce and Community Affairs (DCCA).<p>

More than a hundred applications were submitted applications for this year's awards.  A group of volunteer judges reviewed the applications, judging them on the basis of local need and participation, continuity of the project and results.  The judges personally visited the communities they selected as finalists before making the final ranking decisions.<p>

Awards were presented in eight categories based on community participation.  Eligible projects involve economic development, community service, community facilities, human enrichment, achievements for or by youths and achievements for or by senior citizens.<p>

First place winners of general awards, youth awards, senior awards and economic development awards received commemorative plaques and road signs recognizing their achievements.  Second, third and fourth-place winners received plaques.<p>

A list of the 1996 winners is attached.<p>

<hr>
<h3>CATEGORY I (population up to 1,200)</h3>

<h4>GENERAL AWARD</h4>

<strong>1st Place   Smithfield</strong>--When the Red Brick School closed in 1990, volunteers banded together to ensure continued use of the facility as a Community Center.<p>
 
<strong>2nd Place   Beecher City</strong>--After receiving an initial grant, volunteers continued fundraising efforts to construct a community center. <p>
 
<strong>3rd Place   Ellis Grove</strong>--Members of the volunteer fire department organized efforts to construct a new 3,500 square-foot firehouse.<p>

<strong>4th Place   Pocahontas</strong>--Volunteer efforts helped bring advanced life-saving equipment and training to the Pocahontas-Old Ripley Fire Protection District.<p>

<h4>YOUTH  AWARD</h4>

<strong>1st Place   Germantown</strong>--Volunteers stepped to support the formation of an elementary school marching band, including assisting in the purchase of band uniforms.<p>   

<strong>2nd Place   Cedarville</strong>--Working together, volunteers installed a new playground, picnic shelter and volleyball court on the grounds of the Cedarville Community Center.<p> 


<h4>ECONOMIC DEVELOPMENT</h4>

<strong>1st Place   Ohio</strong>--By providing support for the construction of homes and businesses, volunteers helped spur nearly $3 million in new investments.<p>

<strong>2nd Place   Golconda</strong>--Local businesses, churches and other organizations joined in efforts to revitalize the downtown area, resulting in numerous improvements.<p>

<hr>
<h3>CATEGORY II (population 1,201 to 4,000)</h3>

<h4>GENERAL AWARD</h4>

<strong>1st Place   Lena</strong>--Volunteers donated property, funds and thousands of hours in hard work to complete construction of the Lena Community Center.<p>

<strong>2nd Place   McLeansboro</strong>--Beautification efforts led by volunteers have elevated civic pride and improved the aesthetic appeal of the community.<p>

<strong>3rd Place   Rockton</strong>--Volunteers, including children, contributed to the research and painting of a mural depicting the rich history of the Rockton area.<p>

<strong>4th Place   Greenup</strong>--Area citizens have restored the Greenup Railroad Depot and landscaped its surroundings, creating a heavily visited historic attraction.<p>   

<h4>YOUTH AWARD</h4>

<strong>1st Place   DePue</strong>--In little over a year, nearly 100 youths have become involved in volunteer efforts to organize positive activities for young people.<p>  

<strong>2nd Place   Waverly</strong>--Volunteers spearheaded efforts to make playground improvements that included equipment requested by children of the community.<p>

<strong>3rd Place   Pinckneyville</strong>--High school students wrote dozens of letters in support of the community's bid for a new medium-security prison. <p> 

<h4>ECONOMIC DEVELOPMENT</h4>

<strong>1st Place   Rushville-</strong>-Community leaders and volunteers successfully saved the only local movie theater from permanent closure, improving the town's economic climate.<p> 

<hr>
<h3>CATEGORY III (population 4,001 to 10,000)</h3>

<h4>GENERAL AWARD</h4>

<strong>1st Place   Spring Valley</strong>--Volunteers led efforts to start a Project Success program, promoting child self-development and family stability.<p>

<strong>2nd Place   Round Lake Park</strong>--The new  Round Lake Park Police Station is the result of volunteer efforts to remodel a former pet store.<p>

<strong>3rd Place   Geneseo</strong>--The City of Geneseo Park Board depends heavily on volunteers to maintain, develop and expand outdoor recreation facilities and services.<p> 

<strong>4th Place   Mascoutah</strong>--Volunteer labor helped refurbish a historic railroad car for community use in keeping with Mascoutah's railroad heritage.<p>

<h4>YOUTH AWARD</h4>

<strong>1st Place   Mt. Carroll</strong>--Local school programs such as field trips and the High School spring play are supported by the Mt. Carroll Education Foundation.<p>

<strong>2nd Place   Frankfort</strong>--Volunteers on the Frankfort Youth Commission study youth concerns and initiate positive activities such as food and clothing drive.<p>

<hr>
<h3>CATEGORY IV (population 10,001 to 15,000)</h3>

<h4>GENERAL AWARD</h4>

<strong>1st Place   Pontiac</strong>--A former retail store was converted by volunteers into a new public library, following unsuccessful attempts to pass local referenda.<p>  

<strong>2nd Place   Centralia</strong>--To promote waste reduction and recycling, volunteers provide a drive-through recycling drop-off center and other education activities.<p>

<strong>3rd Place   Bourbannais</strong>--The community's Friendship Festival is organized entirely by volunteers to coordinate everything from the carnival to the first-aid station.<p>

<strong>4th Place   Richton Park</strong>--The volunteer Richton Park Citizen Patrol is being expanded after its initial success in combating gang activity and other crime.<p>

<h4>YOUTH AWARD</h4>

<strong>1st Place   Crest Hill</strong>--Youth athletic programs continued under the leadership of community volunteers when school programs were eliminated.<p>

<strong>2nd Place   Pontiac</strong>--A number of youth programs have been organized by volunteers to combat gang activities and drug use.<p>

<strong>3rd Place   Streator</strong>--The need for recreational improvements prompted formation of a volunteer organization to provide children with new playground equipment.<p>


<strong>SENIOR AWARD </strong>

<strong>1st Place   Crestwood</strong>--Volunteers organize an annual fashion show to benefit residents of the Crestwood Care Centre.<p>
           
<strong>2nd Place   Hickory Hills</strong>--The local Park District depends on senior volunteers to assist with many activities, often partnering them with teen volunteers.<p>

<strong>3rd Place   Washington</strong>--The Washington Senior Citizen Center provides many services to seniors, relying on volunteers to assist in fundraising and operations.<p>

<h4>ECONOMIC DEVELOPMENT</h4>

<strong>1st Place   Hickory Hills</strong>--An apartment complex was renovated and is now a thriving 100 percent rented senior citizen community, with help from senior volunteers.<p>   

<strong>2nd Place   Worth</strong>--Volunteers organized to clean, beautify and revitalize the business district, including conducting a village-wide clean-up day.<p>

<hr>
<h3>CATEGORY V (population 15,001 to 30,000)</h3>

<h4>GENERAL AWARD</h4>

<strong>1st Place   Palos Hills</strong>--A "Multicultural Mural" at the entrance to Oak Ridge School was created by volunteers to build community unity.

<strong>2nd Place   East Moline</strong>--Community volunteers participated in an old-fashioned "barn raising" to construct a 14,000 square-foot playground. 

<strong>3rd Place   Mundelein</strong>--Residents of a high-risk area have benefited from volunteer efforts to provide services such as tutoring programs and free immunizations.

<strong>4th Place   Hinsdale</strong>--Community residents have volunteered to "adopt" small gardens in this effort to beautify the downtown area.

<h4>YOUTH AWARD</h4>

<strong>1st Place   Union County</strong>--Volunteers helped to renovate a small house to provide space for the Early Childhood Resource Center.<p>

<strong>2nd Place   Lake Zurich</strong>--Emergency Services Explorer Post #2, established and staffed by volunteers, is the first such Post in the nation with a joint police/fire discipline.<p>

<h4>SENIOR AWARD</h4>

<strong>1st Place   Vernon Hills</strong>--Senior volunteers created plywood cutouts of favorite children's characters to enhance the community's winter festival.<p>

<strong>2nd Place   Palos Hills</strong>--A "hillbilly" style mock wedding was organized and produced by volunteers to provide entertainment and enjoyment for seniors.<p>

<h4>ECONOMIC DEVELOPMENT</h4>

<strong>1st Place   Union County</strong>--A three-day fall festival is staged by volunteers to increase tourism and promote economic development.<p>

<hr>
<h3>CATEGORY VI (population of 30,001 to 50,000)</h3>

<h4>GENERAL AWARD</h4>

<strong>1st Place   Woodford County</strong>--Donations of time, money and materials by volunteers  resulted in construction of a new community homeless shelter.<p>

<strong>2nd Place   Danville</strong>--An all-volunteer capital campaign helped raise funds needed to construction a new public library. <p> 

<strong>3rd Place   Berwyn</strong>--Volunteers have documented and researched homes and developed criteria for a Century Homes Award Program.<p>

<strong>4th Place   Pekin</strong>--Thanks to a volunteer education campaign, ordinances have been adopted to protect the city's groundwater supply. <p> 

<h4>YOUTH AWARD</h4>
<strong>1st Place   Alton</strong>--A long-time volunteer tutor program helps students with their studies and in developing better social skills.<p>

<strong>2nd Place   Tinley Park</strong>--D.A.R.E. graduates from throughout Illinois attended a music festival supported by volunteers, including entertainers and businesspeople. <p> 

<strong>3rd Place   Kendall County</strong>--A new county fairgrounds, made possible by volunteers, gives 4-H members a place to exhibit their projects and livestock. <p>

<strong>4th Place   Alton</strong>--A volunteer program is aimed at encouraging young minority students to develop interests in areas such as science and the environment. <p>

<h4>ECONOMIC DEVELOPMENT</h4>
<strong>1st Place   Moline</strong>--"Renew Moline" is a not-for-profit development group that has donated time and effort to revitalizing the downtown area.<p>

<strong>2nd Place   Alton</strong>--For the past five years, volunteers, in cooperation with the City of Alton, have worked to devise a plan to redevelop the Riverfront District.<p>

<hr>
<h3>CATEGORY VII (population of 50,001 to 125,000)</h3>

<h4>GENERAL AWARD</h4>

<strong>1st Place   Vermilion County</strong>--A community-wide effort resulted in a free health clinic that has treated nearly 1,200 patients, many of them children. <p> 

<strong>2nd Place   Springfield</strong>--A Women's Self-Help Center undertook a neighborhood clean-up to clear areas that had been targets of illegal dumping. <p>

<strong>3rd Place   Peoria</strong>--Heart of Illinois Harvest volunteers distributed more than 2 million pounds of food to more than 55 agencies in the Peoria area.<p>

<strong>4th Place   Maine Township</strong>--The gang-related shooting of a local teen in 1992 spurred creation of a Neighborhood Watch program that has had continued success.<p> 

<h4>YOUTH AWARD</h4>

<strong>1st Place   Cicero</strong>--Adopt a Block is designed to help improve community appearance while instilling pride in young people.<p>

<strong>2nd Place   Aurora</strong>--Red Cross volunteers worked with the school district to coordinate a disaster education program.<p>

<strong>3rd Place   Naperville</strong>--Youth volunteers help staff the Naper Settlement, interpreting for visitors the 13-acre site that tells the story of Naperville.<p>

<h4>SENIOR AWARD </h4>

<strong>1st Place   Champaign-Urbana</strong>--Volunteers stepped in to save the Food for Seniors program when it lost work space at the local food bank.<p>

<strong>2nd Place   Kankakee County</strong>--A volunteer program to help seniors upgrade their homes and make needed repairs was expanded and now includes three communities.<p>

<h4>ECONOMIC DEVELOPMENT AWARD</h4>

<strong>1st Place   Arlington Heights</strong>--A 479-member Festival Committee leads volunteer efforts to put on the community's summer Frontier Days. <p>

<hr>
<h3>CATEGORY VIII (population over 300,000)</h3>

<h4>GENERAL AWARD</h4>

<strong>1st Place   Mt. Prospect, Arlington Heights, Palatine, Schaumburg and Des Plaines, and Barrrington, Elk Grove, Hanover, Palatine, Schaumburg and Wheeling Townships</strong>--The Access to Care program depends on volunteers to help provides low-cost health care services, and has grown to serve more than 22,000 people.<p>

<strong>2nd Place   Tenth Judicial Circuit of Illinois (Peoria, Tazewill, Stark, Marshall and Putnam Counties)</strong>--The Family Violence Coordinating Council, supported by volunteers, brings together professionals and policy makers to work against family violence.<p>

<strong>3rd Place   Chicago</strong>--Sauganash School is now a source of pride for the neighborhood after volunteers worked to beautify the school grounds.<p> 


<h4>YOUTH AWARD</h4>

<strong>1st Place   Chicago</strong>--The Robert Taylor Learn to Swim Program gets girls involved in sports by offering swimming instruction, water safety instructor training and lifeguard training.<p>

<strong>2nd Place   Cook County</strong>--Volunteers Interested in People (V.I.P.) has successfully created two 4-H clubs to specifically address the needs of the developmentally disabled.<p>

<strong>3rd Place   Cook County</strong>--Thirty-five different agencies are among those that provide support for RAPP, an effort to counteract gang activity.<p>

<strong>4th Place   Montgomery, Christian, Logan, Macoupin, Menard and Sangamon Counties</strong>--Festival of Giving, providing assistance to the needy during the Christmas holiday season, has been a Girl Scout tradition for more than half a century.<p>

<h4>SENIOR AWARD  </h4>

<strong>1st Place   Cook County</strong>--The Collaborative Senior Advocate Program provides individual assistance to help seniors participate in public programs.<p> 

<h4>ECONOMIC DEVELOPMENT </h4>

<strong>1st Place   Cook County</strong>--More than one hundred volunteers contributed 1,400 hours to make the 5th Operation Access Job Fair for disabled workers a success.<p>

<strong>2nd Place   Chicago</strong>--Jordan's Empower, Inc. uses volunteers to link job seekers with major employers in the Austin Community.<p>


<HR>
