<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<font size=+3>1996 News Releases</font>
<br clear=right>
<hr>
<h3 align=center>
June 11, 1996<p>
Governor Announces Water and Sewer Planning Grants
</h3>

SPRINGFIELD, IL - Gov. Jim Edgar today announced 26 communities throughout Illinois will share $500,000 in Community Development Assistance Program (CDAP) grants to help fund planning activities for local water and sewer system improvements.<p>

"Adequate infrastructure is the foundation of community development," the Governor said.  "Improvements to local water and sewer systems enhance a ocmmunity's quality of life and its ability to attract and retain business.  These planning grants help local governments through the first stage of that improvement process."<p>

Edgar said a project in eastern Illinois is an example.<p>

Champaign County applied on behalf of the unincorporated area of Wilbur Heights for a sewer study.  The low-income neighborhood of approximately 80 homes is served by private septic systems, which are experiencing difficulties due to the soil type and small lot sizes.  Alternatives to the individual septic systems will be studied, including connection to existing treatment facilities in a neighboring city.<p>

Units of local goverment may apply ofr up to $25,000 for planning activities which will result in infrastructure improvements to water, sanitary or storm sewer systems.<p>

Lt. Gov. Bob Kustra, the Governor's senior advisor for economic development, said CDAP funds are especially important to smaller communities.<p>

"Infrastructure improvements are expensive," Kustra said.  "This program helps to remove the financial barriers a small community may face in upgrading their water and sewer systems."<p>

CDAP grants are funded with federal block grant funds from the U.S. Department of Housing and Urban Development (HUD).  They are awarded by the Department of Commerce and Community Affairs to units of local government with population of 50,000 or less that are not located within one of the seven large urban counties that receive funds directly from HUD.<p>

At least 51 percent of a proposed project's beneficiaries must be people with low or moderate incomes.<p>

A list of communities receiving CDAP Planning Assistance is below.<p>
<p>
<pre>
<strong>COMMUNITY       COUNTY          PROJECT                            AMOUNT</strong>

Abingdon        Knox            Complete water system analysis     $19,500
Altona          Knox            Sewer study                         21,500
Anna            Union           Water system planning               20,500
Astoria         Fulton          Sewer study                         20,500
Aviston         Clinton         Sewer study                         19,500
Avon            Fulton          Water distribution/storage study    11,000
Bowen           Hancock         Study of health hazards             21,500
Brussels        Calhoun         Waste water treatment study         20,500
Calhoun         Richland        Sewer study                         12,000
Casey           Clark           Study of drainage problems          21,500
Champaign County                Sewer study                         21,500
Colchester      McDonough       Sewer study                         21,500
Cuba            Fulton          Sewer study                         19,500
Grayville       White           Sewer study                         21,500
Havana          Mason           Sewer study                         22,000
Herrick         Shelby          Sewer study                         17,000
Iola            Clay            Sewer study                         17,000
Junction City   Marion          Sewer study                         22,000
Kane            Greene          Wastewater Treatment Study          17,000
Lewistown       Fulton          Sewer study                         21,500
Ludlow          Champaign       Water system study                  19,000
Macoupin County                 Sewer study                         16,500
Marion County                   Water supply study                  21,500
Mill Creek      Union           Sewer system planning               16,000
Pearl           Pike            Wastewater system study             17,000
St. Elmo        Fayette         Sewer study                         21,500    
</pre>

