<HEAD><TITLE>DCCA: News Release -- April 26, 1996</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#8080C0" ALINK="#8080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/logosm.jpg" alt="DCCA Logo" width=165 height=82 align=left>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<h3>
Department of Commerce & Community Affairs<p>
</h3>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<font size=+3>1996 News Releases</font>
<br clear=right>
<hr>
<h3 align=center>
April 26, 1996<p>
Lt. Gov Awards Grants for Multi-Company Network Demonstration Project
</h3>

<strong>SPRINGFIELD, IL </strong> --  Lt. Gov. Bob Kustra has announced that multi-company network demonstration project grants have been awarded to the Center for Governmental Studies at Northern Illinois University and the Illinois Chamber of Commerce.<p>

"This initiative is designed to improve the competitiveness of Illinois' small, medium-sized and mature firms," said Kustra, the Governor's senior advisor for economic development.  "In multi-company networks, firms join forces to accomplish what they cannot do on their own." <p>

The Illinois Department of Commerce and Community Affairs (DCCA) administers the program.  DCCA Director Dennis R. Whetstone explained that two key types of assistance are emphasized in the projects.<p>  

"Network broker training will prepare individuals to act as leaders in establishing manufacturing networks," Whetstone said.  "The brokers will link manufacturing firms to each other in order to promote cooperation.<p>

"Network planning and development will provide for activities which increase the capacity of firms across the state to establish networks or better operate existing networks, which then link them to key markets or public sources of assistance." 	<p>

The Illinois Chamber will oversee the Southern Illinois Linkage Study Project, which will receive $85,000 to inventory, classify and analyze the existing products, manufacturing processes, inputs and outputs of the manufacturing sector in the southernmost 30 counties in Illinois.<p>  

"Assisting businesses in the Southern Illinois region is a major priority for the Illinois Chamber," said Sally A. Jackson, President and CEO of the Chamber.  "We commend the participants for taking this progressive step in economic development.  More business and job creation are our goals, and we are very happy to have a leadership role in this effort."<p>

The results of the inventory will be linked to DCCA's Industry Analysis System, in order to provide a more comprehensive database for brokers and firms to use in building networks.<p>   	

The project is a partnership between the Illinois Chamber, Southern Illinois manufacturers, Central Illinois Public Service Company, Illinois Power, GTE, Carbondale Business Development Corporation, Williamson County Marketing Committee, and the Electric Cooperatives of Southern Illinois.<p>  

The Center for Government Studies at Northern Illinois University will receive $69,920 over two years to deliver broker training services.  The Center will utilize the services of USNet, a program which will supply consultants to train brokers and Center staff.  The Center will coordinate and facilitate broker training, provide technical assistance to networks, and conduct other activities to encourage the development of multi-company networks across the state.<p>  

The grant also serves as the required matching funding for a federal grant which has been provided to USNet to assist states in multi-company network development.<p>

Once the demonstration projects are concluded, the techniques learned will be transferred to local and regional economic development organizations to help them incorporate network development in their day-to-day operations. <p>	  

Anyone interested in further information about the demonstration projects may contact DCCA's Office of Program and Policy Development at 217/524-5696 or TDD 800/785-6055.<p> 

<h4 align=center>###</h4>


