<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>DCCA: 1996 News Release -- March 6, 1996</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#8080C0" ALINK="#8080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/logosm.jpg" alt="DCCA Logo" width=165 height=82 align=left>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<h3>
Department of Commerce & Community Affairs<p>
</h3>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<font size=+3>1996 News Releases</font>
<br clear=right>
<hr>
<h3 align=center>
March 6, 1996<p>
COMMERCE AND COMMUNITY AFFAIRS TO INVEST IN BUSINESS DEVELOPMENT, WORKER TRAINING AND TOURISM
</h3>

<em>SPRINGFIELD, ILL.</em> - Gov. Jim Edgar today recommended a $774.6 million budget for the Department of Commerce and Community Affairs (DCCA) to help Illinois businesses continue to thrive and increase their export capability in a strong and expanding state economy.<p>

The budget will provide additional assistance to business, invest more dollars in worker training, maintain community development projects and promote tourism throughout the state.<p>

"The Illinois economy is very healthy," the Governor said.  "In the past year, we have seen our unemployment rate drop to the lowest level in two decades.  Some of our most prominent corporate citizens, including Motorola and McDonald's, have announced major expansions, and national studies have ranked Illinois and the Chicago metropolitan area among the most attractive in the country for business expansions and relocations.<p>

"To continue our economic momentum and increase our competitiveness, we must be willing to renew our commitment to invest in the services and programs that have encouraged growth.  This budget allows us to train more Illinois worker, improves our ability to help companies and communities seeking assistance and expands our highly successful tourism promotion efforts."<p>

The Fiscal Year 1997 budget request includes $40.2 million in general revenue funds.  The budget also includes $600.4 million in federal funds and $134 million in other state funds.<p>

A highlight of the fiscal 1997 budget request is $39.2 million to fund business development programs.  The Regional Industry Development and Building and Sites initiative is designed to enhance DCCA's working relationships with local economic development officials and improve responsiveness to all in-coming business expansion, retention and location inquiries.  The Building and Sites component will allow the department to more accurately represent facilities and development sites to business prospects.<p>

"This budget makes an important investment in our businesses and our workers," said Lt. Gov. Bob Kustra, the Governor's senior adviser for economic development.  "Increased funding for worker training will help keep businesses in Illinois and make our workforce more competitive.  Worker training funds suffered severe cuts in the early '90s, but this increase recognizes many of our recent successes are due in large part to productive and well-trained workers."<p>

The high quality of the Illinois workforce is a key factor in business expansion and retention.  To keep pace with the demand for worker training, funding for the Industrial Training Program (ITP) will total $15 million, and increase of $2.75 million.<p>

"As technology in the workplace has advanced, so has the need for worker training," said DCCA director Dennis Whetstone.  "The ITP program has been highly successful in ensuring that the quality of Illinois workers is second to none, providing direct grants to individual companies and supporting multi-company networks of small and medium-sized suppliers.  This increase will give nearly 5,000 workers at approximately 350 companies the opportunity to upgrade their job skills."<p>

DCCA's International Business Division will use a budget allocation of $3.5 million to promote the exporting of Illinois goods and services throughout the international marketplace.<p>

An additional $200,000 in funding is provided to continue technology transfer and business modernization efforts provided for in the state's Technology Advancement and Development Act.<p>

The request also includes $2.3 million to fund the state's network of Small Business Development Centers, which provide one-on-one assistance to entrepreneurs.<p>

In addition, DCCA's fiscal 1997 budget request projects $237.2 million for federally funded Job Training Partnership Act (JTPA) programs, which assist dislocated workers, economically disadvantaged youths and adults, older workers, and other who face barriers to employment.<p>

Tourism and film programs will receive $33.4 million under the Governor's budget proposal.  An increase of $1.4 million in tourism promotion funds, generated exclusively by the Illinois hospitality industry, will be used by the Bureau of Tourism to attract major national and international events to the state, develop a heritage-cultural tourism program, increase individual contact with Illinois travelers through a direct marketing effort and handle increasing call volume to the 1-800-2CONNECT hotline.<p>

In addition, $13.6 million has been allocated to administer the Office of Energy Conservation, promoting the efficient and environmentally safe use of Illinois' energy resources.<p>

Appropriations for community development programs that assist low-income Illinoisans and provide services to local governments are proposed at $376.7 million.<p>

The budget proposal also includes $17.8 million for Coal Marketing and Development, of which $2 million will leverage more than $9 million in federal funds for a low emission boiler demonstration project to promote the continued use of Illinois' vast coal resources.  The budget also includes $600,000 in coal bond funding for an ethanol-powered fuel cell bus project and a corn-to-ethanol research pilot plant.<p>


