<h3>
Department of Commerce & Community Affairs<p>
</h3>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<font size=+3>1996 News Releases</font>
<br clear=right>
<hr>
<h3 align=center>
February 9, 1996<p>
GOVERNOR ANNOUNCES FUNDING TO ASSIST SPARTAN PRINTING WORKERS
</h3>

<em>SPRINGFIELD, IL</em> -- Gov. Jim Edgar today announced the state has received $1 million in emergency funding to assist the more than 800 workers affected by the closure of Spartan Printing in Sparta.<p>

"The shut down of Spartan Printing is a severe blow to the residents of Sparta and Randolph County," the Governor said.  "Last month my administration began the process of offering assistance to spartan workers and immediately set in motion the steps to secure the release of emergency funds to continue that effort.<p>

"This grant will support the operation of the Sparta Career Center, where those affected by the shut down will have access to a full range of services, such as job search classes and placement services.  I have also directed the Illinois Department of Commerce and Community Affairs (DCCA) to seek additional funding that will provide dislocated worker services through 1998."<p>

The $1 million grant is being provided through the federal Job Training Partnership Act (JTPA), administered in Illinois by DCCA.<p>

Participants will be provided with a full array of services, including basic readjustment, assessment and job development.<p>

Vocational training, G.E.D. classes and on-the-job training will also be offered, and participants will be able to apply for assistance with transportation and child care.  The Sparta Career Center will also offer ongoing stress counseling in the form of workshops and on an outreach basis.<p>


