<HEAD><TITLE>DCCA: 1996 News Release -- February 8, 1996</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#8080C0" ALINK="#8080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/logosm.jpg" alt="DCCA Logo" width=165 height=82 align=left>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<h3>
Department of Commerce & Community Affairs<p>
</h3>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<font size=+3>1996 News Releases</font>
<br clear=right>
<hr>
<h3><center>
February 8, 1996<p>
GOVERNOR UNVEILS PLAN TO ENHANCE CHICAGO'S POTENTIAL FOR ATTRACTING MEGA CONVENTIONS, ENTERTAINMENT SHOWS AND ATHLETIC EVENTS WITHOUT RAISING OR ADDING TAXES
</center></h3>

<strong>CHICAGO, IL</strong> -- Gov. Jim Edgar today unveiled his plan to enhance the potential for attracting mega conventions, entertainment shows and athletic events to Chicago by further expanding the McCormick Place complex.<p>

"Without raising taxes or creating new taxes, we have a tremendous opportunity to build a facility that will create thousands of jobs and bring hundreds of millions of dollars into the economy of the Chicago metropolitan area and the State of Illinois each and every year,"  the Governor said.<p>

Edgar pointed out that Chicago currently does not have the facilities to accommodate many of the largest conventions and assemblies.<p>

He said the entertainment and convention center he is proposing could allow the city to attract national and international meetings of such groups as the Promise Keepers, which would bring nearly $70 million into the city; Alcoholics Anonymous, which would bring nearly $50 million; the Youth Gathering of the Evangelical Lutheran Church in America, which would bring more than $40 Million, and the Lions International convention, which would bring more than $30 million.<p>

"A super city should be able to host a Super Bowl.  The enclosed facility I am proposing will accommodate a Super Bowl, the Final Four and other events that could bring tens of thousands of people to Chicago.  These events would showcase a world-class city and a great state."<p>

Edgar said, "The facility also would offer the Chicago Bears a state-of-the-art home in which to battle for a Super Bowl berth.<p>

"As I have said repeatedly, I want to keep the Bears in Chicago, but I don't want to subsidize a professional sports team or build a football stadium.  Under this proposal, the Bears will help pay for a facility that can be used for many, many other purposes -- a facility that will attract millions and millions of people to events that have nothing to do with shoulder pads and helmets and pay huge dividends for the city and the state."<p>

The Governor said he is counting on the Bears to help fund the extension of McCormick Place.  "We need the backing of the Bears.  We need the backing of the Legislature.  And we need the backing of the Mayor of Chicago," the Governor said.<p>

"I am optimistic that support will be forthcoming.  It is difficult to imagine that we would not seize this great opportunity to launch an initiative that will create thousands of jobs."<p>

The Bears and the Metropolitan Pier and Exposition Authority would share the cost of constructing the center, which is expected to take four years.<p>

The Bears would provide $175 million, and the authority would provide $185 million.  In addition, the authority would construct and operate a $50 million parking garage and garner all the revenues from it.  It also would contribute $5 million in construction-related administrative costs.<p>

The City of Chicago and the State of Illinois would contribute $25 million each for land acquisition and infrastructure costs.<p>

"The state has provided infrastructure for economic development initiatives throughout the state and typically called upon local governments to do their share.  This is consistent with that policy.  It is consistent with what we did at the United Center, and we will work together with the United Center to assure that it will continue to realize its full potential."<p>

The Metropolitan Pier and Exposition Authority would fund its share by fully utilizing revenues from taxes paid primarily by visitors to Chicago.  The taxes were supported in 1991 by the Governor, the Mayor and the Legislature to expand McCormick Place.  They are pledged at their current rates to bond holders through the year 2029.  However, they will produce a surplus that can be used to add the enclosed facility proposed by the Governor without raising or creating any new taxes.<p>

