<HEAD><TITLE>DCCA: News Release -- August 10, 1995</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#8080C0" ALINK="#8080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/logosm.jpg" alt="DCCA Logo" width=165 height=82 align=left>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<h3>
Department of Commerce & Community Affairs<p>
</h3>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<font size=+3>News Releases</font>
<br clear=right>
<hr>
<h3 align=center>
August 10, 1995<p>
   Illinois Chosen to Implement One-Stop Career Center Network                
</h3>




<EM>SPRINGFIELD, ILL.</EM> - Gov. Jim Edgar today announced that Illinois is one of seven states chosen by the U.S. Department of Labor to implement a One-Stop Career Center Network.<P>

Illinois was awarded a grant of nearly $6.7 million form the U.S. Department of Labor to fund activities during the first year of the three-year project.<P>

"Illinois has always been at the forefront in designing services to help our citizens prepare for rewarding, productive careers," the Governor said. "It is natural, then, that our state should be leader in implementing the new One-Stop Career Center Network concept.<P>

"Two years ago, we started initial planning to consolidate career-related services administered by various agencies and educational institutions under one roof.  Our goal is to make it easier for people who need these services.  Rather than driving all over town, people can visit one place to get the information they need about a wide range of services, from unemployment assistance to job training and educational programs.<P>

"Already, we have opened full-service centers in Decatur, Rockford and Mattoon, and are well on the way to consolidating services in dozens of other communities around our state.  This grant will help us speed up that process so that people throughout our state will benefit from One-Stop Career Centers."<P>

Lt. Gov. Bob Kustra, the Governor's senior adviser on economic development, said state officials worked closely with local service providers to design the Career Center Network.<P>

"Although each center will be customized to fit local labor market conditions and customer needs, they will offer a standard set of high quality employment, unemployment and training services.  They also will make maximum use of computer and telecommunications technology to link center, increase program access and ensure efficient service."<P>

During the three-year implementation period, Illinois plans to establish 55 full-service centers and 93 satellite offices.  It is anticipated that 40 new centers will be operational by the end of the first year.  At the end of the three-year development period, people throughout the state are expected to be served by a Career Center.<P>

Dennis R. Whetstone, Director of the Department of commerce and Community Affairs, which administer Illinois' Job Training Partnership Act (JTPA) programs, said the centers will build upon JTPA's programs to help displaced and disadvantaged workers train for new employment.<P>

"Besides making services convenient to clients, we have built in a new component to tailor our services to the needs of the business community,"  Whetstone said.  "These centers will offer businesses and clients easy access to labor market information, making it possible for clients to match their skills with the places that need those skills.  Center staffers will also work with local businesses to ensure that participants are being trained in skills that those businesses need."<P>

Lynn Q. Doherty, Director of the Department of Employment Security (IDES), said the success of the early one-stop centers has been encouraging, both for the public and for the staff people who work in the centers.<P>

"Illinois has worked hard on its plan for a one-stop system of employment and training centers, and we are proud to have been selected as one of the states to fully launch this program, which offers comprehensive services in one location and also provides cost savings for the people who foot the bill, the Illinois taxpayers," Doherty said.<P>
 

<HR>
