<HEAD><TITLE>DCCA: News Release -- July 13, 1995</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#0080C0" ALINK="#0080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/logosm.jpg" alt="DCCA Logo" width=165 height=82 align=left>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<h3>
Department of Commerce & Community Affairs<p>
</h3>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<font size=+3>News Releases</font>
<br clear=right>
<hr>
<h3 align=center>
July 13, 1995<p>
        Twenty-seven Communities Awarded Grants; Funds Help Plan Public Facilities Improvements            
</h3>




<EM>SPRINGFIELD, ILL</EM>. - Gov. Jim Edgar today announced grants totaling $500,000 to help 27 Illinois communities initiate formal planning for future improvements to public water and sewer systems.<P>

"Infrastructure is one of the foundations of economic development," the Governor said.  "While Community Development Assistance Program (CDAP) public facilities grants can help many smaller communities fund critical improvement sot water and sewer systems, some communities lack even the funds necessary to compile the plans needed to seek the grants.<P>

"For that reason, we have developed a separate CDAP component specifically to help fund these planning efforts.  Once plans have been developed, the communities will be in a position to seek future assistance to actually undertake the improvements needed to meet their public facilities needs."<P>

Lt. Gov. Bob Kustra, the Governor's senior adviser on economic development, said the need is always great.<P>

"Communities know when they have a public facilities problem; however, finding the best and most efficient solution to the problem may not be within their reach," Kustra said.  "Through this program, we can provide assistance that will enable many smaller communities to investigate the various alternatives and develop plans to solve their water and sewer needs."<P>

Projects in Biggsville and Stockton are examples.<P>

Biggsville, population 349, has no sewer system.  Many of the existing septic systems discharge into a community tile constructed in the 1920's, creating a hazard to public health and safety.  The village will receive a $10,800 grant to study various alternatives to collect and treat the sanitary sewer discharge.<P>

The wastewater treatment plant in the Village of Stockton is inadequate to meet its needs, placing the community on restricted development status.  Its water system is also insufficient, causing a threat to public health and safety.  Two major employers are particularly affected.  An egg washing and separating plant that has large wastewater treatment needs has been forced to cut back production and lay off workers to reduce its wastewater discharge.  An automotive systems manufacturer moved some of its production to another community because Stockton's labor force was insufficient - a problem made worse by a shortage of available housing in Stockton and the village's inability to undertake additional housing development to attract new residents.  The village will receive a $21,200 grant to review existing water and sewer facilities and develop alternatives to solve the problems.<P>

CDAP grants, funded with federal block grant funds from the U.S. Department of Housing and Urban Development (HUD), are administered by the Department of Commerce and community Affairs (DCCA).  DCCA awards funds to units of local government with populations of 50,000 or less that are not located within one of the seven large urban counties that receive funds directly form HUD.<P>

The maximum grant available under the CDAP Planning Assistance Grant component is $25,000.  At least 51 percent of the project's beneficiaries must be people with low or moderate income levels.<P>



 

