<CENTER><H2>November, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<HR>

<h3>ILLINOIS F.I.R.S.T. PROMOTES ILLINOIS' POSITIVE BUSINESS CLIMATE</h3>
<h4>by Peter W. Ramirez, DCCA Bureau of Business Development</h4>

Illinois F.I.R.S.T. (Focused Industrial Retention Support Team) is off and running.  Illinois F.I.R.S.T. is a joint effort that brings together the resources of DCCA and Argonne National Laboratory, NORBIC (North Business and Industrial Council), Chicagoland Enterprise Center, ComEd, People's Gas and the Chicago Tribune to identify and assist manufacturers interested in expanding, modernizing, relocating, training, retraining or developing new technologies.<p>    

Illinois F.I.R.S.T. is a pro-active effort that specifically targets manufacturers in Northern Illinois.  Initially, businesses are contacted with an outreach letter from Gov. Jim Edgar, which is followed up by a phone call from Illinois F.I.R.S.T.  After an initial screening, a Client Summary Sheet is filled out that establishes the position of the company and the problems and challenges it faces.  Resources and information are then provided to assist with the client's needs, with all activities tracked and recorded, and files monitored constantly.  In addition, a follow-up survey is sent to each client to provide Illinois F.I.R.S.T. with client satisfaction information.<p>  
 
The response of the manufacturing community to this pilot effort has been gratifying.  Using both marketing efforts and a direct mail campaign, Illinois F.I.R.S.T. has contacted 320 manufacturers.  To date, 70 of these businesses have received information or technical assistance with expansion support, environmental issues, integrated management support, production evaluation, relocation and site selection, training, workers compensation and turnaround services.<p>  

Illinois F.I.R.S.T. continues to work with the private sector to expand its efforts.  The partnership has engaged the Society of the Plastics Industry, American Plastics Industry, and the American Electronics Association to host industry summit meetings to discuss the needs of these specific industries.  It is working with the DuPage Area Association of Business and Industry to assist with client screening and intake.  And nearly two dozen additional professionals have agreed to provide pro bono services in their areas of expertise<p>.

For information about Illinois F.I.R.S.T., contact Peter W. Ramirez in DCCA's Bureau of Business Development at 312/814-5252 (TDD users call 800/419-0667).<p>

<hr>
<h3>TQM TEAMS MAKING A DIFFERENCE</h3>
<h4>by Karen Ruwe, DCCA Division of Fiscal Management</h4>

DCCA's efforts to incorporate the principles of Total Quality Management (TQM) into the agency's processes are beginning to show an impact that will benefit the agency's clients, as well as streamline DCCA's internal processes.  The efforts of the Grant Processing Team, for example, are expected to cut the time it takes for DCCA to process grants, thus improving the grants cycle for external clients.<p>

The Grant Processing Team set out last spring to review the manner in which DCCA processes and awards grants.  The Team conducted both cycle time and quality defect studies to determine where changes could be made.<p>

The Team's review resulted in the elimination of Financial Commitment Committee (FCC) approval for all grant programs that currently have an approved internal review process in place.  With the aid of the Chief Internal Auditor, quality review processes were documented and approved for most grant programs.  These steps are expected to cut grant processing time by approximately two weeks per grant.<p>

The Grant Processing Team also recommended standardizing the agency's grant boilerplates.  DCCA's Legal office, working with representatives from program and fiscal staff, has already completed work on standardizing boilerplate sections that are the same in all agency grants.  Meetings are currently being held to complete program-specific boilerplates.  It is expected that boilerplate standardization will lower the chances that incorrect boilerplate sections are used, and thus lessen the time needed for grant review and copying.<p>

The Grant Processing Team continues to look at new ways to streamline and improve DCCA's grant processes.  Areas now being considered for study include further automation of the review and approval process, and paperwork reduction efforts.<p>

<hr>
<h3>ILLINOIS BUSINESSES LEARNING TO REDUCE ENERGY COSTS</h3>
<h4>by Don McGee, DCCA Bureau of Energy and Recycling </h4>

Businesses are often large users of energy.  To help them identify energy conservation practices that can help them reduce energy usage, DCCA's Bureau of Energy and Recycling and Central Illinois Public Service Company (CIPS), have joined with Southern Illinois University at Carbondale (SIU-C) to establish a prototype energy educational project for regional businesses.<p>   

The new program, Creating Energy Management Opportunities for Industry (CEMOI), under direction of professor Manohar Kulkarni, PE, Ph.D., of the SIU-C Department of Mechanical Engineering and Energy Processes, provides businesses with on-site energy inspections conducted by the university's graduate and engineering students.  Each student receives specialized energy training from DCCA Energy staff and CIPS service representatives to teach ways to identify immediate, low-cost and no-cost dollar savings for businesses.<p>  

As part of the service, Illinois businesses receiving an energy inspection from CEMOI staff are provided an executive summary of the findings.  Participating businesses will receive an "Energy Analysis Report" identifying potential dollar-saving opportunities that require no financial investment or a small investment.  CEMOI also will develop and maintain, free of charge, an Energy Resources Directory, which will include information about private sector energy service providers in their region, as well as governmental and educational resources that are available to assist area businesses.<p>  

This fall, CIPS sponsored a CEMOI kick-off luncheon at the SIU-C Incubator.   Professor Kulkarni reported that in just the preliminary phases of the program, eight businesses receiving services have already realized an average savings of $1500 per business or 10 percent of their annual costs, with a maximum of a five-month payback on investment.<p>   

It is hoped that, with DCCA's assistance and regional support from the private sector, the CEMOI program will eventually become a self-sustaining business assistance program in Southern Illinois.<p>

The CEMOI office is located in the SIU-C Incubator facility at 150 East Pleasant Hill Road, Carbondale, IL  62901-6890, phone 618/453-2067.  Or, for further information, contact Don McGee at DCCA at 217/785-2862 (TDD users call 217/785-0211).<p>

<hr>
<h3>DCCA WINS 1996 "WEB WARRIOR" AWARD</h3>

DCCA's Internet home page is winning recognition for its business savvy.  The page recently was named as the Sixth Place Winner of the "1996 Web Warrior Award" by Fuld & Company Inc. of Cambridge, Massachusetts, a pioneer in the field of competitive and regional intelligence that provides assistance to economic development organizations and utility companies to help them define their competitive advantages.<p>

Fuld & Company selected DCCA's site after a review of more than 100 Websites from around the world.  Using as its criteria Clarity, Strategic Focus, Business Climate, Depth of Resources, and Access to Information, company officials examined the sites from the corporate CEO's perspective and what that individual would need to know when considering relocating or expanding a facility in a region.  The company noted that, "With more than 50 million worldwide users and over 600,000 businesses on-line, the World Wide Web is today's global marketplace.  To effectively compete in this new arena, economic development agencies need to provide relevant, timely and targeted information to business leaders and investors."<p>

In reviewing DCCA's Website, Fuld & Company noted, "The Illinois Department of Commerce and Community Affairs wants your business in Illinois and they have the professional staff, relevant information, and assistance programs to help make your decision an easy one.   This is a no-frills, hands-on site that provides good, detailed information and access to individual assistance to help you find the right location."<p>  

DCCA's home page can be found at http://www.ilcommerce.com/.<p>

<hr>
<h3>ILLINOIS DISLOCATED WORKER PROGRAMS CONTINUE TO WIN RECOGNITION</h3>

Illinois continues to lead the way in promoting excellence in its services to dislocated workers.  Recently, six more of Illinois' 26 Service Delivery Areas (SDAs) were certified as members of the Enterprise, joining nine of their Illinois counterparts as members of this prestigious organization.  Today, nearly 58 percent of Illinois' SDAs are Enterprise members; nationally the average is only 25 percent.  The only states even close to Illinois in membership are Florida, where 48 percent of the state's organizations have won recognition, and Texas, where 34 percent of organizations are members.<p>

What is so important about Enterprise membership?  Selection to the Enterprise signals that a dislocated worker organization is dedicated to providing excellent services to its clients.  To receive membership in the Enterprise, an organization has to achieve at least an 80 percent placement rate for those enrolled in dislocated worker programs, meet or exceed the employment standard for Governor's reserve and national discretionary projects, achieve a rate of at least 75 percent on a standard customer satisfaction survey administered by an independent research firm, and demonstrate a commitment to continuous improvement in 10 quality management dimensions.<p>

Enterprise membership also is rewarding for those organizations that achieve it.  Members benefit from advanced training and assistance provided by nationally-recognized experts and their peers.  In fact, even the process of applying for membership has benefits because the organizations can get important feedback from the independent customer satisfaction survey.<p>

Illinois' leadership is nothing new.  Illinois has long been recognized as a leader in administering the Job Training Partnership Act (JTPA) program.  Between July 1, 1995 and June 30, 1996, 30,588 dislocated workers were served by Illinois' dislocated worker programs.  Of the 17,577 who completed the program, 8,623 re-entered the labor force at an average wage of $10.48 per hour.<p>  

Last year, nine Illinois organizations were named as Charter Members of the Enterprise -- more than any other state.  Equally significant, although only about 4 percent of the nation's SDAs are in Illinois, Illinois SDAs account for nearly one-tenth of the nation's Enterprise members -- a significant measure of the quality of Illinois' services.<p>

<hr>
<h3>DCCA TARGETS "ORPHAN WASTES"</h3>
<h4>by Angie Adkins, DCCA Bureau of Energy and Recycling</h4>

DCCA's Technology and Practices Demonstration Program (TPDP) has taken on the issue of so-called "orphan wastes" in Illinois.  Orphan wastes -- discarded materials other than conventional recyclables, such as aluminum and tin cans, glass bottles and jars, plastic bottles and paper -- often have the potential to be recycled, but face obstacles due to collection and processing problems.<p>  

The Bureau of Energy and Recycling recently awarded grants to the DuPage County Solid Waste Department and a Springfield paint store as part of its effort to encourage more recycling of orphan wastes.<p>

Studies have shown that construction and demolition wastes may contribute up to one-third of the wastes disposed in landfills.  At present, only clean sources of concrete and asphalt rubble from highway construction are routinely recycled as aggregate.  The DuPage County Construction and Demolition Site Recycling Project will identify quantities and types of debris generated in the construction and demolition process, and identify and implement opportunities for recycling.  <p>

DuPage County will contract for waste audits of a number of selected construction sites that volunteer to participate in the project.  Each contractor will receive the results of the audit, educational materials on methods to separate and prepare wastes for recycling, a directory of recycling service providers, and an analysis of the potential savings in waste disposal costs.  The contractors also will be surveyed at a later date to determine whether recycling activities have increased, and by what amount.<p>

The $64,488 grant will pay for subcontractor costs to conduct the waste audits and to develop educational materials for construction and demolition contractors.  Project results will be used to create two documents -- a Construction and Demolition Site Recycling Manual, and a Directory of Construction and Demolition recycling service providers in the Chicagoland area.  The USEPA has agreed to pay for costs associated with publishing the manual and directory.<p>

A $15,474 grant to Friedman's Wallpaper and Paints in Springfield will enable the firm to purchase a Mobile Earth Safe Paint Can Crusher.  Up to 90 percent of the waste collected at IEPA's household hazardous waste collection events has been leftover paint.  A mobile can crusher can promote recycling by eliminating hand scraping, paint fume inhalation, drying time and storage consideration.  <p>

Under the project, citizens may bring leftover paint cans to Friedman's or other participating drop-off locations.  The cans are placed in the mobile can crusher, which can crush up to 15 cans at a time.  Excess paints, as well as the cans, are retrieved for recycling, with the cans sent to a local recycler for further processing.<p>

Because the equipment is mobile, it can easily be transported to other Springfield-area communities for paint can recycling drives.<p>

For further information about the Technology and Practices Demonstration Program, contact Angie Adkins in DCCA's Bureau of Energy and Recycling, at 217/785-2808 (TDD users call 217/785-0211).<p>

<hr>
<h3>HENDERSON, COIL NAMED "ECONOMIC DEVELOPERS OF THE YEAR"</h3>

Two DCCA staffers were recently singled out for special awards for their efforts to promote the state's economic development.<p>

Craig Coil, Manager of DCCA's Industry Development Division, was named "Economic Developer of the Year" by the Illinois Development Council (IDC) during its fall conference held in Chicago.  Tom Henderson, who manages several DCCA programs including the Illinois Enterprise Zone Program, was selected as "Economic Developer of the Year" by the Illinois Enterprise Zone Association (IEZA) at the organization's conference, which was held in conjunction with the IDC conference.<p>

Coil, who joined DCCA in 1988, heads a staff of 18 project managers and regional representatives who work to help businesses locate, expand and prosper in Illinois.  During Fiscal Year 1996, projects undertaken by the Industry Development staff culminated in a capital investment in Illinois totaling more than $1.2 billion that will create nearly 9,000 jobs and retain more than 14,000 jobs.<p>

IDC President Lori Healey said Coil was nominated by several colleagues.  "Craig works hard and has earned the respect of his peers across the state.  We felt he demonstrated the qualities we look for in an exemplary professional in the economic development field."<p>

The IDC has presented the award annually for more than a decade.<p>

IEZA President Jeanne Gustafson said the organization unanimously chose Henderson as the first recipient of its new award.  "Tom has served as an excellent ambassador for the State of Illinois and has initiated and coordinated several partnerships between local and state levels," she said.  As examples, she cited a contract between DCCA and the IEZA for training of local enterprise zone administrators, a joint effort to place an ad in Expansion Management magazine and an Industrial Park survey. <p>   

Henderson, an small business owner who served as an internal auditor for the Illinois Department of Transportation and in numerous private banking positions before joining DCCA,  is an active member of the IEZA, the American Enterprise Zone Association, the Illinois Tax Increment Association and the IDC.<p>

