<CENTER><H2>October, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<HR>

<h3>EXPORTS ARE A VITAL COMPONENT OF ILLINOIS' ECONOMY</h3>

Exporting continues to grow in its importance to the Illinois economy.  Every dollar of exports generates four cents in state tax revenue.  Equally impressive, one in eight jobs in Illinois (and one in four manufacturing jobs) is dependent on exporting.  In  1995, more than 453,000 Illinoisans were employed in jobs sustained by direct and indirect exports.<p>

For the most part, these are both high-paying and permanent jobs.  Exporting companies tend to pay employees higher wages than plants that produce only for the domestic marketplace.  Exporting companies also tend to be larger than others; on average they are four times as large in employment and six times as large in sales.  Companies that export experience high worker productivity, estimated at 30 to 50 percent higher than in non-exporting companies.  Further, value-added per employee is up to 33 percent greater in exporting plants than in non-exporting plants, and sales per employee tend to be 50 percent greater in exporting companies than in non-exporting firms.  <p>

Export-related jobs are globally competitive and proving to be the key to the creation and retention of higher paying and permanent jobs in Illinois.  Wages for workers in the manufacturing and service exporting sectors, where Illinois products are the most competitive, substantially exceed the U.S. average.<p>

In addition, exporting companies are more innovative.  Exporters adopt new technologies far more frequently than non-exporters and report more significant benefits from doing so.  This tendency is especially strong in fabricated metal products, machinery, computers and transportation equipment -- key industrial sectors in Illinois.<p>

DCCA is serious about its efforts to help Illinois businesses expand their exporting opportunities.  With five International Trade Centers located throughout the state, two NAFTA Opportunity Centers, and foreign trade offices in Brussels, Belgium; Hong Kong; Tokyo, Japan; Mexico City, Mexico; Warsaw, Poland; and Budapest, Hungary, DCCA helps entrepreneurs and seasoned companies alike enter the export marketplace and build upon their exporting potential.<p>  

The efforts are working.  Illinois ranked fifth in the nation among the top 10 exporting states in 1995 -- the second consecutive year our state improved its ranking.  Illinois' export growth is evidenced by double-digit export increases in 1993, 1994, and 1995  (24.6 percent, 20.2 percent and 23.6 percent respectively.)  Illinois exports reached an all-time high of $32.6 billion in 1995, an increase of 23.6 percent over 1994 and nearly double the 13.8 percent increase of all U.S. exports for the same period. <p>
 
<hr>
<h3>BIDC WINS NATIONAL HONORS</h3>

As part of its 50th Anniversary celebration, the National Association of State Development Agencies (NASDA) recently created two new awards recognizing researchers' contributions to the success of state economic development programs.  The  Illinois Business and Industry Data Center (BIDC) program, administered by DCCA, won an Honorable Mention in the national competition.<p>

The Illinois Business and Industry Data Center is an innovative way to use an existing program to make it easier for small businesses, independent contractors, and entrepreneurs to access the statistical data they need to make critical business decisions.  Modeled after the U.S. Census Bureau's State Data Center and Business and Industry Data Center, the BIDC is a network of 28 local and regional affiliates, many from colleges and universities, regional planning commissions, public libraries, and small business development centers.<p>  

Local affiliates deal directly with small businesses and other end users of data.  Regional affiliates collect and disseminate information to both end users and local affiliates.  Regional affiliates also prepare quarterly regional analyses that can be distributed to businesses and development offices statewide.<p>  

The BIDC program magnifies DCCA's ability to serve the research needs of entrepreneurs and the Illinois small business community by enabling users to get information locally and tap the resources of a multitude of organizations throughout the state.<p>

NASDA selected the BIDC for recognition from 21 applicants.  In naming BIDC for the Honorable Mention, NASDA said the project demonstrated a key contribution to state economic development efforts, a unique approach to utilizing researchers as part of the economic development team, a potential for applicability in other states, support for economic development across program areas, and the ability to measure success for the research component of the activity, as well as the activity itself.<p>

<hr>
<h3>ILLINOIS COAL DEVELOPMENT BOARD AWARDS <br>
COAL RESEARCH AND DEVELOPMENT PROJECT FUNDING</h3>

Illinois continues to advance clean-coal technologies that allow for the environmentally sound, cost-effective use of our state's high-sulfur coal.  Most recently, the Illinois Coal Development Board awarded more than $3 million for the performance of 34 laboratory-scale research projects and two development-scale, clean-coal technology projects.  DCCA's Office of Coal Development and Marketing (OCDM) will issue grants for these projects which will be monitored by the Illinois Clean Coal Institute (ICCI).<p>

Research into clean-coal technologies is essential to the future of Illinois coal because without these technologies, the market for Illinois' high-sulfur coal will erode.  Most of the basic and applied research is performed at universities, private research institutions and national laboratories.  The research is divided into five categories: coal preparation (cleaning), gas cleanup, coal-related wastes (by-products) management, conversion and combustion.<p>  

Two of the recently awarded projects are development, or proof-of-concept, projects.  The first will test a coal/water slurry in cyclone boilers at the SIPCO power plant in Marion, Illinois.  This technology will help to reduce nitrogen oxide levels (NOx), as well as some sulfur dioxide (SO2) and particulate in the flue gas.  NOx and SO2 are considered by the US Environmental Protection Agency as major contributors to acid rain.  The second development project will test high-sulfur coal in a flue-gas scrubber that will remove SO2, NOx , and very fine, respirable particulate.  Both projects are highly leveraged, so the Illinois Coal Development Board receives a significant "bang for its buck."<p>

Both projects are in step with the goals of the Board, which is chaired by DCCA Director Dennis Whetstone.  The Board believes the time is now to build on existing markets and open new markets for Illinois coal, particularly since more stringent Clean Air Act emission limitations for SO2 will be enforceable in 2000 and 2005, and projected NOx-emission reductions loom on the horizon.  Illinois coal has many advantages, such as a high Btu rating, or heating value, but the high sulfur content is a clear disadvantage.  And, although many current, coal-fired, power company compliance strategies include use of clean-coal technologies, they also include switching to low-sulfur Western coal, which leads to a significant loss in Illinois coal sales contracts and related jobs.<p>  

This makes clean-coal technology research even more important.  The Board, the OCDM and the ICCI are faced with difficult decisions in determining which types of clean-coal technologies and marketing strategies to advance.  But, thanks to grants such as these, new technologies are being tested and, as technologies are advanced, more companies are projected to put them in place, thus rejuvenating the Illinois coal industry in the post-2005 period.<p>  

For more information about the funding of the research and development projects, contact Michael Purnell of DCCA's Office of Coal Development & Marketing at 217-785-0010 (TDD: 217-785-0211).<p>

<hr>   
<h3>LINCOLN FOUNDATION AWARDS PROMOTE ORGANIZATIONAL EXCELLENCE</h3>

Continuous improvement -- both in products and services -- is the key to organizational success in today's competitive global economy.  The Lincoln Foundation for Business Excellence, which is privately supported, is helping encourage Illinois organizations to undertake continuous improvement programs and quality excellence by means of self-assessment tools, best practice workshops, conferences, and the relatively new Award for Business Excellence (ABE).<p>  

Similar to the Malcolm Baldrige National Quality Award, but adapted to the needs of Illinois, the ABE focuses on seven areas deemed essential for organizational success:  leadership; information and analysis; strategic planning; human resource development and management; process management; business results; customer focus and satisfaction.  The award is accessible to both small and large organizations in industry, service, health care and education.  Starting in 1997, the Award will also be available to state and local units of government.<p>

Participation in The Lincoln Foundation program provides a number of important benefits to organizations.  First, by using the Foundation's self-assessment guidelines, organizations can assess their operations against the Foundation's criterial of excellence.  Second, by attending best practice workshops put on by the Foundation, organizations can benchmark their performance with Lincoln Award winners, who share their experience with others.  Third, should an organization decide to apply for a Lincoln Award, it will receive valuable feedback about its operations from more than 60 leading experts from corporations and academia who serve as Lincoln Award examiners and judges -- at a nominal cost to the applicant.  And finally, participation in a continuous improvement program sends a strong signal to employees, customers and competitors that an organization is committed to excellence.  <p>

The actual process for applying for the ABE is explained in an Application Guidelines Book, available from The Lincoln Foundation.  At least five examiners review each application.  A panel of trained judges reviews the examiners' findings and determines finalists, who receive site visits.  Judges then determine if there are winners; winners receive awards at a formal ceremony in December.  Throughout this process, all application information is kept strictly confidential; only the names of Award winners are ever made public.<p>  

All organizations who apply for a Lincoln Award benefit, even if they do not receive an award.  This is because each organization submitting an application receives a detailed written feedback report that assesses its strengths and identifies areas for possible improvement.<p>  

Honeywell's Micro Switch Division in Freeport, and Cash Management Services at The First National Bank of Chicago, were last year's inaugural winners of the Industry and Services Awards.  Two new sectors -- Education and Health Care -- have been added this year, and Government Sector Awards will be added in 1997.<p>

The Lincoln Foundation for Business Excellence is currently reviewing applications for the 1996 Awards, which will be announced in November.  For further information, contact The Lincoln Foundation for Business Excellence, 820 W. Jackson Boulevard, Suite #525, Chicago, IL  60607.<p>

<hr>
<h3>NEW ORGANIZATION WILL ADVOCATE FOR ILLINOIS SMALL BUSINESSES</h3>
<h4>by Joe Weiss, DCCA Small Business Division</h4>

Saying, "Small business is big business in Illinois," Gov. Jim Edgar recently joined with many of the state's leading entrepreneurs to publicly announce the formation of the Illinois Small Business 100 (ISB100), a new advocacy group designed to provide insight, direction and guidance to the Illinois small business community.<p>

Their job is an important one.  Illinois has more than 617,000 small business owners, representing a diverse range of industries and services.  In fact, 85 percent of Illinois companies employ less than 100 people and, therefore, are classified as small businesses.<p>  

The ISB100 has targeted Internet services as an important way to communicate with Illinois small businesses. DCCA is facilitating the creation of the ISB 100's home page on the Internet, which will include a statement of purpose, as well as hotlinks to ISB 100 members' E-mail addresses, chambers of commerce and trade organizations.  Plans also call for creation of an ISB 100 newsgroup on the Internet to poll members about regulatory and business issues.  In addition, the ISB 100 plans to meet annually to discuss long-term plans and programs to assist in business development.<p>
 
Members of the group were selected from nominees submitted by trade associations, professional organizations, the Illinois Small Business Development Network, the U.S. Small Business Administration, and others.<p>                                     
<hr>
<h3>CAMP ENTREPRENEUR COMES TO ILLINOIS</h3>
<h4>by Susan Nicol, Office of Women's Business Development</h4>

Encouraging young women to pursue their dreams of entrepreneurship is one of the driving forces behind Camp Entrepreneur, an award-winning residential camp held each summer at Seton Hill College in Pennsylvania.  This year, DCCA's Office of Women's Business Development, in partnership with DePaul University's Department of Management, successfully coordinated Camp Entrepreneur-Chicago in Illinois.<p> 

In recent years, the original Camp Entrepreneur has provided comprehensive exposure to the principles of business ownership to more than 100 young women graduates.  Camp Entrepreneur-Chicago was designed as a week-long commuter day camp for young women in Cook County entering their junior or senior year in high school who have expressed interest in owning their own businesses.<p>

During the week, Camp Entrepreneur-Chicago campers participated in hands-on seminars presented by local business professionals who volunteered to work with the students in areas such as marketing, financing, management and effective decision making skills, business communications and technologies, utilization of resources, and creating a professional image.<p>

A highlight of the week was a full day devoted to site visits to Chicago area businesses that are owned and operated by women. The campers benefited from the presentations and discussions from a diverse group of women business owners who shared their experiences, and offered information and insight campers will reflect upon for the rest of their lives.  Another highlight was the campers' development of their own business plans, which were presented to a panel of business experts on graduation day.  Drawing upon newly acquired inspiration, their plans reflected the cumulative knowledge and skills they gained throughout the week, as well as true entrepreneurial approaches.  The panelists were unqualifiably impressed! <p>  

Historically, young women have not been exposed to entrepreneurship as a viable career option, nor have they been introduced to business skills.  Camp Entrepreneur-Chicago graduated 16 future leaders who are now positioned to recognize that they have the ability to run their own businesses, and they are equipped with the tools necessary to visualize their own futures and to create their own opportunities.<p>

With rave reviews from this year's graduates, sponsors, staff, and Chicagoland media, the Office of Women's Business Development and DePaul University are already talking about next year's program.<p>

<hr>
<em><strong>DCCA NEWS</strong></em> is published by the Illinois Department of Commerce and Community Affairs. Dennis R. Whetstone, Director.<p>

