<CENTER><H2>July, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<HR>


<H3>WOODFORD COUNTY SHELTER <BR>WINS 1996 GOVERNOR'S CUP</H3>

The 1996 Governor's Home Town Awards are now history, and Woodford County has taken home the coveted Governor's Cup as the project most representative of the spirit of volunteerism this year in Illinois.<P>

At the 15th annual Governor's Home Town Awards banquet on June 13 in Springfield, more than 70 projects from nearly 90 communities received awards thanking them for their efforts to improve their communities and make Illinois a better place to live, work and do business.  Of those, Woodford County's project, "Heart House," was judged as the outstanding volunteer effort of the year.<P>

Four years ago, a group of concerned citizens representing various religions came together to discuss establishing a shelter for homeless people in Woodford County.  They realized that the problems of homelessness and domestic violence  exist in small towns as well as large cities.  Using donated funds, the volunteers opened Heart House in a former fraternity house located near the Eureka College campus.  But problems soon developed.  The national fraternity decided to reactivate its chapter at the college, forcing Heart House to seek new quarters.  After assessing its options, the Heart House board decided to build a new shelter.  Hundreds of volunteers, including civic groups, labor unions and school groups, donated funds and assisted with the construction of the new facility, performing tasks from painting to carpentry.  Their efforts resulted in a new shelter facility valued at more than twice its cost that provides services to its clients without any tax support.<P>

In the 15 years since its inception, the Governor's Home Town Awards program has rewarded many Illinois volunteers like those from Woodford County.  Awards are presented in categories based on population, so that projects compete against activities undertaken in communities of similar size.  Four sub-categories of awards are presented in each population category:  general awards, awards for projects for or by youths, awards for projects for or by senior citizens, and economic development awards.  First place winners in each category receive commemorative road signs and plaques noting their achievements; other winners receive plaques.  All first place winners are eligible to compete for the Governor's Cup.<P>

Judging also is done by volunteers.  This year's judges were all volunteers who had participated in projects that won awards in the 1995 Governor's Home Town Awards competition.  The judges review all applications, then make site visits to finalist communities.  Following the site visits, the judges reconvene to make their final selections and determine the winner of the Governor's Cup, a traveling silver trophy.  <P>

Applications for the 1997 Governor's Home Town Awards will be available in late fall.  For further information, contact Lou Ann Ladage at 217/785-6154 (TDD users call 800/785-6055).<P>


<HR>
<H3>JOB TRAINING LOSES AN ICON</H3>


The Illinois job training community lost an icon with the May 7 death of Samuel C. Bernstein, often called the "father" of the Illinois Unemployment Compensation Act.<P>

Bernstein was working for the Legislative Reference Bureau when he accepted a challenge from then Gov. Henry Horner to develop legislation required by the federal Social Security Act.  In 1937, Bernstein's legislation was enacted, giving Illinois an unemployment compensation law.  <P>

In subsequent years, Bernstein served in numerous state roles, including labor director and commissioner of Illinois employment security.  During the 1970s, he served as assistant to the mayor of Chicago for manpower.  He was a labor adviser to three U.S. presidents, and, until his death, was a consultant for Kane, McKenna and Associates and Target Group, Inc.  He also had been an adjunct professor at the University of Illinois - Chicago.<P>

Bernstein is survived by his wife, Dena, two daughters, one son, six grandchildren and four great-grandchildren.<P>

<HR>


<H3>COAL CALENDAR CONTEST WINNERS NAMED</H3>

About two dozen Illinois school children and their families gathered at the Executive Mansion in Springfield in April to receive their awards as winners in the eighth annual Illinois Coal Calendar Contest.<P>

"This contest was established to highlight the rich heritage and tremendous importance of Illinois coal and coal mining," said John S. Moore, chief of DCCA's Office of Coal Development and Marketing.  "Through this program, young people learn that Illinois' most abundant natural resource -- coal -- can be a safe and environmentally friendly energy source for the future."<P>

Moore joined Taylor Pensoneau, vice president of the Illinois Coal Association, in presenting the winning students with their prizes.  Each winner received a $50.00 U.S. Savings Bond and a certificate of achievement signed by Gov. Jim Edgar.  The winning posters and essays will be included in the 1997 Words and Pictures About Illinois Coal Calendar, which will be available in the fall.<P>

More than 1,200 fifth and sixth grade students from across the state entered this year's competition.  Essay winners included Katie Bochenska, Wood Dale; Kira Essmann, Earlville; Sarah Hamel, Earlville; Katie Kelly, Wheaton; Kyle Ostendorf, Savanna; Bret Owsley, LaHarpe; Shannen Painter, Lomax; Mattie Pesavento, Staunton; Anna Jo Ristow, Cissna Park; Amy Swanson, Savanna; Sarah Talkington, Minooka; and Clint Worley, Staunton.  Poster winners included Courtney Beattie, Mark; Allison Campbell, Ewing; Luke Cloud, Gillespie; Kristen Czarnecki, Wheaton; Mark Dimalanta, Lockport; Ross Frye, Shumway; Steven Isaacson, Carman; Kevin Kamien, Lockport; Leslie Kearby, LaPrairie; Laura Mahrt, Morton; Pat Naurecki, Wood Dale; Sarah Sisterson, Lockport; and Jayna Williams, Harrisburg.<P>

For more information about the contest or to order a copy of the calendar, contact DCCA's Office of Coal Development and Marketing at 217/785-0310 (TDD users call 217/785-0211.)<P>

<HR>

<H3>AMERITECH OPENS FACILITY IN RANTOUL</H3>

Gov. Jim Edgar joined Ameritech officials and workers at ceremonies marking the official opening of the company's $2 million Ameritech Cellular Services call center in Rantoul.  The center, which is expected to create approximately 200 new jobs, is located in a fully renovated facility that formerly housed a Chanute Air Force Base weather training facility.  DCCA is providing up to $210,000 in Industrial Training Program funds to assist in training workers at the center.<P>

<HR>

<H3>ILLINOIS FILM BUSINESS EXPERIENCING STRONG REBOUND</H3>
<EM>by Ron VerKuilen, Manager, Illinois Film Office</EM><P>


1996 has been a strong rebounding year for the Illinois film business!  January started off with a bang (literally!) when director and native son Andy Davis ("The Fugitive," "The Package," "Code of Silence," Above the Law") returned to Illinois to film "Chain Reaction" starring Keanu Reeves and Morgan Freeman.  The film opens in late August and features Chicago, Argonne National Laboratory and Barrington Hills.  Chicago also doubles for Washington D.C. (see if you can spot the Field Museum or the Museum of Science and Industry!)<P>

In March and April, two television series -- "EZ Streets" and "Early Edition" -- were shot here.  Scenes were shot for a new series produced by Chris Columbus ("Home Alone", "Only the Lonely" director), as well as for "ER" and "Chicago Hope," which regularly return to film scenes.<P>

A sizeable chunk of the movie "Michael," starring John Travolta, Andie MacDowell and William Hurt is being filmed in Illinois.  The latter two play tabloid journalists in search of the archangel Michael, played by Travolta.  Also this spring, the adaptation of the John Grisham novel, "The Chamber," has filmed in Chicago with local actor Chris O'Donnell and Gene Hackman.   In addition to these high-profile stars, Larenz Tate and Nia Long star in an independent film, "Love Jones," directed by Chicagoan Ted Wicher.<P>

During the summer, filming will begin on "My Best Friend's Wedding," starring Julia Roberts, Dermott Mulroney and Carmen Diaz; "Gangsters," set in 1930s Harlem, directed by Bill Duke and starring Lawrence Fishburne; and the Miramax feature, "Stepping in the Dog Water," directed by and starring David Schwimmer of "Friends."<P>

That's not all!  John Hughes Productions, in conjunction with Universal Pictures, will be filming a small town movie in Illinois called "Reach the Rock."  Robert Altman will direct a feature film, "The Wild Card," for MGM Studios that stars Woody Harrelson.  Scouting is underway for a feature film, "The Good Guys," starring Don Johnson as a con man who joins the FBI to expose the mob!<P>

Meanwhile, the Film Office staff is working with a number of projects that have a distinct possibility of filming in Illinois.  We take the calls, make the scouts, pass on information, and plead Illinois' case with crews, talent, labor, hotel managers, etc. to welcome the film and television business to Illinois.  This, along with a full plate of steady business with local independent filmmakers, commercial makers, documentary films, educational films, music videos and other projects, keeps the Illinois Film Office hopping!<P>

The film business is cyclical.  Local labor has made adjustments to appeal to Hollywood.  Market forces seem to be smiling on Illinois right now.  And luck always plays a part.  But the Illinois Film Office continues to work hard to attract the film dollar to Illinois.  We're having fun!  The nights and weekends get a bit full at times, but it's worth it to have the film business back strong in Illinois.  <P>

<HR>

<H3>STUDENTS WIN ILEED YOUTH AWARDS </H3>


DCCA Director Dennis Whetstone presented a plaque to teachers Terry Bachenheimer and Dawn Drost and their students from Hunting Ridge Elementary and Energy Club in Palatine during the ILEED Youth Awards for Energy Achievement Program luncheon in Springfield.  More than 250 students and teachers from 60 Illinois schools received recognition this year for their outstanding efforts toward furthering energy and environmental education.  Of the 25 schools that won special State Awards, four advanced to the National Youth Awards program for Energy Achievement held in Washington D.C.  Hunting Ridge advanced to the national program for its project studying wetlands and the effects of tampering with the environment. <P>

ILEED (Illinois Energy Eduction Development) is an energy/environmental education program designed to teach and motivate students to learn more about energy and environmental concerns through school and community projects.<P>

<HR>

<H3>DCCA GRANTS HELP IMPROVE ACCESSIBILITY TO PUBLIC SERVICES</H3>
<EM>by Amy Zachary, Bureau of Community Development</EM><P>


Passage of the Americans with Disabilities Act (ADA) was a giant step forward in raising public awareness of the needs of those with disabilities.  But for many small governments, the cost to remodel and retrofit public buildings can be prohibitive.  The Community Development Assistance Program (CDAP) Removal of Architectural Barriers component can make such improvements affordable.<P>

Each year, DCCA solicits CDAP applications from local units of government -- cities, villages, townships and counties -- in communities with populations of 50,000 or less that are not located within one of the seven urban counties that receive their funds directly from the federal government.  Removal of Architectural Barriers grants of up to $150,000 are available annually to assist local governments in paying for efforts to remove physical barriers that restrict accessibility to basic and essential local government services.  For example, a local unit of government might undertake ramp construction, restroom renovation, elevator or chairlift installation, or designate parking for those with disabilities.  The grants are awarded on a competitive basis, with projects such as improvements to courthouses; city, village or town halls; municipal centers; local government annex buildings; libraries and health departments given top priority.<P>

Since the program began in 1993, 162 units of local government have shared $7 million in CDAP grant funds.  An example is Effingham County, which submitted an application on behalf of projects in the county courthouse, county building, and health department, as well as projects in Mound Township, Douglas Township, the Village of Beecher City, the Town of Mason, the City of Altamont and the Village of Watson.  Effingham County received a $48,000 CDAP grant, which it leveraged with nearly $625,000 in local funds to undertake various improvements, including parking, door hardware, signage, door openers and buzzers, audible/visual alarms, grab bars, restroom renovation, new controls on drinking fountains, and audible controls and tactile instructions for an elevator.<P>

Thirty-three communities have submitted applications for $1 million in CDAP Removal of Architectural Barriers grants this year.  DCCA expects to award the grants later this summer.<P>

<HR>

