<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#8080C0" ALINK="#004080">

<HR>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="/dcca/graph/dnews.gif" WIDTH=414 HEIGHT=127></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>April, 1996</H2></CENTER>
<HR>

<h3>REVOLVING LOAN FUNDS KEEP COMMUNITIES GROWING</h3>
<h4>By Jay Bales, DCCA Bureau of Community Development</h4>

Over the past 14 years, DCCA has awarded $83 million in Community Development Assistance Program (CDAP) grants to 177 local units of government throughout the state to help them provide low-interest loans to businesses locating or expanding within their boundaries.  Approximately $50 million of those funds are already back in circulation, helping more than 1,600 businesses obtain the capital they need to start or expand operations in the communities.  And that's just the beginning.  As those loans are repaid, their dollars also will be used for future business opportunities.<p>

It's all thanks to Revolving Loan Funds, administered by local communities, that are capitalized with moneys repaid by businesses that received the original loans funded through CDAP economic development component grants.<p>

Here's how it works:  DCCA receives Community Development Block Grant funds from the U.S. Department of Housing and Urban Development (HUD).  The funds are used to provide a variety of grants to units of local government in communities with populations under 50,000 that are not located within one of the seven urban counties that receive funds directly from HUD.  CDAP grants range from public facilities grants, that help small communities meet their water and sewer needs, to economic development grants, that help communities attract and retain businesses and their jobs.<p>

When DCCA awards a CDAP economic development grant to a community, the community may use the funds to make infrastructure improvements needed by a business, such as extending water and sewer lines or access roads.  Or it may choose to use the grant funds to provide a low-interest loan to the business.  If a loan is made, the community creates a locally-administered Revolving Loan Fund, which is capitalized by the loan repayment funds.  These Revolving Loan Funds, or RLFs, provide a valuable source of business capital for future business development.<p>

There are many RLF success stories across the state.  For example, the City of Saint Elmo received a $375,000 CDAP economic development grant in 1982.  Since then, the city has made 33 loans totaling $601,811 with a minimal amount of defaults.  The City of Lacon has received two CDAP grants in the amount of $174,180.  From the "recaptured" funds it has made 20 loans totaling $184,172.68.  These "second generation" loans have resulted in 120 jobs being created or retained!<p>

A local government does not have to receive a large CDAP grant to have an effective RLF.  The City of Athens received a $40,000 CDAP grant in 1985.  In the decade since, the city has made six loans totaling $78,300 -- nearly twice the amount of the original CDAP grant.<p>

While most RLFs do not make large loans, their contributions often are an integral part of a business' overall financing package, leveraging larger amounts of private sector dollars.  In particular, CDAP RLF dollars can be an important source of "gap financing" for small, rural businesses.<p>

For more information on CDAP RLFs, or to learn which communities have an active RLF, contact Jay Bales at 217/785-6181 (TDD users call 800/785-6055).<p>

<h4 align=center>###</h4>

<hr>
<h3>FROM THE DIRECTOR.....</h3>

A few weeks ago, Gov. Jim Edgar recommended a $774.6 million budget for DCCA for fiscal year 1997.  I'd like to tell you a little about that budget request and what it means for DCCA's customers.<p>

First, it's important to note that the bulk of our budget request -- $600.4 million -- is federal funds.  Those funds are essential to the training of our workers, the infrastructure of our communities, and the well-being of our citizens.  We're asking for $237.2 million for JTPA for next year as we continue to open new One-Stop Career Centers, and $376.7 million for community development programs like CDAP, LIHEAP, IHWAP and CSBG that help build our infrastructure, attract and retain businesses, and help improve the quality of life for low-income citizens.<p>

We're also asking for $40.2 million in state general revenue funds.   This includes $15 million for the Industrial Training Program (ITP) -- a $2.75 million increase that would enable DCCA to help upgrade the skills of nearly 5,000 more workers from 350 additional Illinois companies.<p>

We're looking at $39.2 million in funds for our business development programs.  Illinois has been very successful in recent years in attracting and retaining businesses and their jobs -- Motorola and McDonald's, for example, have announced projects that will create thousands of new Illinois jobs over the coming years.  But the fact is, Illinois is competing against other states every time a business looks to locate or expand.  We need to have the tools to win that competition.   This budget will enable DCCA to enhance its working relationships with local economic developers and improve our ability to respond to business inquiries.<p>

Our export potential is great.  We're asking for $3.5 million to promote exporting of Illinois' goods and services in the global marketplace.  Illinois is a leader in technology development.  We're asking for an additional $200,000 to help us continue our efforts to transfer these technologies to the workplace to help our businesses expand and modernize to meet the global challenge.<p>

Tourism, one of the fastest-growing industries, will continue to prosper under the $33.4 million budget we've outlined.  These funds will enable us to continue our successful tourism advertising campaign, "Illinois -- A Million Miles from Monday," as well as grant programs to help our communities promote tourism opportunities.<p>

We're working to promote the efficient and environmentally-safe use of Illinois' energy resources, and have allocated $13.6 million to that end.  Another $17.8 million is earmarked for projects designed to utilize and develop new markets for one of Illinois' greatest resources -- coal.<p>

Over the coming weeks, the General Assembly will be considering the Governor's budget request.  It is my hope that you will take a few moments to consider the importance of DCCA's programs and services to your businesses, jobs and communities.  We welcome your support as we work to secure the resources we need to make Illinois the best place to live, work and do business.<p>

<h4 align=center>###</h4>

<hr>
<h3>FIRST-STOP MAKES GOVERNMENT ACCESSIBLE TO BUSINESS</h3>

Illinois has a new and exciting service to help entrepreneurs and business owners access the state regulatory and assistance information they need to achieve success.  It's DCCA's First-Stop Business Information Center, working to improve Illinois' business climate by making it easier for entrepreneurs to comply with state business requirements.<p>

First-Stop, established in 1994 under the Business Assistance and Regulatory Reform Act, includes a number of services and products designed to meet the needs of new and existing businesses.  For example, First-Stop offers the Directory of Business Requirements and Assistance Programs to help new and existing businesses determine the regulations and services applicable to their business activity.  The Directory is a comprehensive resource with nearly 500 profiles from more than 40 state agencies that document virtually every business license, permit, certificate and registration required by the State of Illinois, as well as the various state assistance programs available to help businesses. <p>

First-Stop also offers Starting a Business In Illinois, a comprehensive handbook for those looking to start and do business in Illinois.  The handbook includes general local, state and federal business requirements, a feasibility checklist and a business plan outline. <p>

In the coming months, First-Stop will be improving and expanding its services. "Business Bios," which will give specific, detailed regulatory information for virtually every industry, are currently being updated and expanded.  Also in the works is a comprehensive database, which will inventory business licenses, permits, certificates and registrations required by the State of Illinois.  In addition, First-Stop, with the help of business owners, associations and state agencies, will embark on a new path to search out and identify existing state laws that are burdensome, duplicative or onerous.<p>

First-Stop's effectiveness lies not only in its ability to give start-up and regulatory information to Illinois' businesses, but also in its connections to other business assistance centers.  Local assistance for new or existing businesses is available through the Business and Industry Data Center (BIDC) and the Illinois Small Business Development Center Network (ISBDCN).  The BIDC works to enhance the ability of small business people to plan, market, manage and expand their businesses by providing them with access to statistical data and other sources of practical information. The ISBDCN seeks to increase the competitiveness, profitability and growth of Illinois businesses in a global market through Small Business Development Centers, Procurement Technical Assistance Centers, International Trade Centers, and NAFTA Opportunity Centers.<p>

First-Stop's Directory of Business Requirements and Assistance Programs and Starting a Business in Illinois are available through the World Wide Web (http://ww.accessil.com/dcca/) or the Access Illinois electronic bulletin board (217/787-6255, settings ANSI, 8, N, 1).  Clients also may receive this information free of charge by contacting the First-Stop Business Information Center directly at 800/252-2923 (TDD users call 800/785-6055).<p>

<h4 align=center>###</h4>

<hr>
<h3>ITP HELPS SUPPLIERS IMPROVE QUALITY, PRODUCTIVITY</h3>

"We have to team in excellence to prevail."  Those were the words of Hans Becherer, Chairman and CEO of Deere & Company, commenting on the firm's latest effort to help its Illinois suppliers improve their quality and productivity, in turn helping Deere maintain and improve its own competitiveness in the global economy.<p>

A driving force behind this partnership is Illinois' Industrial Training Program (ITP), administered by the Department of Commerce and Community Affairs (DCCA).  Gov. Jim Edgar recently participated in ceremonies awarding a $574,709 ITP grant to Deere to assist the company in providing training to 4,065 workers from 136 Illinois Deere suppliers.<p>

In its early days, ITP provided state-funded grants to manufacturers like Deere to help them train new employees and upgrade the skills of current workers.  But it became increasingly apparent that a training void existed for small and medium-sized manufacturers.  Thanks to changes in the program enacted in 1992, ITP now provides grants to trade organizations, company consortia, and community colleges, as well as original equipment manufacturers that use the funds to offer training opportunities to workers from their Illinois suppliers.  Deere, for example, has received more than $2.2 million in ITP funds since fiscal year 1993, which it has used to help train nearly 14,000 workers from its Illinois supplier companies.<p>

The program has been a great success.  Everett "Bud" Pierce, President of McLaughlin Body Company in Moline, a Deere supplier that has participated in the training program since 1993, said, "Training is more important than at any time in our careers.  As suppliers, we need to reduce costs and improve productivity.   The fact that we as suppliers can find training that enables us to better service our customers makes the program very valuable."<p>

Jerry Norquist, Manager of Safety and Training for Rockford Products Corp. of Rockford, another Deere supplier, agreed.  "Feedback we're receiving from our customers throughout their quality audits confirms that progress is definitely being made in that direction.  Our quality costs and delivery measures are showing significant improvement trends.  We're gaining market shares.  The education and training made available to our workforce through this program is a major contributor to our organizational development."<p>

ITP grants provide up to 50 percent of the cost of training efforts.  The remaining costs are leveraged with private investment.  Deere provides five categories of training to its suppliers:  supply management, financial; operations improvements; skilled-based; and employee development.<p>

Diana Bump, Education and Training Facilitator, from Reliable Power Products, Franklin Park, said ITP training provided through Deere allowed her company to maximize its training dollars and include more employees.  "During our first year of involvement with this training program, 141 employees participated in 26 different classes.  Benefits of the program that have already been realized and measured are improved customer satisfaction, with shipment compliance improving from 91.4 percent to 97.2 percent.  Job instruction time has been reduced by one-third.  Computer efficiency has improved by 30 percent as a result of the computer skills class, with stress levels being reduced about 70 percent.  In one product area, cycle time has been reduced by 30 percent and our work in process inventories have been reduced by 50 percent overall."<p>

Gov. Edgar said ITP is an important part of the state's effort to ensure job opportunities for its people by helping Illinois businesses improve their competitiveness in the global marketplace.  "It's particularly crucial that we assist small and medium-sized businesses, because that's where most of the job growth will be as we move into the 21st Century.  It's critical to Deere that they have businesses that supply them with the highest quality work products, and important to us in Illinois that our small and medium-sized businesses are able to improve their productivity.  These training dollars will help these suppliers do business with other international companies around the world."<p>

Becherer commended the Governor and the state for having the foresight and the wisdom to stand behind the Industrial Training Program.  "When there is something like this program that provides both an incentive for us and our suppliers to work together on programs to enhance capabilities of suppliers, it provides another competitive edge that is needed in the very competitive markets in which we operate today worldwide."<p>

<h4 align=center>###</h4>

<hr>
<h3>
"CROSSING INTERNATIONAL BORDERS" CONFERENCE<br> 
FEATURES TIPS ON EFFECTIVE EXPORTING
</h3>

Exporters and companies interested in exploring the global marketplace can get valuable tips to help them achieve success at this year's "Crossing International Borders" Conference, to be held at the Chicago Hilton and Towers on May 16.<p>

The conference is co-sponsored by DCCA's International Business Division and Arthur Andersen.  Registration is $95 per person through May 9 or $125 per person following that date.  For conference information or registration, contact Arthur Andersen at 312/507-9664 or Mary Anne Brown-Rogerio at DCCA at 312/814-2325 (TDD 312/419-0667).<p>

<h4 align=center>###</h4>

<hr>
<h3>SCRAP TIRES PROMOTE RECYCLING; PROVIDE SAFER PLAYGROUNDS</h3>

Every year, more than 12 million old tires are scrapped in Illinois, creating a breeding site for disease-carrying mosquitoes, providing a potential fire hazard with the possibility for dense fumes of toxic smoke, and filling up valuable landfill space.  DCCA's Bureau of Energy and Recycling is working to encourage recycling of those old tires in ways that can end the hazards while providing useful products.<p>

One very successful effort is a program that utilizes chips made from recycled scrap tires as a loose playground cover.  The tire chips provide a safer playground surface  because their rubber content has a shock-absorbing quality.  They also help keep maintenance costs down.  Tire chips allow for fast drainage, last for years without rotting or decaying, plus they retard weed growth, reduce dust and mud, are clean and non-toxic, do not produce leachate, and do not attract animals or insects.<p> 

This year, the Used Tire Recovery Program provided $260,000 in grants to 106 public and private schools, day care facilities and park districts to help them purchase the scrap tire playground surfacing material.  Grants of up to $3,600 were provided, with grant recipients required to match at least 40 percent.  Grant funds are generated by a state surcharge on the retail purchase of new automotive tires in Illinois.  The funded projects will use more than six million pounds of scrap tire chips, which equates to recycling more than 300,000 automotive tires.<p>

<h4 align=center>###</h4>

<hr>
<h3>ILLINOIS TOURISM GOES ON-LINE</h3>

Wouldn't it be convenient if you could instantly access information on almost any Illinois tourism destination?  Wouldn't it be ideal to browse through this information any time of the day or night, any day of the week, from the comfort of your home? <p> 

Well, it's possible.  Thanks to the Internet and your computer, potential Illinois travelers can get the information they need conveniently and quickly.<p>

DCCA's Illinois Bureau of Tourism, working closely with Foote, Cone and Belding advertising agency, has developed a new site on the World Wide Web that can help consumers learn about events, sites and activities, lodging, restaurants, sports, weather forecasts, what's on tap at theaters and museums, and just about anything else needed to plan a weekend getaway or a complete vacation.<p>

The tourism database is user-friendly and can be reached from two locations.  At the heart of the new site, accessible by clicking on the Illinois Tourism button on DCCA's home page (http://www.accessil.com/dcca/) or clicking directly to the Illinois Tourism homepage (http://www.enjoyillinois.com), is the Trip Planner.  It includes detailed trip planning information on food, shopping, golf, lodging, special events, outdoor recreation, packaged discounts, etc.  The information in this section is created through tourism's Illinois Travel Counseling System's toll-free hotline database (1-800-2-CONNECT).  The data will frequently be downloaded into the website, ensuring detailed, current travel information.<p>

There's also a What's New section to inform users of upcoming content; Inside Insights, providing first-hand suggestions from real people who have explored and traveled in Illinois; Maps, which includes maps of Illinois regions, biking and hiking trails and special interest maps; Front Lines, with up-to-the-minute data on weather, sports and theater; and a sophisticated Search Engine to easily sort through it all.<p>

No longer will potential travelers have to make separate calls to get information on golf courses and hotels, Cubs schedules, or whatever other activities they might choose.  One visit to the Illinois Tourism website will connect these travelers with all of the answers, enabling them to customize their vacation plans in Illinois.<p>

Future plans also call for development of special contests, meetings and convention information, and the opportunity to purchase Illinois merchandise through tourism's retail outlet, Illinois Marketplace, located at Chicago's Navy Pier.<p>

Obviously, offering these benefits through the Internet is a great convenience to travelers.  But it also is an important tool for the state.  In addition to bringing consumers closer to the information they need to travel in Illinois, the Internet helps Illinois develop a relationship with consumers and generate a customer database by gathering E-mail addresses.<p>

Tourism is big business in Illinois.  In 1994, travelers spent nearly $16 billion in Illinois, contributing more than $995 million in state and local taxes, $1.7 billion in federal taxes, and generating more than 241,000 jobs with a payroll of $4.8 billion.  The Internet can help make travel in Illinois even more convenient and accessible, and help this important industry continue to grow.<p>

<h4 align=center>### </h4>

