<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>DCCA: 1995 Annual Report -- Bureau of Business Development</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#0080C0" ALINK="#0080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/logosm.jpg" alt="DCCA Logo" width=165 height=82 align=left>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<h3>
Department of Commerce & Community Affairs<p>
</h3>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<FONT SIZE=+3>1995 Annual Report: Bureau of Business Development</FONT>
<BR CLEAR=RIGHT>
<HR>
<BODY>
<p>

In Fiscal Year 1995, DCCA's Bureau of Business Development continued its efforts to position Illinois as the location of choice for businesses looking to locate or expand, and to help smaller businesses achieve success.<p>

Late in the fiscal year, DCCA began work toward launching a Fiscal Year 1996 marketing effort built around the theme, "Illinois -- a great place for business keeps getting better."  The marketing effort included a special supplement to Area Development magazine, planning for a special advertising supplement in Business Week magazine, and advertising in magazines and Midwest newspapers, including Crain's Chicago Business, the Chicago Tribune, and the Wall Street Journal.  It was designed to highlight the Fiscal Year 1995 passage of tort reform legislation that made Illinois a more attractive location.  The reforms, enacted by the General Assembly and signed by Gov. Jim Edgar, abolished the antiquated Structural Work Act that was duplicative of workers' compensation.  They also abolished the doctrine of joint and several liability and reformed product liability litigation, capped punitive damages, limited non-economic damages and made other significant changes to underline Illinois' image as a business-friendly state.<p>  

<strong>
<a href="#Industry Development">Division of Industry Development</a><br>
<a href="#Small Business">Small Business Division</a><br>
<a href="#SBDC">Illinois Small Business Development Center Network</a><br>
<a href="#Women">Office of Women's Business Development</a><br>
<a href="#Minority">Office of Minority Business Development</a><br>
<a href="#First Stop">First Stop Business Information Center</a><br>
<a href="#AI">Access Illinois</a><br>
<a href="#Industrial">Industrial Services Division</a><br>
<a href="#Loan">Loan Administration Division</a><br>
<a href="#International">International Business Division</a><p>
</strong>

<a name="Industry Development"><hr></a>
<h3>Division of Industry Development</h3>

DCCA's Division of Industry Development is the agency's central source of economic development information and assistance for businesses and local economic development organizations.  Division staffers work to provide direct and technical assistance to companies wishing to locate or expand in Illinois.<p>

In Fiscal Year 1995, Industry Development recorded many important successes.  Among the projects:<p>

<ul type=square>
<li> DeMert & Dougherty, Inc. broke ground for a 100,000 square-foot, $5 million expansion of its Coal City Manufacturing Center, nearly doubling the size of the plant, retaining 152 jobs and creating 75 new jobs within two years.<p>
<li> Motorola, Inc. announced plans to build a $10 million cellular telephone distribution facility in McHenry, creating 300 jobs.  The 217,000 square-foot facility will be an extension of the company's 3,000-employee, $100 million plant under construction in Harvard.<p>
<li> Independence Tube Corp. announced plans for a 200,000 square-foot expansion of its Marseilles plant, creating 42 new jobs with the potential for 100 new employees.<p>
<li> SMF, Inc. purchased and remodeled the former Hyster facility in Danville.  The company, which manufactures metal fabricated components, will create as many as 50 new jobs.<p>
<li> Simonton Building Products, Inc., a West Virginia manufacturer of windows and doors, chose Paris for its expansion, which will employ 300 workers within 18 months of opening.<p>
<li> Maytag Corporation decided to invest $160 million to upgrade manufacturing processes and equipment at its Galesburg plant.  The project will retain approximately 2,300 jobs and bring the corporation's refrigerator products line into compliance with future federal environmental standards.<p>
<li> Knapheide announced plans to build an $18.6 million manufacturing plant in Quincy, retaining 400 jobs.  The new plant will replace assembly and warehouse operations lost in the Great Flood of 1993.<p>
<li> National Steel Corporation chose to undertake a $67 million expansion and modernization of its Granite City Steel Division.  The project, which will add a new coating line at the plant, will create 40 new jobs and retain 350 jobs.
<li> C. J. Vitner Company announced a $3.65 million expansion of its Freeport snack foods plant, which is expected to result in 80 new jobs.<p>
<li> U. S. Robotics decided to invest more than $15 million to expand its operations in Morton Grove, creating more than 500 new jobs within three years.<p>
<li> Honeywell's Micro Switch Division announced plans to invest $30 million in its Freeport operation, adding additional manufacturing space and solidifying the jobs of 3,000 workers.<p>
<li> Cotter & Co. decided to keep the company's headquarters in Chicago, retaining 750 jobs.  The member-owned cooperative of more than 6,000 True Value hardware stores is the world's largest distributor of hardware and related products entirely owned by retailer-members.<p>
<li> Roberson Transportation Company decided to consolidate company operations at a new general headquarters in Mahomet.  The $3 million project will retain 180 jobs in Central Illinois and is expected to create up to 100 new administrative and operational positions over the coming five years.<p>
<li> The U.S. Postal Service announced plans for a new $1.2 million regional remote encoding center in Peoria, which will create up to 800 jobs, including 225 full-time jobs, and have an annual economic impact of nearly $19 million.<p>
<li> PMP Fermentation Products, Inc. broke ground for a $45 million expansion of its Peoria facility.  The 60,000 square-foot expansion of the food additive plant is expected to create 30 new jobs.<p>
<li> J. D. Cahill Co., Inc. announced plans to open a manufacturing facility in Centralia, creating 30 new jobs within the first year of operation.  The New Hampshire-based company will manufacture paperboard at the plant for use in high-quality prepared food cartons.<p> 
</ul>


<a name="Small Business"><hr></a>
<h3>Small Business Division</h3>

DCCA's Small Business Division, a part of the Illinois Small Business Development Center Network (ISBDCN), provides focused assistance to small and medium-sized Illinois businesses.  Through the ISBDCN, which functions in partnership with the U.S. Small Business Administration, companies receive technical and management assistance to help them achieve success.<p>

Among services of the Small Business Division are:<p>

<ul type=square>
<li> Regulatory Flexibility Program, which reviews proposed rules affecting small businesses, including in-depth analyses into their impact on Illinois small businesses.<p>
<li> Illinois Business Energy and Environmental Technology Program, which provides information and referral assistance to firms looking to improve their profitability through efficiencies in their energy systems, as well as by reducing wastes in their production processes.  During Fiscal Year 1995, a clearinghouse of information was created containing more than 1,000 sources of assistance.  Information or assistance was provided to 1,100 businesses.  Program staff also co-sponsored the first Illinois Energy and Environmental Expo, slated to become an annual event.<p>
<li> Small Business Environmental Assistance Program, created in Fiscal Year 1995.  This program, federally mandated under the Clean Air Act Amendments of 1990, provides assistance to Illinois small businesses through a toll-free help line, an Environmental Clearinghouse containing 250 documents, an Environmental Services Directory of 272 firms with environmental expertise, and sponsorship of educational seminars.  The program provided 1,053 small businesses with compliance assistance and information during Fiscal Year 1995.<p>  
</ul>


<a name="SBDC"><hr></a>
<h3>Illinois Small Business Development Center Network</h3>

The Network is comprised of 40 Small Business Development Center (SBDC) locations, including:<p>

<ul type=square>
<li> Small Business Development Centers, which provide businesses with management, marketing and financial counseling.<p>
<li> Procurement Technical Assistance Centers, which assist existing businesses in contracting with state, federal and local governments by offering general procurement counseling and other services.<p>
<li> International Trade Centers (ITCs) at five locations around the state, including two NAFTA Opportunity Centers (NOCs).  The ITCs provide business owners with professional advice and resources to prepare them to enter the global marketplace.  The NAFTA Opportunity Centers offer specialized assistance to companies entering the Mexican and Canadian marketplaces.<p>  
<li> Small Business Innovative Research Center, which provides counseling, training and technical assistance to technology-oriented entrepreneurs to enhance their ability to compete for federal research and development awards.<p>
<li> Small Business Incubators, which provide businesses in the early stages of development with shared resources to help them achieve success.<p>
</ul>


In Fiscal Year 1995, the ISBDCN counseled 9,348 companies and assisted in the management training of 10,177 individuals, resulting in the creation of 1,534 new jobs, retention of 1,721 jobs, start-up of 379 new businesses, 219 business expansions and securing of more than $52.3 million in business financing.  The 15 Procurement Technical Assistance Centers conducted 7,643 counseling sessions, helping their clients obtain 2,656 government contracts totaling $164.4 million, create 330 new jobs and retain 1,709 jobs.  The ITCs and NOCs provided individual exporting advice and training to more than 1,700 small businesses entering the export marketplace.<p>

The ISBDCN played an important role during Fiscal Year 1995 in supporting the White House Conference on Small Business, held in Washington D.C. in June 1995.  The conference, which offered small business people an opportunity to voice their concerns and ideas for improving the strength of the nation's small business climate, was attended by a 67-member delegation from Illinois, which included 44 delegates elected at Illinois conferences held in August 1994 and April 1995, as well as 23 delegates appointed by Gov. Edgar and members of the Illinois Congressional Delegation.<p>

Another major effort undertaken by the ISBDCN in Fiscal Year 1995 was a partnership with the QVC television shopping network.  Working with QVC's national campaign to showcase products from each of the 50 states, the ISBDCN and DCCA's Illinois Bureau of Tourism organized a statewide competition to identify local and regional products to be featured on a special QVC program focusing on Illinois.  Nearly 500 Illinois vendors took part in the competition that resulted in selection of 20 products and five alternates to be featured on the nationally-televised program.<p>   


<a name="Women"><hr></a>
<h3>Office of Women's Business Development</h3>

The Office of Women's Business Development sponsors and implements a wide range of programs for women business owners active in domestic and international markets.  Staffed by the Illinois Women's Business Advocate and the Women's Business Liaison, the office promotes greater understanding of the women's business community, with special emphasis on minority women's business issues and development of a comprehensive database on women business owners.  The Office works with individual companies, corporations and professional associations to help women entrepreneurs tackle the wide range of challenges they may encounter in their businesses.  The Office serves as a conduit to business resources throughout the state, providing information, referral and procurement assistance for women business owners in Illinois.  It also provides administrative support to the Illinois Women's Business Ownership Council.<p>


<a name="Minority"><hr></a>
<h3>Office of Minority Business Development</h3>

The Office of Minority Business Development works to enhance the impact of minority business entrepreneurs by promoting greater understanding of business issues affecting minority businesses.  The Office is staffed by two minority business advocates, including a bilingual liaison to the Hispanic business community.  These advocates work closely with local minority business councils, as well as through a statewide mentoring program implemented through the Illinois Small Business Development Center Network.<p>


<a name="First Stop"><hr></a>
<h3>First-Stop Business Information Center of Illinois</h3>

Development of the ambitious First-Stop Business Information Center of Illinois continued in Fiscal Year 1995.  The Center is being designed as a statewide program to enhance the state's business climate by making it easier for Illinois businesses to deal with state requirements.  The Center will provide businesses with easy access to the information and services they require to be more competitive, including information on permitting, licensing and regulatory procedures, as well as links to other resources.  Besides providing access to trained information specialists, the Center will provide information through hard-copy booklets, computerized services on the Access Illinois bulletin board and the World Wide Web, and a toll-free telephone service.<p>  


<a name="AI"><hr></a>
<h3>Access Illinois</h3>

During Fiscal Year 1995, DCCA continued its efforts to make its products and services more accessible through communications technology.  As a charter subscriber to the Access Illinois computerized bulletin board, DCCA made its information available to any consumer with a telephone, computer, communications software and a modem.  Among services available on-line:  loan applications, calendars of events, international trade leads, general information on programs and services, a database of Illinois community profiles, and the ability to download or order hard-copies of many DCCA publications.  Access Illinois also includes a number of issue-related forums that allow the exchange of ideas, as well as electronic mail access to the Internet.  DCCA also began working with Access Illinois during Fiscal Year 1995 toward the Fiscal Year 1996 launch of an agency Home Page on the World Wide Web.<p>


<a name="Industrial"><hr></a>
<h3>Industrial Services Division</h3>

The Industrial Services Division assists Illinois businesses by performing on-site safety and health consultations that help firms identify and correct health and safety hazards in the workplace.  In Fiscal Year 1995, the Division completed more than 735 consultations, responded to 4,700 calls for technical assistance, and trained more than 2,700 employers and employees on workplace safety and health.<p>  

In conjunction with the Office of the Governor and the private sector, the Industrial Services Division worked during Fiscal Year 1995 to help coordinate efforts of Project Safe Illinois, an outreach program directed toward the Illinois business community. The goal of Project Safe is to make employers aware of the benefits of workplace safety and health.  Plans were begun to establish a strategy for a 1996 Safety and Health Conference that will offer exhibits and training workshops of interest to the businesses of Illinois.<p>

The Division also has expanded its education and training section to reach out to additional industries with information on safety and health management, confined space entry, chemical exposure, ergonomics, machinery guarding, blood-borne pathogens, tuberculosis and many other related subjects of concern to Illinois industries.<p>  

The Division will continue to provide information and assistance on new regulations and workplace hazards to those industries that request, primarily concentrating on the Illinois small business community.<p>


<a name="Loan"><hr></a>
<h3>Loan Administration Division</h3>

DCCA's Loan Administration Division consolidates all agency business loan programs in one place, lessening confusion for loan applicants.  Division staffers also provide fiscal analyses for many of DCCA's grant programs.  During Fiscal Year 1995, the Division analyzed 105 applications totaling $36.8 million.  Included among the applications were 16 Community Development Assistance Program (CDAP) applications totaling $9.5 million, seven Business Development Public Infrastructure applications totaling $3.1 million, 61 applications for assistance through the Industrial Training Program (ITP) totaling $19.75 million, and 19 applications for assistance through the Small Business Development Program/Participation Loan Program totaling $4.26 million.<p>

Primarily, the Division focuses its efforts on management of the Participation Loan Program that provides assistance to Illinois small businesses through participation in loans made through financial intermediaries.  During Fiscal Year 1995, 13 Participation Loans were funded totaling $2.9 million.  The projects resulted in the creation and retention of more than 1,458 jobs and stimulated private sector investment of approximately $15.3 million.<p>

The Division also administers the Community Development Corporation Program through establishing bank-driven Community Development Corporations (CDCs).  These CDCs enable DCCA to provide matching-grant funding to help finance the establishment of initial lending pools.  DCCA is committed to the continued establishment of CDCs and makes financial assistance available to them through participation in their loans to qualified local businesses when that funding demonstrates a positive impact on the competitiveness of the firms and the number of jobs they create.  In Fiscal Year 1995, four new CDCs were formed with DCCA's assistance, bringing the total number of CDCs operating in Illinois to 39.  DCCA made 10 grants to CDCs totaling $583,000.  CDCs capitalized by DCCA financed 16 projects utilizing $294,000 in DCCA funds.  These loans stimulated private sector investment of approximately $8.2 million and resulted in the creation of 311 jobs and retention of 169 jobs. <p> 

During Fiscal Year 1995, the Division initiated the Contractor Bond Guaranty Program designed to assist small and disadvantaged Illinois contractors and subcontractors to obtain bid, payment and performance bonds through surety companies.  DCCA entered into a financial intermediary agreement with the First Illinois Development Credit Corporation to administer the program.  By the end of the fiscal year, the program was up and running with two contractors having successfully secured contracts totaling $740,000 that were guaranteed by $267,000 in DCCA funds.<p>


<a name="International"><hr></a>
<h3>International Business Division</h3>

DCCA's International Business Division (IBD) helps Illinois firms develop their export capabilities and assists foreign companies in expanding or locating in the state.  The IBD focuses its efforts on exploring and expanding opportunities for Illinois businesses in foreign markets, thus increasing the opportunities for their success in an increasingly global economy.<p>

DCCA's IBD provides assistance to Illinois exporters through a three-tiered export infrastructure that includes local, state and overseas resources.  Among those:<p>

<dl><dd>
 Five International Trade Centers (ITCs) located throughout the state that assist Illinois businesses in their efforts to achieve success in the export marketplace.  These centers, located at the College of DuPage in Glen Ellyn, Bradley University in Peoria, NORBIC in Chicago, the University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign, and at Southern Illinois University at Edwardsville, provide one-on-one counseling to potential Illinois exporters and are a component of the Illinois Small Business Development Center Network.  The Centers at NORBIC and Bradley University are also NAFTA Opportunity Centers that specialize in assisting Illinois businesses to achieve success in the Canadian and Mexican marketplaces.<p>

 The IBD's Chicago headquarters, staffed by trade specialists with international expertise in regional markets, provides assistance to companies with specific needs related to doing business in Europe, the Far East, Canada and Latin America.  Regional marketing specialists in Chicago also coordinate a number of activities and programs to assist Illinois exporters, including international trade shows and missions, catalog shows, a trade lead program, and the Illinois Export Alliance.<p>

 International resources, including six foreign trade offices located in Brussels, Belgium; Hong Kong; Tokyo, Japan; Warsaw, Poland; Budapest, Hungary; and Mexico City, Mexico.  These offices assist Illinois companies in identifying and securing in-country business partners, distribution channels and market intelligence.  The foreign trade offices also assist foreign investors and buyers seeking Illinois products and services or site locations in Illinois.<p>
</dd></dl>

During Fiscal Year 1995, DCCA's International Business Division:<p>

<ul type=square>
<li> Assisted 27 Illinois exhibitors at foreign trade shows, generating $500,000 in immediate sales with projected 12-month increased sales of more than $9.3 million.<p>
<li> Provided international marketing assistance to 600 Illinois companies.<p>
<li> Represented 534 companies at catalog shows, identifying more than 5,272 foreign trade leads for Illinois companies.<p>
<li> Co-sponsored more than 55 export development seminars, conferences or workshops attended by more than 4,500 participants.<p>
</ul>


In Calendar Year 1994, Illinois exports grew from $21.9 billion to $26.4 billion.  Illinois' export growth rate of 20.2 percent between 1993 and 1994 was six times greater than the national export growth rate of 10.2 percent, and moved the state up to fifth place in direct exports, marking the second consecutive year the state's ranking has improved.<p>

Illinois' top six trading partners in 1994 and the dollar value of those exports:<p>

<dl><dd>
 Canada  - $6.3 billion<br>
 Japan   - $2.2 billion<br>
 Mexico  - $2.0 billion<br>
 United Kingdom - $1.3 billion<br>
 Germany - $1.3 billion<br>
 China   - $1.0 billion<p>
</dd></dl>

In Calendar Year 1994, Illinois' leading export categories and their dollar value included:<p>

<dl><dd>
 Industrial Machinery/Computer Equipment - $7.2 billion<br>
 Electric Machinery - $5.1 billion<br>
 Chemical Products - $3.7 billion<br>
 Transportation Equipment - $1.7 billion<br>
 Food Products - $1.3 billion<br>
 Agricultural Products - $1.2 billion<br>
 Instruments - $993 million<p>
</dd></dl>

The importance of the IBD's efforts is best illustrated by a look at the importance of exporting to the Illinois economy.  It is estimated that more than 668,000 Illinoisans are employed in jobs sustained by direct or indirect exports, with 248,000 Illinois workers employed by foreign-owned companies with locations in the state.  One in four manufacturing jobs and one in eight jobs in Illinois are dependent upon exports.  Additionally, every dollar of Illinois exports generates $.04 in state tax revenue.<p>

<P>
