<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>DCCA: 1995 Annual Report -- Bureau of Tourism</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#0080C0" ALINK="#0080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/logosm.jpg" alt="DCCA Logo" width=165 height=82 align=left>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<h3>
Department of Commerce & Community Affairs<p>
</h3>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>

<FONT SIZE=+3>1995 Annual Report: Bureau of Tourism</FONT>
<BR CLEAR=RIGHT>
<HR>
<p>

DCCA's Illinois Bureau of Tourism maximizes the state's competitive positioning as a destination for business and leisure travel by shaping public and private initiatives into an integrated marketing program that promotes the state with a unified strategy and a consistent message.  The Bureau's primary goal is to leverage travel revenues for the benefit of the travel industry, state and local government, the state economy and the citizens of Illinois.  The Bureau's marketing also produces secondary benefits in terms of Illinois' general public profile, including its desirability as a business and residential location.<p>

In Fiscal Year 1995, the Illinois Bureau of Tourism built on its past successes to take the marketing of Illinois as a tourism destination to new levels.  Strategic alliances with public and private-sector partners leveraged the Bureau's effectiveness in promoting Illinois tourism in both U.S. and international markets.<p>  

Domestic and international tourism revenues in Illinois reached a record $15.9 billion during Calendar Year 1994.  Visitors primarily spent their funds on transportation, lodging, food, entertainment, recreation and incidentals.  Calendar Year 1994 tourism revenues represented a 6.3 percent increase over the previous year, making it the tenth year in a row that Illinois tourism revenue growth has outpaced that of the U.S. as a whole.  During the same period, tourism growth for the United States was only 4.9 percent.  Illinois continued to rank fifth in domestic travel spending among the states.<p>

Growth was even stronger in terms of the number of trips taken to or within Illinois.  A total of 50.5 million domestic leisure trips represented a growth rate of 10 percent over Calendar Year 1993.  More than 1.4 million international visitors spent $1.1 billion.  Just under one million international arrivals originated overseas.  Tourism contributed $995 million in local and state taxes and generated a payroll of $4.8 billion, supporting 241,500 jobs in the state.<p>

In Fiscal Year 1995, the Bureau conducted an integrated marketing program designed to identify and reach the state's most likely tourism customers.  The advertising component positioned Illinois as the ideal weekend getaway destination, promoting the new theme, "Illinois:  A Million Miles from Monday."  Advertising and public relations strategies also heavily promoted the Bureau's new toll-free information number, 1-800-2CONNECT.  Innovative use of television and print media built recognition and momentum during the prime summer season and paved the way for a major off-season campaign targeted for FY 1996.  International marketing efforts expanded, primarily targeting Canada and selected European markets.<p>

The Bureau launched a state-of-the-art Illinois Travel Counseling System, which enables consumers for the first time to call a toll-free number and speak with a trained tourism counselor, who answers questions and sends a customized itinerary to the customer via fax, on-line computer services or mail.  The system allows unprecedented flexibility and customization thanks to a multi-million-word database of statewide tourism information that is constantly updated to reflect new and changed attractions, seasonally-related events and other new data.  Monitoring of telephone inquiry statistics enables the Bureau to adapt its marketing to up-to-the-minute consumer demand trends and respond to advertising and public relations strategies.  When the system opened it was only the second such state travel information service in the U.S.  With the system, the Illinois tourism industry -- attractions, lodgings, restaurants, museums, recreational areas, as well as cities, towns, counties and regions -- has a new and powerful means to tell its stories to those consumers who are most likely to travel.<p>

The marketing program was launched by Gov. Jim Edgar at a high-profile news conference on April 21, 1995 in Chicago.  Chicago Tribune columnist Bob Greene called the new advertising campaign "as insightful as any I've ever seen."  Coverage by major media was pivotal in spreading the word about the advertising and introducing the Travel Counseling System to the traveling public.  The Fiscal Year 1995 marketing program also included special outreach to the African-American and Hispanic communities.<p>

During Fiscal Year 1995, the Bureau multiplied its effectiveness by forming working partnerships with public and private tourism entities.  The Bureau provided public relations support to the Lincoln-Douglas debate reenactment series that was sponsored by the cable network C-SPAN and held live in seven Illinois towns.<p>

The Bureau expanded its partnership with the City of Chicago and the Metropolitan Pier and Exposition Authority in supporting Illinois Market Place at Navy Pier, a unique, self-supporting shop that sells Illinois products as it promotes statewide tourism.  The Bureau also lent its expertise and personnel to two vitally important tourism meetings, the Illinois White House Conference on Travel and Tourism and the Illinois Governor's Conference on Tourism, as well as preparations for the national White House Conference on Tourism, the first-ever national forum for the tourism industry.<p>

Another Bureau innovation was the Sports Marketing Program.  During Fiscal Year 1995, the Sports Marketing team held seminars for most of the convention and visitors bureaus in Illinois, leading them through the process of creating local and regional sports commissions, evaluating potential sports events sites, bringing in sporting events, and publicizing those events.  The Bureau created a "how-to" kit that is being used by regions, cities and towns to develop their own sports marketing efforts.<p>

The Bureau also targeted prime international markets by working with Hill & Knowlton public relations offices in London, Frankfort and Ontario, and representative firms in the United Kingdom and Germany who work with tourism representatives, the Bureau and Hill & Knowlton.<p>

A Bureau-sponsored series of tourism packaging seminars held across the state for members of the travel industry helped participants learn the secrets of cooperative tourism marketing through such topics as market identification, creative packaging techniques, pricing, packaging for groups and tour operations, value-added programming and development of balanced itineraries.  The seminars led to the development of 97 vacation packages in Illinois and were culminated by publishing of Great Getaways in Illinois, which lists those vacation packages.<p>    

Other Fiscal Year 1995 Bureau publications included a new and expanded Illinois Visitors Guide 1995 and the first year-round edition of the Illinois Calendar of Events.  Illinois Tourism by the Numbers, a summary of tourism's economic impact on the state, was distributed at the Illinois Governor's Conference on Tourism in January 1995, and provided to the media and legislators.  Bureau publications were enhanced with completion of a major photo shoot that generated more than 1,000 new color images of state tourism attractions and locations.  The photo library is made available to the media as a means of encouraging more press coverage for Illinois destinations.<p>  

To enhance its mission of communicating with the state tourism industry, the Bureau created a quarterly report, Illinois Tourism News, with a new design and editorial content that keeps the Bureau's partners in touch with the latest tourism developments.  The newsletter was slated for bi-monthly publication beginning in Fiscal Year 1996.<p>  

The Illinois Bureau of Tourism also continued to administer grant programs designed to help enhance tourism opportunities around the state.  In Fiscal Year 1995, the Bureau coordinated and awarded 151 Tourism Matching Grants totaling $1,450,000.  These grants pay a portion of the costs of promotional materials designed to attract tourists to various sites and events.  The Bureau also awarded 31 Tourism Attraction Development Grants totaling $1,063,443 to help renovate and develop tourist attractions; and eight Tourism Private Sector Grants totaling $1,840,000 which were matched by private sector contributions to help attract world-class tourism opportunities to Illinois.  In addition, the Bureau awarded $8 million to 35 local tourism and convention bureaus to help them coordinate tourism efforts in their areas.<p>

The Illinois Film Office, a part of the Illinois Bureau of Tourism, provides technical assistance to film, television and commercial production companies to help them scout locations and find production and support services in Illinois.  The Office also acts as a liaison for businesses, communities, government and labor.  In Fiscal Year 1995, it was estimated that a portion or all of 26 productions generated $21 million in direct cash revenues to the state.  Based on a state General Revenue Fund budget of $475,000, Illinois realized a $45 return on each dollar allocated to the Illinois Film Office.<p> 

<P>
<HR>
