<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>DCCA: 1995 Annual Report -- Coal Development & Marketing</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#0080C0" ALINK="#0080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/logosm.jpg" alt="DCCA Logo" width=165 height=82 align=left>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<h3>
Department of Commerce & Community Affairs<p>
</h3>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<font size=+3>Illinois Facts</font>
<hr>
<FONT SIZE=+3>1995 Annual Report: Coal Development & Marketing *</FONT>
<BR CLEAR=RIGHT>
<HR>

<p>

DCCA's Office of Coal Development and Marketing (OCDM) supports the research, development, demonstration and commercial application of technologies that offer environmentally safe and economically competitive ways to use Illinois coal for energy generation.  OCDM accomplishes these goals by funding basic and applied research on the characteristics of high-sulfur coal, financing the development and demonstration of advanced technologies for clean coal combustion, and promoting coal awareness and education to the citizens of Illinois.<p>

<strong>
<a href="#Coal Research">Coal Research</a><br>
<a href="#Coal Development">Coal Development</a><br>
<a href="#Coal Demonstration">Coal Demonstration</a><br>
<a href="#Coal Awareness & Education">Coal Awareness & Education</a><br>
<a href="#Coal Development Board">Illinois Coal Development Board</a><p>
</strong>


<a name="Coal Research"><hr></a>
<h3>Coal Research</h3>

Illinois administers the largest state-sponsored coal research program in the United States.  The Coal Research Program, administered by OCDM, and under the technical oversight of the Illinois Clean Coal Institute, is considered to be in the forefront of state coal research programs, nationally and internationally.  In Fiscal Year 1995, OCDM awarded $2,762,947 in state funds and $1,000,000 in federal funds for the completion of 44 coal research projects.<p>

Building on recent research findings, Gov. Jim Edgar signed Senate Bill 327 (Public Act 89-93) into law allowing the beneficial use of coal combustion by-products.  As more clean coal technologies become operational, more potentially useful by-products are generated.  This Act builds on state efforts to remove unnecessary barriers to the use of Illinois coal by providing numerous alternatives for by-product utilization.<p>


<a name="Coal Development"><hr></a>
<h3>Coal Development</h3>

The Coal Development Program provides funds to advance promising new coal research technologies through the proof-of-concept stage to the commercial demonstration stage.  Development processes include technology maturation, technology transfer and related studies.  Priorities for the Development Program are established by tracking key market issues and projecting how technology can take advantage of these issues to increase new markets for Illinois coal.<p>

In Fiscal Year 1995, OCDM awarded $864,655 in state funds for the completion of four development projects.  One project examined the technical and economic feasibility of wheeling electricity from Illinois to neighboring states.  Another provided for a test burn of Illinois coal in an pressurized fluidized bed boiler pilot plant in Finland, paving the way for future demonstration of this technology in Illinois.<p>  


<a name="Coal Demonstration"><hr></a>
<h3>Coal Demonstration</h3>

The State of Illinois has committed nearly $139 million from the Coal and Energy Development Bond Fund for 18 projects over the past 13 years.  To date, this program has attracted $191 million in additional funds from the U.S. Department of Energy and $462 million in public and private investments.  Each of these projects provides near- and long-term benefits to the State of Illinois that include economic growth, cleaner air and energy conservation.<p>

One such significant clean coal technology project is the City of Rochelle micronized coal project.  Coal is micronized by pulverizing it to the consistency of talcum powder.  Micronized coal burned with micronized limestone at Rochelle effectively reduced sulfur emissions by 50 percent and NOx by 40 percent.  The $18 million clean coal technology project was partially funded by a $3.6 million grant from OCDM.<p>

Although coal micronization technology has been used on a smaller scale in the past, the Rochelle demonstration marks its first application as a fuel source for electrical generation by a utility.  Selection of this technology by the U.S. Department of Energy as an outreach project for the Krakow, Poland Clean Fossil Fuels and Energy Efficiency Program advances this technology into the next step of commercialization and paves the way for Illinois to participate in an expanding export market for coal and clean coal technologies.<p>


<a name="Coal Awareness & Education"><hr></a>
<h3>Coal Awareness and Education</h3>

Coal education continued to be a priority for OCDM in Fiscal Year 1995 with the development of an educational activity book, Coal is Cool, for kindergarten through fourth-grade students.  This book and Illinois Coal, the newly-revised guide for teachers in fifth through eighth grades, are now available to educators throughout the state and nation.<p>

OCDM held the annual Energy and the Environment "Words and Pictures About Illinois Coal" art and essay calendar contest to raise coal awareness in schools and homes.  More than 650 fifth- and sixth-grade students throughout the state participated.  Winning pictures and essays were included in 7,000 calendars and posters distributed throughout the state.<p>

As a part of state coal education efforts, Gov. Edgar proclaimed the month of October as "Coal Awareness Month."  Throughout October, OCDM sponsored coal awareness activities that included day-long educational events in Springfield and DuQuoin, distribution of tray liners with coal facts and word puzzles at Wendy's restaurants in central Illinois, and numerous radio and television interviews on the importance of the coal industry to the Illinois economy.<p>

In its everyday activities throughout the year, OCDM responded to numerous requests for information on the Illinois coal industry, coal consumption and uses, and a wide range of miscellaneous energy topics.  To aid in these requests, OCDM maintains databases on the characteristics of Illinois coal, coal production and consumption, industry contacts and many other aspects of the coal industry.<p>


<a name="Coal Development Board"><hr></a>
<h3>Illinois Coal Development Board</h3>

OCDM worked to fulfill many of the legislative mandates of the Illinois Coal Development Board during Fiscal Year 1995.  The Board, appointed by the Governor, reviewed and approved all coal research, development and demonstration projects, and provided oversight of the Coal Technology Development Assistance Fund and Coal and Energy Development Bond Fund.<p>

OCDM prepared and distributed the Illinois Coal Development Board's annual report, Outlook for the Illinois Coal Industry.  Delivered to Gov. Edgar, members of the General Assembly and interested citizens, the report identified strategies to preserve existing markets, develop new markets and uses for high-sulfur coal and to minimize the adverse impact of national environmental policies on the Illinois coal industry and its workers.<p>

<hr>
<strong>*The Office of Coal Development and Marketing was under the direction of the Illinois Department of Energy and Natural Resources during Fiscal Year 1995.  The Office became a part of DCCA in Fiscal Year 1996.</strong>

<P>
<HR>
<STRONG>| <A HREF="http://www.ilcommerce.com">DCCA Home Page</A> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/95annrep.htm">1995 Annual Report</A> |</STRONG>
</BODY>
</HTML>
