<H3>Women's Business Council sets research agenda</H3>

<H4>By Susan E. Nicol</H4>

The National Women's Business Council (NWBC) recently hosted the National
Research Strategy Agenda Conference at Northwestern University's Kellogg
Graduate School of Management in Evanston.<P>

The purpose of the strategy conference was to bring together leaders in the
field of entrepreneurial research, government, academia and the private
sector, with specific emphasis on women-owned businesses. The participants
reviewed research in the field of women-owned business and identified
further research necessary to advance women's entrepreneurial issues.<P>

Eight strategy groups met to establish research priorities in the following
topic areas:<P>

Access to Capital and Credit - Start Up and Expansion<BR>
Women's Business Formation and Operating Patterns<BR>
The Role of Business Training, Technical Assistance and Education in the
Incidence and Performance of Women-Owned Businesses<BR>
The Contributions of Women-Owned Businesses to Society and the Economy<BR>
The Role of State and Federal Governments in Supporting Women's
Entrepreneurship<BR>
The Role of Private Companies and Institutions and Private/Public
Partnerships in Supporting Women's Entrepreneurship<BR>
The Economic Performance of Women-Owned Businesses Nationally<P>

Among conference presenters and participants were Betsy Meyers, Deputy
Assistant to President Clinton and Director for Women's Initiatives and
Outreach; Cassandra Pulley, Deputy Administrator of the U.S. Small Business
Administration (SBA); Lindsey Johnson, Women, Inc.; Julie Weeks, Director
of Research, National Foundation of Women Business Owners; Bruce Phillips,
Office of Advocacy, SBA; Dr. Candy Brush, Author, Women's Entrepreneurship:
Undervalued to Value Added, and Professor, Boston University; Joline
Godfrey, Author; Amy Millman, Executive Director, NWBC; academicians;
business owners; members of the financial community; representatives of
economic development organizations; government agencies; and prominent
women business owners from across the country.<P>

Some of the research will have begun in time for NWBC's Economic Summit
'96, scheduled for May 29-30. The summit will include approximately 400
participants from the private and public sector including women business
owners, corporate officers, leaders and members of national business
organizations.<P>

Summit '96 will address issues important to women and to business
including:<P>

Expanding public and private market opportunities<BR>
Expanding financial resources available to women business owners and
ensuring their access to them<BR>
Strengthening the network capabilities of the women's business sector as
well as the training and technical assistance available to women<BR>
Promoting the development of a national research agenda for women's
entrepreneurial issues<P>

The summit will develop and promote new initiatives designed to contribute
to the establishment and growth of women's business enterprise in Illinois
and throughout the country.<P>

For more information about the National Women's Business Council, the
National Research Agenda Strategy Conference and Summit '96, please call
202/205-3850 or SBA's Office of Women's Business Ownership at 202/205-6673;
TDD, 202/205-7333.<P>

<EM>Susan E. Nicol is the Women's Business Liaison for the Office of Women's
Business Development of the Illinois Small Business Development Center
Network of the Illinois Department of Commerce and Community Affairs.</EM><P>


<H3>Governor's Export Awards</H3>

<H4>By Patty Makropoulos</H4>

Acknowledging exports as a vital component of the Illinois economy is an
important factor for continued economic growth. The Governor's Export
Awards were created by legislation to recognize and encourage small and
medium-sized Illinois exporters and organizations that work to promote
export awareness for Illinois products and to highlight the significance of
Illinois in the world marketplace.<P>

Exports are an essential element to Illinois' economic base. In 1994
Illinois exports grew to $26.4 billion representing a 20.2 percent growth
over the previous year. Illinois ranks fifth in the nation among the top
ten exporting states marking the second consecutive year that Illinois has
improved its export ranking. One in eight jobs in Illinois is dependent
upon exports; in the manufacturing sector one in four jobs is a direct
result of exports.<P>

Currently in its third year the awards program is administered by the
Illinois Department of Commerce and Community Affairs (DCCA) as part of the
agency's overall strategy to promote business expansion into global
markets. In 1994 small and midsize enterprises were responsible for more
than one-third of total merchandise exports. These companies play a crucial
role in driving the next generation of U.S. jobs. Companies that are
competing to overcome the "export gap" should apply for this prestigious
award.<P>

Businesses and organizations are recognized for outstanding achievement in
global competition in the following three categories:<P>

1. New to Export - honoring companies that have successfully exported
Illinois products for one to five years<P>
2. Continuing Exporting Excellence - honoring companies that have
successfully exported for more than five years<P>
3. Export Awareness and Development - honoring not-for-profit organizations
involved in the promotion of Illinois exporting and raising export
awareness.<P>

Representatives from DCCA, the Illinois Department of Agriculture, and
Illinois-based trade organizations and firms experienced in international
business comprise the Governor's Export Award Review Committee.<P>

Applications are judged on a total of factors: export sales as a percentage
of total company sales, growth of export sales, number of employees
involved in export sales and distinct factors indicating progressive
international marketing strategies. Deadline for application is March 29.<P>

The Governor's Export Awards will be presented at the Crossing
International Borders Annual Conference on May 16 at the Chicago Hilton and
Towers. The event is sponsored by DCCA's International Business Division
and Arthur Andersen.<P>

For information on obtaining a Governor's Export Award application or for
information regarding the Crossing International Borders Conference call
312/814-2325; TDD, 800/419-0667.<P>

<EM>Patty Makropoulos is an Export Coordinator for the Illinois Department of
Commerce and Community Affairs' International Business Division.</EM><P>


<H3>Environmental Business No Nova</H3>

<H4>By Mark Enstrom</H4>

In November of 1992, at the Illinois Energy Conference in Chicago, I had
the pleasure of meeting Soyini Walton, an energy and environmental
consultant just starting out in her own new business. She had the
educational background, technical expertise, work experience, the desire to
be a success in her future enterprise -- and lots of questions. Where could
she get assistance for marketing, planning, financing and help with the
many other issues and problems she would face? I encouraged her to contact
the Women's Business Development Center (WBDC) in Chicago for assistance.
She made that call. Today, with help from the WBDC, Asset Environmental
Services is a successful, growing business with four employees. In 1995,
one of her personal goals was accomplished as she was presented the "Rising
Star Entrepreneur Award" at the Entrepreneurial Women's Conference in
Chicago.<P>

This story is far from over. You see, a rising star is constantly in
motion, moving higher and faster as time goes by. Congratulations Asset
Environmental Services!<P>

Here is Walton's acceptance speech:<P>

"A rising star - Rises up on the horizon - Reaches it zenith and "glows"
brightly ------and then, it can fall from the horizon and FLASH out of
sight just as quickly as it rose OR...It can settle in among the rest of
the stars and remain a part of the starscape for years and years. I choose
to do the latter, to be one of the stars of the business community for
years to come. In choosing to be a successful business owner, I am learning
one thing: That success is a state of mind. One of my biggest challenges is
to maintain the "success" attitude on a daily basis. And as hard as I work
my business, I work just as hard to achieve the balance so necessary to
maintain a positive state of mine. Yes, success does mean making lots of
money but it also means personal satisfaction, economic stability,
community involvement and being able to offer other people a job.<P>

Success is setting goals and achieving them. When Carol Dougal, Co-director
of the WBDC, ceremoniously handed me a check for $3,500 two years ago, as
one of the first recipients of the microloan program, I said to Carol, "My
goal is to achieve the Rising Star Award," and Carol said to me in her very
direct and challenging way "Oh Honey - I want you to go for the
Entrepreneur of the Year Award" -- encouraging me to set higher goals.<P>

So I stand here today, the proud recipient of the Rising Star Award even
though I have not hit that one million dollars in revenues which I was
convinced was a requirement. And now Carol, I'm ready to work on the next
goal.<P>

As I continue on this journey, this rise up above the horizon, I invite you
to watch me as I grow my energy and environmental engineering business. For
those of you who are my clients, I pledge to help you grow or sustain your
business. And I appreciate the opportunity to serve you. For those of you
who are my mentors, please continue to work with me and to share your
insight and information.<P>

I thank (WBDC Co-director) Hedy Ratner and Carol for working against the
odds to bring the WBDC into being and for maintaining it as an excellent
resource center.<P>

I want to thank my Mama and Daddy, Doris and Russell Ricks, my husband,
Chaga, and my brothers and sisters and extended family. Thanks to all of
you for your support."<P>

Mark Enstrom is the Manager of the Illinois Department of Commerce and
Community Affairs' Small Business Environmental Assistance Program.<P>


<H3>Network Notes</H3>

Amy Shank, director of the Small Business Incubator at the Quincy Business
Technology Center, was named Incubator Director of the Year by the Illinois
Small Business Development Association. NetWorks apologizes for omitting
her name from the previous edition's list of award winners.<P>

There are several new Small Business Development Center (SBDC) directors.
Welcome to Joyce Wade at the Women's Business Development Center in
Chicago, Carmen Jimenez at the Latin American Chamber of Commerce in
Chicago and Charles Slowe at College of Lake County in Grayslake. Wade
replaces Paula Carlin who is now a vice president at Harris Bank and Trust.
Jimenez replaces Arturo Venecia who is now an assistant vice president for
community development at Bank of America. Slowe replaces Art Cobb who is
now the owner of a Heavenly Ham franchise.<P>

Congratulations to Pam See, director of the Procurement Technical
Assistance Center (PTAC) at College of Lake County, and her husband on the
recent birth of their first child. It's a girl!<P>

Timothy Budd, Associate Dean for the Center for Economic Development at
College of Lake County, recently passed away. Budd oversaw the college's
SBDC and PTAC.<P>

