<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>DCCA: Illinois Economic Bulletin, December 1996</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#8080C0" ALINK="#004080">

<h2 align=center>Department of Commmerce & Community Affairs</h2>
<center><img src="/dcca/graph/ieb.gif" alt="Illinois Economic Bulletin" width=575 height=75></center>
<H3 align=center>Vol. 9 No. 6, December 1996</H3>

<hr>
<h3>JOB  HOLDERS  AT  RECORD  LEVEL</h3>

Employment in Illinois topped 5,840,000 during October to reach an all-time high.  The Illinois Department of Employment Security (IDES) reported that during the month the number of unemployed dropped nearly 8,900 while total employment grew by 20,210.  IDES added that total employment crossed the 5.8 million mark for the first time in January and remained above that level every month since, as job expansion held steady.<p>

Personal income growth held relatively stable in the second quarter with a 5.4 percent annualized increase.  The quarterly change compares to a 5.8 percent rise in the first quarter.  It was reported by the U.S. Department of Commerce that the leading growth in Illinois during the period occurred in the volatile farm income, which was up 29.9 percent over the previous quarter.  It was followed by finance, insurance and real estate with 3.2 percent and services at 1.9 percent quarterly growth.<p>

A report titled Export Markets for Illinois Coal indicated that the state's international shipments of coal increased 10-fold during 1995 to a record 2.7 million tons.  The study noted that the principal importers were Morocco, Germany, the United Kingdom and Denmark.  The report was released by Lieutenant Governor Bob Kustra who forecasts that Illinois' annual coal exports could realistically increase by another 3 to 5 million tons in the next decade.<p>

The Illinois Association of Realtors reported that the statewide median price of an existing home rose to $128,400 in the third quarter.  This was $4,300 above the cost of a year ago for a 3.5 percent increase during the period.  Prices in the Chicago metropolitan area also trended upward to $155,400 during the quarter, rising at a slightly higher 4.2 percent rate over the past 12 months.  Statewide, the 26,170 homes sold during the quarter was 417 units below the number purchased in the third quarter of last year as mortgage rates had risen a half point during this time.<p>

A November publication by the Illinois Economic and Fiscal Commission (IEFC) related that some softening has occurred in consumer spending, exports and manufacturing in the state.  They add that building permits and first-time unemployment insurance claims suggest less vigorous growth.  The IEFC's analysis foresees modest but stable growth in the months ahead. <p>

The University of Illinois Flash Index of Economic Growth decreased to 102.3 in November from 102.7 the previous month.  Its compilers reported that the state index mirrors national economic trends.  They note that the steady but slow growth suggests moderate expansion in the second half of 1996 and into 1997.<p>

<hr>
<h3>AVERAGE  ANNUAL  PAY  BY  INDUSTRY</h3>

The average annual pay of $30,099 in Illinois was 8.1 percent above the national rate of $27,845 in 1995.  Both the state and national averages rose 3.4 percent last year with Illinois maintaining its eighth place ranking among the states.<p>

Among the industry classifications, mining retained its top pay position despite a modest 1.7 percent increase last year.  Finance, insurance and real estate also maintained its second position, with the assistance of the largest annual gain of 6.7 percent.  The smallest payroll increase was in government where the average pay rose 1.4 percent in 1995.<p> 

<hr>
<h3>ILLINOIS  HIGHLIGHTS</h3>

Seven Illinois firms made Forbes magazine's 1996 roster of the 200 Best Small Companies in America.  Their area of concentration was in health care, electronics, telecommunications and energy.<p>  

INC. magazine's recent annual top-500 list of America's fastest-growing companies included 20 firms that are headquartered in the state.<p>

There were five Illinois companies listed on Fortune magazine's 1996 ranking of the fastest-growing companies.<p>

<hr>
<h3>WEFA  - NOVEMBER  U.S.  ECONOMIC  OUTLOOK - FORECAST  OVERVIEW</h3>

The WEFA Group estimates that the economic expansion will continue for at least another year.  The forecasting firm notes that growth is slowing and adds that the indicators which typically signal a recession are not doing so now.  WEFA feels that over the next six months the probability of a recession will rise as economic growth slows and the yield curve flattens.<p> 

They expect employment growth to remain moderate over the next six months, wage gains to be noninflationary and economic growth to be about 2 percent.  WEFA adds that the Federal Reserve is unlikely to raise interest rates in such an environment.<p>

WEFA predicts that credit expansion will continue to decelerate.  They note that monthly payments on mortgages, consumer debt and vehicle leases have reached a critical point, which reveals the average consumer to be somewhat stretched.  WEFA estimates that consumers will remain cautious, spending their income gains without increasing their debt substantially.  They expect a subdued holiday selling season.<p>

WEFA forecasts that President Clinton and Vice President Gore in their second term will focus on cutting taxes for educational expenses, revising welfare reform, cleaning up the environment, keeping the deficit down, and fixing the financing for Medicare and Social Security.  WEFA estimates that the federal government purchases of goods and services, after inflation, will decline for a couple more years before leveling off. <p>

They expect exports to grow about 6 percent over the next couple of years and import growth will continue strong.  WEFA adds that net exports are no longer expected to contribute to growth over the next few years.<p>

They expect exports to grow about 6 percent over the next couple of years and import growth will continue strong.  WEFA adds that net exports are no longer expected to contribute to growth over the next few years.<p>

They relates that housing starts fell from a 1.53 million pace in August to a 1.44 pace in September, but new home sales were at a very high 816,000 rate in September.  WEFA notes that housing starts and sales are at a very high level, but feel that residential investment will not be contributing to much economic growth.  They feel that housing starts and sales are unlikely to rise from their current lofty heights.<p>


<HR>
<STRONG>|<A HREF="http://www.ilcommerce.com"> DCCA Home Page</A> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/econbull.htm"> Illinois Economic Bulletins</A> |</STRONG>
