<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>DCCA: Illinois Economic Bulletin, October 1996</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#8080C0" ALINK="#004080">

<h2 align=center>Department of Commmerce & Community Affairs</h2>
<center><img src="/dcca/graph/ieb.gif" alt="Illinois Economic Bulletin" width=575 height=75></center>
<H3 align=center>Vol. 9 No. 4, October 1996</H3>

<hr>
<h3>ILLINOIS'  EXPORTS  TO  MEXICO  REBOUND</h3>

Exports to Mexico have risen sharply and returned to their record 1994 level.  Through the first half of this year shipments of Illinois goods have topped $1 billion, moving Mexico back to the state's third largest export market.  The 35 percent year-to-date gain was led by the strong increase in crops and coal shipments.  Canada and Japan continue to be Illinois' top foreign markets and along with Mexico account for over one-third of the states' exports.<p>

The Illinois Department of Employment Security reported that Illinois employment remains solid with strong growth in trade and moderate expansion across other industries, including services and manufacturing.  They noted that brisk tourism activity in August pushed total employment in trade to the second-highest level on record, 1,355,000.  IDES added that the number of people filing first-time claims for unemployment benefits declined 2.1 percent from the year-ago level.<p>

Manpower Inc.'s fourth quarter 1996 Employment Outlook Survey indicated that 27 percent of the participating employers in Illinois planned to increase the size of their workforce while 8 percent anticipate a decrease.  Additionally, 61 percent expected no change.  By percentage, the DeKalb/Sycamore and Champaign area employers were the most optimistic in the state followed by the Bloomington and North Riverside areas.<p>

Retail sales have experienced some up-and-down months recently as receipts soared in May, declined in June and rebounded in July.  The $9 billion July total was the sixth largest on record, topped only by the $9.2 billion sales in May and the past three Decembers' receipts.  The weather may have aided the monthly total as the unseasonally mild summer made shopping easier.<p>

Coldwell Banker Commercial's industrial vacancy index for the Chicago area rose to 7.2 percent in the second quarter from 6.6 percent a year ago.  CB Commercial also reported that their commercial office vacancy index for the Chicago metropolitan area decreased to 14.6 percent from 15.8 percent during the same 12 month period.  The Chicago area industrial rate is below the 7.4 percent U.S. level, while the metropolitan office rate is above the national rate of 13.1 percent.<p>

The University of Illinois Flash Index of Economic Growth registered 103.2 in September from 104.2 the previous month.  Its compilers reported that sales tax collections were sluggish, while corporate tax payments rose modestly and personal income tax collections were strong in September.<p>

<hr>
<h3>ILLINOIS' BUSINESS TAX COMPETITIVENESS</h3>

A study by Robert Tannenwald, Senior Economist of the Federal Reserve Bank of Boston compares after-tax returns on capital investments in 22 states.  The report placed Illinois sixth for the best overall return for the five representative types of manufacturing firms selected.  The study reviews indicators of tax competitiveness which focus on the taxes that most directly affect a firm's bottom line and measures their impact on the profitability of potential business investment projects.  The analysis is not limited to taxes on corporate profits and net worth.  Property taxes and, in some cases, sales taxes and unemployment insurance taxes are also taken into account.<p>

The report finds that the business tax climate exerts only a small, highly uncertain effect on capital spending.  It adds that states may be more likely to stimulate their economy by enhancing public services valued by businesses.  It should also be noted that since the year from which the data was taken, Illinois has placed strong emphasis on reducing business costs.<p>

<hr>
<h3>Illinois Highlights</h3>

This year's list of FORTUNE magazine's "Most Admired Companies" included 11 Illinois headquartered firms in the top 100 companies.<p>

State Farm Insurance of Bloomington reports that their current employment within Illinois has reached 12,500.  Their large headquarter staff along with their network of claims offices places them 25th on the 1996 list of the Top In-State Employers.<p>


DCCA's Illinois Bureau of Tourism's award winning  "Million Miles from Monday" advertising campaign reports that telephone interest has increased 84 percent year-to-date through August.  Calls to their 1-800-2-CONNECT allow vacationers to contact travel counselors for help with their specific getaway plans. <p>   

<hr>
<h3>WEFA - SEPTEMBER - U.S. Economic Outlook - Forecast Overview</h3>

The forecasting firm expects increasingly moderate employment gains in the second half of 1996.  WEFA relates that as economic growth softens, job gains will diminish.  It's their view that the Federal Reserve will not raise interest rates because there are sufficient signs of economic weakness to allow the Fed to postpone any decision until the evidence of inflationary pressure is overwhelming.  They note however that the risk of the Fed raising interest rates has increased since the economy is doing fairly well and labor markets continue to tighten. <p> 

WEFA predicts that productivity growth will improve over the next year, reducing the inflationary impact of wage gains.  They add that though wage and employment gains have become more robust recently, productivity increases will compensate for the higher wage costs, keeping inflation in check.<p>

They anticipate that labor force growth will improve.  WEFA estimates that this will take some of the pressure off of the labor market, keeping wage gains only slightly above the pace of inflation.<p>

WEFA expects gasoline prices to rise by 2 to 5 cents per gallon within the next month, as the impact of the collapse of the Iraqi oil-for-humanitarian-aid program filters through to the consumer market.  They feel that this is too small of a price change to affect consumers, or the economy, significantly. <p>

They note that real consumption expenditures were down in July and likely to drag down real Gross Domestic Product growth to close to 1.5 percent.  WEFA adds that vehicle sales have fallen off pretty much as expected and this explains a great deal of the decline in consumption.<p>

WEFA forecasts that exports are expected to grow by about 7 percent to 8 percent over the next couple of years.  They report that import growth continues to be surprisingly strong and will average about 6 percent growth.<p>


<HR>
<STRONG>|<A HREF="http://www.ilcommerce.com"> DCCA Home Page</A> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/econbull.htm"> Illinois Economic Bulletins</A> |</STRONG>
