<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>DCCA: Illinois Economic Bulletin, August 1996</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#8080C0" ALINK="#004080">

<h2 align=center>Department of Commmerce & Community Affairs</h2>
<center><img src="/dcca/graph/ieb.gif" alt="Illinois Economic Bulletin" width=575 height=75></center>
<H3 align=center>Vol. 9 No. 2, August 1996</H3>

<hr>

<h3>PERSONAL INCOME AND GSP POST QUARTERLY INCREASES</h3>

First quarter personal income in Illinois rose at a 5.9 percent annualized rate for its twelfth consecutive quarterly increase.  In current dollars this was a $4.3 billion gain over the previous quarter and a $13.5 billion improvement over a year ago.  Earnings in retail trade led the advance with a 10.6 percent annualized gain followed by construction with 7.9 percent and services at 6.2 percent.<p>

In a comparable report, Illinois' first quarter Gross State Product rose at a 3.1 percent annualized rate.  The chain-weighted constant dollar increase followed a relatively flat quarter and continued the sawtooth pattern of last year.  <p>

The Illinois Department of Employment Security reported that Illinois' labor force expanded to 6,158,917 in June to reach a new high.  Employment also continued at a high level topping 5.8 million for the sixth straight month.  IDES added that the unemployment rate has remained stable in the low range of 5.1 percent to 5.3 percent, reflecting the continued strength of the Illinois economy.<p>

Retail sales topped $9.27 billion in May for the largest non-December monthly total on record.  Despite the lofty level, receipts are up a modest 3.6 percent year-to-date.  Nationally, retail sales have increased 6.8 percent during the period.<p>

Construction activity in Illinois is up slightly for the year according to F. W. Dodge's report on contracts for future construction.  Through the first six months of the year, contracts are positive by 0.9 percent.  The mainstay has been residential construction which is above last year's pace by 17.4 percent.  Nonbuilding contracts (infrastructure improvements) also were up by 2.5 percent with nonresidential construction off 18.4 percent.<p>

New business incorporations in the state declined in June after three months of growth.  Domestic filings were off by 188 from the previous June, but the 18,931 year-to-date total  is ahead of last year's pace by 772 incorporations or 4.3 percent.<p>

The University of Illinois Flash Index of Economic Growth rose slightly to 104.9 in July from 104.8 the previous month.  Its compilers reported that the Illinois economy grew moderately last month, reflecting the go-slow expansion of the national economy after four years of growth.  They added that both income and corporate profits in Illinois were strong in July but noted that they were somewhat offset by weak retail sales, as measured by sales-tax collections. <p>


<hr>
<h3>ILLINOIS  EXCELS  IN  MANUFACTURING - PART II</h3>

The previous edition of the Illinois Economic Bulletin listed the 35 industrial categories in which the state was the national leader.  This issue presents the 44 classifications in which Illinois placed second in value of shipments. It is notable that the amount of commercial printing is larger than the items rated number one.  The listing is in standard industrial classification order (not shown due to the limited space).<p>


<hr>
<h3>ILLINOIS  HIGHLIGHT</h3>

The 1996 Olympic theme song "Reach" recorded by Gloria Estefan was written by Chicago song writer Diane Warren, reportedly in one day.<p>


<hr>
<h3>WEFA - JULY - U.S. ECONOMIC OUTLOOK - FORECAST OVERVIEW</h3>

WEFA predicts that employment growth will moderate in the second half of 1996 as housing activity weakens, vehicle sales slump, exports to Europe dampen and nonresidential construction falls.<p>

They forecast that the Fed will continue to hold the funds rate at 5.25 percent for the time being.  WEFA notes that employment growth has spooked the bond market, but expect that inflation is unlikely to accelerate.  They add that as further evidence of moderate inflation unfolds and signs of slower growth appear, bond prices will rise, lowering yields of long-term bonds.<p>

WEFA anticipates that consumer price inflation will remain close to 2.5 percent per year.  They estimate that as economic growth moderates, inflationary pressures will ease keeping inflation stable.<p>

They predict that export growth will remain close to 8 percent for the rest of the year and into 1997.  WEFA anticipates that import growth will moderate, but only slightly.  They add that it now looks unlikely that exports will boom sufficiently to add much to real GDP growth in the second half of 1996 and 1997.<p>

WEFA forecasts a tough and prolonged negotiation between the unions and management in the automobile industry this summer and fall.  They feel that the probability of a strike is high.<p>


<HR>
