<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>DCCA: Illinois Economic Bulletin, June1996</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#8080C0" ALINK="#004080">

<h2 align=center>Department of Commmerce & Community Affairs</h2>
<center><img src="/dcca/graph/ieb.gif" alt="Illinois Economic Bulletin" width=575 height=75></center>
<H3 align=center>Vol. 8 No. 12, June 1996</H3>

<HR>
<h3>NEW BUSINESS INCORPORATIONS SET MONTHLY RECORD</h3>

Entrepreneurial optimism abounded in April with a record setting 3,770 domestic business filings.  The large monthly total topped the previous high set in December, 1992 by 280 incorporations.  April's surge added to March's substantial filings, increasing the year-to-date total to 7.6 percent above a year ago.  In the first four months, new business incorporations have risen by 910 filings over last year's growth.<p>

Following a lackluster March, the U.S. Department of Commerce reported that residential building in the state rebounded in April.  Their numbers indicate that  housing starts rose to a near record 5,418 units authorized for construction during the month.  A relatively drier April  allowed building activity to progress more rapidly with year-to-date permit issuance above last year's level by 12.2 percent.<p> 
  
The Chicago all urban consumer price index rose 2.2 percent in April from last year's level as overall costs moderated.  The major upward push in prices occurred in energy, led by natural gas and followed by motor fuel cost increases.  Offsetting the rise were subdued medical care costs and a decline in apparel and upkeep.  Without energy costs,  the index would have risen only 1.6 percent in April.<p>

The Department of Employment Security reported that after setting a new record in January, total employment in the state remained above 5.8 million for the fourth consecutive month.  IDES added that the unemployment rate at 5.1 percent in April experienced little change since the previous month and has remained below the U.S. level for 30 straight months.<p>

Employment in manufacturing was up by 12,800 in April over the previous year with growth occurring primarily in durable goods.  Approximately 9,500 jobs were added in the production of industrial machinery with the manufacture of electronic equipment expanding by 3,300 workers.  Nationally, there has been a sharp decline in manufacturing employment over the past year.<p>

An economic forecasting firm, Regional Financial Associates, related that the Chicago-metro area trails only the San Jose and Boston areas in the number of high-tech manufacturing jobs with nearly 163,000.  RFA added that the Chicago area is enjoying steadily increasing high-tech employment led by the Motorola and U.S. Robotics (modems) expansions.<p>  

The University of Illinois Flash Index of Economic Growth registered 105.1 in May from 106.1 the previous month.  Its compilers reported that evidence grows the Illinois economy is slowing to a more moderate pace after two years of rapid expansion.<p>   

<hr>
<h3>RECENT INDICATORS</h3>

Unemployment Rate                 5.1%<br>
(April-SA)<p>

Consumer Price Index              2.2%<br>
