<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>DCCA: Illinois Economic Bulletin, February 1996</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#8080C0" ALINK="#004080">

<h2 align=center>Department of Commmerce & Community Affairs</h2>
<center><img src="/dcca/graph/ieb.gif" alt="Illinois Economic Bulletin" width=575 height=75></center>
<h3 align=center>Vol. 8 No. 8, February 1996</h3>


<HR>
<H3>STRONG ECONOMIC YEAR FOR STATE IN 1995</H3>

Available information indicates that last year provided substantial economic growth in Illinois.  The recent federal government shutdowns have slowed the flow of data, but early reports confirm that 1995 was a prosperous year.  The following provides brief summaries of the employment gains and notes business growth in the state.<P>  

The Illinois Department of Employment Security reported that the state's 5.2 percent average unemployment rate in 1995 was the lowest in 21 years.  Additionally, its 5.7 percent seasonally adjusted December unemployment rate was lower than any of the five more populous states.  IDES also noted that the 12-month average of 5,780,000 employed persons last year was the highest number on record in Illinois.<P>
 
Illinois' exports continued their robust growth in the third quarter with nearly $8 billion in international shipments.  Electronic and electric equipment such as communication devices, generators and controls led the advance with a 45.6 percent year-to-date increase. The only  classification to decrease was oil and gas extraction with the export of these commodities to Mexico and Canada declining.  Several Asian countries posted strong growth with China (Mainland) and Korea each accounting for over $1 billion of the state's shipments.<P>

Despite sluggish November and December new business filings, the 34,495 domestic incorporations in 1995 set a record.  For the year, total filings were up by 208 for a slight 0.6 percent annual gain.  This was the smallest increase since the -0.7 percent decline in 1991 but the fourth consecutive yearly advance.   <P>

Noted regional economist Diane Swonk of First Chicago NBD Corporation reports that the five state Great Lakes region (which includes Illinois) is starting the year on a much better footing than other areas of the country.  She relates that comparatively, real wages are growing (albeit modestly); debt is less of a problem; consumers are more confident; and, homes are still appreciating.  She adds that these trends are likely to continue in 1996.<P>

According to the Mortgage Bankers Association, the percent of total past due loans in Illinois was up slightly to 4.20 percent in the third quarter from 3.88 percent a year ago.  Those in foreclosure had decreased however, declining to 0.70 percent from 0.80 percent a year ago. Nationally the comparable third quarter mortgage delinquency rate was 4.38 percent.<P>

The University of Illinois Flash Index of Economic Growth registered 106.5 in January from 107 the previous month.  Its compilers noted that the decline in the Index does not indicate a significant downturn in the Illinois economy.  Rather, they add, it indicates a modest slowing of the state's growth rate, similar to what has been registered by many forecasts of the U.S. economy.<P> 

<HR>
<H3>RECENT INDICATORS	</H3>

Unemployment Rate: 5.7%<BR>
(December-SA)<P>

