<HR>
<H3>ILLINOIS HIGHPOINTS</H3>

 A recent edition of The Kiplinger Washington Letter forecasts that Illinois was one of the 10 best states for job seekers.  It also cited a need for more factory workers around the Great Lakes area and noted that experienced computer experts are in demand just about everywhere. <P>

 Ameritech and Motorola have been jointly testing their Integrated Services Digital Network in Champaign County.  The system uses a modem-like device that allows public subscribers to send and receive computer data (including Internet access), video or voice messages over a standard telephone line about nine times faster than conventional modems.<P>  

 Chicago and the Illinois Department of Commerce and Community Affairs were joint recipients of a $450,000 grant awarded by the U.S. Department of Commerce to 10 entities nationwide.  The grant will fund export development assistance to small-medium size firms that vary from new-to-export to export-ready companies. <P>

<HR>
<H3>THE WEFA GROUP - JANUARY U.S. ECONOMIC OUTLOOK - FORECAST OVERVIEW</H3>

 WEFA expects growth to be modest in the first quarter of 1996.  They predict that the longer the budget impasse continues, the more likely growth will be closer to 1 percent rather than their current forecast of about 2 percent.<P>

 They estimate that the 30-year Treasury bond will remain close to 6 percent in 1996 and the Federal Reserve will continue cutting the Fed funds rate.  They expect the funds rate to be cut from its present level of 5.5 percent to 4.75 percent by mid-year.<P> 

 WEFA anticipates that recessionary pressures will ease as the Federal Reserve lowers    short-term interest rates and output improves after the resolution of the budget impasse.  They note that their Recession Barometer tends to rise above 1.0 about 12 months prior to the onset of a downturn.  They report that it currently reads 0.85 indicating that the probability of a recession is only about 25 percent in 1996. <P>

 WEFA adds that over the past 12 presidential elections, real disposable income growth above 3 percent (WEFA forecasts 0.7 percent for 1996) has resulted in a win by the incumbent party.  They also note that a Gallup Presidential Job Approval rating above 50 percent usually results in a win by the incumbent party, unless the economy is very weak, as it was in 1960. <P>

 They expect export growth to continue to be robust in 1996 as the weak dollar and high quality of U.S. goods bolster demand for American products in foreign markets.  WEFA notes that shipments to the weak Mexican market are being offset by exports to Japan and Germany.  They also predict that import growth will slow down as U.S. growth decelerates.<P>


<HR>
