<a name="Introduction"><hr></a>
<h3>INTRODUCTION</h3>

In this issue of The Grant Manager we will be discussing a number of topics pertinent to administration of your CDAP grants.  Every day, our grants managers respond to questions from potential grant applicants as well as experienced grantees.  Constant communication is one of the important aspects of good grant administration.  Grantees and grant administrators should always be aware that the CDAP staff are here to assist and will make every attempt to ensure your ideas are discussed and your questions answered.<p>

Most of the information included in this issue comes from communication grants managers have had with grantees.  The Question and Answer section has been expanded to cover a variety of questions which might arise during the administration of your grant.  To some of you "veterans" a few of the questions may seem simple and unnecessary.  But to many of the new grantees even the smallest problem can be overwhelming.  We hope you find this information useful.<p>

For those of you who are receiving The Grant Manager for the first time, this newsletter is being prepared to assist grantees, administrators, consultants and others who administer CDAP grants.  This is your newsletter and we welcome your questions and comments.  We want to keep an open dialogue of information and knowledge between you and the CDAP staff.  Readers who would like to submit questions for the "Q & A" section or have topics they would like to see discussed in future articles, should submit their written topics or questions to their CDAP Grants Manager.  We will make every attempt to include your information or answer your questions in future newsletters.<p>

The Grant Manager is published twice a year by the Illinois Department of Commerce and Community Affairs, 620 East Adams Street, Springfield, Illinois 62701.  Telephone 217/785-6142.  Fax 217/782-1206.  TDD 800/785-6055.  Internet http://www.ilcommerce.com<p>

Topics to be covered and questions should be submitted in writing and are subject to editing.<p>


<strong>CDAP Manager:</strong> Jean Thomas<br>
<strong>Managing Editor:</strong> Sarah Bates<br>
<strong>Editorial Board:</strong> Pete Arnolds, Tim Call, Jim Wallwork, Shirley Watkins, Amy Zachary<p>

<a name="Federal Prevailing Wage Requirements"><hr></a>
<h3>FEDERAL PREVAILING WAGE REQUIREMENTS</h3>

When CDAP funds are used in whole, or in part, for construction, federal prevailing wages must be paid.  The Davis-Bacon Prevailing Wage Act requires that all laborers and mechanics employed on any federally-assisted construction project must be paid wages that are prevailing in their labor market for the corresponding classes of workers as determined by the U.S. Secretary of Labor.  Sometimes CDAP grantees confuse federal prevailing wages with Illinois prevailing wages, which are provided by the Illinois Department of Labor.  They are not the same. The only way to receive the correct wage scales for your CDAP construction project is to submit a CDAP WAGE RATE DETERMINATION REQUEST form to DCCA.  A copy of this form can be found in Chapter 2, Section 3 of the CDAP Grants Management Handbook (June 1995).  Questions regarding prevailing wages should be directed to Bill Rhodes at 217/785-6132, TDD 800/785-6055.<p>


<a name="Questions & Answers"><hr></a>
<h3>QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS</h3>

Often you may feel there are no answers available to questions that develop in administering your grant.  The answer may not be found in the Grants Management Handbook because the question or problem is a "unique" situation that requires more definition or clarification.  This section of The Grant Manager will be devoted to questions from you, the grantees, and answers from the CDAP staff.  We will also include common concerns encountered by grants managers during their site visits.  In each newsletter we will answer your questions and share your comments with other grantees who may have experienced similar problems.<p>


<h4>ENVIRONMENTAL PROCESS</h4>

Q.   What is the purpose of the Environmental Status Checklist? <p>

A.    The Environmental Status Checklist (ESC) takes the place of the former finding letters that were approximately two pages long and explained the environmental finding of your project.  In an effort to streamline the environmental process, we developed this form as a type of checklist to help administrators and local officials send the correct information with their environmental packets.  The grantee should place a checkmark next to the finding (exempt, categorically excluded, or environmental assessment) and then fill in the regulations from the Federal Register used to support the environmental finding.  Next, the grantee should look under the space provided for the regulation for a checklist of other items that should be sent in cooperation with the environmental status checklist.  This form should be signed and dated by the chief elected official AFTER the local comment period has expired if a publication was deemed necessary for the project.<p>


<h4>PUBLIC FACILITIES</h4>

Q.   If the resident occupying the household is renting, should you submit the household income of the resident living in the household or the owner of the property?<p>

A.  You should provide the renter's household income.<p>

Q.  Where can a community get funds for a fire truck?<p>

A.  The Illinois Rural Bond Bank at 217/524-2663, or Rural Development at 217/398-5412 (formerly FmHA) through the Community Loan Program, might be able to help with loan funds.<p>


<h4>ADMINISTRATION</h4>

Q.  Is increased fidelity bonding an eligible expense for CDAP funded projects?<p>

A.  Yes.  It must be charged to administrative costs.<p>


<h4>FINANCIAL CLOSE-OUT PACKAGE</h4>

Q.   When completing the "Analysis of Benefit to Low and Moderate Income Persons" page in the close-out package, should we also include the administration costs as well as the construction costs?<p>

A.   Yes.  Column "A" should identify each activity including administration.  Column "E" should identify the costs allocated for each activity including administration.  The total of all (which is the total amount of the grant) should reflect figures in Column "E".<p>


<h4>HOUSING/ADMINISTRATION</h4>

Q.   What rehabilitation standards are required under the CDAP housing grant?<p>

A.   Your application submitted for funding should have stated any local building codes which have been adopted.  If not, the Illinois State Plumbing Code, National Electrical Code (NEC) and HUD Housing Quality Standards (HQS) must be met at a minimum.  DCCA sponsored housing conferences have suggested the Council of American Building Officials (CABO) One and Two Family Dwelling Code, but this is not required.<p>

Q.   Can funds from two separate grants be used to rehabilitate a single home or housing unit (split funding)? <p>

A.  No.  All funds drawn on a grant must be expended during the grant period and prior to submittal of  the financial close-out.  Any funds not expended cannot be "carried over" to be used with another year's grant funding.  These funds must be returned to DCCA and reported as such in the financial close-out and Grantee Evaluation Report (GER).<p>


<h4>LABOR STANDARDS</h4>

Q.  How is a bona-fide self-employed contractor to be determined/documented?<p>

A.  A bona-fide self-employed contractor is a contractor who has no other employees and whose business can be documented by at least one of the following:<p>

     1)   A Federal Taxpayer Identification Number (TIN) (FEIN).<p>

     2)   A certificate of registration or license issued by the state.<p>

     3)   A listing in the business advertising section of the telephone directory.<p>

     4)   A business advertisement published in a newspaper of  general circulation in the area of the business' address.<p>

     5)   A legal notice of an assumed business name published in a newspaper of general circulation in the area of  the business' address.<p>

Q.  What constitutes Force Account Labor?<p>

A.   Force account labor is work performed on a project by the regular employees (mechanics and/or laborers) of a unit of local general government as a part of the employee's normal work duties.<p>

Q.   Can a private company use force account labor and not pay federal prevailing wages?<p>

A.   No.   Only a unit of  local government using force account labor does not pay federal prevailing wages.  All others must pay federal prevailing wages.<p>

Q.  When monitoring federal prevailing wages, if the contractor's computerized payrolls do not show fringe benefits, can we accept the "Statement of Compliance" form if checked (4a) where fringe benefits are paid to approved plans, funds or programs?<p>

A.  Yes.<p>

Q.  How often must employee interviews be completed?<p>

A.  The grantee must conduct employee interviews with a member of each craft at least once per month.  Interviews must be conducted to assure that the payroll information is consistent with the wage rate determination and that the employees are working in their proper job classifications.<p>

Q.  If there is no contract awarded on a project, when should the wage decision be requested?<p>

A.  If no contract is awarded on a project (for instance when the grantee acts as its own contractor), the wage decision published and in effect 10 days prior to the start of construction will apply.<p>

Q.  Does the Davis-Bacon Act Contract for Prevailing Wages remain in effect for the life of the contract?<p>

A.  Yes.  Unless substantial changes are made in the terms of the contract.<p>


<h4>FLOOD PROCESS</h4>

Q.  Is Historic Preservation field work associated with structures in the buy-out program considered an eligible grant cost?<p>

A.  Yes.  FEMA pays 90 percent and DCCA pays 10 percent out of the Demolition Line Item.<p>

Q.  Can a grantee incur costs for appraisals prior to receiving a release of funds letter?<p>

A.  Yes.  Appraisals-related activities are exempt pursuant to 24 CFR Part 58.34 (a).  The grantee may incur costs and request reimbursement for these activities prior to release of funds.  However, acquisitions of property may not occur until the grant complies with all environmental requirements of 24 CFR Part 58. <p>


<h4>EEO PROCESS</h4>

Q.   On the quarterly contract and subcontract report, should Column "B" (amount of contract) reflect only the CDAP amount of the contract?<p>

A.   Yes.  Column "B" should reflect CDAP dollars only in the contract amount.  The grant total of the contract could be reflected near the bottom of the page highlighted with an asterisk.  This form will be revised in the near future to include columns indicating the total amount of the contract and CDAP amount of the contract.<p>


Q.  If a grantee only knows the total amount of the subcontract and does not know how much is DCCA-funded, how would you calculate the amount for reporting the quarterly contract and subcontract activity report figures?<p>

A.  You would calculate the percentage at the same rate as the injection of CDAP funds in the general contract.<p>


Q.  Is it required that the above activity report be submitted to DCCA quarterly?<p>

A.  Yes.  When a contract has been awarded you are required to forward a copy of the activity report within that respective quarter.  Timeliness is important as these statistics are submitted to HUD.  Also, this activity will be monitored during future site visits.<p>


<h4>ECONOMIC DEVELOPMENT</h4>

Q.  Should a grantee/company use the HUD Section 8 Income Guidelines from the application year of the grant for the entire grant period when verifying job creation/retention?<p>

A.  No.  A copy of the current year income guidelines to verify job creation/retention for that respective year should be requested from the grantee's grants manager. <p>

Q.  Is the grantee responsible for reviewing economic development CDAP funds that are loaned to a company?<p>

A.  Yes.  The grantee should review these expenditures prior to submission to DCCA for reimbursement/payment.  It is the grantee's responsibility to have available at the site visit all documentation from the company verifying CDAP economic development funds.  The grantee should also have available documentation of leverage funds from a company for review.<p>

Q.  What activities can funds be used for under the economic development component?<p>

A.  Generally, CDAP funds are granted to communities to be loaned to for-profit or not-for-profit private entities who must document the need for grant and/or loan assistance.  The borrower may use the funds for land acquisition, construction, reconstruction, installation or rehabilitation of commercial or industrial buildings, structures and other real property, equipment and improvements, and working capital.  Working capital is defined as inventory, employee salaries, general operation expenses and advertising/marketing.  In addition, communities may use CDAP funds for public facilities and improvements in support of economic development.  CDAP funds may not be used for debt refinancing.<p>


<a name="Public Hearing"><hr></a>
<h3>PUBLIC HEARING - PROGRAMMATIC CLOSE-OUT</h3>

As a condition of the programmatic close-out, all CDAP grants awarded after November 1992 must conduct a public hearing to review program performance and obtain citizen views regarding program activities and performance.  The Notice of Public Hearing must be published at least once in a newspaper of general circulation at least seven calendar days (excluding the date of publication) prior to the public hearing.  Your documentation to DCCA should include a copy of the publication/certification, minutes of the meeting certified by the chief elected official or another authorized official, and the attendance sheet which identifies private citizens and local officials.  Once your project has been completed and all CDAP funds drawn, you can proceed with the second public hearing.  It is not necessary to wait until you receive your close-out package from DCCA to conduct the public hearing.  Grants managers will not process programmatic close-out packages unless this information is included.  If you have any questions concerning this process, please contact your grants manager.<p>


<a name="Completing GER"><hr></a>
<h3>COMPLETING GER FOR REMOVAL OF ARCHITECTURAL BARRIERS GRANTS</h3>

When completing the Grantee Evaluation Report (GER) for CDAP Removal of Architectural Barriers grants, remember to use Census PCH-5-15 tables 7 and 8 to calculate the total number of persons served (column b).  The number of low-to-moderate persons served (column c) should be the same as column b.  The percent of persons served who are LMI (column d) should be 100 percent.  Column e should be the amount of the grant.  Column f should be the same as column e.  On the page for benefit to minorities, handicapped, and female heads of households, the total number of persons served should be the same as column b on the preceding page.  Data for compiling numbers of minorities is not available.  If you need any assistance in completing this information, please contact your grants manager.<p>


<a name="CDAP Loan Pricing"><hr></a>
<h3>CDAP LOAN PRICING POLICY</h3>

Under the Community Development Assistance Program Economic Development component, DCCA can grant funds to local governments, which in turn, loan these funds to private businesses to create and retain jobs.  As part of DCCA's review of CDAP Economic Development applications, the federal regulations require the department to "price" each loan.  At the time of the award, DCCA establishes the term, interest rate and conditions for the loan.  The term and rate set by the department may differ from the rate and term requested by the applicant.<p>

DCCA has established three percent as the minimum rate for CDAP loans.  However, the interest rate established by DCCA, after completion of the financial analysis, may be higher.  Many factors are included in DCCA's pricing evaluation, including, but not limited to, profitability, cash flow and collateral coverage.<p>

CDAP Economic Development funds are a valuable and popular source of  subordinate, fixed, below-market financing.  However, it is important that, up front, businesses are told that the interest ultimately approved by DCCA may be higher than the minimum three percent.<p>


<a name="Bid Negotiations"><hr></a>
<h3>BID NEGOTIATIONS</h3>

It is not unusual for CDAP projects which involve construction to exceed the funding originally budgeted for the activities.  Since DCCA obligates 100 percent of the funds allocated for each CDAP program component, additional CDAP funds cannot be made available.  Therefore, it is extremely important upon grant award that the grantee review the Grant Award Document, Scope of Work, and Activity Budget.  If it is determined at that time that insufficient funds are budgeted for the project, the grantee should contact DCCA to modify the Scope of Work.  This should be done prior to executing and returning the Grant Award Document.<p>

Leverage funds, if available, can always be used to supplement project cost "overruns".  If local funds are not available, other sources of leverage may include:  1) The Illinois Environmental Protection Agency (IEPA); 2) Rural Development; 3) Illinois Rural Bond Bank (IRBB); 4) Illinois Housing Development Authority (IHDA); and 5) private financial institutions (banks).<p>

Should a situation arise where the total costs are within the total budget, but a particular activity line exceeds the budgeted amount, it may be possible (through a grant modification) to allow an increase in the amount budgeted for that activity line by reducing the amount budgeted for another.<p>

Construction contracts for activities which have been advertised for bids where the bids received exceed the amount budgeted should never be awarded to any contractor unless funds are assured, or the contracting agency is ready and willing to accept any and all legal consequences.  Once bids are received, a bid cannot be negotiated.  The bids must be rejected and the proposal readvertised.  All bidders must be given an equal opportunity to bid on the project (activity) described in the bid specification.  The regulations do contain provisions stating that, under certain special circumstances and conditions, bids may be negotiated, provided those special provisions are met.<p>

If it is anticipated that the bids for a specific activity will exceed the funds allocated for that activity, it is strongly urged that the bid specifications contain provisions for deductible alternatives whenever feasible.  If properly done, it may be possible to reduce the cost of the activity without readvertising and rebidding.  This method allows all prospective bidders equal opportunity to bid on the same activity and also allows the contracting agency the opportunity to select the lowest bid, or in some cases, the lowest "combination of bids."  It also reduces the possibility of an unsuccessful bidder suggesting that a bid was negotiated.<p>


