<h3>EDGAR MEETS WITH SMALL BUSINESS LEADERS</h3>

Governor Jim Edgar was on hand as the Illinois Small Business
100 (ISB100) held its first meeting to discuss issues important
to small business owners.<p>

The ISB100, which consists of 100 entrepreneurs throughout the
state, will serve in an advocacy role for the state's 617,000
small business owners. Members were nominated by trade
associations, professional organizations, Illinois Small
Business Development Network centers, the U.S. Small Business
Administration and others.<p>

"Through the Illinois Small Business 100, my administration is
forging an even stronger relationship with small business - one
that is designed to foster a better understanding of the ongoing
issues and challenges facing this important segment of the
economy," Edgar said. "We will work together to promote business
growth and expansion in a low-tax, common sense climate that
does not choke economic growth."<p>

The group will communicate electronically via fax and the
Internet to provide nearly instant feedback to the latest issues
affecting small businesses.<p>

"Small businesses are the backbone of the state's economy,"
Edgar said. "They play vital roles as job creators, employing
millions of Illinois citizens, and they provide tremendous
opportunities for those from every corner of Illinois who have
the determination to work hard and succeed. We are seeing some
of the most dramatic growth in small businesses owned by women
and minorities."<p>

Edgar also presented the first Governor's Award for Small
Business Achievement to Turano Bakeries of Berwyn. The Turano
family started the business in the 1960s as a small Chicago
neighborhood bakery. Today Turano is a nationally known company,
servicing accounts that include fast food outlets and
supermarket chains. Edgar cited them as an example of how a
small business can grow through hard work.<p>

Turano's Berwyn facility was the site of Edgar's formal
announcement of the creation of the ISB100. Prior to the
announcement Edgar toured the facility and purchased bread from
their bakery shop.<p>

<hr>
<h3>MEXICAN VISIT HELPS ILLINOIS SMALL BUSINESSES</h3>

<em>Editor's Note: </em>Rebecca Lake, International Trade Center director
at North Business and Industrial Council (NORBIC) in Chicago,
recently traveled to Mexico City to assist several Illinois
small businesses.<p>

By Rebecca Lake<p>

I heard it at a breakfast meeting over huevos rancheros and a
glass of orange juice: it is the best of times, it is the worst
of times. While I had listened to this phrase uttered many times
before, never had it described a situation so perfectly. The
conclusions I had drawn from my two week visit in Mexico about
economic and social life fit nicely into those 12 words. On a
trip sponsored by the NAFTA Opportunity Center (NOC) at NORBIC,
I had the opportunity to support Illinois trade with Mexico,
while discovering firsthand how Mexico City was dealing with the
worst of times, following 1994's peso devaluation and resulting
economic crisis.<p>

Much of my time in Mexico City was spent working at the State of
Illinois booth at Mexican Manufacturing Week `96, Mexico's
premier trade show for manufacturers. Helping represent the 11
Illinois companies that participated in the catalogue show, I
spoke with numerous distributors and potential buyers from
throughout Latin and South America. Some of these companies were
one-man operations, looking to represent anybody that will give
them a chance. Many, however, were established companies eager
to incorporate U.S. products into their lines. After just a few
discussions, it became clear that companies in Mexico and beyond
associated not just U.S., but specifically Illinois products
with quality.<p>

Another major part of my trip consisted of on-site market
research for some of the NOC's clients. I visited local retail
outlets throughout Mexico City, including the popular department
store, Sanborne's, the big grocery store chains, even Sam's
Club. Most of the stores were filled with consumers, similar to
a Saturday afternoon at a Sam's Club in Chicago. Store shelves
were stocked with everything from ice cream to Ralph Lauren
bedding, leading me to the conclusion that even though Mexicans
are feeling the pinch from a hurting economy, they are still
welcoming U.S. products into their homes and dessert menus. <p>

Unfortunately, once outside the busy stores, I again witnessed
the countless people doing whatever they could to get by.
Washing windshields for a peso (about fifteen cents) was one
popular means, performing acrobats in front of cars stopped at
stoplights, another. The image that I recall most vividly is of
men, lined up along a fence on a busy city square, holding
shabby pieces of cardboard stating the trades that they were
skilled in. They'd stand there all day if they had to, looking
for work. <p>

The Illinois Department of Commerce and Community Affairs'
Mexico Office served as homebase for me during my time in Mexico
City. If ever there was a group of dedicated, productive, and
giving people, it is the staff in this office. Armed with a
desk, computer, and phone, I was able to work without
interruption to gather as much information as possible to bring
back as resources for Illinois companies. Using the Mexico
office's conference rooms, I met with Mexican companies looking
to do business with Illinois. Currently, we're in the process of
matching them with potential business partners here at home. It
certainly is the best of times for Illinois companies who are
taking advantage of opportunities within this emerging market.<p>

Specifically, the Illinois companies that research was carried
out for included a Des Plaines-based processor of quality
seafood, a Chicago manufacturer of industrial and graphic arts
rollers, a Batavia-based company that manufactures financial
equipment, a manufacturer of electronic equipment in Chicago,
and a Lake Bluff-based processor of dietary supplements. <p>

Another highlight of this trip included a meeting with the
Economist Magazine's Conference Director, Alfonso Cortina. He
will serve as the keynote speaker in the NAFTA Opportunity
Center at NORBIC's upcoming seminar, "Doing Business in Mexico -
from Devaluation to Re-evaluation." A dynamic speaker with a
thorough knowledge of Mexico's economic and political life,
Cortina will analyze implications of the current and future
Mexican economy for Illinois exporters. For more information on
this informative seminar, or to register, call 312/588-5137.<p>

I'm anxious to hear if Mr. Cortina's perceptions of where his
country is and where it's going are in line with mine. In my
meeting with him, it was my impression that he sees an expanding
economy for Mexico, but like in all market economies, there are
growing pains to deal with. It seems to me that the Mexican
people are accepting these challenges, and moving on the best
way they know how.<p> 

<hr>
<h3>HAZARDOUS WASTE INFO AVAILABLE</h3>

By Tom Kamykowski<p>

The Illinois Hazardous Waste Research and Information Center
(HWRIC) will combine research with information collection and
analysis to provide small businesses with direct technical
assistance and educational materials on matters of waste
management and pollution prevention.<p>

Since 1986, HWRIC, a non-regulatory, non-profit agency, has been
helping industry reduce waste at the source. The Illinois Toxic
Pollution Prevention Act expanded HWRIC's mandate "to promote
toxic pollution prevention as the preferred means for achieving
compliance with environmental laws and regulations."<p>

Pollution prevention programs not only help reduce waste, but
often also reduce raw material, labor and disposal costs. These
cost savings can help Illinois' business and industry become
more competitive.<p>

For some companies, reporting of pollution prevention progress
is required under the federal Pollution Prevention Act of 1990.
Each facility required to file an annual toxic chemical release
report must include a toxic chemical source reduction and
recycling report on each chemical.<p>

HWRIC works with industry, government and academia to find
effective solutions to Illinois' waste problems, offering the
following services:<p>

<ul>
<li>Engineering solutions
<li>On-site assessments
<li>Training
<li>Case studies
<li>Waste reduction
<li>Matching funds for research
<li>Information services
<li>Environmental regulatory compliance
<li>Improved productivity, process efficiency and cost accounting
</ul>

For more information contact HWRIC's office in Champaign at
217/333-8940 or in Chicago at 312/265-2188.<p>

Tom Kamykowski is the director of the Small Business Development
Center at North Business and Industrial Council (NORBIC) in
Chicago.<p>


<hr>
<h3>EVEN SMALL FIRMS CAN BID ON GOV'T CONTRACTS</h3>

This is not your normal success story. This success story does
not include the award of a multi-million dollar government
contract, or even a $100,000 contract. Instead, it is about a
small construction/roofing business that, thanks to a little
help, submitted its first bid on a government contract.<p>

Shingles Plus submitted bids for several roofing projects with
the Champaign County Housing Authority. Just by just submitting
a bid, this small business has become a success in the ever
changing world of government contracting.<p>

Shingles Plus became a client of the University of Illinois'
Cooperative Extension Service's Procurement Technical Assistance
Center (PTAC) last year. Since then, time has been spent
applying for Capital Development Board certification, securing
bonding, and filling out the numerous pieces of paper required
to bid on both state and federal government contracts. Before
Shingles Plus became a PTAC client, they had not bid on any
government contracts. "We were on the outside looking in," says
Mandy Bogdan, Shingles Plus' main company contact.<p>

The PTAC provided Shingles Plus with all of the necessary forms
to become certified with the Illinois Capital Development Board.
Shingles Plus also received assistance in finding bidding
opportunities with many local and federal government agencies in
Illinois.<p>

"The company is small and relatively new. So, I restricted their
bid match profile to Illinois only. I told them that this would
reduce the number of opportunities available. But the company
was very patient. So, when the perfect match was finally found,
they jumped on it with both feet," said Doug Harlan, PTAC
Director.<p>

Once the bidding opportunity was identified, the PTAC provided
assistance in interpreting the solicitation packet, obtaining
required forms, and general encouragement.<p>

Shingles Plus being awarded the contract is immaterial to this
success story. They have successfully entered a new market, one
in which they were not previously involved. The Housing
Authority will continue to keep them on their active contractors
list. This, coupled with the invaluable experience of bidding on
their first government contract, is bound to produce contract
awards in the near future.<p>

There are Procurement Technical Assistance Centers located
throughout Illinois. For the location nearest you call
217/524-0160.<p>

<hr>
<h3>ILLINOIS FEMALE ENTREPRENEURS OVERCOME OBSTACLES</h3>

National trends reveal that women own an increasingly large
proportion of small businesses in the United States. Currently,
women own about 30 percent of all private businesses and are
opening new businesses at twice the rate of their male
counterparts. It is estimated that at current rates of growth,
women could own 50 percent of all businesses by the first decade
of the next century. These figures reflect the hard work and
determination exhibited by women business owners during the past
decade. However, one must be cautious because these positive
national trends obscure the obstacles that continue to hinder
female entrepreneurial success, particularly in Illinois.<p>

A recent survey conducted by John Gruidl and Chris Merrett at
the Illinois Institute for Rural Affairs notes that Illinois
ranks forty-fifth out of fifty states in the proportion of women
who own their own businesses. Women who owned businesses had
higher business failure rates than their male counterparts.
Female business owners simply face more obstacles than their
male competition on the road to business success. <p>

Results from the survey of 712 business owners in downstate
Illinois revealed that female entrepreneurs start businesses
with fewer years of work experience, with less education in
business, with fewer business contacts, and with less startup
capital. Furthermore, female-run businesses tend to be in
sectors such as retail trade and consumer services that
traditionally generate lower profits than sectors dominated by
men such as manufacturing and construction.<p>

The survey also revealed that women continue to be optimistic
about business opportunities in Illinois despite the barriers
blocking their progress. This optimism can be traced in part to
innovative projects such as the mentor program run by Small
Business Development Centers. According to survey results,
business contacts and access to credit after the initial startup
phase are crucial to ongoing business success. Mentor programs
pair experienced female business owners with inexperienced
female entrepreneurs to help them sustain early successes. These
experienced female entrepreneurs can provide access to knowledge
and credit that may be otherwise unattainable.<p>

Overall, the future for businesses run by women seems to be
improving. Research shows that while a gender gap persists in
entrepreneurial success, women are narrowing that gap because of
their optimism, determination and burgeoning support networks.<p>

This research is part of a larger ongoing project conducted by
the Illinois Institute for Rural Affairs to examine the role of
women in rural economic development. Gruidl and Merrett are
currently examining female entrepreneurs in non-metropolitan
counties of Illinois and the Midwest. Early results show that
rural female entrepreneurs experience higher business failure
rates than urban females, or males in either rural or urban
counties. In other words, geographic location can compound the
barriers to female entrepreneurial success. Final results are
expected to be released this fall.<p>


<hr>
<h3>ENTREPRENEURIAL CAMP HELD FOR YOUNG WOMEN</h3>

By Susan E. Nicol<p>

The Illinois Department of Commerce and Community Affairs'
Office of Women's Business Development, in partnership with
DePaul University's Department of Management, successfully
brought Camp Entrepreneur-Chicago to Illinois this past summer.<p>

For over three years, Camp Entrepreneur has operated as an
award-winning residential camp at Seton Hill College in
Pennsylvania, and has provided comprehensive exposure to the
principles of business ownership to its 100+ young women
graduates. Camp Entrepreneur-Chicago was designed as a week-long
commuter day camp for young women in Cook County entering their
junior or senior year in high school interested in owning their
own businesses.<p>

During the week, the campers participated in hands-on seminars
presented by local business professionals who volunteered to
work with the students in areas such as marketing, financing,
management and effective decision making skills, business
communications and technologies, utilization of resources, and
creating a professional image.<p>

One of the week's highlights included a full day devoted to site
visits to Chicago area businesses that are owned and operated by
women. The campers benefited from the presentations and
following discussions as a diverse group of women business
owners shared their experiences, offering information and
experiences they will reflect upon for the rest of their lives.
Another highlight was the campers' development of their own
business plans, which were presented to a panel of business
experts on graduation day. Drawing upon newly acquired
inspiration, the plans reflected the cumulative knowledge and
skills gained throughout the week and true entrepreneurial
approaches. The panelists were unqualifiably impressed! <p>

Historically, young women have not been exposed to
entrepreneurship as a viable career option, nor have they been
introduced to business skills. Camp Entrepreneur-Chicago
graduated sixteen future leaders who are now positioned to
recognize their ability to run their own businesses, and are
equipped with the tools necessary to visualize their own futures
and to create their own opportunities.<p>

With rave reviews from this year's graduates, sponsors, staff,
and Chicagoland's premier media, the Office of Women's Business
Development and DePaul University are already talking about next
year.<p>

Susan E. Nicol is the Women's Business Liaison for the Office of
Women's Business Development of the Illinois Department of
Commerce and Community Affairs' Small Business Division.<p>

