<H2>May, 1996</H2>
</CENTER>

<HR>
<h3>Herb Dennis Represents Illinois on National Committee</h3>

Herbert D. Dennis, Illinois Department of Commerce and Community Affairs Job Training Division Manager, has been appointed to serve on the Executive Committee of the National Association of Workforce Development Liaisons.  On behalf of all state Job Training Partnership Act (JTPA) liaisons, the Association is responsible for developing positions for improving the nation's workforce development strategy.  Appointments to the Executive Committee are limited to ten nationwide; one individual from each U.S. Department of Labor (USDOL) region.  Additionally, Mr. Dennis has been appointed to the Association's Job Training Partnership Transition Committee.  The purpose of this committee is to identify transition issues of the JTPA system as the federal programs move toward block grants.  The committee will work closely with the USDOL and expects to be active in influencing policy changes, identifying transition issues and ensuring the development of a system that will address a wide variety of concerns of employment and training stakeholders.  The National Governors' Association provides staff support to the National Association of Workforce Development Liaisons.<p>

<hr>
<h3>Illinois Human Resource Investment Council Members Announced</h3>

On April 1, 1996, Governor Jim Edgar announced his appointment of the 33-member Human Resource Investment Council.  The Council was established through Public Act 89-0382 for the purpose of creating a state advisory board on workforce preparation policy.  The Council is charged with ensuring that Illinois' workforce preparation services and programs are coordinated and integrated, and measuring and evaluating the overall performance and results of such programs.  Additionally, the Council is to promote a flexible, client-centered, equitable and cost effective workforce preparation system within Illinois.<p>

Lt. Governor Bob Kustra, the Governor's senior advisor on economic development, and  Barry MacLean, President of MacLean-Fogg Company, Mundelein, will serve as Co-Chairs of the Council.  The board's membership includes representatives of the private sector as well as representatives of education, labor and community-based organizations, including:<p>

M. Blouke Carus, Chairman and CEO of Carus Corporation, Peru <p>
Powhatan Collins, Officer for High School Services and Support, Chicago Public Schools, Matteson<p>
