<hr>
<h3>United States Department of Labor's Technical Assistance Guide</h3>

Training conducted by U.S. Department of Labor (USDOL) staff resulted in almost 700 individuals nationwide being exposed to cost allocation strategies which support the establishment of one-stop career centers.  Barry Dale, Financial Manager, and Nick Lammers, Systems Accountant, Division of Financial and Grants Management of Region V of the USDOL Employment and Training Administration, conducted a total of eight Cost Allocation for Integrated Program Delivery Systems training sessions in Austin, Texas; Baltimore, Maryland; San Diego, California; and Chicago, Illinois.  The Sharing Resources to Provide Integrated Services technical assistance guide (TAG), developed by a work group of  federal, state and local staff,    was the basis for the curriculum.<p>

In a drive to improve customer service, many federal employment and training programs have developed a single point of entry in an integrated program setting such as employment and training centers.  Consequently, the programs serve more customer groups, provide a wider range of services and receive funds from multiple funding sources.  The centers have required existing program deliverers to work together to coordinate the delivery of services, co-locate into one facility, or consolidate operations.  The concepts and examples in the TAG illustrate how organizations may approach the allocation of costs in situations where programs with differing enabling legislation and regulations share in the funding of a local program or facility.  There is no implied requirement that these methods be used.<p>

The cost allocation TAG is in final draft and is being circulated among other federal agencies for comment.  The USDOL Office of the Inspector General supports the approach presented in the TAG.  One-stop implementation states may immediately implement this cost allocation approach for USDOL programs on a pilot basis.  If non-USDOL programs also are included in a one-stop career center, grantees should notify and request clearance from the appropriate federal agency in order to use this TAG for allocating non-USDOL costs.<p>

<hr>
<h3>Illinois Employment & Training Center Update</h3>

The state continues to move toward achieving its goal of establishing 40 Illinois Employment & Training Centers (IETCs) by September 1996.  As of the end of March 1996, 34 IETCs exist in the following communities:  Woodstock, Rockford, Freeport, Sterling, Lombard, Maywood, Arlington Heights, Evanston, Chicago, Joliet, Ottawa, LaSalle, Moline, Galesburg, Quincy, Peoria, Bloomington, Pekin, Urbana, Danville, Decatur, Springfield, Jacksonville, Carlinville, Litchfield, Alton, Glen Carbon, Olney, East St. Louis, Belleville, Mt. Vernon, Carterville, Herrin, and Murphysboro.<p>

These offices provide citizens the opportunity to access an array of community services.  The primary focus of the centers is to assist individuals interested in enhancing their employment prospects.  While the services offered through the centers are locally determined, at a minimum the Job Training Partnership Act program training and services, as well as services delivered through local Illinois Department of Employment Security offices, e.g., unemployment insurance and job service, are available at all centers.  In the coming months, look forward to the opening of new centers and expended offering of services throughout Illinois.<p>
  

<hr>
<h3>
Editorial
Illinois Employment & Training Centers and Education-to-Careers
</h3>

Education-to-Careers has been defined as a "community-based education system to prepare all learners for meaningful work."  This definition acknowledges that opportunities for gaining and expressing knowledge and skills, e.g., education, take place in the whole community, not just schools and other educational institutions.  The educational process involves providing direct instruction, influencing instructional content or context, supporting learners to take advantage of the opportunities before them, evaluating the effectiveness of that learned, and enhancing theoretical instruction through direct experience.  With this broad definition in mind, it becomes easier to understand why the State of Illinois requires that the local Education-to-Careers partnership include representation from the Private Industry Council/JTPA Administration.<p>

As envisioned, the Illinois Employment & Training Centers (IETCs) will serve as clearinghouses of information that is relevant to the career preparation process of everyone.  Although this information will be "universally accessible" at the Centers themselves, the technology also will be available to create electronic linkages with other institutions and organizations participating in Education-to-Careers.  How this functions exactly must be determined by the local partners.  As another example, some of the IETCs will have facilities on-site to provide direct instruction, others will not.  Therefore, the role the Centers can play in direct instruction must be locally determined by the Education-to-Careers partnership.  As the responsibilities of various community partners emerge through Education-to-Careers planning, the results should influence  how the  IETCs operate.  As the IETCs evolve, their service delivery offerings should influence how the local Education-to-Careers system functions.<p>

It is important the  Education-to-Careers and the IETC planning and implementation taking place are viewed as complimentary initiatives.  All of the local partners involved in these efforts are trying to provide learners with the best information and opportunities they can access to have meaningful careers.  This goal will only be accomplished if the individuals involved are talking with each other and working together to maximize their resources and use each others strengths.<p>

We encourage active involvement of all of our local IETC partners in the local planning and implementation of Education-to-Careers.  The State of Illinois guarantees you a seat at the table.<p>

<hr>
<h3>Calendar of Events</h3>

May 7-8, 1996<br>
Creative Marketing Techniques For Your One-Stop Career Center<p>

Learn valuable tips for saving money and maximizing time while producing marketing materials with a non-bureaucratic appearance, and utilizing a positive and upbeat approach to marketing job training programs.<p>

May 14-15, 1996<br>
Communication: Is Your Message Clear?<p>

This workshop will concentrate on communication styles, verbal communication, body language, listening skills and business writing.<p>

<hr>
<h3>Resources</h3>

The ILLINOIS WORKFORCE BENCHMARK REPORT, 1995 was developed by the Illinois Job Training Coordinating Council (IJTCC), predecessor to the newly formed Human Resource Investment Council.  The Report's central focus is to respond to the need for "clearer benchmarks of the State's current position and progress toward improvement" identified by both the IJTCC and the Illinois Economic Development Board.  The Report establishes a benchmarking system to regularly assess the status of the workforce preparation system in supporting Illinois' economic competitiveness.<p>

Public/Private Ventures (P/PV) has published an executive summary of MAKING A DIFFERENCE:  AN IMPACT STUDY OF BIG BROTHERS/BIG SISTERS.  The summary is part of P/PV's eight-year investigation of a range of adult-youth relationship projects and provides scientifically reliable evidence that mentoring programs can positively affect young people.<p>

The U.S. Department of Labor has issued the EMPLOYMENT AND TRAINING ADMINISTRATION FY95/PY95 CUSTOMER SATISFACTION REPORT.  The report addresses activities the Employment and Training Administration has undertaken to measure and improve services provided to its program customers and delivery system partners.<p>

The INDIVIDUAL TRAINING VOUCHER SYSTEM,  A PRACTITIONER'S IMPLEMENTATION GUIDE was developed by Onstott Powell and Associates and provides the current best practices for designing and implementing a training voucher system which results in increased customer choice in selecting both the most appropriate training program and training institution.<p>

