<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#8080C0" ALINK="#004080">

<HR>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="/dcca/graph/wforce.gif" WIDTH=272 HEIGHT=109>
<H2>January, 1996</H2>
</CENTER>

<HR>
<H3>WORK ILLINOIS - FIRST IN QUALITY</H3>

Illinois celebrated a year of delivering quality programs and assisting clients realize success at the 1995 Illinois Job Training Partnership Act (JTPA) conference, Work Illinois - First in Quality, on October 26 & 27, 1995 at the Holiday Inn East in Springfield, IL.  Almost 700 employment and training professionals attended the sixth annual conference sponsored by the Illinois Department of Commerce and Community Affairs, the Illinois Employment and Training Partnership, the Illinois Employment and Training Association and the Region V Office of the U.S. Department of Labor.<P>

Over the two-day period attendees chose from among 28 workshops conducted by nationally recognized consultants.  The six workshop tracks offered a variety of information on One-Stop Career Centers, education-to-careers transition programs, customer satisfaction, client services,  management/leadership skills and personal development.  Attendees also were provided the opportunity to visit 34 exhibits to view products and explore services available through organizations and companies.<P>

Norm Bossio, Norm Bossio Enterprises, provided a lively presentation for the opening luncheon entitled "Quality First" which encouraged employment professionals to be serious in delivering quality programs without taking themselves too seriously.  Larry Winget of WIN Seminars! closed the conference with his interpretation of the meaning of success entitled "The Ya Gotta's for Success!" <P>

<HR>
<H3>STATEWIDE AWARD WINNERS HONORED</H3>

The 11th annual Illinois Job Training Partnership Act (JTPA) awards banquet, held the evening of October 26, 1995 as part of the Work Illinois - First in Quality conference, honored 27 JTPA 1995 state award winners.  Dennis R. Whetstone, Director of the Illinois Department of Commerce and Community Affairs, provided the opening remarks for the banquet.  Master of Ceremonies Vince Serritella, Manager of Business Partnerships, Motorola University, presided over the awards ceremony.  Herbert D. Dennis, Illinois Department of Commerce and Community Affairs, Job Training Division Manager, presented the award winners with a plaque honoring their achievements and recognizing their contributions to the JTPA program.  <P>

General Program Awards recognized programs which met the needs of the local economy by using innovations or unique approaches providing JTPA services.  Award winners and their sponsoring JTPA organizations included:  Clean Air Employment and Training Transitional Assistance Program, St. Clair County Intergovernmental Grants Department  Employment & Training Services Division; Enhancing Employment Opportunities For Women Program, Kankakee Community College; Kankakee High School Business Partnership Academy, Grundy Livingston Kankakee Private Industry Council; and Workforce On-Line, Private Industry Council of Northern Cook County (PIC).        <P>

Private Sector Awards were presented to individuals or companies who are members of the private for-profit sector who have made a significant contribution to the JTPA program.  Private Sector award winners and the sponsoring JTPA organizations included:  Abbott Laboratories, The Private Industry Council of Lake County; Steve Husak, Plant Manager of Armstrong World Industries, Inc., Grundy Livingston Kankakee Private Industry Council; and Judith A. Sanders, President and Owner of Select Office Service, Inc., DuPage Private Industry Council/ Job Training. <P>

Collaboration Awards acknowledged special efforts within a community involving various entities which formed effective, ongoing collaborative relationships with the JTPA program.  Collaborative Award winners and sponsors were:  Central Illinois Workforce Network, Central Illinois Private Industry Council; Macon-DeWitt Employment & Training Center, Macon County Employment & Training Grants Administration; Wings at Glenview Naval Air Station, Private Industry Council of Northern Cook County; and the Youth Program, McHenry County Job Training.<P>

The Staff Awards acknowledged JTPA staff who have gone beyond the requirements of their jobs to assist clients to become successful.  Those recognized were:  Kathleen Ahern-Gray, Private Industry Council of Northern Cook County; Carrie Folken, Business Employment Skills Team, Inc.; Len Kaufmann, McHenry County Job Training; and Joyce Mayo, Private Industry Council of Lake County.<P>

Awards also were presented to individuals who overcame significant obstacles to participate in the JTPA program, demonstrated perseverance throughout the program, and attained their academic or work related goals.  The 12 individuals honored in the category and the organizations which assisted these individuals achieve their goals included:  Kimberly Alexander, Private Industry Council, Inc. - SDA 21; Shelli Comer Anderson, Northwest Illinois JTPA; Lorena Balcazar, Private Industry Council, Inc. of Will County; Christy Inboden Bissel, Wabash Area Development, Inc. of SDA 26; Carolyn Chapman, Business Employment Skills Team, Inc.; James Dudley, Rock Island Tri-County Consortium; Elaine Hamilton, Champaign Consortium; Alice Nichols, Rock Valley College Dislocated Worker Program; Cindy Quick, Madison County Employment and Training Department; Bonnie Suggs, DuPage Private Industry Council/ Job Training; Michael Terry, Private Industry Council of Lake County; and Lori Willenborg, Lake Land College Dislocated Worker Program.<P>

The evening concluded with a dance featuring Out of the Woods and hosted by the Illinois Employment and Training Association.<P>

<HR>
<H3>PROFESSIONAL OF THE YEAR</H3>  

Terry Edwards was recognized as the 1995 Professional of the Year at Illinois Employment and Training Association's (IETA) annual awards banquet October 25, 1995.  Edwards serves as the Acting State Director of Green Thumb, Inc. for Illinois.  He began his career in employment and training in 1977 as a public service employee with Green Thumb, Inc. and has held state director posts in Iowa and Illinois.  He is the current 1996 President of IETA, Vice President of Divisions for the Illinois Adult and Continuing Educators Association, and Chairman of the Illinois Older Worker Task Force. <P> 

Funding for Green Thumb, Inc. is authorized under Title V of the Older Americans Act to provide employment and training for low income older Americans, and the organization serves approximately 1200 Illinois participants annually across 38 counties.  Congratulations Terry!<P>

<HR>
<H3>ILLINOIS PIC/CEO CONFERENCE:  POSITIONING FOR THE FUTURE</H3>

Mik Arnett, President of the Illinois Employment and Training Partnership (IETP) welcomed 130 private industry council (PIC) members, chief elected officials (CEOs) and invited guests to the PIC/CEO conference on December 15-16, 1995 at the Ambassador West Hotel in Chicago.  The IETP, an organization whose members are directors of  local service delivery areas which provide quality workforce development in local communities, and the Illinois Department of Commerce and Community Affairs (DCCA) sponsored the event.<P>

The program was designed to provide PIC members and CEOs with the information they need to assume a leadership role in response to national changes affecting local workforce preparation programs.  Dennis Whetstone, Director of DCCA, provided attendees with a perspective of the   changes Illinois' employment and training professionals and their administrating boards will be facing in the coming months.  Rochelle Daniels, the featured speaker, has assisted local leaders nationwide in implementing local workforce development strategies to address the decline in funding levels and the structuring of the one-stop career centers.  Her presentation focused on the impact proposed legislation could have on the current workforce preparation system.<P>

<HR>
<H3>CALENDAR AND RESOURCES</H3>
<PRE>
<EM>February 6 - 7        February 27 - 28
February 8 - 9        February 29 - March 1
Baltimore, Maryland   San Diego, California</EM>
</PRE>
<STRONG>COST ALLOCATION FOR INTEGRATED PROGRAM DELIVERY SYSTEMS TRAINING</STRONG><BR>
Sponsored by the Employment & Training Administration of the U.S. Department of Labor, each one and one-half day training session, offered twice in each city to accommodate schedules, is recommended for financial managers and program planners and will provide a detailed explanation of the Technical Assistance Guide on Cost Allocation for Integrated Program Delivery Systems, including examples, applications and models.<P>

<EM>February 6 - 7</EM><BR>
<STRONG>MANAGING THE "PROFESSIONAL LEVEL" DISLOCATED WORKER</STRONG><BR>
Job search strategy information for upper and mid-level unemployed professionals will be provided including overcoming barriers such as age, qualifications and salary expectations.<P>

<EM>February 21 - 22</EM><BR>
<STRONG>INDEPENDENCE 1996:  YOU CAN DIVERSIFY YOUR ORGANIZATION'S SOURCES OF REVENUE </STRONG><BR>
Learn how nonprofit or public organizations can replace depleted government funding with diversified, self-generating sources of revenue when equipped with the right processes and tools to plan and deliver services and products.<P>

<EM>February 27 - 28 and February 20 - March 1</EM><BR>
<STRONG>CONGRATULATIONS!! YOU'RE A SUPERVISOR!! NOW WHAT??</STRONG><BR>
Each of these two-day sessions will visit the basics of effective supervision, explore common supervisory mistakes, resolve disagreements by converting conflict situations into collaborative relationships and motivate supervisors and staff to work as a successful team.<P>

<EM>March 5 - 6 and March 7 - 8</EM><BR>
<STRONG>AVOIDING BURNOUT/DEVELOPING THE RESOURCES WITHIN</STRONG><BR>
These workshops will explain why burnout is a part of the social service industry today and how it can be overcome.<P>

<EM>March 14</EM><BR>
<STRONG>IT'S ALL IN YOUR MIND! AN INTRODUCTION TO LEARNING STYLES</STRONG><BR>
This workshop explains how personal learning styles affects success in acquiring new job-related knowledge and skills for the 21st century. <P>

If you are interested in attending or obtaining more information regarding upcoming training or require special accommodations, please direct inquiries to Deb Pellegrini at the Illinois Department of Commerce and Community Affairs, 620 East Adams,  Springfield, Illinois 62701, 217/524-8335; TDD, 800/785-6055.<P>

<EM><STRONG>EMPLOYMENT AND TRAINING ADMINISTRATION FY95/PY95 CUSTOMER SATISFACTION REPORT</STRONG></EM> addresses the activities the Employment and Training Administration has undertaken to measure and improve services provided to program customers and delivery system partners for FY95.<P>

<EM><STRONG>ONE-STOP CAREER CENTERS PRODUCTS CATALOGUE</STRONG></EM> provides resource materials related to implementation of One-Stop Career Centers nationally.<P>

The Employment and Training Administration of the U.S. Department of Labor has issued the first Job Corps yearbook, <EM><STRONG>MOVING AHEAD WITH QUALITY</STRONG></EM>, to celebrate the success of graduates from among the 110 Job Corps campuses across the nation.<P>


