<H1>The University of Maryland</H1><IMG SRC="Building.gif" HEIGHT=200 WIDTH=300 ALIGN=RIGHT>

<H1>Department of Microbiology</H1>
1109 Microbiology Building<br>
University of Maryland<br>
College Park, MD&nbsp;&nbsp;20742<br>
301/405-5435<br>
<UL>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.life.umd.edu/grad/micb/index.html">Graduate Program</A></LI>

<LI><A HREF="micbUgrad.html">Undergraduate program</A></LI>

<LI>Research - Alphabetical listing of <A HREF="http://www.life.umd.edu/grad/micb/fac-list.html">Faculty
</A></LI>
</UL>

<P>
<HR WIDTH="100%"></P>

<H3><A NAME="History"></A>History</H3>

<P>The College Park campus of the University of Maryland has a long history
of teaching and research in Microbiology. In l885, Dr. Thomas Taylor was
&quot;lecturer in microscopy&quot;, and Professor F. Lamson-Scribner, of
the United States Department of Agriculture, presented a course on fungi.
Since these early beginnings, when the College Park institution was still
known as the Maryland Agricultural College, interest in bacteria and related
microorganisms has continued without interruption. </P>

<P>From 1885 until the founding of the Department, various courses in bacteriology
were offered on the campus. The Department of Microbiology historically
is one of the oldest departments on campus having originated in 1922 as
the Department of Bacteriology and Sanitation. It grew out of an agricultural
base with expanded course offerings by two veterinarians around l917. The
name was changed to The Department of Pathology and Bacteriology in 1929
and the first departmental Ph.D. was awarded in 1931 to William Malcolm,
who went on to become Chairman of the Board of American Cyanamid Corporation.
The faculty soon included Dr. John E. &quot;Jack&quot; Faber, who later
became Chair of the Department in 1946 and remained so until 1968. During
Dr. Faber's tenure, the Department first gained its national recognition.
Since 1968 there have been only three other permanent chairs of the Department.
</P>

<P>Dr. Sam W. Joseph was the Chair from 1981 to 1989. Dr. Frank Hetrick
was Acting Chair from 1989 until his retirement in 1992. Dr. Albert Ades,
an Associate Professor in the Department of Zoology, succeeded Dr. Hetrick
as the Acting Chair in 1992, and was made permanent chair in 1995. </P>

<P>Since 1989, there have been significant changes and improvements in
both the undergraduate and graduate programs. A new graduate program has
been approved and implemented. The numbers of students in the undergraduate
program are at an all-time high with students being turned away from many
courses for lack of space. We have recently hired faculty whose interests
reflect the change in orientation of the Department. The nucleus of a eukaryotic
contingent has been formed with the addition of a virologist and a three
immunologist. The Department is evolving to fill a niche within the college
focusing on prokaryotic biology and immunology/virology. </P>

<H3><A NAME="accompl"></A>Accomplishments</H3>

<P>The Department of Microbiology has demonstrated strength in its educational
and service activities and with the addition of several new faculty members,
the potential for increased research activity is quite large </P>

<UL>
<LI>Contract and grant funding has ranged from approximately $575,000 to
$830,000 during the period FY '89 to FY '94.</LI>

<LI>The faculty average 2.4 research publications per faculty member each
year.</LI>

<LI>We hired three new faculty members in 1993-1994.</LI>

<LI>Our graduate program has been revised.</LI>

<LI>We graduated an average of 6 Ph.D. and 3 M.S. students each year.</LI>

<LI>We teach over 1000 undergraduates each year, and the numbers are increasing.</LI>

<LI>We graduate 40-60 Microbiology majors each year.</LI>

<LI>Our faculty receives high evaluation marks for teaching and advising.
</LI>

<LI>We have approved a new departmental Honors program.</LI>

<LI>We have increased the total number of students taught</LI>
</UL>

<H3>Mission of the Department: </H3>

<P>To provide training in Microbiology and its related disciplines to our
undergraduate majors integrating practical laboratory skills with theoretical
concepts,</P>

<UL>
<LI>to provide to the College and University courses that convey the discipline
of Microbiology including the fields of Virology, Immunology and Molecular
Biology, </LI>

<LI>to provide our graduate students with general training in the field
of Microbiology as well as specialized training in their area of research
interest,</LI>

<LI>to provide an environment that fosters and rewards research, teaching,
and other scholarly pursuits of our faculty and students,</LI>

<LI>to educate the larger community as to the importance of, and the benefits
derived from, the field of Microbiology,</LI>

<LI>and to interact with surrounding industrial and federal laboratories
to provide expertise in the fields of Microbiology and Biotechnology.</LI>
</UL>

<P>
