<head>
<TITLE>Department of Zoology</TITLE>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<img align=left vspace=3 hspace=3 src="jfishsm.gif" alt="[picture of jelly fish]">
<center><h1>University of Maryland<br>at College Park<br>College of Life Sciences<br>
<p>
<font size=+5>Department of Zoology</font></center></h1>
<p>
<br clear=left><br>
<p>
The Department of Zoology offers graduate training in many areas
of biology, with particular emphasis in three broad areas:  Cellular
and Molecular Biology; Neurobiology; and Ecology, Evolution, and Behavior.
<p>
The <font size=+1>Cellular and Molecular Biology</font> group includes faculty and adjunct 
professors with research interests in Gene Regulation, Metabolic Regulation,
Signal Transduction, Physiology, Membrane Biology, Cell Differentiation, 
and Cell Motility.  Organisms from protists to marine invertebrates to mammals
are used in research.  These faculty interact closely with inter-campus
<a href="/grad/mocb.html">Molecular and Cell Biology Graduate Program</a>.
<p>
The <font size=+1>Neurobiology</font> group consists of faculty members who are allied
closely with the new <a href="http://www.inform.umd.edu/PNACS"> Program in Neuroscience
and Cognitive Science</a>.  Research interests among the Zoology 
neurobiologists include Sensory Physiology, Audition, Neurophysiology, Developmental 
Biology, Neuroethology, Motor Systems, Behavioral Physiology, and Neuromuscular 
Physiology.  Research involves a variety of organisms, including horseshoe crabs, 
jawless and jawed fishes, owls and small mamals. 
<p>
The <font size=+1>Ecology, Evolution, and Behavior</font> group includes faculty and
adjunct professors with primary interests in Population, Community, and Evolutionary
Ecology, Plant/Animal Interactions, Evolutionary Biology (including Functional
Morphology, Paleontology, Systematics, and Molecular Evolution), and Behavioral Biology.
Field Studies include marine, fresh water, and terrestrial environments in tropical
as well as temperate locales.  A number of our ecology and evolution faculty are actively 
involved in the growing convservation biology program at UMCP.
<p>

<font size=+1>
<b>Positions Available in the Department of Zoology:</b>
<ul>
   <li><a href=http://www.life.umd.edu/positions/index.html#chair><b>Chair and Professor of Biological Sciences</b></a>
   <li><a href=http://www.life.umd.edu/positions/index.html#zool><b>Assistant Professor, Physiology (tenure track)</b></a>
</ul>
</font><p>

<b>Zoology Laboratories Online:</b>
<ul>
