<head><title>Howard Hughes Medical Institute</title>
<head>
<!--body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" link="#2F4F2F" vlink="#D98719" alink="#FFFFFF" background="back4.gif">
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="back4.gif">

<center>
<a href=http://www.hhmi.org><img src="hhmi.gif" align=left></a>
<font size=+2>Undergraduate Research Fellowships</font>
<hr width=30%>
<font size=-1>Sponsored by the</font><br>
<b>Howard Hughes Medical Institute<br>
and the<br>
<a href="http://www.life.umd.edu/">College of Life Sciences</a>, University of Maryland at College Park
</b></center>
<br clear=all>
<p>
<img src=const2.gif align=left>Please excuse the dust...These pages are still
under construction...
<br clear=all>
<p>

<blockquote>
<a href=http://www.hhmi.org>The Howard Hughes Medical Institute (HHMI)</a> has selected the College of Life Sciences
at the University of Maryland, College Park, as the recipient of a $1.3 million
award.  HHMI funds innovative proposals to improve undergraduate education in the biological
sciences at selected American colleges and universities.  The participating institutions are
those "with demonstrable records in preparing students for graduate education and careers in
research, teaching, or the practice of medicine."  Selection criteria include the percentage
and number of graduates who attend medical schools, earn doctorates in the sciences, and the
quality of an institution's programs.
</blockquote>

<p>

<center>
<a href="applications.html"><font size=+1>Applications and Information</font></a>
<p>

<a href="http://www.life.umd.edu/zoology/paynterlab/Kenhome.html"><b>Dr. Kennedy Paynter</a> Program Coordinator &#164; 1221 Symons Hall &#164; (301) 405-3353<br>
<a href="bh-cv.html">Dr. William Higgins</a> Program Director &#164; 1212 Symons Hall &#164; (301) 405-2908<br>
HHMI Undergraduate Research Fellowship Program &#164; College of Life Sciences<br>
University of Maryland &#164 College Park, MD 20742-5565
</b></center>

<p>

<h3>Program Objectives</h3>
The HHMI Undergraduate Research Fellowship Program establishes important student-mentor
relationships with the very best research faculty in the College of Life Sciences. Fellows
are exposed to the entire scope of the investigative process--from formulating questions,
hypotheses, and experiments in a grant-style proposal to conducting experiments, analyzing
data, drawing conclusions, and defending and publishing a finished product. Upon completion
of their degrees, fellows are well prepared for careers in basic and applied biomedical research
and in the health professions.

<p>

<h3>Financial Support</h3>
The program offers academic year stipends of $1,800 as well as $2,000 summer awards. Fellows
compete for supplemental grant funds of $500 to $2,000 to offset the direct costs of the
research project.  Summer fellows in residence at College Park may request a housing allowance
of $1,100.

<p>

<h3>Application Procedures</h3>
Fellowship applications are accepted each Fall and Spring semester.  Candidates are expected to
hold junior or senior standing with a competitive grade point average (minimum of 3.0) and have
completed at least one upper-level laboratory course within the College.  Candidates are also
encouraged to be members of a departmental honors program.<p>

Applications consist of grant-format project proposals, project budgets, and letters of support
from the faculty sponsor.  Applicants are evaluated by a panel of UMCP faculty.  Before
submitting a proposal, applicants are encouraged to develop and discuss their research project
with appropriate faculty investigators.
<p>
