<html>
<head>
<title>Biology of Small Populations: A Research and Training Program</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">

<!-- When you have an "aligned image", as above align=right, the text following-->
<!-- it will not move underneath the picture unless you have a special <br> tag-->
<!-- e.g.  <br clear=right> or <br clear=left> or <br clear=all> to end the -->
<!-- alignment.-->


<h1>
  Biology of Small Populations:<br> 
A Research and Training Program</h1>
<h2>University of Maryland College Park and the <br>
Smithsonian Institution</h2>
<br>
<p>
  The Program on the Biology of Small Populations is a collaborative enterprise of
  several departments at the <a href=http://www.umcp.umd.edu>University of Maryland, College Park</a>, 
  and several branches of 
  the <a href=http://www.si.edu>Smithsonian Institution</a>.  It was funded as part of the National
  Science Foundation's Research Training Group Program in 1996.  The goals of the program are to carry out
  research on the biological consequences of small population sizes and to train students
  and postdoctoral scientists in this area.  The underlying rationale for the program is the
  perceived need for a "basic science" approach to the implications of small or greatly
  reduced population sizes.  Such an approach can help form and strengthen the foundation
  for applied work in conservation biology.  Given the rapid rate at which many biological
  populations are being reduced, a greater understanding of all aspects of the biology of
  small populations is urgently needed.  Faculty participants in the program come from a
  wide variety of disciplines within organismal biology, and promoting interdisciplinary
  work is one of the reasons for founding the group.
<p>
<ul>
<li><b><a href=whatisit.html>What is it?</a></b>
<p>
<li><b><a href=whoare.html>Who are the Faculty? </a></b>
<p>
<li><b><a href=postdoc.html>Interested in a Post Doctoral Fellowship?</a></b>
<p>
<li><b><a href=doctoral.html>Interested in a Doctoral Fellowship?</a></b>
<p>
<li><b>Interested in a Undergraduate Opportunities?</b>
<p>
<li><b><a href=current.html>Are you currently a UMD student?</a></b>
</ul>
<p> <hr align=center width=93% size=3> <p>
<b>Go to: <a href=http://www.inform.umd.edu:8080/EdRes/Colleges/LFSC/.FacultyStaff/dinouye/BEES/>
Behavior, Evolution, Ecology, and Systematics (BEES)</a></b>
<p> 
<b>Go to: <a href=http://www.life.umd.edu/>Life Science Home Page</a></b>
<p>
<b>Go to: <a href=http://www.inform.umd.edu:8080/EdRes/GradInfo/.WWW/grad/>Graduate School</a></b>
<p> 
<b>Go to: <a href=http://www.umcp.umd.edu/>University of Maryland Home Page</a></b>
<p>  
<hr>
<center>
<font size=-1><address> 
For information and application forms Email <A
HREF="mailto:bsp-rtg@zool.umd.edu">bsp-rtg@zool.umd.edu</A><br>
Department of Zoology, University of Maryland, College Park, Maryland
20742-4415 (USA).<br>
Comments and suggestions about this page can be directed to <A
HREF="mailto:paintner@zool.umd.edu">paintner@zool.umd.edu</A><br>
