<HTML>
<Head>
<!--body Background=Satpic5.gif BGcolor=#439746 link=#c4000f Vlink=#FDF502-->
<body BGcolor=#3399cc link=#c4000f Vlink=#FDF502>

<title>NSCSD</title>
<center><H1>NSCSD</H1>
<H2>The North South Center</H2>
for
<H2>Sustainable Development</H2>
<H4>At the University of Maryland</H4></center>
<HR>
<body>
<center>
<TABLE BORDER>
<TR><ROWSPAN=3>
<TR><ALIGN=LEFT><TD><A HRef="northsouth.html">North South Center</a><TD><A HRef="glt.html">Golden Lion Tamarin</a>
<TR><ALIGN=LEFT><TD><A HRef="ied-big.html">Ilha Grande Bay, Brazil</a><TD><A HRef="tep.html">Tropical Ecosystem Program</a>
<TR><ALIGN=LEFT><TD><A HRef="bahia.html">Vera Cruz Florestal</a>
</TABLE>
</center>
<HR>
<h4><img src=NSCSD2.gif align=left>The North South Center for 
Sustainable Development at the University of Maryland is the 
creation of the late Dr. Cyril Ponnamperuma of the University of 
Maryland It is presently lead by co-directors 
<A Href="mailto:dietz@zool.umd.edu">Professor James Dietz</a> 
for South American Programs and 
<A Href="mailto:rk13@umail.umd.edu">Professor Raj Khanna</a> for 
African and Asian Programs.<p>
<Br>
<HR>
<HR>
<A HRef="northsouth.html"><img src=NSCSD2.gif align=left>An overview</A> 
of the North South Center for Sustainable Development. The alarming 
growth in the technology and industry gap between the nations of the 
North and South and the environmental destruction which has 
accompanied unplanned economic development in the Third World now 
pose grievous threats to the global habitat. The efforts of Less 
developed nations to build human capital and assert themselves in 
the global marketplace need to go hand-in-hand with efforts to 
preserve the environment and enrich the quality of life. The North 
South Center for Sustainable Development in the College of Life 
Sciences, University of Maryland, College Park, is committed to 
efforts to improve communication and the exchange and training of 
personnel with these less developed nations. <p>
<HR>
<center><img src=BahiaMap1.gif align=left><hspace=2 vspace=2>
<img src=BahiaMap2.gif align=right></center><Br><Br>
The<A HRef="bahia.html">Vera Cruz Florestal Project</A> is located 
in Southern Bahia near the coastal city of Porto Seguro, site of 
the first permanent settlement in Brazil. This area of Bahia was 
once almost totally covered by Atlantic Rain Forest. Unrestricted 
cutting of the forest and conversion to low quality pasture land 
has led to a situation where less than 5% of the original forest 
remains. The change from 1946 to 1990 is dramatically illustrated 
in the two maps (above.) University of Maryland scientists are 
collaborating with local investigators to study several interesting 
questions having to do with biodiversity and sustainable development.
<p>
<Hr>
<A HRef="glt.html"><img src=NSCSD2.gif align=left></A><Br>
<A HRef="glt.html">The Golden Lion Tamarin</A> is an endangered 
primate native to Brazil. Researchers at the University of Maryland 
are studying methods of protecting and nurturing these small animals 
to prevent their extinction while expanding habitat and reintroducing 
captive-born offspring.
<br>
<br>
<Hr>
<A HRef="ied-big.html"><img src=NSCSD2.gif align=left></A><Br>
The Institute for Sustainable Development in <A HRef="ied-big.html">
Ilha Grande Bay</A> is a project of a consortium of universities, 
industry, and government organizations. Its mission is to 
establish sustainable development programs while protecting the 
local environment. You can learn what this group of institutions is 
doing to improve the health of the marine habitat in Ilha Grande Bay.
<br>
<br>
<Hr>
<!--center><!--img src=Monk.gif align=center><!--/Center><Br><Br>
<A HRef="grad.html">Conservation Biology</A> is a graduate program 
at the University of Maryland. Students are involved in an intensive 
program encompassing environmental and biological sciences and 
policies.<p>
<Hr>
<A HRef="tep.html"><img src=NSCSD2.gif align=left></A><Br><A HRef="tep.html">The Tropical 
Ecosystem Program</A> is a joint venture of Universidade Federal Fluminense, 
Universidade Estadual do Rio de Janeiro, Universidade Federal do Rio de Janeiro, 
Universidade de S&#227o Paolo, and the University of Maryland. The Purpose of TEP is to 
promote research and education initiatives involving tropical rain forests.<p>
<Hr>
<Br>
<Br>
We are providing information on a variety of the individual projects 
which are being conducted in conjunction with NSCSD. In keeping with 
the environmentally conscious ideals of the center, this information 
is provided in below Adobe PDF (Portable Document Format) format, and while 
there are limited hard copies of these papers available, electronic 
publishing is environmentally conscious. Not only is the information 
readily available, it conserves valuable resources by using less 
paper and not requiring physical distribution. More information on  
Adobe Acrobat and PDF can be obtained at the 
<A HRef="http://www.adobe.com/acrobat/readstep.html">Adobe web site</A>, 
where you can download a free version of the Acrobat PDF reader. 
If you are using Netscape Navigator 2.0 you can obtain a plug-in 
that will allow you to view these documents within Netscape.<p></h4>
<center>
<TABLE BORDER>
<TR><ROWSPAN=3>
<th colspan=3>Adobe PDF Files
<TR><ALIGN=LEFT><TD><A HRef="NSCSD.pdf">North South Center</a><TD><A HRef="GLT.pdf">Golden Lion Tamarin</a>
<TR><ALIGN=LEFT><TD><A HRef="IED-BIG.pdf">Ilha Grande Bay, Brazil</a><TD><A HRef="TEP.PDF">Tropical Ecosystem Program</a>
<TR><ALIGN=LEFT><TD><A HRef="Bahia.pdf">Vera Cruz Florestal</a><TD><a href=Grad.pdf>Conservation Biology</a>
</TABLE>
</center>
<Hr>
<ADDRESS>
Page Design, Graphics, & PDF files - Pete Mazzocchi<br>
PeteCM@AOL.com<br>
</ADDRESS>
</body>
