<html>
<head><title>Maryland Association of Biology Teachers</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<img align=left vspace=5 hspace=5 src=mabt.gif alt="Logo for MABT" >
<center>
<font size=+3><b>Maryland Association of Biology Teachers</b></font>
</center><br clear=all><p>
    
 Maryland Association of Biology Teachers was founded in
1934 by a group of high school and college biology
teachers.  The first meeting was held at Western Maryland
College in the Spring of 1934, and the topic was "What's
New in Diatom Research?"  Dr. Lloyd Bertolf, Professor of
Biology, Western Maryland College served as the first
president.  A constitution was not written and adopted
until 1942 and the annual dues were seventy-five cents. 
No meetings were held during the war years of 1943, 1944,
and 1945, presumably because of gas rationing.
<p>
The goals of MABT were to:
<p>
<ul>
<li>increase and disseminate the knowledge related to the
       biological sciences,<p>
<li>study and promote new trends and methods relative to
       the teaching of biology and life sciences,<p>
<li>protect and maintain high ethics and standards of the
       teaching profession,<p> 
<li>maintain high ethics and standards of the teaching
       profession, and recognize special accomplishments in
       biology teaching.
</ul>
<p>
<hr width=45%>
<p>
<center><b>       
Maryland Association of Biology Teachers
<p>                               
1997 Spring Meeting,
<p>
<h2><i>Connections</i></h2>

March 14 & 15, 1997
<p>
University of Maryland, College Park
</b></center><p>
<hr width=45%>
<p>
The Spring 1997 MABT meeting will be held March 14
and 15 at College Park.  Hosted and co-sponsored by UMCP's
College of Life Sciences, the 1997 meeting will focus on
the theme of "<i><b>Connections</b></i>".  This theme refers to the
major goals and objectives of this meeting:
<p>
to establish connections:
<p>
<ul>
<li>among high school and middle school
           colleagues,<p> 
           
<li>among these teachers and their
           university counterparts,<p>
           
<li>with current ideas and innovations in
           laboratory instruction, the
           instructional resources on the Internet
           and World Wide Web, and relevant
           vendors and publishers.
</ul>
<p>

The MABT organizers recognize the importance of a
well attended, high quality forum for the exchange of
ideas.  To accomplish the stated objectives and facilitate
the formation of connections, support must be obtained
from the State, from UMCP, and from the private sector.
<p>
A future mailing will include registration forms, a
finalized program agenda, and travel and lodging
information.  Please mark your calendars and reserve 14
and 15 March <font size=+1>NOW!</font>
<p>
<hr width=45%>
<p>
<center>
