<html>
<head
<title>JOINT INSTITUTE FOR FOOD SAFETY AND APPLIED NUTRITION</title>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><h2>JOINT INSTITUTE FOR FOOD SAFETY AND APPLIED NUTRITION</h2></center>
<p>
The Joint Institute for Food Safety and Applied Nutrition (JIFSAN) is 
a cooperative venture of the Federal Food and Drug Administration (FDA) 
and the University of Maryland at College Park (UMCP).  The Director of 
JIFSAN is a tenured Professor at UMCP and reports to an Executive Committee 
consisting of personnel from UMCP and FDA.  JIFSAN will operate on a budget 
provided by UMCP and FDA, as well as research grant, contract, and gift 
funds.  The mission of JIFSAN is to establish and carry out cooperative 
research and education programs that are consistent with the mission of 
FDA and UMCP.  Examples include:  food safety and nutrition research programs, 
including cooperative research programs between JIFSAN and other federal, 
state and private organizations;  and the development  of educational programs, 
including academic  courses, short courses, workshops, and seminars;  and 
programs for student internships, visiting scholars, industrial research 
fellows, and executive training.
<p>
FDA is the lead United States regulatory agency responsible for assuring the 
safety of the nation's food supply.  The Center for Food Safety and Applied 
Nutrition (CFSAN) has responsibilities for research, policy, and regulation 
in food safety, nutrition, food labeling, and cosmetics.  The Center for 
Veterinary Medicine (CVM) has responsibilities for research, policy, and 
regulation of animal drugs, food additives, feed ingredients, and medical 
devices.  FDA's mission in food safety, applied nutrition, and veterinary 
medicine is to ensure that:
<p>
1.  The food supply is microbiologically, nutritionally and toxicologically 
safe and wholesome and cosmetics are safe.
<p>
2.  Food and cosmetic products are honestly, accurately and informatively labeled.
<p>
3.  Animal drugs, food additives, feed ingredients, and medical devices are 
safe and effective.
<p>
FDA carries out its mission with a staff that includes a large cadre of 
chemists, microbiologists, biologists, toxicologists, nutritionists, food 
technologists, physicians, and veterinarians.  JIFSAN will reside in a new 
$84M laboratory/office at the College Park/University of Maryland Metro site 
as well as FDA's existing state-of-the-art animal testing facilities in close 
proximity at Beltsville, MD.  Selected CFSAN scientists will have adjunct and 
research faculty positions at UMCP.  JIFSAN scientists will also participate 
in FDA regulatory policy and review functions.  The participation  of JIFSAN 
scientists in research programs related to the FDA regulatory activities and 
the consultative arrangements with other scientists that will be facilitated 
by JIFSAN will ensure the critical science-based foundation for FDA regulatory 
policy.  JIFSAN will expand FDA collaborative research networks, such as are 
underway at FDA's National Center for Food Safety and Technology.
<p>
UMCP is the most comprehensive research and educational institution of the 
national capital region, with programs in a broad spectrum of disciplines.  
UMCP programs that are particularly relevant to the FDA mission include 
nutrition, chemistry, biology, food science, microbiology, animal science, 
veterinary medicine, public policy, statistics, computer science, communications, 
and survey methodology.  In addition, the UMCP campus provides excellent research, 
library and computer infrastructure facilities to all of these programs.  JIFSAN, 
as a collaborative venture of FDA and UMCP, will enhance the availability of 
these programs and facilities for public policy purposes while expanding the 
educational research and training programs of both institutions.
</DOC>
