<b><u><p>
Objectives</u></b>:<p>
<p>
1.	Discuss the function and regulation of the organ systems of mammalian
organisms.<p>
2.	Come to an understanding of these systems through a series of self-paced,
comprehensive laboratory exercises.<p>
3.	Enjoy ourselves and create a classroom environment conducive to
<u>active</u> learning and <u>independent</u> investigation.<p>
<b><u><p>
Prerequisites</u></b>:  Zoology 211 and Chemistry 233 (as listed in the UMCP
Undergraduate Catalog).<p>
<p>
	All students are expected to be familiar with the following topics from Zool
211.  You will have the opportunity to review some of them in laboratory.
Refer to the <b><i>optional</i></b>  exercises on <b><i>muscle structure and
function </i></b>and <b><i>neurosys</i> </b>located in the laboratory section
of this volume.<p>
-Lipids and cell membranes<p>
-Membrane permeability and transport	<b>Please note that these topics are
also</b><p>
-Osmotic pressure			<b>	all covered in unassigned sections of</b><p>
-Muscle contraction			<b>	your textbook.</b><p>
-Membrane potentials and action potentials<b><u><p>
Lecture</u></b>:	Monday, Wednesday, and Friday @ 8:00 A.M. in ZOP 1240<p>
<p>
	All lectures will be taped and copies will be available for student use in the
NonPrint Media Center, Room 4210, Hornbake Library.  Request a tape by the
course (Zoology 422) and the date of the lecture.  It usually takes two working
days to copy a lecture tape for distribution.  Twenty-two years of 422 history
have shown that students gaining an extra hour of sleep and relying on lecture
tapes do not fare well!  Use these tapes as a lecture supplement, not as a
substitute!<p>
<b><u><p>
Textbook</u></b>:<p>
Rhoades, R.A. and G.A. Tanner (1995) <i>Medical Physiology</i>, First Edition,
Little, Brown and Co., Boston, MA.<p>
<p>
(Please note that this text was selected by a panel of former and current ZOOL
422 students.  You may also elect to use the text assigned last year, Rhoades
& Pflanzer (1992) <i>Human Physiology</i>, Second Edition, Saunders
Publishing Co., N.Y.)<b><u><p>
<p>
Laboratory Manual</u></b>:<p>
