<H1><FONT COLOR="#800000">Department of Microbiology (MICB)</FONT></H1>

<H4>
<HR size=4 width="100%"></H4>

<H4>Chair: Ades <BR>
Professors: Colwell, Gantt, Joseph, Weiner, Yuan <BR>
Associate Professors: Benson, Hutcheson, Stein <BR>
Assistant Professors: DeStefano, Farber, Pontzer, Song, Stewart <BR>
Instructors: Gdovin, Smith<BR>
Emeritus Faculty: Cook, Doetsch, Hetrick, Pelczar, Roberson</H4>

<H3>Undergraduate Program</H3>

<P>A major in Microbiology is offered through the Biological Sciences Program.
Microbiology is a field fundamental to all of biology. Microorganisms provide
the primary steps in the food chain. The metabolic pathways and genetic
systems within bacteria have served as stepping stones for later discoveries
in other systems. Specialization in the field of microbiology encompasses
not only study of the fundamental processes of bacteria, but also the examination
of animal, plant and bacterial viruses, animal and plant defense systems
that counter infection and invasion by microorganisms. Microbiology, including
subfields of virology and immunology, continues to be at the forefront
of scientific investigation. Microbiological principles are being applied
in ecology, biotechnology, medicine, agriculture and the food industry.
The field is full of potential. Students of microbiology will find opportunities
in academia, industry, medicine, public health, biotechnology and law.</P>

<H3>Requirements for MICB Specialization</H3>

<P>Students who choose to declare a specialization in MICB should do so
by visiting the College of Life Sciences Office, 1224 Symons Hall. A Bachelors
degree at UMCP requires that students complete 120 credits. Students must
complete:</P>

<P><IMG SRC="yelball.gif" HEIGHT=14 WIDTH=14>The <A HREF="reqmts.html">basic
requirements of the Biological Sciences Program</A></P>

<P><IMG SRC="yelball.gif" HEIGHT=14 WIDTH=14><A NAME="Advanced"></A><A HREF="reqmts.html">Advanced
Program in the area of Microbiology</A> (this link includes a suggested
4-year <A NAME="curriculum"></A>curriculum for Microbiology majors)</P>

<P><IMG SRC="yelball.gif" HEIGHT=14 WIDTH=14><A HREF="http://www.inform.umd.edu:8080/EdRes/UgradInfo/GeneralEducation/.WWW/index.html">University
CORE&nbsp;Program</A>. </P>

<H3>Advising</H3>

<P>All students in the Biological Sciences Program are required to see
an advisor each semester. Students who choose to specialize in Microbiology
will be assigned to one of our faculty for advising. General questions
regarding advising should be directed to the Coordinating Advisor, <A HREF="mailto:asmith@microb.umd.edu">Dr.
Ann Smith.</A><I> </I></P>

<H3>Research Experience and Internships</H3>

<P>Students may gain research experience in laboratories off campus with
cooperating institutions such as NIH, Walter Reed and USUHS, by registering
for MICB 388R or on campus in faculty laboratories by registering for MICB
399. These courses can be used for credit to the MICB&nbsp;major. The research
commitment is usually for one semester. Students interested in a long term
research commitment are encouraged to apply to the Microbiology Honors
Program.</P>

<H3>Honors and Awards</H3>

<P>Each year one outstanding senior, graduating in the field of Microbiology,
will be honored by faculty vote to receive the Sigma Alpha Omicron Award.
This honored student receives an individual award and their name is added
to a plaque of previous SAO&nbsp;recipients which is displayed in the Atrium
of the Microbiology Building. Sigma Alpha Omicron is a UMCP&nbsp;undergrduate
honor society for microbiologists. Students who achieve a GPAof 3.0 overall
and a 3.5 in microbiology courses after completing 11 credits in microbiology
courses, are invited to the society. Students completing the Microbiology
Honors Program are eligible for the Arne P. Hanson Award. The award is
given to the student, who by faculty vote, has had the most outstanding
honors project during that year. These awards are given yearly in the spring
at the SAO&nbsp;initiation ceremony.</P>

<H3>Student Organizations</H3>

<P>Our department houses a student chapter of the <A HREF="http://www.asmusa.org/">American
Society for Microbiology</A>. The group plans academic and social events
that would be of interest to any student interested in Microbiology or
related fields. Leave a message in the ASM mailbox (MICB Building, room
1109) and a member will contact you with more information. Sigma Alpha
Omicron, the Microbiology Honor Society, serves as a subcommittee of the
ASM student chapter.</P>

<P><IMG SRC="yelball.gif" HEIGHT=14 WIDTH=14><B><A HREF="http://www.life.umd.edu/grad/micb/fac-list.html">Microbiology
Faculty List</A></B></P>

<P><IMG SRC="yelball.gif" HEIGHT=14 WIDTH=14><B><A HREF="http://www.life.umd.edu/grad/micb/index.html">Graduate
Program in Microbiology </A></B></P>

<P><IMG SRC="yelball.gif" HEIGHT=14 WIDTH=14><B><A HREF="http://www.inform.umd.edu:8080/ugradcat/">University
of Maryland Undergraduate Catalog On-line</A></B></P>

