<HTML>
<head>
<TITLE>Graduate Programs - Molecular and Cell Biology</TITLE>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" link="#2F4F2F" vlink="#D98719" alink="#FFFFFF">
<img align=left vspace=3 hspace=3 src="mocb.gif" alt="Picture of DNA here...">
<center>
<h3> University of Maryland<br>College of Life Sciences<br>Graduate Programs<br></h3>
<strong><font size=+3>Molecular and Cell Biology (MOCB)</font></strong><br>
</center>
<p>
<hr size=8 width=60%>
<br clear=left><br>
<p>
Fifty-five faculty members from nine departments, the Virginia/Maryland Regional College of
Veterinary Medicine, two centers of the Maryland Biotechnology Institute, and the National
Institutes of Health are affiliated with the
program, providing individual training and guidance for students.  
<p>
<strong>Requirements for Admission:</strong><p>
<ul>
<li>At least a B.S. degree from a regionally accredited institution (or the international equivalent)
<li>An overall grade point average of 3.0
<li>GRE General Test scores
<li>TOEFL scores from international applicants
<li>Three letters of recommendation from professional or academic references
<li>A statement of purpose for pursuing the degree, including goals and objectives
for future work in the field.
</ul>
<p>
<strong>Areas of Emphasis:</strong><p><center>
<i>
<img src="red2.gif">Biochemistry
<img src="red2.gif">Biophysics
<img src="red2.gif">Cell Biology
<img src="red2.gif">Developmental Biology
<img src="red2.gif">Genetics
<img src="red2.gif">Immunology
<img src="red2.gif">Neurobiology
<img src="red2.gif">Oncology
<img src="red2.gif">Plant Sciences
<img src="red2.gif">Prokaryotic Biology
<img src="red2.gif">Virology<p>

<a href="mocb/research.html">List of Faculty by Research Subject</a></center>

</i></blockquote>
<hr><P>

<h3> Introduction </h3><P>

The graduate program in molecular and cell biology at the <a
href="http://www.umcp.umd.edu">University of Maryland College Park (UMCP) </a> offers
study leading to the Doctor of Philosophy degree.  The program is multidisciplinary and
interdepartmental, supported by faculty from the Departments of Plant Biology,
Chemistry and Biochemistry, Entomology, Microbiology, and Zoology in the College of Life
Sciences; the Departments of Agronomy, Animal Sciences, Horticulture and Poultry Science in
the College of Agriculture; Virginia-Maryland Regional College of Veterinary Medicine; the
Center for Agricultural Biotechnology and the Center for Advanced Research in Biotechnology in
the Maryland Biotechnology Institute; and from several institutes in the National Institutes of
Health.</p> 
<p> The core requirements of the program consist of four lecture courses in molecular and cell
biology, genetics, and biochemistry and two one-semester rotations in the laboratories of the
participating faculty.  After completion of the core requirements, usually in
the first year, each student must take three semesters of advanced, second-level courses in
specialty areas and topical subjects tailored to his or her development and needs.  Students are
required to attend weekly seminars, sponsored by the program, in which outstanding
molecular/cell biologists from other institutions and this campus give presentations about their
ongoing research.<p>
The UMCP student body is composed of persons from every state and sixty other countries.   The
graduate programs at UMCP are quite vigorous.  For example, about 250 graduate students are
enrolled in the College of Life Sciences. <p>
<hp>
<h3>Finances</h3>
The program offers teaching assistantships and research assistantships to admitted
students on a competitive basis.  For 1995-96, the stipends provide $9,900-$10,770 for the
academic year (9 1/2 months) plus tuition remission and, in most cases, eligibility for health
insurance coverage.  Summer stipends are available from various sources as well.  In addition,
the program recommends outstanding applicants to the Graduate School for its fellowships. 
When supplemented with matching funds from the program, these fellowships enhance the
financial support of the awardees at a level much higher than the regular fellowships and
assistantships.<br>
<h4>Cost of Study</h4>
In 1995-96, tuition is $230 per credit hour for in-state students and $375 per credit hour for out-
of-state students.  There are additional mandatory and optional fees.
<h4>Living and Housing Costs</h4>
The Off-Campus Housing Office provides assistance to graduate students seeking
accommodations.   Average monthly rent in the area ranges from $500 to $800.  Food prices are
similar to those in other large metropolitan areas. 

<h3>Applying </h3>
All application materials should be submitted by February 1 for admission in the fall semester
and by August 1 (June 1 for international students) for admission in the spring semester.  All
applicants must submit three letters of recommendation, official college transcripts, and Graduate
Record Examinations (GRE) scores.  International applicants must also submit a Test of English
as a Foreign Language (TOEFL) score.  Applicants must have a bachelor's degree and a strong
background in physical and biological sciences.  Applicants are encouraged to visit the
University to meet with faculty and to discuss their interests and possible course of study.  Click
here to request an <a href= "http://www.ads-rr/Grad/appreq.html">application to the University
of Maryland Graduate School.</a>
</ul><P>
<hr><P>
<h3>Correspondence</h3>
    Email: <a href="mailto:bev@microb.umd.edu">Mocbgrad@deans.umd.edu</a><p>
     <dl>
     <dd> Dr. I. Z. Ades, Director
     <dd> Molecular and Cell Biology Program
     <dd> Microbiology Building
     <dd> University of Maryland
     <dd> College Park, MD  20742<p>
     <dd> Telephone:  301/405-6991
     <dd> Fax: 301/314-9921
     </dl><P>
