   <title>Graduate Programs - Microbiology</title>
   <meta name="GENERATOR" content="Mozilla/2.01Gold (Win32)">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">

<center><p><img src="mscope.gif" alt="Picture of microscope here..." hspace=3 vspace=3 border=0 height=90 width=64 align=left></p></center>

<h3 align=center>Microbiology Graduate Program 
<br>University of Maryland 
<br>College of Life Sciences 
<br>Graduate Programs</h3>

<h3><b><font SIZE=+3>Microbiology (MICB)</font></b> 
<hr size=8 width=60%>
<br clear=left><b>Areas of Emphasis:</b></h3>

<center><p><a href="#genetics"><img src="cy_ball.gif" border=2 height=16 width=17></a><a name="genetics"></a><i><a href="#genetics">Genetics
<a href="#Immunol"><img src="cy_ball.gif" border=2 height=16 width=17></a><a name="immunol"></a></a><a href="#Immunol">Immunology
<a href="#micrecol"><img src="cy_ball.gif" border=2 height=16 width=17></a><a name="micrecol"></a></a><a href="#micrecol">Microbial
Ecology <a href="#molbio"><img src="cy_ball.gif" border=2 height=16 width=17></a><a name="molbio"></a></a><a href="#molbio">Molecular
Biology <a href="#pathogen"><img src="cy_ball.gif" border=2 height=16 width=17></a><a name="pathogen"></a></a><a href="#pathogen">Pathogenics
<a href="#plantsci"><img src="cy_ball.gif" border=2 height=16 width=17></a><a name="plantsci"></a></a><a href="#plantsci">Plant
Sciences <a href="#prokbio"><img src="cy_ball.gif" border=2 height=16 width=17></a><a name="prokbio"></a></a><a href="#prokbio">Prokaryotic
Biology <a href="#signal"><img src="cy_ball.gif" border=2 height=16 width=17></a><a name="signal"></a></a><a href="#signal">Signal
Transduction <a href="#virol"><img src="cy_ball.gif" border=2 height=16 width=17></a><a name="virol"></a></a><a href="#virol">Virology</a></i></p></center>

<center><p><i><font COLOR="#004080"><a href="fac-list.html">List
of Faculty by Research Subject</a></font><a href="#virol"> </a></i></p></center>

<h3><b>Requirements for Admission:</b></h3>

<ul>
<li>At least a B.S. degree from a regionally accredited institution (or
the international equivalent) </li>

<li>An overall grade point average of 3.0 </li>

<li>GRE General Test scores </li>

<li>TOEFL scores from international applicants </li>

<li>Three letters of recommendation from professional or academic references
</li>

<li>A statement of purpose for pursuing the degree, including goals and
objectives for future work in the field. </li>
</ul>

<h3>Introduction </h3>

<p>The graduate program in microbiology at the<a href="#virol"> </a><a href="http://www.umcp.umd.edu">University
of Maryland College Park (UMCP) </a>offers study leading to the Doctor
of Philosophy degree or the Master of Science degree. The department consists
of 14 research faculty and 2 instructors, and affords exposure to a variety
of disciplines. The core requirements of the program consist of four lecture
courses in genetics, microbial physiology, immunology and virology. Students
are required to attend weekly seminars, sponsored by teh program, in which
outstanding scientists from other institutions and this campus give presentations
about their ongoing research. Laboratory research or a rotation is initiated
immediately upon beginning the program.</p>

<p>The UMCP student body is composed of persons from every state and sixty
other countries. The graduate programs at UMCP are quite vigorous. For
example, about 250 graduate students are enrolled in the College of Life
Sciences. The central location of the UMCP campus facilitates interaction
with local government agencies such as FDA &amp; NIH, as well as with industry
in the technology corridor. </p>

<h3>Finances</h3>

<p>The program offers teaching assistantships and research assistantships
to admitted students on a competitive basis. For 1996-97, the stipends
provide $10,800-$11,200 for the academic year (9 1/2 months) plus tuition
remission and, in most cases, eligibility for health insurance coverage.
Summer stipends are available from various sources as well. In addition,
the program recommends outstanding applicants to the Graduate School for
its fellowships. When supplemented with matching funds from the program,
these fellowships enhance the financial support of the awardees at a level
much higher than the regular fellowships and assistantships. </p>

<h4>Cost of Study</h4>

<p>In 1996-97, tuition is $250 per credit hour for in-state students and
$375 per credit hour for out- of-state students. There are additional mandatory
and optional fees. </p>

<h4>Living and Housing Costs</h4>

<p>The Off-Campus Housing Office provides assistance to graduate students
seeking accommodations. Average monthly rent in the area ranges from $500
to $800. Food prices are similar to those in other large metropolitan areas.
</p>

<h3>Applying </h3>

<p>Click here to request an<a href="#virol"> </a><a href="http://www.ads-rr/Grad/appreq.html">application
</a>to the University of Maryland Graduate School. 
<br>All application materials should be submitted by February 1 for admission
in the fall semester and by November 1 for admission in the spring semester.
All applicants must submit three letters of recommendation, official college
transcripts, and Graduate Record Examinations (GRE) scores. International
applicants must also submit a Test of English as a Foreign Language (TOEFL)
score and a Test of Spoken English (TSE) score. Applicants must have a
bachelor's degree and a strong background in physical and biological sciences.
Applicants are encouraged to visit the University to meet with faculty
and to discuss their interests and possible course of study. </p>

<h3>Correspondence</h3>

<p>Email:<a href="#virol"> </a><a href="mailto:gradinfo@microb.umd.edu">Gradinfo@microb.umd.edu</a><a href="#virol">
</a></p>

<dl>
<dd>Dr. Carol Pontzer, Director </dd>

<dd>Microbiology Graduate Program </dd>

<dd>Microbiology Building </dd>

<dd>University of Maryland </dd>

<dd>College Park, MD 20742 
<br></dd>

