<html>
<head>
<title>What is it?</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<h1> What is it?</h1>
<p>
  The Program on the Biology of Small Populations is a collaborative enterprise of
  several departments at the <a href=http://www.umcp.umd.edu>University of Maryland, College Park</a>, 
  and several branches of 
  the <a href=http://www.si.edu>Smithsonian Institution</a>.  It was funded as part of the National
  Science Foundation's  Research Training Group Program in 1996.  The goals of the program are to carry out
  research on the biological consequences of small population sizes and to train students
  and postdoctoral scientists in this area.  The underlying rationale for the program is the
  perceived need for a "basic science" approach to the implications of small or greatly
  reduced population sizes.  Such an approach can help form and strengthen the foundation
  for applied work in conservation biology.  Given the rapid rate at which many biological
  populations are being reduced, a greater understanding of all aspects of the biology of
  small populations is urgently needed.  Faculty participants in the program come from a
  wide variety of disciplines within organismal biology, and promoting interdisciplinary
  work is one of the reasons for founding the group.  
<p>  
   The program is supported by the faculty expertise and the wide range of laboratory
  and field facilities available from three departments at the University of Maryland at
  College Park and three nearby Smithsonian Institution facilities. The faculty includes
  researchers with field, laboratory, and theoretical expertise, and with experience in a wide
  variety of animal, plant, and microbial systems; see the following list of faculty for a brief
  description of current research interests.  The combined physical facilities include
  unparalleled facilities for managing and observing captive populations, and several state-
  of-the-art molecular laboratories.
<p>Current research projects span a wide range of organisms and approaches.  Here is a small sample of some ongoing research projects: 
<ul>
	<li>Analyses of mathematical models to determine the community-level consequencesof selectively eliminating top predators
which often have the smallest population sizes and largest habitat requirements of the species in a community.<p>
	<li>Studies of the effect of subdivision and patterning of food resources for benthic organisms in stream communities.<p>
	<li>Experimental studies of the extent of purging of deleterious genes via inbreeding in small populations.<p>
	<li>Studies of the effects of population bottlenecks on the nature and extent of variation in populations using both plants and viruses as subjects.<p>
	<li>Investigation of the interaction between the Baltimore checkerspot butterfly (currently endangered in Maryland) and its food plant for use in
reintroduction programs.<p>
      <li>Studies of the effect of social learning of foraging behaviors by golden lion tamarins for use in reintroductions.<p> 
</ul>
     The Biology of Small Populations RTG (Research Training Group) program
  includes activities at the undergraduate, graduate, and postdoctoral levels. 
  Undergraduates take a special seminar course and carry out a research project under
  faculty supervision.  Predoctoral participants receive their degree from one of the
  participating departments at the University of Maryland.  They are required to take a
  flexible, but broad curriculum, that includes a one-semester course specifically on the
  biology of small populations.  Ph.D. candidates carry out their dissertation research under
  the direction of one or more faculty members.  Postdoctoral participants design and carry
  out independent research projects under the sponsorship of two faculty members.  The
  program includes a number of additional activities that are open to participants at all
  levels.  At least two "technical training sessions" are given each year; these are several-day-long
  courses on research techniques such as DNA sequencing or Geographic
  Information Systems.  A year-long seminar course explores a different aspect of the
  general research theme each year.  There is also a research meeting each spring with
  invited speakers and presentations by members of the program. 
<p>  
  
<hr align=center width=93% size=3>
<p>
