<html>
<head>
<title>Who are the faculty?</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<h1> Who are the faculty?</h1>
<p>    
  The following list of faculty members gives a brief list of their research interests,
  and their email and mailing addresses.  For more details about the research programs of
  individual faculty members, contact them directly or send a request to the program's
  email address, <a href=mailto:bsp-rtg@zool.umd.edu>bsp-rtg@zool.umd.edu</a>.<p>
  
<h2>A.  Participating Faculty</h2><p>  
<b>UNIVERSITY OF MARYLAND</b>
<p>  
  <b><a href=http://www.life.umd.edu/zoology/index.html>Department of Zoology</a></b> (Department of Zoology, University of Maryland, College Park,
     MD 20742)
<p>     
     <b><a href=http://www.life.umd.edu/zoology/abrams.html>Peter Abrams</a></b> (Mathematical ecology; community and food web dynamics; coevolution
     of interacting species; incorporating adaptive foraging and anti-predator behavior into
     community ecology; evolutionary game theory) <a href=mailto:abrams@zool.umd.edu>abrams@zool.umd.edu</a>
<p>    
     <b><a href=http://www.life.umd.edu/zoology/borgia.html>Gerry Borgia</a></b> (Behavioral 	ecology; sexual selection; mating systems; behavior and phylogeny of bowerbirds)
      <a href=mailto:borgia@zool.umd.edu>borgia@zool.umd.edu</a>
<p>    
     
     <b><a href=http://www.life.umd.edu/zoology/chao.html>Lin Chao</a></b>  (Evolution theory;
 	evolution of sex; population genetics of RNA viruses; role of
     mutations in evolution; parasite-host interactions)
	<a href=mailto:chao@zool.umd.edu> chao@zool.umd.edu</a>
<p>
      <b><a href=http://www.life.umd.edu/zoology/dietz.html>Jim Dietz</a></b> (Primate mating systems and foraging and social behavior; conservation
     	biology; conservation biology; reintroduction programs; ecology of the golden lion
     	tamarin)<a href=mailto:dietz@zool.umd.edu> deitz@zool.umd.edu</a>
 <p>    
     <b><a href=http://www.life.umd.edu/zoology/gill.html>Doug Gill</a></b> (Field ecology;
 	evolution in metapopulations; host-parasite evolution; pollination biology and life
 	histories of orchids; genetic mosaicism)<a href=mailto:gill@zool.umd.edu>gill@zool.umd.edu</a>
<p>
     
