<head>
<title>Interested in a Post Doctoral Fellowship?</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<h1>Interested in a Post Doctoral Fellowship?</h1><p>
Applicants may request awards for 1 or 2 years.  The one-year awards are 
"research-only", while the 2-year awards require a 20-hour per week teaching commitment
during one semester, normally in the second year.  Individuals applying for either type 
of award are expected to take part in a weekly seminar and may be asked to participate 
in special short (3-5 day) courses to explain technical research methods (for example; 
DNA sequencing; using software for analysis of dynamical systems; geographic information
systems).  The timing and nature of the teaching commitment is somewhat flexible, but 
most awards will involve teaching laboratory or discussion sections in undergraduate 
biology courses.
<p>
A wide range of research projects will be supported under the training grant.  The main
research activities of postdoctoral fellows should involve investigation of some aspect
of the effects of population size on ecological, evolutionary, or behavioral processes.  We encourage
applications both from individuals who want to work closely with faculty members in the 
group, and from individuals with independent research projects.  The fellowships include 
a $4000 per year research allowance.  If your proposed research requires the use of 
laboratory facilities, you should communicate with the appropriate faculty member or 
with one of the co-directors of the program (Gerald Wilkinson, Peter Abrams) before 
applying, to ensure availability and access to the facilities.  Postdoctoral trainees 
can be located at any of the participating institutions/departments, depending on the 
trainee's interests.  The participating Smithsonian facilities are all within a 25-50 
minute commute from the University of Maryland at College Park, and seminars, courses 
and meetings will be held in both institutions.
<p>
In addition to the 18 faculty who are group members, there are a number of additional 
scientists at the participating institutions whose interests overlap with those of the 
group, and who can contribute to the research and training activities.  You can look at
information about their research and publications and send email from <b><a 
href=whoare.html>Who are the Faculty?</a></b>
<p>
<b>Compensation</b><br>
Trainees will receive a $25,000 stipend, health insurance, and a research allowance of 
$4000 each year.  Only U. S. citizens and permanent residents are eligible for these 
positions.  However, note that the Smithsonian Institution gives postdoctoral fellowships
 that are not restricted to U.S. nationals, and these fellowships may be used to support
work under our program, provided your sponsor in the Smithsonian is a group member.
<p>
<h2>Applications will consist of:</h2>
<p>
<ol> <li>A cover letter that states whether a one- or two- year position is being 
	requested.  The cover letter should also include the applicant's mailing address,
	 phone number(s) and email address.  It should identify the anticipated starting
	date, and should identify any requirements for lab facilities from faculty 
	members in the group. 
<p>
	<li>A curriculum vitae, including a current list of publications
<p>
	<li>A research proposal.  The proposal should be between four and six 
	single-spaced pages of text, and should include a section describing how the 
	project relates to the training grant theme of biological implications of small 
	population size. 
<p>
	<li>Three letters of recommendation. 
<p>
	<li>(if available) Copies of up to (but no more than) two representative reprints or preprints.
<p>
	<li>A graduate school transcript or a list of graduate courses taken and grades 
	received.
</ol>

Please send one copy of items (1), (4), (5) and (6), and five copies of items (2) and
(3) to BEES c/o Department of Zoology, University of Maryland, College Park, MD 20742. 
<p>
<b>The deadline for applications for postdoctoral positions is January 31, 1997.</b>  We
hope to announce awards by 1 March 1997. The awards must started before December 31, 1997.  
There will be another competition for postdoctoral fellowships with a 31 January, 1998 
application deadline. 
<p>
Applicants are encouraged to submit separate applications for <b><a href=http://www.si.edu/youandsi/studies/ofg/ofgintro.htm>
Smithsonian Institution Postdoctoral Fellowships</a></b>,
 which can also be used to support work within the Biology of Small Populations program.
 <b>Note</b> that, unlike the RTG Fellowships, the Smithsonian Fellowships are not 
restricted to U.S. citizens.
<p>
Applications can be obtained from:<br>
Office of Fellowships and Grants<br>
Smithsonian Institution<br>
Washington, D. C. 20560<br>   
(202-287-3271)<br>
E-mail: <b><a href="mailto:siofg@sivm.si.edu">siofg@sivm.si.edu</a></b>
<p> <hr align=center width=93% size=3> <p>

<b>Return to: <a href=index.html>Biology of Small Populations</a></b>
<p> 
<b>Return to: <a href=http://www.life.umd.edu/>Life Science Home Page</a></b>
<p> 
<b>Return to: <a href=http://www.umcp.umd.edu/>University of Maryland Home Page</a></b>
<p>  
