<head>
<title>Interested in a Doctoral Fellowship?</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<h1>Interested in a Doctoral Fellowship?</h1><p>
  <h2>Graduate Training</h2>
 <p> 
  Participants in the predoctoral program must meet the general requirements of the
  department or program in which they are enrolled.  In addition, there are specific
  requirements of the training program.  In all cases, there is overlap between the
  departmental/program requirements and those of the training program, so at least some of
  the RTG requirements also satisfy departmental requirements.  The addresses of the
  department and program offices are listed below; these offices should be
  contacted for further information on departmental requirements. 
 <p> 
   <b>Core Courses:</b><br>  To obtain broad training in the fundamental principles of the related
  sub-disciplines at an advanced level, all RTG trainees are required to take a graduate
  course from each of following four categories during their first two years in the program.
<p> 
 <table border=1 cellpadding=3 cellspacing=1>
   <tr><td valign=top>EVOLUTION
       <td valign=top>PBIO 745
       <td valign=top>Plant Ecological Genetics
       <td valign=top>Fenster
   <tr><td>
       <td valign=top>ENT 688
       <td valign=top>Insect Population Genetics
       <td valign=top>Hawthorne
   <tr><td>
       <td valign=top>ZOOL 640
       <td valign=top>Population Genetics
       <td valign=top>Highton/Stephan
   <tr><td>
       <td valign=top>ZOOL 671
       <td valign=top>Evolutionary Theory
       <td valign=top>Chao
   <tr><td valign=top>ECOLOGY
       <td valign=top>ENTM 612
       <td valign=top>Insect Ecology
       <td valign=top>Denno
   <tr><td>
       <td valign=top>PBIO 740
       <td valign=top>Plant Population Biology
       <td valign=top>Dudash
   <tr><td>
       <td valign=top>ZOOL 670
       <td valign=top>Concepts in Ecology
       <td valign=top>Gill
   <tr><td>
       <td valign=top>ZOOL 608T
       <td valign=top>Population and Comm. Ecology
       <td valign=top>Abrams
   <tr><td valign=top>BEHAVIOR
       <td valign=top>ZOOL 665
       <td valign=top>Behavioral Ecology
       <td valign=top>Borgia
   <tr><td>
       <td valign=top>ZOOL 708
       <td valign=top>Principles of Animal Behavior
       <td valign=top>Wilkinson
   <tr><td>
       <td valign=top>ZOOL 627
       <td valign=top>Behavioral Endocrinology
       <td valign=top>Carter
   <tr><td valign=top>STATISTICS
       <td valign=top>BIOM 602
       <td valign=top>Experimental Design
       <td valign=top>Douglass
   <tr><td>
       <td valign=top>BIOM 603
       <td valign=top>General Linear Models
       <td valign=top>Russek-Cohen
  </table>
  Substitutions from this list are permitted with the approval of the steering committee.
<p>  
   In addition to these four courses, RTG graduate students must take a new course titled
  "Biology of Small Populations".  The aim of this course is to provide second or third year
  students with a technical and conceptual framework to understand the biology of small
  populations.  This course covers a range of topics that focus on unique aspects of small
  populations, and tools that are required to study or understand small populations.  Topics
  covered include stochastic processes, statistics of small samples, individual-based
  simulation models, and empirical problems associated with experiments on small
  populations.
<p> 
   All RTG students are also required to take a course on "Race, Gender, and Scientific
  Knowledge" currently offered in alternate years by Dr. Margaret Palmer. This course
  focuses on: (1) how women and persons of color have participated in and contributed to
  the sciences, as well as how barriers have influenced their participation; and (2) how
  gender, race, and scientific knowledge are linked.  Students are also encouraged to take a
  course, "Ethics in scientific research", currently offered annually by Dr. Arthur Popper
  (Zoology) and Dr. Robert Dooling (Psychology).  Both of these courses meet once a
  week.
<p>  
  <b>Other Available Graduate Courses and Seminars:</b><br>  A wide variety of other relevant
  courses are currently offered each year or in alternate years by Entomology, Plant
  Biology or Zoology faculty.  These include insect ecology, insect evolutionary biology,
  conservation biology, theoretical population and community ecology, concepts in
  ecology, ecology of marine communities, physiological plant ecology, plant population
  biology, population genetics, plant ecological genetics, principles of systematics,
  evolutionary theory, behavioral ecology, sociobiology and a three-semester series in
  statistics, which includes probability, experimental design, and general linear models,
  each with SAS laboratories, offered by BEES faculty in the Department of Animal
  Sciences.  In addition to lecture format courses, each department regularly offers graduate
  seminars on selected topics of interest to faculty and students.  These graduate seminars
  are frequently attended by multiple faculty and have provided an excellent forum for
  focused training on topical issues.  There is a weekly seminar in the <a href=http://www.inform.umd.edu:8080/EdRes/Colleges/LFSC/.FacultyStaff/dinouye/BEES/>
  BEES (Behavior, Evolution, Ecology, and Systematics) program</a></b>.  Additional
  seminars of related interest may be found in Maryland departmental seminar programs, 
  like those of the Entomology Department, and in the regular seminar programs at the
  National Zoo and Smithsonian Environmental Research Center. 
<p>  
   <b>Graduate Discussion Course/Annual Meeting:</b><br>  A key component of graduate training
  in the Biology of Small Populations is a new, year-long graduate discussion course that is
  organized each year by two RTG faculty from different departments, disciplines, or
  institutions.  The goal of this course is to explore some aspect of small population size
  from a multi-disciplinary perspective appropriate for the participating faculty.  Topics
  differ each year depending on the interests of the organizing faculty.  As part of the
  course, four or five noted scholars with expertise unavailable among the RTG faculty are
  invited to a three-day meeting during spring-break.  At this meeting all RTG
  undergraduate, graduate, and postdoctoral trainees, core faculty and visiting scholars
  present papers; and hold panel discussions to identify especially promising research areas. 
  These meetings provide an annual opportunity for all of the RTG participants to interact
  with each other as well as with visiting scholars. 
<p> 
   <b>Technical Training Sessions:</b><br> Students are eligible to enroll in any of a number of
  intense, short-term (1-7 day) technical training sessions that are offered either during the
  semester break or summer by UMCP and SI faculty or postdocs.  These training sessions
  provide hands-on experience to enable the RTG trainees to acquire technical skills
  necessary for assessing the consequences of small population sizes.  Some examples
  include application of Geographic Information Systems (GIS) to small population
  problems, radiotelemetry techniques, sound analysis and synthesis, microsatellite typing,
  multi-locus fingerprinting, DNA sequencing, population viability analysis, coalescent
  theory, and mathematical analysis or dynamical systems.  
<p>  
   <b>Research Internships:</b><br>  RTG predoctoral fellows are encouraged to participate in a
  	summer-long research internship at a <b><a href=http://www.si.edu/youandsi/studies/infell.htm>
	Smithsonian Institution</a></b> facility, faculty research
  	lab, or field site under the supervision of RTG faculty, preferably during their first or
  	second year. 
<p>  
   As a member institution of the <b><a href=http://www.ots.duke.edu/docs/main.htm>Organization for Tropical Studies (OTS)</a></b>, UMCP
  graduate students are eligible for priority consideration in the application process for OTS
  graduate courses offered each year in Costa Rica.
<p>  
  <b> Teaching:</b><br>  Because success in science requires effective communication, RTG
  fellows are required to spend at least three semesters during their doctoral program as
  graduate teaching assistants. 
<p>  
   <b>Program Progression:</b><br>  Just prior to their first semester in residence, each RTG trainee
  meets with three faculty who make suggestions and recommendations for any additional
  coursework.  During their second year students identify a dissertation research problem
  and form a preliminary examination committee containing five faculty, including one
  member from outside the home department.  After discussing the proposed research with
  their committee, students then are expected to collect sufficient pilot data, usually during
  the second summer in the program, to be able to defend a research proposal no later than
  the end of their fifth semester.  Most students will then spend two to three years
  conducting research prior to defending a dissertation.
<p>  
   <b>Financial Support:</b><br> Normally students admitted to the Ph.D. program will be
  guaranteed five years of financial support, including two full years of fellowship support
  from the research training grant, as long as they make satisfactory progress toward their
  degree.  Current stipends for the 9.5 months of the academic year are $10,800 for students
  who have not yet taken and passed their oral preliminary examination; and $11,200 for
  students who have passed their preliminary exam (usually taken in the fourth or fifth
  semester), and have thus officially advanced to PhD candidacy.  The RTG fellowships
  entail 12 months of support, so the amounts are $13,642 before advancement to
  candidacy and $14,147 after.  Fellowship support from the grant also includes tuition
  remission and health insurance.  Students accepted into the program may elect to defer
  part or all of their fellowship support until after their first two years, and may hold a
  teaching assistantship concurrently with the fellowship.
<p>  
   Support for the time during which a student does not have an RTG fellowship can
  come from a variety of sources: (1) teaching assistantships (3 semesters of teaching are
  required, but students are still eligible to apply for assistantships after completing this
  requirement); (2) faculty research grants, which provide support as research assistants
  over the summer or in the academic year; and (3) other fellowships from within and
  outside of the University.  All students are encouraged to apply for <b> <a href=http://flnew.nsf.gov/a10/A10Menu.htm>
  National Science Foundation Graduate Fellowships</a></b>.  Some students may be eligible to apply for other
  national fellowships, such as the <b><a href=http://fellowships.nas.edu/hhmireq.html>
  Howard Hughes Foundation Fellowship</a></b>.  The <b><a href=http://www.si.edu/youandsi/studies/ofg/ofgintro.htm> 
  Smithsonian Institution</a></b> also has predoctoral fellowships that are available on a
  competitive basis, and provide a full year of support (currently $14,500) to students
  who have advanced to PhD candidacy.  The <b><a href=http://www.inform.umd.edu:8080/EdRes/GradInfo/Fellowship>
  Graduate School at the University of Maryland</a></b> also provides 2 year fellowships on a university-wide competitive basis, and
  entering RTG students may be nominated for these.  Additional University of Maryland
  and Smithsonian Institution fellowship funds have been targeted for qualified ethnic
  minorities.  If you would like more information about fellowship opportunities, contact
  the RTG office or any of the faculty involved in the program.
<p> 
   Teaching assistantships may be held concurrently with some forms of fellowship
  support, including RTG fellowships.  Teaching assistantships include health insurance
  and tuition remission.  Although summer support is not guaranteed when the student does
  not have an RTG fellowship, in most cases, summer funds are available either from
  research grants or other programs. 
<p>  
<hr align=center width=93% size=3> 
<p>  
  <h2>Application Procedure:<br>
 Graduate Studies in the Biology of Small
  Populations</h2>
<p>  
  At the graduate level, students who wish to pursue research on the evolution,
  ecology or behavior of small populations must apply to and matriculate in a Ph.D.
  program within a participating academic department on the College Park campus
  (presently, the departments of  <b><a href=http://www.inform.umd.edu/pbio>Plant Biology</a></b>,
  <b><a href=http://www.entm.umd.edu/welcome.htm>Entomology</a></b>, or
  <b><a href=http://www.life.umd.edu/zoology/index.html>Zoology</a></b>; in July 1997,
  Plant Biology and Zoology will be merged into a single Biology Department) or an
  intercampus degree-granting program.  The primary related intercampus program is the
  <b><a href=http://www.inform.umd.edu:8080/MEES>Marine, Estuarine, and Environmental
  Sciences (MEES) program</a></b>.  Addresses for these
  departments or programs are listed below.  Applicants who would like to discuss choice
  of a program may wish to contact one or more faculty members whose interests are
  closest to theirs.  All graduate students in research degree programs must have a major
  advisor before admission; thus it is a good idea for all applicants to communicate with
  potential advisors before submitting their application, see <b><a href=whoare.html>
  Who are the Faculty?</a></b> Students who wish to be advised by a faculty member from the Smithsonian Institution
  must also obtain a coadvisor in one of the University of Maryland departments.
<p>    
  When submitting an application to a department or program, prospective students
  should request in their cover letter that they be considered for the  Biology of Small
  Populations' program.  They should also include a statement (of not more than two pages,
  single spaced) describing their particular interests in the Biology of Small Populations. 
  For consideration by the Biology of Small Populations program, applications should be
  received by <b>January 31, 1997</b>. 
<p> 
  If you need application materials they can be obtained by following the links or
  writing to the following address(es) for the departmental programs:<p> 
  Director of Graduate Studies<br>
  Department of ____ (Zoology, Plant Biology, or Entomology)<br>
  University of Maryland<br>
  College Park, MD 20742<br>
<p>
<b><a href=mailto:pbiograd@deans.umd.edu>Plant Biology - pbiograd@deans.umd.edu</a></b>
<p>
