<head>
<title>Are you currently a UMD student?</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<h1>Are you currently a UMD student?</h1><p>

 Part of the funds available from the research training grant on the
 Biology of Small Populations will be given to current students.  The
 following text describes the application procedures for the two types
 of fellowship (long- and short- term) that are available under the
 program.
<p> <hr align=center width=93% size=3> <p>
<h2>Application Procedures for Current UMD Students for Fellowship
Support from the Biology of Small Populations Research Training Grant</h2>
<p>
<b>1. Long-term fellowships</b>
<p>
PhD students enrolled at UMCP who have not yet advanced to candidacy
are eligible to apply for the long-term fellowships that entail 12 or
24 months of support at the normal TA/RA rate. The fellowship also
includes a tuition remission for the period of fellowship support. 
There may be flexibility in when money is received.  If awarded a
fellowship, students would then have to complete the coursework and
other requirements of the RTG program found in
<b><a href=http://www.life.umd.edu/bsprtg/doctoral.html>Interested in a Doctoral Fellowship?</a></b>
<p> 
Individuals wishing to be considered for these fellowships should submit:<p>
<ol><li>A two page essay describing how their interests fit into the research theme of
the "Biology of Small Populations"<p>
<li>Two letters of
recommendation, at least one of which must be from the research
supervisor<p>
<li>Unofficial copies of undergraduate and graduate
transcripts and GRE scores<p>
<li>If the applicant has already begun a
research project he or she should also include a 3-5 page description
of that project.</ol><p>
 Students supported by RTG fellowships may be asked to
give a presentation of their work at an annual spring meeting of the
RTG in either 1998 or 1999.
<p>
<b>The deadline for applications is January 31, 1997.</b><br>  Applications
should be sent to Kara Paintner/BEES, Department of Zoology,
University of Maryland, College Park, MD 20742
<p>
<b>2. Short-term fellowships</b>
<p>
A limited number of short-term RTG fellowships will be awarded in
1997.  These are open to Ph.D. students in good standing in MEES,
Zoology, Plant Biology, or Entomology.  Short term fellowships to be
awarded in the spring of 1997 provide a stipend for either one
semester during the 1997-98 academic year or for the summer of 1997 at
normal TA/RA levels. They may also include a request for up to $1000 in supplies as justified
in the proposal(see below).<p>
The application procedure is as follows:<p>
<ol><li> Three copies of a 5 page research proposal that describes your
proposed work<p>
<li> A brief summary that describes how it is related to
the general theme of the RTG (i.e., how decreased population size
affects biological processes)<p>
<li>Two letters of recommendation, one
of which must be from your research supervisor<p>
<li>  If research expenses are requested, a 1 page budget and budget justification must
be included with the proposal. </ol><p>
Students supported by such a short-term
fellowship will be asked to give a presentation of their results at an
annual spring meeting of the RTG in either 1998 or 1999.  The Research
Training Grant should be acknowledged in any publications that result
from the supported work.
<p>
<b>The application deadline is March 1, 1997.</b><br>  Applications should be
sent to Kara Paintner/BEES, Department of Zoology, University of
Maryland, College Park, MD 20742
<p>
The maximum amount of fellowship support to any one individual under
the RTG grant is 24 months.  Thus, if you receive a 1-semester award
and subsequently apply for a long-term award, the maximum support on
the long-term award will be 2 years minus one semester. 
<p>
<p> <hr align=center width=93% size=3> <p>
<b>Return to: <a href=index.html>Biology of Small Populations</a></b>
<p> 
<b>Return to: <a href=http://www.life.umd.edu/>Life Science Home Page</a></b>
<p> 
<b>Return to: <a href=http://www.umcp.umd.edu/>University of Maryland Home Page</a></b>
<p>  
