<HTML>
<head>
<TITLE>Wolfgang Stephan</TITLE>
</head>
<body BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">
<img align=right hspace=3 vspace=3 src="stephan.gif" alt="[picture of Dr. Stephan]">
<H3>Dr. Wolfgang Stephan<br><i>Associate Professor</i></H3>
<p>
Department of Zoology<br>
University of Maryland, College Park, Maryland  20742<BR>
email: <a href="mailto:stephan@zool.umd.edu">stephan@zool.umd.edu</a><BR>
phone: (301) 405-6912
<BR clear=left>
<p>
<HR>
Research Interest: <b>Molecular Evolution and Population Genetics</b><br>
 
We are pursuing experimental and theoretical studies in molecular evolution and population genetics. Our research focuses on three major areas: (i) genetic variation in natural populations of Drosophila, (ii) epistatic selection mediated by RNA secondary structure interactions, and (iii) molecular evolution of metallothionein genes in Drosophila. The first project is concerned with the detection of natural selection at the DNA level and the effects of genetic recombination and population subdivision on nucleotide sequence variation. The second project studies RNA secondary structure as a potential source of epistatic fitness interactions within genes. A mRNA secondary structure is constructed based on phylogenetic comparisons and mutation analysis. This structure is then used to analyze the evolution and population genetics of coupled ("compensatory") nucleotide substitutions. In the third project, we are reconstructing the recent history of Drosophila metallothionein genes. This work provides insights into the evolutionary significance of gene duplications and into intron evolution.
<BR>
<BR> 

<H3>Representative Publications</H3>

Stephan, W., Wiehe, T.H.E. and Lenz, M.W., The effect of strongly 
selected substitutions on neutral polymorphism: Analytical results based on 
diffusion theory. <i>Theoret. Pop. Biol. 41,</i> 237-254 (1992)
<p>
Stephan, W. and Mitchell, S.J., Reduced levels of DNA polymorphism and 
fixed between-	population differences in the centromeric region of 
<I>Drosophila ananassae. Genetics 132,</i> 1039-1045 (1992)
<p>
Wiehe, T.H.E. and Stephan, W., Analysis of a genetic hitchhiking model and 
its application to DNA polymorphism data from <I>Drosophila melanogaster. 
Mol. Biol. Evol. 10,</i> 842-854 (1993)
<p>
Stephan, W. and Kirby, D.A., RNA folding in Drosophila shows a distance effect 
for compensatory fitness interactions. <i>Genetics 135,</i> 97-103 (1993)
<p>
Stephan, W., Rodriguez, V.S., Zhou, B. and Parsch, J., Molecular evolution of the
metallothionein gene <I>Mtn</i> in the <I>melanogaster</i> species group: 
Results from <i>Drosophila ananassae. Genetics 138,</i> 135-143 (1994)
<p>
Charlesworth, B.,Sniegowski, P. and Stephan, W., The evolutionary dynamics of 
repetitive DNA in eukaryotes. <i>Nature 371,</i> 215-220 (1994)
<p>
Kirby, D.A., Muse, S.V. and Stephan, W., Maintenance of pre-mRNA secondary 
structure by epistatic selection. <i>Proc. Natl. Acad. Sci. USA 92,</i> 9047-9051 (1995)
<p>
Kirby, D.A. and Stephan, W., Haplotype Test Reveals Departure From Neutrality in a Segment of the <i>white</i>  Gene
of <i>Drosophila melanogaster</i>. <i>Genetics 141,</i> 1483-1490 (1995)
<p>
Stephan, W. An Improved Method for Estimating the Rate of Fixation of Favorable Mutations 
Based on DNA Polymorphism Data.  <i>Mol. Biol. Evol. 12</i> 959-962 (1995)
<p>

<A HREF="stephanweb.html">Return to Wolfgang Stephan Lab home page</A>
<br>
<A HREF="/zoology/welcome.html">Return to Zoology Home Page</a>
<br>

