<head>
<TITLE>Michael Perlitz</TITLE>
</head>
<body background="back4.gif">
<img align=right vspace=3 hspace=3 src="perlitz.gif" alt="[picture of Michael Perlitz]">
<H1>Michael Perlitz</H1>
<B>MAPL (Program in Applied Mathematics)</B>
<BR>
<B>University of Maryland<br>
College Park, Maryland  20742</B>
<BR>
<B>email: <a href="mailto:mp98@umail.umd.edu">mp98@umail.umd.edu</a></B>
<BR>
<B>phone: (301)  405-6912</B>
<BR>
<HR>
<BR>
<H3>ABSTRACT</H3>
<BR>
<h4>Estimating the rate of fixation of favorable mutations</h4>
<BR><BR>
Michael Perlitz* and Wolfgang Stephan
<BR>
*MAPL and Department of Zoology
<BR>
University of Maryland, College Park, Maryland
<BR><BR>

Low recombination rates around a locus can cause a complete loss of heterozygosity if at this locus an advantageous mutation appears which is driven to fixation by directional selection. Such a process of fixation including loss of heterozygosity is called a  hitchhiking process.
Since the whole process takes place during a relatively short time period [t = (2 / s)ln(2N), where s is the selection coefficient] we can assume, that by measuring time in units of 2N generations the whole process lasts only a single time point. Under this assumption we talk about a hitchhiking event.
Given a sample of n genes of a region of very low recombination, we ask what is the expected time back to the occurrence of the last hitchhiking event?
To answer this question we used the coalescent approach. The time passed since the last hitchhiking event can be estimated by considering the number of segregating sites within the region in question, and so the pure genealogical coalescent process is not enough for approaching this problem - the mutational process is needed too.
The basic idea was to cut all possible coalescent trees of a sample of n alleles at the time of the hitchhiking event and to calculate the expected number of segregating sites on them. We obtained a function for the average number and variance of segregating sites dependent on time.
Example: The last hitchhiking event at the <I>vermilion</I> locus in  <I>Drosophila ananassae</I>  (sample size n = 19, theta/bp = .0075, 2 segregating sites) happened approximately .14 N generations back in the past.
<BR><BR>
Poster presented July 1995 at the annual meeting of the Society for the Study of Evolution, McGill University, Montreal, Quebec, Canada.
<BR>
<BR>
<A HREF="stephanweb.html">Return to Wolfgang Stephan Lab home page</A>
<br>
