<html>
<title>North South Center for Sustainable Development</title>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center>
<img src=NSCSDlogo.gif alt="NSCSD Logo">
</center>
<p>
The alarming growth in the technology and industry gap between the nations 
of the North and the South has overwhelmed the Souths efforts to achieve 
social and economic progress or make significant contributions to the global 
marketplace. At the same time, the environmental destruction which has 
accompanied unplanned economic development in the Third World now poses 
grievous threats to the global habitat, with potentially devastating effects 
on the health and well-being of local populations. The efforts of less 
developed nations to build human capital and assert themselves in the 
global marketplace need to go hand-in-hand with efforts to preserve the 
environment and to enrich the quality of life.
<p>
The Administrations <i>Peace, Prosperity, and Democracy Act of 1994</i> has 
this to say about sustainable development: "Sustainable Development is 
in the long term interest of the United States because it builds the 
economic, political, environmental and social foundation for a secure 
and prosperous future. Without active United States support for sustainable 
development activities, the problems of persistent poverty, population 
growth, and environmental degradation threaten to undercut the best efforts 
of nations to build peace and prosperity."
<p>
The North South Center for Sustainable Development (<i>NSCSD</i>) in the College 
of Life Sciences, University of Maryland, College Park, is committed to 
efforts to improve communication and the exchange and training of personnel 
with these less developed nations. The University of Maryland is the ideal 
location for such a center because of its proximity to Washington D.C., the 
hub of the worlds largest brain trust of applied high-technology science and 
research institutions, global policy makers, and international conservation 
organizations.
<p>
<img align=right src=researcher.gif alt="Picture of researcher with microscope">
The purpose behind <i>NSCSD</i> is to enable experts across the range of conservation 
development and modern technology fields to efficiently and effectively 
exchange ideas and information, advance training and educational initiatives, 
respond to environmental problems, and promote economic advancement through the 
sustainable use of the earths resources. While the mission of <i>NSCSD</i> is to 
improve the human capital and address the problems of Third World countries, 
many of the projects will use models and results from similar problems here. 
The results of these efforts will also often find applications in the USA. For 
example, many of the urban growth versus environmental resources problems in 
this country are very similar, if only milder, to the problems facing less 
developed countries in the South. By way of example, <i>NSCSD</i> could address such 
diverse concerns as how to preserve the Chesapeake Bays fragile ecosystem 
without curtailing Marylands growth, how to combat the West Coasts chronic 
smog problems, or how to develop an implement improved early warning systems 
so as to reduce human harm and minimize damage from hurricane related weather. 
Clearly, the solutions to all os these national sustainable development problems 
have global applications.
<p>
<i>NSCSD</i> will have a unique focus on global human capacity building. It will:
<p>
<ul>
<li>Foster scientific collaboration between North and South;
<li>Integrate scientific disciplines;
<li>Develop new models for sustainable development;
<li>Pursue collaborative cutting-edge research;
<li>Promote self sufficiency through entrepreneurship; and 
<li>Develop training programs.
</ul><p>
The <i>NSCSD</i> has instituted several projects since it's inception in 1994 and 
will continue to expand its efforts over the coming years.
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT11-B12-274</DOCNO>
