<html>
<title>Golden Lion Tamarin Conservation Project</title>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center>
<img align=middle src=gltmap.gif alt="Golden Lion Tamarin Conservation Project Map Logo"><br>
</center>
<p>
<img align=right src=gltamarin.gif alt="Picture of Golden Lion Tamarin">
One of the best known rain forest conservation efforts in Brazil, 
the Golden Lion Tamarin Conservation Project (<i>gltcp</i>), is a mere two
hour drive from the city of Rio de Janeiro. The golden lion tamarin 
(<i>glt</i>), a strikingly beautiful squirrel sized primate, that exists only
in the lowland Atlantic Forest of the state of Rio de Janeiro, is 
one of the most endangered primate species on earth. All of the 
approximately 550 remaining wild individuals are found in the Po&#231o 
das Antas Federal Biological Reserve and the surrounding private 
land. The major threat to this species is habitat destruction for 
urban and resort development along the coast, and rice fields and 
cattle pasture farther inland. Less than 2% of the tamarins original 
forest habitat remains today, and all of that in small forest 
fragments. Essentially all of the diverse species native only to this 
forest are threatened with extinction.
<p>
The <i>gltcp</i> utilizes the golden lion tamarin as a flagship species to 
increase support for the conservation of what remains of this forest.
The project, which began in 1983, serves as a demonstration of the 
state-of-the-art conservation biology and organizational cooperation 
necessary to mobilize a region, and indeed the global community, to 
join forces in an effort to conserve a viable portion of one of the 
most endangered tropical forest ecosystems in the world. Faculty and 
students from the University of Maryland were instrumental in the 
founding of the project and continue to participate in all aspects of 
its conservation and research efforts. Additional partners include 
the Brazilian federal environment agency (<i>ibama</i>), the Rio state 
environmental agency, several Brazilian universities, local municipal 
governments, local non-government organizations, local landowners, 
community organizations and schools, World Wildlife Fund, zoos around 
the world, the Smithsonian Institution-National Zoological Park, 
along with many other local and international organizations.
<p>
The conservation of species such as golden lion tamarins, whose 
numbers have been so drastically reduced, requires the collaboration 
of experts from several disciplines. Each component of the project 
has clear objectives, documents its methods, and periodically 
evaluates results. Those working on the project have produced over 
130 scientific publications to date, helping to make it an 
internationally recognized model for understanding the forces that 
shape a primates behavior and probability for survival.
<p>
The components of this unique multidisciplinary approach, integrating 
scientific research and applied conservation, include:
<p>
<img src=gltamarin2.gif align=right alt="Picture of Golden Lion Tamarin">
<ul>
<li><i>Ecological studies of wild golden lion tamarins and other species</i> to 
better understand what is necessary to ensure this ecosystem has a future 
for the next 200 years and to monitor the projects success. By monitoring 
20 family groups, the research on wild <i>glt</i>s is the largest long-term field 
study on any primate in the world in terms of numbers of groups studied.
<p>
<li><i>Habitat protection and management</i> to increase the amount of forest habitat 
available. An inventory of suitable habitat outside the Reserve is now complete. 
Fire towers and a communication system are in use to protect the forest in the 
Reserve, and development of cost-effective techniques for forest restoration are 
underway.
<p>
<li><i>A community education program</i> focusing on developing support for forest 
conservation on private as well as public land. This program has documented its 
ability to effect significant changes in knowledge and attitudes of the local 
people. Furthermore, it has succeeded in making the golden lion tamarin a symbol 
for forest conservation throughout Brazil.
<p>
<li><i>Development and refinement of techniques for conservation of a viable population 
of golden lion tamarins</i>, including reintroduction of zoo-born family groups and 
translocation of wild tamarins into protected habitat. Worldwide, over 100 zoos 
participate in an international cooperative program for captive breeding of 
golden lion tamarins. The project, using techniques it developed, is reintroducing 
zoo-born family groups to their native forest habitat in Rio, thereby increasing 
the population size and genetic health of golden lion tamarins in the wild, as 
well as involving local landowners in guaranteeing the protection of the remaining 
forest on their land. Since 1984, 141 captive-born golden lion tamarins have been 
released into the wild. As a consequence of this reintroduction, approximately 
125 survive in the wild, including 25 captive-born reintroductees and about 100 
of their wild-born offspring, thus increasing the population by approximately 
23% to 575.
<p>
<li><i>Training</i> of a significant number of young Brazilian professional 
conservationists and technicians to carry on and expand conservation efforts 
in this and other areas. Several field courses are offered each year.
<p>
<li><i>Extension</i>. The <i>gltcp</i> serves as a model for conservation and research 
activities with the other three species of lion tamarins in Brazils Atlantic 
Forest. As is the case for <i>glt</i>s, the other species are highly endangered and 
found only in small forested areas surrounded by cattle pasture. Conservation 
theory and methods developed during a decade of work on <i>glt</i>s is now being 
extended to include caissara and black lion tamarins in S&#227o Paulo State and 
golden-headed lion tamarins in Bahia State.
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT11-B12-275</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA033-000671-B041-375</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://mtgmkr.life.umd.edu:80/nsc/ied-big.html 128.8.90.214 19970209160338 text/html 5392
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Sun, 09 Feb 1997 16:02:38 GMT
