<html>
<title>Institute for Sustainable Development - Ilha Grande Bay</title>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center>
<img align=middle src=isdlogo.gif alt="Institute for Sustainable Development Logo"><br>
</center>
<p>
Ilha Grande Bay sits in the southern part of the State of Rio de 
Janeiro in Brazil and appears to be a tropical paradise. With the 
clear blue waters of the Costa Verde surrounding 365 islands it 
should be a vacation wonderland. Its ecosystem of diverse life 
forms in lagoons, salt marshes, mangroves and forests make it an 
outstanding natural laboratory.
<p>
But this paradise is being threatened. The Bay is suffering from 
over-fishing, oil spills, sewage, unregulated dumping of trash, 
deforestation and the disorganized expansion of coastal cities 
without the slightest urban or ecological planning. For example, 
the sewage from Angra dos Reis, the largest city on the Costa Verde, 
is discharged directly into the waters of the Bay, without treatment. 
On the weekends the scene is chaotic with thousands of power boats 
speeding to deserted beaches often leaving trash and waste in their 
wake. Near the beaches, jet-skis roar through fish spawning grounds.
The Bay suffers from unrestricted over fishing year round. Large 
commercial fishing boats use drag nets, keeping the large fish and 
returning the smaller ones to the sea, dead. As a result the local 
fishermen and their families, the twenty thousand people that depend 
on the waters of the Bay to survive, have little hope of sustaining 
their livelihood. For example, the sardine catch that in 1985 averaged 
240,000 fish, is currently just 20,000.
<p>
<img align=right src=bay.gif alt="Picture of Ilha Grande Bay">
It was concern about the future of Ilha Grande Bay and the 
possibilities of reintroducing life to this marine ecosystem, 
preserving the environment and repopulating the water with select 
marine species, that led to the foundation of the Institute of 
Sustainable Development of Ilha Grande Bay in 1991. <i>IED-BIG</i>, with a 
center on the island of Jipoia and a laboratory facility in Angra 
dos Reis, is a non-profit public association with educational, 
scientific, and cultural goals. <i>IED-BIG</i> is supported by local citizens 
and industry, with Petrobras (Brazilian oil company) and Furnas
(Brazilian atomic energy company), Brazilian Universities and the 
University of Maryland (usa) as major participants.
<p>
Projects conducted under the auspices of <i>IED-BIG</i> will be many and 
varied. They will span the gamut from environmental educational 
efforts with school children to environmental research on the ecology 
of the Bay, the rivers that flow into it and the surrounding forests. 
Indeed, the ecology of one of the rivers in question is the subject 
of an ongoing research project being conducted by the University of 
Maryland faculty.
<p>
Perhaps the most important project underway at <i>IED-BIG</i> is related to 
sustainable development for local residents of the Bay of Ilha Grande. 
The concept is simple. The greatest threat to Ilha Grande Bay is 
uncontrolled development and the greatest impediment to uncontrolled 
development is economic stability for the local population. If local, 
environmentally friendly industry exists for the local population, 
there will be resistance to outside developmental pressures. The 
objectives are to protect and study the ecosystem of the Bay of Ilha 
Grande, promote the socio-economic recovery of local fishing by the 
inhabitants of the region and improve the quality of life of the 
inhabitants with the participation of universities, industry, 
government and the community.
<p>
One of the critical facilities to achieving the goal of this 
project is a research lab in Angra dos Reis. Constructed by 
Petrobras, the lab provides housing facilities to visiting scientists 
working on collaborative projects in larval culture and oceanographic 
research. <img align=left src=oysters.gif alt="Picture of Oyster Aquaculture and Facilities Construction">
A hatchery on the island of Jipoia provides oyster and 
scallop spat for research projects on improving hatchery yields and 
studies to select species that are most adaptable to the conditions 
found in this region. These research projects will foster the 
development of marine aquaculture suitable to the local environment, 
and industry that has already proven to be highly successful in many 
parts of the world. At present there are a number of small aquaculture 
projects in the Bay that, with the support of the Institute, are 
developing into successful enterprises.
In brief, the waters of the Bay can return and again support the 
fishermen and provide them a guaranteed living. However it will only 
happen if there is a seamless web of research, development and 
education, a mechanism which turns basic research into an economically 
viable business opportunity for local inhabitants and an educational
program that maintains and protects this fragile ecosystem while 
providing the expertise needed by the developing environmentally 
friendly industries.
</DOC>
