<html>
<title>Tropical Ecosystem Program</title>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center>
<img align=middle src=teplogo.gif alt="Tropical Ecosystem Program Logo"><br>
</center>
<p>
<img align=right src=amazon.gif alt="Pictures of Amazon">
The Tropical Ecosystem Program (<i>TEP</i>) is a joint venture of 
Universidade Federal Fluminense, Universidade Estadual do 
Rio de Janeiro , Universidade Federal Rural do Rio de Janeiro, 
Universidade de S&#227o Paulo and the University of Maryland. The 
purpose of the <i>TEP</i> is to promote research and education initiatives 
involving tropical rain forests. The program, through Universidade 
Federal Fluminense, provides scientists and students access to a 
research station located at Oriximina, a village in the heart of 
undisturbed Amazon jungle. Indeed, groups of UMCP faculty and 
students (graduate and undergraduate) have traveled to Oriximina 
in each of the last three summers to conduct ecological research 
projects and to learn about this sensitive ecosystem. Students 
from Brazil have also traveled to Maryland to study ecosystems 
such as the Chesapeake Bay.
<p>
<img align=right src=deer.gif alt="Picture of person holding deer">
Critical to the preservation of the biodiversity in the Amazon 
and other tropical rain forests, is an understanding of the value 
of this resource to the world community and a parallel understanding 
of the needs of the inhabitants. Only when we have developed 
strategies that will allow the use of the rain forests in a 
sustainable manner, strategies that allow the inhabitants to 
derive a living from their environment without damaging it, will 
the threat to this resource be diminished. It is the mission of the 
<i>TEP</i> to increase understanding and develop the necessary strategies 
to accomplish these goals.

</DOC>
