<html>
<title>Vera Cruz Southern Bahia Biodiversity Project</title>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center>
<img align=middle src=bahialogo.gif alt="Vera Cruz Southern Bahia Biodiversity Project Logo"><br>
</center>
<p>
The Vera Cruz Florestal project is located in Southern Bahia near the 
coastal city of Porto Seguro, site of the first permanent settlement in 
Brazil. This area of Bahia was once almost totally covered by Atlantic 
Rain Forest. Unrestricted cutting of the forest and conversion to low 
quality pasture land has led to a situation where less than 5% of the 
original forest remains. The change from 1946 to 1990 is dramatically 
illustrated in Figures 1 and 2. The local farmers now earn subsistence 
level income.
<p>
This area of Bahia is a classic case for a sustainable development 
initiative, an area in need of a model industry that will provide 
livelihood for the local inhabitants while preserving the environment, 
particularly the remaining patches of Atlantic Rain Forest.
<p>
For several years, the Vera Cruz Forestry Company has been working on 
just such a project; the development of a sustainable pulp industry. This 
region of Bahia is ideally suited to such a project. The topography 
consists of plateaus, now used as pasture land, interspersed with steep 
valleys that provide excellent drainage. The area has a rather even 
distribution of rainfall throughout the year and has high light flux 
necessary for photosynthesis. It is an ideal area for growing eucalyptus, 
a tree that can be harvested in 6 to 7 years as opposed to the 25 to 70 
years needed for typical species used in North America for pulp. Indeed, 
eucalyptus is almost 5 times as efficient as southern pine in fixing CO<sub>2</sub>, 
a significant environmental benefit.
<p>
<center>
<img src=forestcover.gif alt="Pictures showing forest coverage in 1946 and 1990">
</center>
<p>
Vera Cruz presently has 40,000 acres planted in fast growing hybrid 
eucalyptus (Figure 3) and will eventually expand to 200,000 acres. Plans 
are underway for a pulp mill with construction to start in three years. 
The mill is being designed to be environmentally neutral, with the best 
new technology (scrubbers, electrostatic precipitators, non-chlorine 
bleaching techniques, etc.) incorporated. With construction years away, 
$1,000,000 has already been spent on environmental impact studies.
<p>
As part of their land acquisition, Vera Cruz has obtained a large tract 
of original Atlantic Rain Forest, which is contiguous with a smaller 
federal reserve. Together they constitute a 13,000 acre tract which will 
be maintained as a preserve, one of the largest in Brazils Atlantic 
forest. Vera Cruz is also committed to conserving the valleys, unsuitable 
for tree farming, that have not been clear cut and still contain original 
rain forest and to reforest those valleys that have been clear cut.
<p>
This project has many positive aspects. It will provide employment 
for 10,000 people using a renewable resource, trees. At the same time, 
it will attempt to conserve and, indeed, expand a segment of the Atlantic 
Rain Forest, one of our most sensitive ecosystems.
<p>
University of Maryland scientists are involved in many aspects of this 
project (Figure 4). There are several interesting questions that fascinate 
the ecological community that can be addressed here. One of these concerns 
the minimum size patch that will support the same biodiversity as that of 
a large area. The second is whether an ecosystem that has been severely 
damaged or destroyed can be regenerated. In Bahia we have an excellent 
opportunity to address these questions since the ongoing inventory of 
the 13,000 acre patch gives us a reliable reference with which to compare 
smaller patches. One project involves developing an inventory of a small 
patch ecosystem (one or more of the uncut valleys) to assess whether it 
has the same level of biodiversity as the reference patch. Concurrently, 
we would look at similar patches that have been damaged to monitor their 
ability to regenerate.
<p>
As a result of these studies we hope to develop reliable information 
that will allow us to predict reasonable sizes for tropical forests 
that will result in the maintenance of the existing biodiversity while 
surrounding areas support sustainable development initiatives.
<p>
<center>
<img src=rainforest.gif alt="Pictures of Hybrid Eucalyptus and Researchers
Studying a Patch of Rain Forest">
</center>
</DOC>
