<html>
<title>Sustainable Development and Conservation Biology at Univ. of Maryland</title>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center>
<img align=middle src=conslogo.gif alt="Graduate Training in Sustainable Development and Conservation Biology at Univ. of Maryland Logo"><br>
</center>
<p>
Conservation biology is a relatively new field of science 
which has quickly become a crisis discipline. The rapid 
growth of the human population, the destruction and fragmentation 
of natural ecosystems and the resulting threat to countless 
species of plants and animals have all created a tremendous 
need for information so that accurate assessments can take 
place regarding appropriate use of the Earths remaining 
biodiversity. The potential adverse consequences of these 
losses for human welfare are numerous, and are only slowly 
becoming appreciated. There is now a pressing need for 
fundamental changes in the roles that scientists play in 
helping understand and address these global problems.
<p>
Recognizing that solutions to these complex problems requires 
multidisciplinary training, The University of Maryland at 
College Park created a new graduate program in Sustainable 
Development and Conservation Biology (<i>CONS</i>). This program, 
initiated in 1991, currently has 30 graduate students from 
the United States and 7 from other countries. Students in 
the cons program take core courses in conservation biology, 
resource economics, public policy and multidisciplinary 
problem-solving, as well as electives from a wide array of 
disciplines. Students also fulfill an internship requirement 
in one of the Washingtons many conservation or development 
agencies and write a thesis based on science and economics 
and that results in policy recommendations.
<p>
<img align=right src=Monk.gif alt="Sketch of Monkeys">
In addition, the Department of Zoology has graduate students 
working in conservation biology with adjunct faculty members 
from the National Zoological Park, the Smithsonian Institutions 
Front Royal Conservation Research Center, the U.S. Museum of 
Natural History and the National Institutes of Health.
<p>
Thus, the University of Maryland has all the components 
necessary to provide training for graduate students in 
sustainable development and conservation biology: modern 
and diverse facilities located near Washington, D.C., relevant 
conservation and zoology courses, related graduate programs, 
as well as an internationally respected research and teaching 
faculty.
</DOC>
