<HTML> 
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Biochemistry of Bivalve Hemocyte Phagocytosis</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="Images/back4.gif">

<H3>Current Projects in the Paynter
Lab</H3><P>

<H4>Biochemistry of Bivalve Hemocyte Phagocytosis.</H4><P>

<BR>


<IMG ALIGN=Right SRC="Images/cells.jpg" WIDTH=288 HEIGHT=216>	We are
examining the cellular physiology and biochemistry of the phagocytic response of bivalve hemocytes. 
Although several avenues of investigation are underway, the most active are the
purification and characterization of myeloperoxidase from the hemocytes of the
Eastern oyster,<I> Crassostrea virginica</I>.  Jennifer Wojcik, a senior majoring in
Zoology, is conducting this work.  Myeloperoxidase is an important enzyme
activated when an oyster blood cell engulfs a foreign body like a protozoan
parasite.  Myeloperoxidase produces hypochlorous acid which is extremely toxic to
most cells.<P>

<P>
<P>

In closely related work, we are using pH-sensitive fluorescent dyes to elucidate
the changes in the phagosome environment after a cell is engulfed.  In vertebrate
white blood cells (the equivalent of oyster blood cells) the pH of the phagosome
lumen is acidified very quickly to activate a number of enzymes including
myeloperoxidase.  The oyster blood cells shown here appear to have brightly
fluorescent areas within them suggesting that the phagosomes have become
acidified.  We are characterizing the typical response of molluscan cells so we can learn more about their response to parasites like <I>Perkinsus</I> which appear to alter the hemocytic response in some way so as to neutralize its cytotoxicity.<P>
<P>
<P>Click for full sized images
<P>
<a href="Images/Jen1.jpg"><IMG WIDTH=85 HEIGHT=75 ALIGN=abs SRC="Images/Jen1.jpg" ></a>
<a href="Images/Amy1.jpg"><IMG WIDTH=85 HEIGHT=75 ALIGN=abs SRC="Images/Amy1.jpg" ></a>
<a href="Images/cells.jpg"><IMG WIDTH=85 HEIGHT=75 ALIGN=abs SRC="Images/cells.jpg" ></a>

<BR>

