<head><TITLE>Department of Zoology - Dr. Kennedy T. Paynter, Jr.</TITLE></head>

<BODY background="Images/back4.gif">

<IMG ALIGN=Right SRC="Images/Kensmall.jpg" WIDTH=216 HEIGHT=158 ALT="Picture of Ken">
<h3>Dr. Kennedy T. Paynter, Jr.<br><i>Associate Research Scientist</i></h3>
Dept. of Zoology<br>University of Maryland<br>College Park, Maryland 20742<br>
email:  <a href="mailto:paynter@zool.umd.edu">Paynter@zool.umd.edu</a><br>
phone:  (301) 405-7684<br>
FAX:  301-314-9358<br>
<br clear=left>
<p><hr>Research Interest: <b>Physiology and Biochemistry of Estuarine Organisms</b><br>
<p>

<BR>
<B>Research Summary</B><BR>
<BR>


	Estuarine animals possess a unique set of cellular mechanisms which allow them to survive in the everchanging conditions typical of an estuary.  Research in my lab is focused on the comparative biochemistry and physiology of estuarine animals especially bivalves.  My students and I are conducting a wide range of laboratory and field experiments in order to learn more about bivalve growth, how bivalves respond to environmental challenges, and how external factors such as diseases affect the bivalves ability to cope with environmental stress.  Since bivalve ecophysiology is so complex, we have employed a scientifically broad, interdisciplinary approach including genetics, physiology, biochemistry, endocrinology, and pathology.  This has led to productive collaborative efforts between my laboratory and several other labs in the Middle Atlantic region.   This approach allows us to learn more about the complex relationship between both physiological acclimation at the whole organism level and molecular responses at the cellular level to environmental stresses characteristic of the estuary.<BR>

<BR>

<B>Education</B><BR>

<BR>

The College of William and Mary, B.S. - Biology, 1976-1980.<BR>

	Advisor - Charlotte P. Mangum.<BR>
<BR>


Iowa State University, PhD. - Zoology, 1980-1985.<BR>

	Advisor - Stephen H. Bishop.<BR>

<BR>
<BR>


<B>Professional Experience</B><BR>
<BR>


Director of the Howard Hughes Medical Institute Undergraduate Fellowship Program, University of Maryland College of Life Sciences, 1994 - present.<BR>
<BR>


Research Associate Professor, Department of Zoology, University of Maryland, 1991 - present.<BR>

<BR>

Adjunct Assistant Professor, Horn Point Environmental Laboratory, University of Maryland, 1991 - present.<BR>

<BR>
