<i>Neisseria gonorrhoeae</i>: production of multiple lipooligosaccharides.
In Press: J. Bacteriol. </p>

<p>
<hr></p>

<h2><a href="research.html">Research program</a></h2>

<p>Dr. Stein's research focuses on the mechanisms by which the human pathogen,
<i>Neisseria gonorrhoeae</i>, is able to synthesize and regulate the expression
of one of its major outer membrane antigens, lipooligosaccharide (LOS).
Students use molecular, immunological and biochemical techniques to further
our understanding of the role of LOS in gonococcal disease. Information
gleaned from these studies is directly applicable to understanding pathogenic
mechanisms. </p>

<p>
<hr></p>

<h2>Classes</h2>

<p>Microbiology and the Public <a href="http://www.life.umd.edu/classroom/micb100">MICB 100</a> </p>

<p>General Genetics <a href="http://www.life.umd.edu/classroom/biol222">BIOL 222</a></p>

<p>
<hr><a href="http://www.life.umd.edu/grad/micb/index.html">MICROBIOLOGY
</a>home page </p>

