<html>
<head>
   <title>FACULTY</title>
   <meta name="GENERATOR" content="Mozilla/2.01Gold (Win32)">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<img src="trun.gif" alt="[Picture of Dr.

Nancy Trun]" hspace=5 vspace=5 border=0  align=right>
<h2>Nancy J. Trun</h2>

<p><b>Adjunct Faculty
<br>Department of Microbiology
<br>Molecular Biologist
<br>Ph.D., Princeton University, 1988
<br>Telephone:</b> 
<br><b>Fax:</b> 
<br><b>E-mail:</b><i><a href="mailto:trun@helix.nih.gov">trun@helix.nih.gov</a>

<br></i><b>Research Interests:</b>Chromosome Biology in <i>E.coli. </i>
<br></p>

<p>Dr. Trun is a tenure track investigator in the National Cancer Institute
at the <a href="http://www.nih.gov/welcome/">National Institutes of Health
</a>in Bethesda, MD. She also holds an adjunct assistant professorship
at the University of Maryland at College Park. Dr. Trun received her Ph.D.
from Princeton University and was a Jane Coffin Childs Postdoctoral Fellow
at NCI.</p>

<p>Many cellular processes require spatial and temporal coordination of
a complex series of events. One of the most intricate of these is replication
and segregation of daughter chromosomes. Using <i>E. coli </i>as a model
system, we have been focusing on two aspects of chromosome biology: replication
of the chromosome and condensation of the DNA into a functional nucleoid.
Both projects were initiated by isolating cells that are resistant to the
diploidizing agent, camphor. By isolating camphor resistant chromosomal
mutants, we have identified a leading strand helicase that functions to
regulate the number of replication forks that can traverse the chromosome.
By isolating high copy number plasmids that confer camphor resistance,
we have identified a three gene system that functions to condense the chromosome
across actively transcribed genes. </p>

<p><i>nbrA4 </i>is a chromosomal camphor resistant mutant that contains
twice as much DNA as wild type. We have suggested that mbrA may define
a novel coupling between DNA replication and cell elongation that
functions after initiation of replication and serves to keep chromosome
number tied to growth rate. Fine structure mapping and plasmids were used
to show that <i>mbrA</i> is allelic to the previously identified <i>rep</i>
gene which encodes a f' to 3' DNA helicase (leading strand) that is
used for, but not essential for replication of the chromosome. The <i>rep
</i>deletion cannot be maintained in combination with a deletion of another
leading strand helicase, <i>uvrD</i>. Rep and UvrD can interact in vitro
and form an active DNA helicase suggesting that there are several
leading strand helicases that E.coli uses for replication under different
conditions. We are currently investigating if <i>rep</i> and <i>uvrD</i>
are coordinately regulated and under what conditions each is used. </p>

<p>To begin to understand the mechanism of action of camphor and identify
its target, we isolated high copy number plasmids that confer resistance.
One fragment of chromosomal DNA, that maps to 14.2 min., when present in
the plasmid vector, pBR322, gives this phenotype. While the plasmid confers
camphor resistance, we have determined that it does not result in diploidy.
Deletion analysis and sequencing indicates that three genes are responsible
for the phenotype, <i>cspE</i>, a cold shock gene homologue and two other
ORF's (<i>crcA</i> and <i>crcB</i>). All three genes are required in the
correct ratios to confer camphor resistance. These same three genes also
suppress a temperature sensitive defect in the chromosomal partition gene,
<i>mukB</i>.</p>

<p>All of our data on <i>crcA, cspE </i>and <i>crcB</i> led us to suspect
that the genes are affecting chromosome condensation. In a direct test
of this, we have demonstrated that, both in vivo and in vitro, camphor
does indeed cause unfolding of the chromosome and overproduction of the
three genes results in more tightly condensed nucleoids. The original work
of Burgi and Worcell on the nucleoid demonstrated that mRNA is one
of the major components holding the nucleoid together. The recent discovery
that CspE binds to the 5' end of mRNA in an active transcription complex
suggests that this condensing mechanism senses actively transcribed genes
and may condense using the mRNA. Further experiments should shed light
on this intriguing mechanism of chromosome condensation. </p>

<p>Recent Publications</p>

<ul>
<p>Hu, K.H., Liu, E., Dean, K., Gingras, M., DeGraff, W., Trun, N.J. Overproduction
of three genes leads to camphor resistance and chromosome condensation
in <i>Escherichia coli.</i> Genetics, 143:1521 - 1532. 1996.</p>

<p>Trun, N.J. Bacterial Genomes: Physical Structure and Analysis. F. de
Bruijn, J. Lupski and G. Weinstrock, eds. Chapman and Hall, NY. 1996.</p>
</ul>

