<a href ="research.html">Return to list of other research areas in MOCB
</a>

<p>
<a name ="a"><strong>Ibrahim Z. Ades</a></strong>  Assoc. Professor, Ph.D., UCLA, 1976. 
Second messengers
and signal transduction pathways.<br>
     The research activities of Dr. Ades have focused on two areas and deal with the regulatory
processes that govern the development of eukaryotic cells.  One group of studies aims to identify
the
enzymes responsible for modulating porphyrin production and to determine how the enzymes are
regulated.  Research in the second area is examining the signalling cascades triggered by
interleukin 6 in
lymphocytes and in cells of neural origin.
<blockquote>   McKinney, C. E. and Ades, I. Z., Production of -aminolevulinic acid:
Characterization of murine liver 4,5-
dioxovaleric acid:L-alanine aminotransferase. <i> Int. J. Biochem.</i> 23:803-810 (1991).<br>
     Ryan, G. and Ades, I. Z., On the mechanism of induction of hepatic -aminolevulinate
synthase by translational blockers. 
<i>Biochem. J</i>. 272:619-621 (1991).<a href ="#list">  Return to list</a></blockquote> <p>

<a name ="b"><strong>Spencer A. Benson</a></strong>  Assoc. Professor, Ph.D., U. Chicago,
1978.  Mechanisms of bacterial evolution and genetic regulation of function of bacterial
envelopes.<p> 
     Research interests in Dr. Benson's laboratory are directed at several aspects of environmental
interactions and bacterial cell surfaces. Using<i> Escherichia coli</i> as a model system, his
group has
developed several novel genetic approaches for the isolation and characterization of mutations
that alter
cellular permeability.  The goal is to define at the molecular level how a specific class of
transmembrane
proteins (the porins) functions to allow small molecules to diffuse across the outer membrane
barrier. 
<blockquote>   Benson, S.A., DeCloux, A.M. and Munro, J.,  Mutant bias in non-lethal
selections results from selective recovery
of mutants. <i> Genetics </i> 129:647-658 (1991).<br>
     Gauthier, M.J., Benson, S.A., Flatau, G.N., Clement, R.L., Breittmayer, V.A. and Munro,
P.M.,  OmpC and OmpF porins
influence viability and culturability of<i> Escherichia coli </i>cells incubated in seawater. <i>
Microb. Releases  </i>1:47-50
(1992). <a href ="#list">  Return to list</a></blockquote>

<a name ="c2"><strong>Caren Chang  </a></strong> California Inst. of Technology, 1988. 
Molecular mechanisms of ethylene signal transduction in plants.<p>
Dr. Chang's research focuses on the mechanisms involved in the perseption and signal
transduction of the
plant hormone ethylene.  The research is based on the ethylene receptor gene, ETR1, which was
cloned from
the plant Arabidopsis thaliana.  ETR1 is a type of receptor not found previously in higher
eukaryotes, and it
is becoming apparent that there are several ETR1-related ethylene receptors in A. Thaliana.  Dr.
Chang is
interested in the molecular, genetic, and biochemical characterization of this receptor family, as
well as the
identification of components acting downstream of these receptors in the ethylene-response
pathway(s).
<blockquote>Chang, C., Kwok, S.F., Bleecker, A.B. and Meyerowitz, E.M.,  Arabidopsis
ethylene-response gene ETR1: similarity of
product to two-component regulators.  Science 262:539-544 (1993).<br>
     Hua, J., Chang, C., Sun, Q. And Meyerowitz, E.M.,  Ethylene insensitivity conferred by
Arabidopsis ERS gene.  Science, in
press (1995).<a href ="#list">  Return to list</a></blockquote>

<a name ="c"><strong>Marco Colombini</strong></a>  Professor, Ph.D., McGill U., 1974. 
Molecular mechanism
underlying the voltage control of membrane channels.<br>
     Dr. Colombini's interests are focused on the macromolecules, mainly proteins, that are lodged
within cells membranes and translocate small molecules and ions across the membrane.  Most of
the work
is being performed on the voltage-dependent channel-former VDAC, a protein located in the
outer
mitochondrial membrane.  Currently, the role of VDAC in regulating mitochondrial function and
energy
metabolism is also under investigation.  Currently, the role of VDAC in regulating mitochodrial
function
and energy metabolism also under investigation.
<blockquote>   Zambrowicz, E.B. and Colombini, M.,  Zero-current potentials in a large
membrane channel: A simple theory
accounts for complex behavior. <u> Biophys. J.</u>, 65:1093-1100 (1993).<br>
     Zizi, M., Forte, M., Blachly-Dyson, E. and Colombini, M.,  NADH regulates the gating of
VDAC, the mitochondrial outer
membrane channel. <u> J. of Biol. Chem.,</u> 269:1614-1616 (1994).
<a href="#list">  Return to list</a></blockquote>

<a name ="d"><strong>Jeffrey J. DeStefano </a> </strong>Asst. Professor, Ph.D., U.
Connecticut, 1990. 
Mechanisms of viral replication in eukaryotes.<p>
     Dr. DeStefano's studies have dealt with the mechanisms of viral replication.  He has been
particularly interested in genome replication of the human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) and the
enzymology of that particle's reverse transcriptase.  Retroviruses like HIV undergo genomic
recombination
at a high rate.  This process contributes to the substantial genetic diversity among these viruses
by
allowing for the exchange of genetic material between viruses.  Dr. DeStefano's work focuses on
the role
the viral polymerase plays in recombination.
<blockquote>   DeStefano, J.J., Bambara, R.A. and Fay, P.J.,  Affinity of human
immunodeficiency virus reverse transcriptase for
various nucleic acid structures that are present during replication.  <i>Biochemistry </i>
32:6908-6915 (1992).<br>
     DeStefano, J.J., Bambara, P.J. and Fay, P.J.,  The mechanism of human immunodeficiency
virus reverse transcriptase
catalyzed strand transfer between internal regions of heteropolymeric RNA templates. <i> J.
Biol. Chem</i>.  269:161-168
(1994)..<a href ="#list">  Return to list</a></blockquote>

<a name ="e"><strong>Edward Eisenstein</a></strong>  Asst. Professor, Ph.D., Georgetown
U., 1985.  Control of
oligomeric regulatory enzymes.<br>
     The research interests of Dr. Eisenstein are focused generally on the folding, assembly,
architecture, stability and the control of activity of proteins.  Current research on the regulation of
catalysis
by allosteric threonine deaminase and the control of cellular protein folding by the GroES/GroEL
molecular chaperones is being approached using molecular biological, biochemical and
biophysical
methods.  These tools are yielding structural, kinetic and energetic clues concerning the
mechanisms of
protein function and the control of enzyme activity.
<blockquote>   Eisenstein, E.,  Cloning, expression, purification and characterization of
biosynthetic threonine deaminase from
<i>Escherichia coli.  J. Biol. Chem.</i>  266:5801-5807 (1991).<br>
     Fisher, K.E. and Eisenstein, E.,  An efficient approach to identify ilvA mutations reveals an
amino-terminal catalytic domain
in biosynthetic threonine deaminase from <i>Escherichia coli.  J. Bacteriology 
</i>175:6605-6613 (1993).<a href ="#list">  Return to list</a></blockquote>

<a name ="g"><strong>Elisabeth Gantt</strong>  Professor, Ph.D., Northwestern U., 1963. 
Assembly and
functional development of photosynthetic membranes.<br>
     The objectives of Dr. Gantt's studies include elucidation of mechanisms by which plants
utilize
photosynthetically active energy, and the biosynthetic pathway of carotenoid synthesis in
microalgae. 
Cellular and physiological changes are being correlated, including determining topography,
functional
interactions, and regulation of the major complexes of photosynthetic membranes.  Microalgae
are being
used for enhanced productionof carotenoids (-carotene and astaxanthin) which are important for
the
aquaculture and food industry.
<blockquote>   Cunningham, F.X., Chamovitz, D., Sun, Z., Hirschberg, J. and Gantt, E., 
Molecular structure and enzymatic
function of lycopene cyclase from an oxygenic photosynthetic organism. <i> The Plant Cell.</i> 
6:1107-1121 (1994).<br>
     Gantt, E., Supramolecular membrane organization.  In: D.A. Bryant (ed.),<i> The Molecular
Biology of Cyanobacteria. </I>
Kluwer Academic Publishers, pp. 117-136 (1994).<a href ="#list">  Return
to list</a></blockquote><p>


<a name ="h"><strong>J. Norman Hansen</strong> </a> Professor, Ph.D., UCLA, 1968. 
Genetics and
functions of bacterial peptide antibiotics.<br>
     Dr. Hansen's group is studying some novel ribosomally-synthesized peptide antibiotics
(subtilin
and nisin) produced by gram-positive bacteria.  The antibiotic peptides contain many unusual
amino acids
that are introduced by post-translational modification of a precursor peptide.  These antibiotics
are being
studied to define their genes and the mechanisms of maturation of the peptide products and for
ways to use
genetic engineering to design and construct new antibiotics.
<blockquote>   Chung, Y.J. and Hansen, J.N.,  Determination of the sequence of spaE and
identification of a promoter in the
subtilin (spa) operon in <i>Bacillus subtilis.  J. Bacteriol. </i> 174:6699-6702 (1992).<br>
     Liu, W. and Hansen, J.N.,  Enhancement of the chemical and antimicrobial properties of
subtilin by site-directed
mutagenesis. <i> J. Biol. Chem.</i>  267:25078-25085 (1992).<a href ="#list">  Return to
list</a></blockquote>

<a name ="h2"><strong>Osnat Herzberg  </strong></a>Assoc. Professor, Ph.D., Weizman Inst.
of Science, Israel,
1982. 
Application of protein crystallography in the study of enzyme substrate interactions.<br>
     The bacterial PTS system is responsible for the transport of sugar substrates across the
cytoplasmic membrane, coupled with their phosphorylation.  Crystallization of cloned proteins of
the
system (cloned and expressed by Dr. Reddy from CARB and Dr. Reizer from UCSD) has been
undertaken
in Dr. Herzberg's laboratory.  So far crystals of HPr and Enzyme III have been obtained. 
Crystallographic
work is in progress towards the three dimensional structure determination of these molecules.
<blockquote>   Chen, D.C.H. and Herzberg, O.,  Inactivation of -lactamase by clavulanate:
Trapped intermediates in
cryocrystallographic studies.  <i>J. Mol. Biol.  </i>224:1103-1113 (1992).<br>
     Herzberg, O., Reddy, P., Saier, M.H., Jr., Reizer, J. and Kapadia, G.,  Structure of the
histidine-containing phosphocarrier
protein HPr from<i> Bacillus subtilis </i>at 2.0  resolution. <i> Proc. Natl. Acad. Sci.
USA.</i>  89:2499-2503
(1992).<a href ="#list">  Return to list</a></blockquote>

<a name ="j"><strong>Douglas A. Julin</strong> </a> Assoc. Professor, Ph.D., U. Calif. at
Berkeley,
1984.  DNA-protein interactions in DNA repair and recombination.<br>
     Dr. Julin is studying the action of the recBCD enzyme from E. coli, an important enzyme in
the
recombination and repair of DNA.  The approach of his group has been to dissect the enzyme
into its
component parts by studying individual subunits, combinations of two subunits, and site-directed
mutations of the subunits.  The aim is to define how the enzyme's three subunits interact with
each other
and with the substrates ATP and DNA during repair and in recombination.
<blockquote>     Korangy, F. and Julin, D.A.,  Kinetics and processivity of ATP hydrolysis and
DNA
unwinding by the RecBC enzyme from
<i>Escherichia coli.  Biochem.</i>  32:4873-4880 (1993).<br>
     Korangy, F. and Julin, D.A.,  Efficiency of ATP hydrolysis and DNA unwinding by the
RecBC enzyme from
<i>Escherichia coli.  Biochem.</i>  33:9552-9560 (1994).<a href ="#list">  Return to
list</a></blockquote>

<a name ="ka"><strong>Jason D. Kahn </a></strong>Dept. of Chemistry and Biochemistry,
Ph.D., U.
California, Berkeley, 1990.  Protein-nucleic acid interaction.<p>
     Dr. Kahn's research concerns DNA structure in multi-protein DNA complexes and the role of
such
structure in controlling transcription initiation and other DNA transactions.  New experimental
and
computational methods are being developed to study bending and looping in complicated DNA
shapes. 
DNA-binding proteins under study include E. coli RNA polymerase and the TATA-box binding
protein.<p>
<blockquote>Haran, T.E., Kahn, J.D. and Crothers, D.M.,  Sequence elements responsible for
DNA curvature.  J. Mol. Biol.  244:135-143 (1994).<br>
     Kahn, J.D. and Crothers, D.M.,  DNA bending in transcription initiation.  Cold Spring Harbor
Symp. in Quant. Biol.  58:115-122 (1993).<a href ="#list">  Return to list</a></blockquote>

<a name ="ma"><strong>Roy Mariuzza </a></strong>Center for Advanced Research in
Biotechnology, Ph.D., U. Paris, France 1985.  Molecular basis of antigen recognition by the
immune
system.<p>
     The binding of foreign antigens to complementary structures on the surface of  - and
T-lymphocytes represents the initial step in the sequence of events leading to activation of the
immune
system.  Two distinct classes of molecules, both members of the immunoglobulin supergene
family, are
responsible for antigen recognition.  These are antibodies, which function both as antigen
receptors on  -lymphocytes and as circulating effector molecules, and T-cell receptors, which
occur only in membrane-bound form.  The main interest of Dr. Mariuzza's laboratory is to
investigate the molecular basis of
antigen recognition by these two classes of receptor molecules through a combined protein
engineering, X-ray crystallographic, and physical chemical approach.<p>
<blockquote>Bentley, G.A., Boulot, G., Karjalainen, and Mariuzza, R.A.,  Crystal structure of
the   chain of a T cell
antigen receptor.  Science, 267:1984-1987 (1995). <br>
     Fields, B.A., Goldbaum, F.A., Ysern, X., Poljak, R.J., and Mariuzza, R.A.,  Molecular basis of
antigen mimicry by an
anti-idiotope.  Nature, 374:739-742 (1995).<a href ="#list">  Return to
list</a></blockquote><p>
<a name ="m"><strong>Ian H. Mather </strong> Professor, Ph.D., Univ. College of North
Wales, 1971. 
Expression and function of mammary glycoproteins.<br>
     Dr. Mather's group is currently determining the function of butyrophilin, a major protein of
the
apical surface of mammary epithelial cells by targeting a disruption to the endogenous gene in
mice by
homologous recombination.  They are also interested in characterizing the sequences associated
with the
butyrophilin gene which direct mammary-specific gene expression.  Such sequences may be used
to direct
the expression of human genes in transgenic dairy animals for commercial purposes.
<blockquote>   Bucci, C., Parton, R.G., Mather, I.H., Stunnenberg, H., Simons, K., Hoflack, B.
and Zerial, M.,  The small
GTPase rab5 functions as a regulatory factor in the early endocytic pathway. <i> Cell</i> 
70:715-728 (1992).<br>
     Vernet, C., Boretto, J., Mattei, M-G., Takahashi, M., Jack, L.J.W., Mather, I.H., Rouquier, S.
and Pontarotti, P., 
Evolutionary study of multigene families mapping close to the human MHC class I region.<i>  J.
Mol. Evol</i>. 37:600-612 (1993).<a href ="#list">  Return to list</a>
</blockquote>




<a name ="o"><strong>John Orban  </strong></a>Asst. Professor, Ph.D., Australian National
U., 1985. 
Biomolecular
NMR spectroscsopy.<br>
     The principal focus of the NMR group at CARB is the study of structure and dynamics in
biological macromolecules such as proteins and nucleic acids.  Of particular interest is the 56
amino acid
IgG-binding domain of streptococcal protein G(GB).  Our present interests include: (1) structure
determination; (2) analysis of the IgG-binding site using hydrogen-deuterium exchange
measurements; (3)
use of GB as a model to study protein folding and stability using amide exchange/protection
methods.  We
are also interested in the structure and dynamics of RNA bulged loops.  These motifs play an
important
role in RNA-protein interactions such as the HIV-TAR:tat complex.
<blockquote>   Orban, J., Alexander, P., and Bryan, P., Sequence-specific 1H NMR assignments
and secondary structure of the
streptococcal protein G B2 domain.  <i>Biochemistry </i>31:3604-3611 (1992).<br>
     Orban, J., Alexander, P., and Bryan, P., Hydrogen-deuterium exchange in the free and
immunoglobulin G-bound protein G
B-domain.<i>  Biochemistry </i>33:5702-5710 (1994).<a href ="#list">  Return to
list</a></blockquote>

<a name ="p"><strong>Richard Payne </strong> Associate Professor, Ph.D., Australian National
U.,
1982; Mechanisms of visual excitation and signal transduction in photoreceptors.<br>
     Dr. Payne investigates mechanisms of visual excitation in photoreceptors.  The research
concentrates on messenger molecules released by light inside photoreceptor cells.  These
messengers
mediate and modulate the electrical response of the photoreceptor to light.  The messenger
currently under
investigation is inositol trisphosphate, which releases calcium from internal stores within a wide
range of
animal and plant cells. The research combines methods of micro-injecting messengers into cells
with
optical and electrophysiological techniques that monitor intracellular calcium release and the
activity of
ionic channels.
<blockquote>   Levitan, I., Hillman, P. and Payne, R., Fast desensitization of the response to
photoreceptors.<i>  Biophys. J.</i>
64:1354-1360 (1993).
     Peretz, A., Suss-Toby, E., Rom-Glas, A., Arnon, A., Payne, R., and Minke, B.  The light
response of drosophila
photoreceptors is accompanied by an increase in cellular calcium.<i>  Neuron </i> 12:1257-1267
(1994).<a href ="#list"> 
Return to list</a></blockquote><p>

<a name = r><strong>Kevin D. Ridge </strong>Center for Advanced Research in Biotechnology,
Ph.D., U. Pittsburgh, 1989.  Structure and function of proteins of the visual system. <br> 
     The research in my laboratory is primarily focused on the static and dynamic aspects of
membrane
protein structure, with particular emphasis given to the dim-light photoreceptor rhodopsin. 
Biochemical,
genetic, and biophysical methods are currently being used to understand the mechanisms, kinetics,
and
thermodynamics of rhodopsin folding and assembly.  Research in a second area is devoted to the
structural
analysis of several soluble proteins involved in visual transduction and desensitization.
<blockquote>   Ridge, K. D., Lee, S. S. J. and Yao, L. L., In vivo assembly of rhodopsin from
expressed polypeptide fragments.
<i>Proc. Natl. Acad. Sci. USA </i>92:3204-3208 (1995).
     Ridge, K. D., Lee, S. S. J. and Abdulaev, N. G.,  Examining rhodopsin folding and assembly
through expression of polypeptide
fragments. <i>J. Biol. Chem.</i> 271:7860-7867 (1996).<a href ="#list">  Return to
list</a></blockquote>

<a name ="st"><strong>Richard C. Stewart </a></strong>  Dept. of Microbiology, Ph.D., U. of
Michigan,1984.  Signal transduction in microorganisms.<p>
     Microorganisms are chock-full of fascinating sensory-response systems that enable them to
respond
to changes in their immediate environments.  Research activities in Dr Stewart's laboratory focus
on
identifying and characterizing the interactions among components in several such signal
transduction
systems.  For example, current work will lead to an understanding of how the activity of a protein
kinase
(CheA) in the E. coli  chemotaxis system is controlled at a molecular level.  This control enables
E. coli  to
modulate its swimming movements in response to changes in the cell's chemical environment. 
Also under
investigation is a second distinct system that directs the activity of Skn7, a transcription factor
that operates
in Saccharomyces cerevisiae (yeast) and that appears to be involved in regulating synthesis of the
yeast cell
wall.  The goal of current efforts is to identify the signaling circuitry that regulates Skn7.<p>
<blockquote>Brown, J.L., Bussey, H., and Stewart, R.C.,  Yeast Skn7p functions in a eukaryotic
two-component regulatory pathway. 
EMBO J. 13:5186-5194 (1994).<br>
     Tawa, P. and Stewart, R.C.,  Mutational activation of CheA, the protein kinase in the
chemotaxis system of Escherichia coli. 
J. Bacteriol. 176:4210-4218 (1994).<a href ="#list">  Return to list</a></blockquote>
<a name ="s"><strong>Heven Sze</strong>  Professor,  Ph.D., Purdue U., 1975.  Biochemistry
and molecular
biology of ion pumps, cotransporters and channels.<br>
     The long-range goals of Dr. Sze's research are to understand the mechanisms of ion transport
across plant membranes, the factors that regulate them, and how membrane energization and
solute fluxes
are integrated into cell functions.  A combination of cell biology, biochemical and molecular
approaches
are being used to study H+ pumps, Ca2+ pumps, H+-coupled cotransporters and ion
channels.
<blockquote>   Lai, S., Watson, J.C., Hansen, J.N. and Sze, H.,  Molecular cloning and
sequencing of cDNAs encoding the
proteolipid subunit of the vacuolar H+-ATPase from a higher plant. <i> J. Biol. Chem.</i> 
266:16078 (1991).<br>
     Ward, J. and Sze, H.,  Subunit composition and organization of the vacuolar H+-ATPase from
oat roots.  <i>Plant Physiol.
</i> 99:170 (1992).<a href ="#list">  Return to list</a></blockquote><p>

<a name ="v"><strong>Inder K. Vijay </strong> Professor, Ph.D., U. Calif. at Davis, 1971. 
Developmental
regulation of mammary glycoprotein synthesis.<br>
     The overall objective of Dr. Vijay's research program is to understand the molecular basis for
gene
expression during animal growth and differentiation.  The focus of investigation is on the
biosynthesis and
hormonal regulation of N-linked glycoproteins in the mammary gland during its ontogeny.  These
proteins
are fundamentally involved in a myriad of biological recognition phenomena.
<blockquote>   Shailubhai, K., Pukazhenthi, B., Saxena, E.S., Varma, G. and Vijay, I.K., 
Glucosidase I, and endoplasmic
reticulum protein with high mannose type oligosaccharides.  Release of the catalytic domain by
selective proteolysis. <i> J. Biol.
Chem. </i> 266:16587-16593 (1991).<br>
     Rajput, B., Ma, J., Muniappa, N., Schantz, L., Naylor, S.L., Lalley, P.A. and Vijay, I.K., 
Mouse UDP-GlcNAc:dolichol
phosphate N-acetylglucosamine-1-phosphate transferase: molecular cloning of the cDNA,
generation of anti-peptide antibodies and
chromosomal localization. <i> Biochem. J. </i> 285:985-992 (1992).<a href ="#list">  Return to
list</a></blockquote>


<a name ="w"><strong>Sarah A. Woodson </strong></a> Asst. Professor, Ph.D., Yale U., 1987. 
Folding of catalytic RNA and of self-splicing introns.<br>
     The goal of research in Dr. Woodson's laboratory is to identify interactions that are important
for
forming the tertiary structure of self-splicing intron RNAs.  RNA molecules that have catalytic
activity are
of particular interest because their enzymatic properties suggest that they fold into globular
structures in
the same manner as protein enzymes.  Moreover, it is thought that assembly of large transcripts
in vivo
requires the assistance of other RNAs or of RNA-binding proteins.  A continuing project uses
self-splicing
of the Tetrahymena intron to study RNA folding both in vitro and in vivo.  A bacterial expression
system
should facilitate biochemical and genetic approaches to identifying elements important for
accelerating
splicing reactions.  Future projects will also include the use of spectroscopic or other physical
methods for
tracking the folding of smaller RNAs in vitro.
<blockquote>  Woodson, S. A. and Emerick, V. L.,   An alternative helix in the 26S rRNA
promotes excision and integration of
the Tetrahymena IVS. <i> Mol. Cell. Biol. </i> 13:1137-1145 (1993).<br>
     Emerick, V. L. and Woodson, S. A.,  Fingerprinting the folding of a group I precursor
RNA.<i>  Proc. Natl. Acad. Sci.
USA</i> (1994, in press).<a href ="#list">  Return to Biochemistry research list</a><p>
</a></blockquote>
<a href ="research.html">Return to "Research Areas"page</a>
