<body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<h2>University of Maryland<br>
Molecular & Cell Biology Program </h2><a name="list">
<h2>Cell Biology Faculty</h2>
<a href="#a"><strong>Ibrahim Z. Ades   </a></i></strong> Second
messengers and signal transduction pathways.<br>
<a href="#c"><strong>Marco Colombini  </a></i></strong> 
Molecular mechanism underlying the voltage control of membrane channels.<br>
<a href="#g"><strong>Elisabeth Gantt  </a></strong>  Assembly and
functional development of photosynthetic membranes.<br>
<a href="#go"><strong>M. Dennis Goode  </a></strong>   Mechanisms
of cell motility. <br>
<a href="#m"><strong>Ian H. Mather  </a> </strong> Expression and function of mammary
glycoproteins.<br>
<a href="#p"><strong>Sidney K. Pierce  </a></strong>  Physiology of cell volume
regulation.<br>
<a href="#r"><strong>Rodolfo J. Rivas  </a></strong>  Molecular and cellular mechanisms of
neuronal morphogenesis and polarity. <br>
<a href="#s"><strong>Heven Sze  </a></strong>   Biochemistry and molecular
biology of ion pumps, cotransporters and channels.<br>
<a href="#v"><strong>Inder K. Vijay  </a></strong>  Developmental
regulation of mammary glycoprotein synthesis.<br>
<a href="#w"> <strong>Stephen M. Wolniak  </a> </strong> Biology of cell motility, mitotic
mechanisms, and signal transduction.<br>
<p>
<a href ="research.html">Return to "Research Areas"page</a>
<hr>
<a name ="a"><strong>Ibrahim Z. Ades</a></strong>  Assoc. Professor, Ph.D., UCLA, 1976. 
Second messengers
and signal transduction pathways.<br>
     The research activities of Dr. Ades have focused on two areas and deal with the regulatory
processes that govern the development of eukaryotic cells.  One group of studies aims to identify
the
enzymes responsible for modulating porphyrin production and to determine how the enzymes are
regulated.  Research in the second area is examining the signalling cascades triggered by
interleukin 6 in
lymphocytes and in cells of neural origin.<br>
<blockquote>   McKinney, C. E. and Ades, I. Z., Production of -aminolevulinic acid:
Characterization of murine liver 4,5-
dioxovaleric acid:L-alanine aminotransferase. <i> Int. J. Biochem.</i> 23:803-810 (1991).<br>
     Ryan, G. and Ades, I. Z., On the mechanism of induction of hepatic -aminolevulinate
synthase by translational blockers. 
<i>Biochem. J</i>. 272:619-621 (1991).<a href ="#list">  Return
to list</a></blockquote> <p>

<a name ="c"><strong>Marco Colombini</strong></a>  Professor, Ph.D., McGill U., 1974. 
Molecular mechanism
underlying the voltage control of membrane channels.<br>
     Dr. Colombini's interests are focused on the macromolecules, mainly proteins, that are lodged
within cells membranes and translocate small molecules and ions across the membrane.  Most of
the work
is being performed on the voltage-dependent channel-former VDAC, a protein located in the
outer
mitochondrial membrane.  Currently, the role of VDAC in regulating mitochondrial function and
energy
metabolism is also under investigation.  Currently, the role of VDAC in regulating mitochodrial
function
and energy metabolism also under investigation.
<blockquote>   Zambrowicz, E.B. and Colombini, M.,  Zero-current potentials in a large
membrane channel: A simple theory
accounts for complex behavior. <u> Biophys. J.</u>, 65:1093-1100 (1993).<br>
     Zizi, M., Forte, M., Blachly-Dyson, E. and Colombini, M.,  NADH regulates the gating of
VDAC, the mitochondrial outer
membrane channel. <u> J. of Biol. Chem.,</u> 269:1614-1616 (1994).<a href ="#list">  Return
to list</a></blockquote><p>



<a name ="g"><strong>Elisabeth Gantt</strong>  Professor, Ph.D., Northwestern U., 1963. 
Assembly and
functional development of photosynthetic membranes.<br>
     The objectives of Dr. Gantt's studies include elucidation of mechanisms by which plants
utilize
photosynthetically active energy, and the biosynthetic pathway of carotenoid synthesis in
microalgae. 
Cellular and physiological changes are being correlated, including determining topography,
functional
interactions, and regulation of the major complexes of photosynthetic membranes.  Microalgae
are being
used for enhanced productionof carotenoids (-carotene and astaxanthin) which are important for
the
aquaculture and food industry.<br>
<blockquote>   Cunningham, F.X., Chamovitz, D., Sun, Z., Hirschberg, J. and Gantt, E., 
Molecular structure and enzymatic
function of lycopene cyclase from an oxygenic photosynthetic organism. <i> The Plant Cell.</i> 
6:1107-1121 (1994).<br>
     Gantt, E., Supramolecular membrane organization.  In: D.A. Bryant (ed.),<i> The Molecular
Biology of Cyanobacteria. </I>
Kluwer Academic Publishers, pp. 117-136 (1994).<a href ="#list">  Return
to list</a></blockquote><p>

<a name ="go"><strong>M. Dennis Goode</strong>  Assoc. Professor, Ph.D., Iowa State U.,
1967.  Mechanisms
of
cell motility. <br>
     The major goal of research in Dr. Goode's laboratory is to determine how microtubule-based
movements such as secretory granule and mitotic chromosome movements are regulated. 
Recently the
work has focused on the role of kinesin, a microtubules-associated motor protein, in the
movements of
secretory granules containing insulin.<br>
<blockquote>   Farshori, P.Q . and Goode, D.,  Kinesin is phosphorylated during stimulation of
insulin secretion and associates
with secretory granules in HIT cells. <i> J. Cell Biol</i>.  115:390 (1991).<br>
     Farshori, P.Q. and Goode, D.,  Effects of the microtubule depolymerizing and stabilizing
agents Nocodazole and taxol on
glucose-induced insulin secretion from hamster islet tumor (HIT) cells.<i>  J. Submicrosc. Cytol.
Pathol</i>.  26:137-146
(1994).<a href ="#list">  Return
to list</a></blockquote><p>

<a name ="m"><strong>Ian H. Mather </strong> Professor, Ph.D., Univ. College of North
Wales, 1971. 
Expression and function of mammary glycoproteins.<br>
     Dr. Mather's group is currently determining the function of butyrophilin, a major protein of
the
apical surface of mammary epithelial cells by targeting a disruption to the endogenous gene in
mice by
homologous recombination.  They are also interested in characterizing the sequences associated
with the
butyrophilin gene which direct mammary-specific gene expression.  Such sequences may be used
to direct
the expression of human genes in transgenic dairy animals for commercial purposes.<br>
<blockquote>   Bucci, C., Parton, R.G., Mather, I.H., Stunnenberg, H., Simons, K., Hoflack, B.
and Zerial, M.,  The small
GTPase rab5 functions as a regulatory factor in the early endocytic pathway. <i> Cell</i> 
70:715-728 (1992).<br>
     Vernet, C., Boretto, J., Mattei, M-G., Takahashi, M., Jack, L.J.W., Mather, I.H., Rouquier, S.
and Pontarotti, P., 
Evolutionary study of multigene families mapping close to the human MHC class I region.<i>  J.
Mol. Evol</i>. 37:600-612 (1993).<a href ="#list">  Return to list</a>
</blockquote>


<a name ="p"><strong>Sidney K. Pierce </a></strong> Dept. of Zoology, Ph.D., Florida State
U.,
1970.  Physiology of cell volume regulation.<p>
     The biochemical and molecular mechanisms regulating cell volume recovery are the focus of
research
in Dr. Pierce's laboratory.  Currently, the role of calcium in the regulation of cell membrane
permeability to
amino acids and inorganic ions during hypo-osmotic stress is being studied.  All work has been
done on the
cells of estuarine and intertidal invertebrates.  Many of these organisms are able to withstand a
wide range of
salinity fluctuations while continuing to regulate cell volume.<p>
<blockquote>Pierce, S.K.,  Osmolyte permeability in molluscan red cells is regulated by Ca2+ and
membrane protein phosphorylation:
The present perspective.  In: L. Deaton and S.K. Pierce (eds.), Cell volume regulation
symposium, J. Exp. Biol.  268:166-170
(1994).<br>
     Rumpho, M.E., Mujer, C.V., Andrews, D.L., Manhart, J.R. and Pierce, S.K.,  Extraction of
DNA from mucilaginous tissues of
a sea slug (Elysia chlorotica).  BioTechniques.  (1994). <a href ="#list">  Return to
list</a></blockquote><p>
 
<a name ="r"><strong>Rodolfo J. Rivas </a></strong> Dept. of Zoology, Ph.D., U. Calif. at
Berkeley,
1988.  Molecular and cellular mechanisms of neuronal morphogenesis and polarity. <p>
     Using cerebellar granule neurons as a model system, the objective of Dr. Rivas's research is to
understand how neuronal polarity is generated in the developing nervous system.  A combination
of cellular
and molecular approaches is being used to study the mechanisms that generate and maintain
distinct axonal
and dendritic distributions of cytoskeletal elements, membranous organelles, and
membrane-associated
proteins.
<blockquote>Rivas, R.J. and Hatten, M.E.,  Motility and cytoskeletal structure in migrating
cerebellar granule neurons.  J. Neurosci.
15:981-989 (1995).<br>
     Rivas, R.J., Burmeister, D.W., and Goldberg, D.J.,  Rapid effects of laminin on the growth
cone.  Neuron 8:107-115 (1992).
<a href ="#list">  Return to list</a></blockquote><p>
 

<a name ="s"><strong>Heven Sze</strong>  Professor,  Ph.D., Purdue U., 1975.  Biochemistry
and molecular
biology of ion pumps, cotransporters and channels.<br>
     The long-range goals of Dr. Sze's research are to understand the mechanisms of ion transport
across plant membranes, the factors that regulate them, and how membrane energization and
solute fluxes
are integrated into cell functions.  A combination of cell biology, biochemical and molecular
approaches
are being used to study H+ pumps, Ca2+ pumps, H+-coupled cotransporters and ion
channels.<br>
<blockquote>   Lai, S., Watson, J.C., Hansen, J.N. and Sze, H.,  Molecular cloning and
sequencing of cDNAs encoding the
proteolipid subunit of the vacuolar H+-ATPase from a higher plant. <i> J. Biol. Chem.</i> 
266:16078 (1991).<br>
     Ward, J. and Sze, H.,  Subunit composition and organization of the vacuolar H+-ATPase from
oat roots.  <i>Plant Physiol.
</i> 99:170 (1992).<a href ="#list">  Return to list</a></blockquote><p>

<a name ="v"><strong>Inder K. Vijay </strong> Professor, Ph.D., U. Calif. at Davis, 1971. 
Developmental
regulation of mammary glycoprotein synthesis.<br>
     The overall objective of Dr. Vijay's research program is to understand the molecular basis for
gene
expression during animal growth and differentiation.  The focus of investigation is on the
biosynthesis and
hormonal regulation of N-linked glycoproteins in the mammary gland during its ontogeny.  These
proteins
are fundamentally involved in a myriad of biological recognition phenomena.<br>
<blockquote>   Shailubhai, K., Pukazhenthi, B., Saxena, E.S., Varma, G. and Vijay, I.K., 
Glucosidase I, and endoplasmic
reticulum protein with high mannose type oligosaccharides.  Release of the catalytic domain by
selective proteolysis. <i> J. Biol.
Chem. </i> 266:16587-16593 (1991).<br>
     Rajput, B., Ma, J., Muniappa, N., Schantz, L., Naylor, S.L., Lalley, P.A. and Vijay, I.K., 
Mouse UDP-GlcNAc:dolichol
phosphate N-acetylglucosamine-1-phosphate transferase: molecular cloning of the cDNA,
generation of anti-peptide antibodies and
chromosomal localization. <i> Biochem. J. </i> 285:985-992 (1992).<a href ="#list">  Return to
list</a><br></blockquote>

<a name ="w"><strong>Stephen M. Wolniak </strong> Assoc. Professor, Ph.D., U. Calif. at
Berkeley, 1979. 
Biology of cell motility, mitotic mechanisms, and signal transduction.<br>
     The theme of Dr. Wolniak's research program centers on the roles of ions and other factors in
the
regulation of microtubule arrays that function in motility and development in plant and animal
cells. 
Work in his laboratory has focused on the possible involvement of calcium and protein
phosphorylation in
the regulation of mitotic events. His experiments on stamen hair cells of the spiderwort plant,
Tradescantia
virginiana have led to a working model for the regulatory cascade that culminates in anaphase
onset where
it appears that elevations in protein kinase activities early in prometaphase and again late in
metaphase are
punctuated by a period of high protein phosphatase activity that occurs in mid-metaphase.<br>
<blockquote>   Wolniak, S.M. and Larsen, P.M.,  Changes in the metaphase transit times and the
pattern of sister chromatid
separation in stamen hair cells of <i>Tradescantia</i> after treatment with protein phosphatase
inhibitors.<i> J. Cell Sci.</i>
102:691-715 (1992).<br>
     Larsen, P.M. and Wolniak, S.M.,  Asynchronous entry into anaphase induced by okadaic acid:
spindle microtubule
organization and microtubule/kinetochore attachments.<i>  Protoplasma </i> 177:53-65 (1993).
<a href ="#list">  Return to list</a><br>
</blockquote>
<a href ="research.html">Return to "Research Areas"page</a>
