<head>
<title>University of Maryland
Molecular & Cell Biology Program</title> </head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<h2>University of Maryland<br>
Molecular & Cell Biology Program </h2><a name="list">
<h2>Developmental Biology Faculty</h2>
<a href="#b1"><strong> Eric Baehrecke</a></strong> Steroid regulation of development in
Drosophila.<br>
<a href="#c"><strong>Catherine Carr </a></strong> Processing of temporally ordered
information in the CNS. <br>
<a href="#c2"><strong>Caren Chang  </a></strong> Molecular mechanisms of ethylene signal
transduction in plants.<br>
<a href="#d"><strong>Shyam K.  Dube  </a></strong> Gene regulatory mechanisms.<br>
<a href="#h"><strong>Bruce Howard  </a></strong> Regulation of cell growth with an emphasis
on the roles of anti-oncogenes.<br>
<a href="#k"><strong>Wayne J. Kuenzel </a></strong> Neuroanatomy and neurobiology of
avian development.<br>
<a href="#l"><strong>Zhongchi Liu </a></strong>  Molecular genetics of flower development in
Arabidopsis.<br>
<a href="#m"><strong>Michael C. Ma </a> </strong> Insect reproductive physiology and
neuroendocrinolgy. <br>
<a href="#o"><strong>David O'Brochta </a></strong> Biological
consequences and molecular genetics of transposable elements in insects.<br>
<a href="#r"><strong>Jerome C. Regier </a></strong>  Molecular systematics of insects and
gene families.<br>
<a href="#t"><strong>Soichi Tanda </a></strong>  Roles of
transposable elements in the development of the insect visual system.<br>
<p> <a href ="research.html">Return to "Research Areas"page</a>
<hr>
<a name ="b1"><strong> Eric Baehrecke</a></strong>Center for Agricultural Biotechnology,
Ph.D., U.  Wisconsin, Madison, 1992.  Steroid regulation of development in Drosophila.<p> 
     Research in the Baehrecke laboratory focuses on determining the molecular and genetic
mechanisms that enable a single steroid hormone to elicit diverse biological responses during
metamorphosis of the fruit fly, Drosophila melanogaster.  Projects are aimed at understanding
how steroids activate either programmed cell death or cell differentiation in the context of
development.  Studies of these cellular responses has direct relevance to higher organisms, since
steroid regulation of processes as different as metabolism, reproduction, and development have
been conserved throughout eukaryotes. <br>
<blockquote>   Woodard C.T., Baehrecke E.H., and Thummel C.  S.  A molecular mechanism for
the stage-specificity of the Drosophila prepupal genetic response to ecdysone.<i> Cell</i>
79:607-615 (1994).<br>
     Baehrecke E.  H., and Thummel C.  S.  The Drosophila E93 gene from the 93F early puff
displays stage-and tissue-specific regulation by 20-hydroxyecdysone.  <i> Escherichia coli
</i>cells incubated in seawater. <i>
Dev. Biol.  </i>171:85-97
(1995). <a href ="#list">  Return to list</a></blockquote>
<a name ="c"><strong>Catherine Carr  </a></strong>Ph.D., University of California San Diego,
1984.  Processing of temporally ordered information in the brain.<p>
When sound reaches one ear before the other, the brain uses the resulting interaural time
differences to
localize the sound.  The barn owl is a nocturnal hunter and a good model for how we localize
sound and
process temporal information in general.  In the auditory brainstem, the owl translates interaural
time
differences into location in space.  Current research is focused on models of the neural circuit and
on the
assembly of the map of sound location during development  All projects develop from initial
behavioral
observations into systems, cellular and molecular levels of analysis.
<blockquote>Carr, C. E.,  Timing mechanisms in the CNS. Annual Review of Neuroscience
16:223-243 (1993).<a href ="#list"> 
Return to
list</a></blockquote>
<a name ="c2"><strong>Caren Chang  </a></strong> California Inst. of Technology, 1988. 
Molecular mechanisms of ethylene signal transduction in plants.<p>
Dr. Chang's research focuses on the mechanisms involved in the perseption and signal
transduction of the
plant hormone ethylene.  The research is based on the ethylene receptor gene, ETR1, which was
cloned from
the plant Arabidopsis thaliana.  ETR1 is a type of receptor not found previously in higher
eukaryotes, and it
is becoming apparent that there are several ETR1-related ethylene receptors in A. Thaliana.  Dr.
Chang is
interested in the molecular, genetic, and biochemical characterization of this receptor family, as
well as the
identification of components acting downstream of these receptors in the ethylene-response
pathway(s).
<blockquote>Chang, C., Kwok, S.F., Bleecker, A.B. and Meyerowitz, E.M.,  Arabidopsis
ethylene-response gene ETR1: similarity of
product to two-component regulators.  Science 262:539-544 (1993).<br>
     Hua, J., Chang, C., Sun, Q. And Meyerowitz, E.M.,  Ethylene insensitivity conferred by
Arabidopsis ERS gene.  Science, in
press (1995).<a href ="#list">  Return to
list</a></blockquote>

<a name ="d"><strong> Shyam K.  Dube  </a></strong> Center for Agricultural Biotechnology,
Ph.D., Kansas State U., 1961.  Gene regulatory mechanisms.<p>
Gene regulatory mechanisms in a broader sense constitute the major thrust of the laboratory's
interest.  One project is concerned with mechanisms of plant protection from environmental
stresses.  We have developed a soybean chalcone synthase gene family system consisting of seven
genes, one inducible by broad spectrum light as well as UV - B, another only by UV - B, yet
another by sucrose and two genes in a bidirectional promoter linkage, differing in their light
responsiveness.  The other project is concerned with the roles of unusual structural features within
the body of the genes.  In this category, we have developed two systems, one consisting of four
non-coding exons and the other of an anti-sense transcript region. 
<blockquote> Akada, S.  and Dube, S.K.  Organization of soybean chalcone synthase gene
clusters and characterization of a new member of the family. <i>Plant Mol. Biol.</i>29:189-199
(1995).<br>
     Hua, S.B., Dube, S.K. and Kung, S.D.  Molecular evolutionary analysis of the PSbP gene
family of the photosystem II oxygen-evolving complex in Nicotiana. <i> Genome</i> 36:483-488
(1993).<a href ="#list">  Return tolist</a></blockquote>


<a name ="h"><strong>Bruce H. Howard  </a></strong> Lab of Molecular Growth Regulation ,
NICHHD, M.D., U. California at San Francisco, 1972.  Mammalian cell cycle regulation and
chromatin-mediated gene silencing mechanisms.<p>

     Dr. Howard's research focuses on the molecular mechanisms that underlie immortalization and
senescence in mammalian cells.  His laboratory uses a variety of novel gene transfer techniques to
study the
function of tumor supporessor genes.  In addition, his group has recently sought to relate cell
cycle-linked
defects in the reassembly of repressive chromatin domains to checkpoint controls.  Interpersed
repeat
elements are studied as model systems for chromatin-mediated gene silencing.
<blockquote>Ogryzko, V.V., Hirai, T.H., Shih, C.E., and Howard, B.H.,  Dissociation of
retinoblasoma gene protein
hyperphosphorylation and commitment to enter Sphase.  J. Virology, 68(6):3724-3732
(1994).<br>
     Englander, E.W. and Howard, B.H.,  Nucleosome positioning by human Alu elements in
chromatin.  J. Biol. Chem.
270(17):10091-10096 (1995). <a href ="#list">  Return to
list</a></blockquote>

<a name ="k"><strong>Wayne J. Kuenzel </a></strong> Dept. of Poultry Science, Ph.D., U.
Georgia,
1969.  Neuroanatomy and neurobiology of avian development.<p>
     The overall goal in Dr. Kuenzel's laboratory is to document functional neuroanatomical
pathways
throughout the avian brain.  Research being conducted involves exploring mechanisms that affect
the neural
regulation of food intake and early onset of gonadal development.  Two examples of
neuromodulators being
studied include neuropeptide Y (NPY) and vasoactive intestinal polypeptide (VIP). 
Immunocytochemistry is
first used to map the distribution of perikarya and fibers throughout the chick brain.  In situ
hybridization is
then applied to determine gene expression during specific periods of development or experimental
manipulation.  Sterotaxy and tract-tracing procedures are utilized to ascertain which groups of
neurons
significantly alter feeding behavior or onset of puberty.<p>
<blockquote>   Kuenzel, W.J. and Blhser, S., Vasuactive intestinal polypeptide (VIP)-containing
neurons: distribution throughout
the brain of the chick<i> (Gallus domesticus)</i> with focus upon the lateral septal organ. <i>Cell
Tissue Res. </i>275:91-107
(1994).<br>
     Kuenzel,W.J.,  Central neuroanatomical systems involved in the regulation of food intake in
birds and mammals.  J. Nutr.
142:13555-13705 (1994). <a href ="#list">  Return to
list</a></blockquote>

<a name ="l"><strong>Zhongchi Liu</strong>  Dept. of Plant Biology, Ph.D., Harvard U., 1990. 
Molecular genetics of flower development in <i>Arabidopsis</i><p>.
     The research activities in Dr. Liu's laboratory are aimed at understanding the molecular and genetic
basis of pattern formation and organ morphogenesis in higher plant development.  Using <i>Arabidopsis
</i>as a model system, genes that regulate both flower organ formation and cell division in flowers have
been identified.  These genes will be cloned using methods of map-based cloning and transposon tagging and
will be characterized at the molecular level.  Ultimately, by changing the regulation of these genes in
transgenic plants, new types of flowers will be created.<br>
 <blockquote>       Liu, Z. and Meyerowitz, E. M.  LEUNIG regulates AGAMOUS expression in Arabidopsis flowers. <i> Development
</i> 121: 975-991 (1995).<br>
        Liu, Z., Kirch, S., and Ambros, V.  The <i>C. elegans </i>heterochronic gene pathway controls stage-specific transcription of
collagen genes. <i>Development </i>121:2471-2478 (1995).</blockquote>
<a name ="m"><strong>Michael C. Ma </a></strong> Dept. of Entomology, Ph.D., U.
Wisconsin, Madison, 1978.  Insect reproductive physiology and neuroendocrinology.<p>
     Dr. Ma's group is broadly interested in insect reproductive physiology with emphasis on
vitellogenesis and ovarian development.  They hope to understand the different mechanisms
involved in the regulation of vitellogenin production and its internalization in developing egg
follicles and the development of oogonia into mature eggs. <p>
<blockquote>Song, Q. and Ma, M.,  A monocolonal antibody to a 56 KD neurosecretory
polypeptide from the posterior
lateral neurosecretory cells of the housefly, Musca domestica.  Insect. Biochem. Molec. Biol. 
22:149-157 (1992).<br>
     Blackburn, M.B., Kingan, T.G., Bodnar, W., Hunt, D.F., Kempe, T., Wagner, R.M., Raina,
A.D. and Ma, M., 
Isolation and identification of a new diuretic peptide form the tobacco hornworm, Manduca sexta. 
Biochem. Biophy. Res.
Comm.  181:927-932 (1992).<a href ="#list">  Return to
list</a></blockquote>

<a name ="o"><strong>David O'Brochta  </a></strong> Asst. Professor, Ph.D., U. Calif. at
Irvine, 1985.  Biological consequences and molecular genetics of transposable elements in
insects.<p>
     The research in Dr. O'Brochta's laboratory is concerned with the molecular genetic analysis of
insect systems.  Currently, their effort is focused on a unique and important class of genetic
element called transposons.  These ubiquitous and abundant components of probably all genomes
can have profound influences on the organism, for example, by causing mutations and
chromosomal rearrangements.  In addition, transposons can be harnessed to serve as vectors by
which foreign DNA can be introduced into the genome of an individual.  The research in Dr.
O'Brochta's laboratory has specifically focused on the <i>hobo </i>transposon from
<i>Drosophila melanogaster</i>.  Dr. O'Brochta is interested in elucidating the mechanisms
responsible for regulating this movement.<p>
<blockquote>   O'Brochta, D.A., Warren, W.D., Saville, K.J. and Atkinson, P.W.,  Interplasmid
transposition of Drosophila hobo elements in non-drosophilid insects. <i> Molec. Gen. Genet.
</i> 244:9-14 (1994).<br>
     Warren, W.D., Atkinson, P.W. and O'Brochta, D.A.,  The Hermes transposoble element from
the house fly, Musca domestica, is a short inverted repeat-type element of the hobo, Ac, and
Tam3 (HAT) element family.<i>  Genetical Research </i>  (in press).<a href ="#list">  Return to
list</a></blockquote>

<a name ="r"><strong>Jerome C. Regier </a></strong> Assoc. Professor, Ph.D., Harvard U.,
1975.  Molecular systematics of insects and gene families.<p>
     Dr. Regier's laboratory reconstructs phylogenetic relationships among arthropod species based
on generation and analysis of nuclear gene sequences.  Students are exposed to the many
controversies and
challenges in the fields of molecular evolution and systematics.  A central goal of the laboratory
is to
develop efficient and accurate methods for identifying new, phylogenetically informative gene
sequences
and to apply them to outstanding questions in arthropod phylogeny.  Over the last several years,
research
has focused on relationships at the base of the Lepidoptera (moths) and within the speciose moth
superfamily Noctuoidea.  More recently, genes for exploring ordinal relationships within
chelicerates
(spiders, scorpions, etc.) and sub-phylum relationships within arthropods are being identified and
tested.<p>
<blockquote>   Friedlander, T.P., Regier, J.C. and Mitter, C.,  Nuclear gene sequences for
higher-level phylogenetic analysis: 14
promising candidates.  <i>Systematic Biol.</i>  41:483-490 (1992).<br>
     Friedlander, T.P., Regier, J.C. and Mitter, C., Phylogenetic information content of five nuclear
gene sequences: Initial
assessment of character sets from concordance and divergence studies.  <i>Systematic Biol. </i>
(Dec. 1994, in press). <a href ="#list">  Return to list</a></blockquote>

<a name ="t"><strong>Soichi Tanda </a></strong> Asst. Professor, D.Sc., Hokkaido U. (Japan),
1985.  Roles of transposable elements in the development of the insect visual system.<br>
     Dr. Tanda's research focuses on the biology of transposons in<i> Drosophila.</I>  The
transposons are mobile DNA elements that are capable of changing their locations in the genome. 
Most
spontaneous mutations in<i> Drosophila </I >ave been found associated with the insertions of
transposons.  It is unclear at this stage whether or not these elements play roles in the
evolutionary process. 
Dr. Tanda's research interests are directed at elucidating the roles that insertion elements (tom,
Om(1D),
and P-elements) play in the development of the adult compound eye of<i> Drosophila.</i><p>
<blockquote>Tanda,  S. and Corces, V.G.,  Retrotransposon-induced overexpression of a
homeobox gene causes defects in eye
morphogenesis in<i> Drosophila.  EMBO J.</i>  10:407-417 (1991).<br>
     Tanda, S., Leshko, L.A. and Corces, V.G.,  Genetic and molecular analysis of Optic
morphology mutants.  In: Y.N. Tobari
(ed.)<i>,  Genetical and Biological Aspects,</I> Japan Scientific Society Press, Tokyo and
KARGER, Basel, pp. 89-119
(1993).<a href ="#list">  Return to list</a><br>
</blockquote>
<a href ="research.html">Return to "Research Areas" page</a>
