genetics of transposable elements in insects.<br>
<a href="#r"><strong>Jerome C. Regier </a></strong>  Molecular systematics of insects and
gene families.<br>
<a href="#s"><strong>Daniel C. Stein</a> </strong>  Modulation of
expression of prokaryotic antigens in pathogenesis.<br>
<a href="#s2"><strong>Wolfgang Stephan</a></strong>  Molecular evolution and population
genetics.<br>
<a href="#t"><strong>Soichi Tanda </a></strong> Roles of transposable elements in the
development of the insect visual system.<br>
<p><a href ="research.html">Return to "Research Areas"page</a> <hr>

<a name ="b1"><strong> Eric Baehrecke</a></strong>Center for Agricultural Biotechnology,
Ph.D., U.  Wisconsin, Madison, 1992.  Steroid regulation of development in Drosophila.<p> 
     Research in the Baehrecke laboratory focuses on determining the molecular and genetic
mechanisms that enable a single steroid hormone to elicit diverse biological responses during
metamorphosis of the fruit fly, Drosophila melanogaster.  Projects are aimed at understanding
how steroids activate either programmed cell death or cell differentiation in the context of
development.  Studies of these cellular responses has direct relevance to higher organisms, since
steroid regulation of processes as different as metabolism, reproduction, and development have
been conserved throughout eukaryotes. <br>
<blockquote>   Woodard C.T., Baehrecke E.H., and Thummel C.  S.  A molecular mechanism for
the stage-specificity of the Drosophila prepupal genetic response to ecdysone.<i> Cell</i>
79:607-615 (1994).<br>
     Baehrecke E.  H., and Thummel C.  S.  The Drosophila E93 gene from the 93F early puff
displays stage-and tissue-specific regulation by 20-hydroxyecdysone.  <i> Escherichia coli
</i>cells incubated in seawater. <i>
Dev. Biol.  </i>171:85-97
(1995). <a href ="#list">  Return to list</a></blockquote>


<a name ="b"><strong>Spencer A. Benson</a></strong>  Assoc. Professor, Ph.D., U. Chicago,
1978.  Mechanisms of bacterial evolution and genetic regulation of function of bacterial
envelopes.<p> 
     Research interests in Dr. Benson's laboratory are directed at several aspects of environmental
interactions and bacterial cell surfaces. Using<i> Escherichia coli</i> as a model system, his
group has
developed several novel genetic approaches for the isolation and characterization of mutations
that alter
cellular permeability.  The goal is to define at the molecular level how a specific class of
transmembrane
proteins (the porins) functions to allow small molecules to diffuse across the outer membrane
barrier. <br>
<blockquote>   Benson, S.A., DeCloux, A.M. and Munro, J.,  Mutant bias in non-lethal
selections results from selective recovery
of mutants. <i> Genetics </i> 129:647-658 (1991).<br>
     Gauthier, M.J., Benson, S.A., Flatau, G.N., Clement, R.L., Breittmayer, V.A. and Munro,
P.M.,  OmpC and OmpF porins
influence viability and culturability of<i> Escherichia coli </i>cells incubated in seawater. <i>
Microb. Releases  </i>1:47-50
(1992). <a href ="#list">  Return to list</a></blockquote>


<a name ="c"><strong>Lin Chao </strong> Assoc. Professor, Ph.D., U. Massachusetts, 1979. 
Microbial
evolution.<p>
     Dr. Chao's research examines evolutionary processes in microbes: bacteria and their viruses. 
His
current studies deal with the evolution of sex in RNA viruses, using as a model system
bacteriophage 6
particles and its host bacterium <i>Pseudomonas syringae. </i> By developing computer models
for the
population genetics of 6 and then testing their predictions with laboratory population of 6, it
is hoped
that the evolutionary advantage of genome segmentation (sex) in 6 and in other organisms will
be better
understood.<p>
<blockquote>   Chao, L.,  Using negative cross-resistance to reduce levels of antibiotic resistance
in bacterial populations.  In: S.
Levy and R. Novick (eds.),<i> Antibiotic Resistance Genes: Ecology, Transfer, and
Expression</i> (Banbury Report 24), Cold Spring
Harbor Laboratory, New York, pp. 71-80 (1986).<br>
     Chao, L.,  Evolution of sex in RNA viruses.<i>  J. Theor. Biol.</i>  133:99-112 (1988). <a

href ="#list">  Return to list</a></blockquote>

<a name ="d"><strong> Shyam K.  Dube  </a></strong> Center for Agricultural Biotechnology,
Ph.D., Kansas State U., 1961.  Gene regulatory mechanisms.<p>
Gene regulatory mechanisms in a broader sense constitute the major thrust of the laboratory's
interest.  One project is concerned with mechanisms of plant protection from environmental
stresses.  We have developed a soybean chalcone synthase gene family system consisting of seven
genes, one inducible by broad spectrum light as well as UV - B, another only by UV - B, yet
another by sucrose and two genes in a bidirectional promoter linkage, differing in their light
responsiveness.  The other project is concerned with the roles of unusual structural features within
the body of the genes.  In this category, we have developed two systems, one consisting of four
non-coding exons and the other of an anti-sense transcript region. 
<blockquote> Akada, S.  and Dube, S.K.  Organization of soybean chalcone synthase gene
clusters and characterization of a new member of the family. <i>Plant Mol. Biol.</i>29:189-199
(1995).<br>
     Hua, S.B., Dube, S.K. and Kung, S.D.  Molecular evolutionary analysis of the PSbP gene
family of the photosystem II oxygen-evolving complex in Nicotiana. <i> Genome</i> 36:483-488
(1993).<a href ="#list">  Return to list</a></blockquote>

<a name ="g"><strong>Jane Glazebrook </strong>  Center for Agricultural Biotechnology, Ph.D.,
Massachusetts Institute of Technology, 1991. Genetic analysis of plant defenses against pathogen attack.<p>
     Research in Dr. Glazebrook's laboratory is directed toward understanding the molecular mechanisms
that plants use to defend themselves from pathogen attack, and how these responses are regulated. 
<i>Arabidopsis thaliana </i>has been used as a model system to take a genetic approach to this problem. 
Many mutants with defects in defense responses have been isolated, including mutants with defects in
synthesis of a plant antibiotic, called camalexin, and mutants with defects in regulation of defense responses. 
Current work includes cloning of genes identified by the mutations, and molecular analysis of their roles in
disease resistance.<p>
<blockquote>   Glazebrook, J., and Ausubel, F.M., Isolation of phytoalexin-deficient mutants of Arabidopsis thaliana and
characterization of their interactions with bacterial pathogens.<i>  Proc. Natl. Acad. Sci.</i> USA 91:8955-8959 (1994).<br>
     Glazebrook, J., Rogers, E.E., and Ausubel, F.M., Isolation of <i>Arabidopsis</i> mutants with enhanced disease
susceptibility by direct screening. <i>Genetics</i> 143:973-982 (1996). <a href ="#list">  Return to
list</a></blockquote>

<a name ="h"><strong>Steven W. Hutcheson </strong>Assoc. Professor, Ph.D., U. Calif. at
Berkeley, 1982. 
Molecular events in plant-microbe interactions in bacterial pathogenesis and disease
resistance.<p>
     Dr. Hutcheson's research aims at identifying some of the molecular mechanisms controlling
the
pathogenicity of the gram negative bacterium, Pseudomonassyringae.  His group studies the
<i>hrp</i>
gene cluster that encodes a secreted proteineceous pathogenicity factor, a protein secretion
system similar
to that used by several mammalian pathogens to secrete virulence factors and an apparently
dedicated
regulatory system involving several alternative sigma factors and novel regulatory components. 
The
studies are now attempting to determine the function for each of the<i> hrp </i>gene products
and their
integration into functional complexes necessary for pathogenesis.<br>
<blockquote>   Xiao, Y., Heu, S., Yi, J., Lu, Y. and Hutcheson, S.W.,  Identification of a
putative alternate sigma factor and characterization of a multicomponent regulatory cascade
controlling the expression of <i>Pseudomonas syringae</i> pv. syringae
Pss61 hrp and hrmA genes. <i> J. Bacteriol</i>. 176, 1025-1036 (1994).<br>
     Lidell, M. and Hutcheson, S.W.,  Characterization of the <i>hrpJ and hrp</i>U operons of
<i>Pseudomonas syringae</i>
pv. syringae Pss61: Similarity with components of enteric bacteria involved in flagellar
biogenesis and demonstration of their role in
harpin secretion.  <i>Mol. Plant-Microbe Interactions  </I>7:488-497 (1994).<a href ="#list"> 
Return to list</a> </blockquote>

<a name ="l"><strong>Zhongchi Liu</strong>  Dept. of Plant Biology, Ph.D., Harvard U., 1990. 
Molecular genetics of flower development in <i>Arabidopsis.</i><p>
     The research activities in Dr. Liu's laboratory are aimed at understanding the molecular and genetic
basis of pattern formation and organ morphogenesis in higher plant development.  Using <i>Arabidopsis
</i>as a model system, genes that regulate both flower organ formation and cell division in flowers have
been identified.  These genes will be cloned using methods of map-based cloning and transposon tagging and
will be characterized at the molecular level.  Ultimately, by changing the regulation of these genes in
transgenic plants, new types of flowers will be created.<br>
 <blockquote>       Liu, Z. and Meyerowitz, E. M.  LEUNIG regulates AGAMOUS expression in Arabidopsis flowers. <i> Development
</i> 121: 975-991 (1995).<br>
        Liu, Z., Kirch, S., and Ambros, V.  The <i>C. elegans </i>heterochronic gene pathway controls stage-specific transcription of
collagen genes. <i>Development </i>121:2471-2478 (1995).<a href ="#list">  Return to list</a></blockquote>
<a name ="mo"><strong>Stephen M. Mount</strong></a>  Dept. of Zoology, Ph.D., Yale U.,
1983. 
Pre-mRNA splicing.<p>
     Research in the Mount laboratory focuses on the splicing of precursors to messenger RNA,
and how
organisms with complex and alternatively spliced genes achieve accuracy in this process.  Our
primary tool is
molecular genetics in the fruit fly Drosophila melanogaster.  Current projects focus on B52, a
major SR
protein splicing factor, and U 70K, a small nuclear ribonucleoprotein particle protein.<p>
<blockquote>   Guo, M., Lo, P.C.H. and Mount, S.M.,  Species-specific signals for the splicing of
a short Drosophila intron in
vitro.  Mol. Cell. Biol.  13:1104-1118 (1993).<br>
     Lo, P., Roy, D. and Mount, S.M.,  Suppressor U1 snRNAs in Drosophila melanogaster. 
Genetics  138:365-378 (1994). 
<br> <a href ="#list">  Return to list</a>  </blockquote><br>


<a name ="o"><strong>David O'Brochta </strong> Asst. Professor, Ph.D., U. Calif. at Irvine,
1985.  Biological
consequences and molecular genetics of transposable elements in insects.<p>
     The research in Dr. O'Brochta's laboratory is concerned with the molecular genetic analysis of
insect systems.  Currently, their effort is focused on a unique and important class of genetic
element called
transposons.  These ubiquitous and abundant components of probably all genomes can have
profound
influences on the organism, for example, by causing mutations and chromosomal
rearrangements.  In
addition, transposons can be harnessed to serve as vectors by which foreign DNA can be
introduced into
the genome of an individual.  The research in Dr. O'Brochta's laboratory has specifically focused
on the
<i>hobo </i>transposon from <i>Drosophila melanogaster</i>.  Dr. O'Brochta is interested in
elucidating the mechanisms responsible for regulating this movement.<p>
<blockquote>   O'Brochta, D.A., Warren, W.D., Saville, K.J. and Atkinson, P.W.,  Interplasmid
transposition of Drosophila hobo
elements in non-drosophilid insects. <i> Molec. Gen. Genet. </i> 244:9-14 (1994).<br>
     Warren, W.D., Atkinson, P.W. and O'Brochta, D.A.,  The Hermes transposoble element from
the house fly, Musca
domestica, is a short inverted repeat-type element of the hobo, Ac, and Tam3 (HAT) element
family.<i>  Genetical Research </i>  (in
press). <a href ="#list">  Return to list</a></blockquote>

<a name ="s"><strong>Daniel C. Stein </strong> Assoc. Professor, Ph.D., U. Rochester, 1981. 
Modulation of
expression of prokaryotic antigens in pathogenesis.<p>
     Dr. Stein's research focuses on the mechanisms by which the human pathogen,<i> Neisseria
gonorrhoea</i>, is able to synthesize and regulate the expression of one of its principal outer
membrane
antigens, lipooligosaccharides (LOS).  This question is being addressed in two different ways. 
His lab has
cloned and is characterizing genes involved in LOS biosynthesis.  He has used these cloned
genes to
construct site-directed mutants in the gonococcus and is currently studying how these mutations
affect
LOS expression.<br>
<blockquote>   Sandlin, R.C. and Stein, D.C.,  Role of phosphoglucomutase in
lipooligosaccharide biosynthesis in <i>Neisseria
gonorrhoeae.  J. Bacteriol.  </i>176:2930-2937 (1994).<br>
     Danaher, R.J., Petricoin, E.F., III and Stein, D.C.,  Use of xylE fusions to demonstrate that
lsi-1, a Neisseria gonorrhoeae
lipooligosaccharide biosynthetic gene. and lsi-3 are not transcriptionally linked. <i> J. Bacteriol.
</i> 176:3428-3432
(1994). <a href ="#list">  Return to list</a></blockquote>
<a name ="r"><strong>Jerome C. Regier </strong> Assoc. Professor, Ph.D., Harvard U., 1975. 
Molecular
systematics of insects and gene families.<p>
     Dr. Regier's laboratory reconstructs phylogenetic relationships among arthropod species based
on
generation and analysis of nuclear gene sequences.  Students are exposed to the many
controversies and
challenges in the fields of molecular evolution and systematics.  A central goal of the laboratory
is to
develop efficient and accurate methods for identifying new, phylogenetically informative gene
sequences
and to apply them to outstanding questions in arthropod phylogeny.  Over the last several years,
research
has focused on relationships at the base of the Lepidoptera (moths) and within the speciose moth
superfamily Noctuoidea.  More recently, genes for exploring ordinal relationships within
chelicerates
(spiders, scorpions, etc.) and sub-phylum relationships within arthropods are being identified and
tested.<p>
<blockquote>   Friedlander, T.P., Regier, J.C. and Mitter, C.,  Nuclear gene sequences for
higher-level phylogenetic analysis: 14
promising candidates.  <i>Systematic Biol.</i>  41:483-490 (1992).<br>
     Friedlander, T.P., Regier, J.C. and Mitter, C., Phylogenetic information content of five nuclear
gene sequences: Initial
assessment of character sets from concordance and divergence studies.  <i>Systematic Biol. </i>
(Dec. 1994, in press).  <a href ="#list">  Return to list</a></blockquote>


<a name ="s2"> <strong>Wolfgang Stephan</a></strong>  Molecular evolution and population
genetics.<br>
     Dr. Stephan's group is pursuing experimental and theoretical studies in molecular evolution
and population genetics, a modern interdisciplinary area of biology which combines molecular
genetics and evolutionary biology.  The research focuses on three major projects: the evolution of
multigene families,
genetic variation in natural populations of<i> Drosophila,</i> and epistatic selection mediated by
RNA secondary structure interactions.<p>
<blockquote>   Stephan, W., Rodriguez, V.S., Zhou, B., and Parsch, J.,  Molecular evolution of
the methallothionein gene Mtn in
the <i>melanogaster</i> species group: Results from <i>Drosophila ananassae.  Genetics</i>. 
138:135-143 (1994).<br>
     Charlesworth, B., Sniegowski, P. and Stephan, W.,  The evolutionary dynamics of repetitive
DNA in eukaryotes. 
<i>Nature</i> (1994, in press). <a href ="#list">  Return to list</a></blockquote>

<a name ="t"><strong>Soichi Tanda </strong> Asst. Professor, D.Sc., Hokkaido U. (Japan),
1985.  Roles of
transposable elements in the development of the insect visual system.<br>
     Dr. Tanda's research focuses on the biology of transposons in<i> Drosophila.</I>  The
transposons are mobile DNA elements that are capable of changing their locations in the genome. 
Most
spontaneous mutations in<i> Drosophila </I >ave been found associated with the insertions of
transposons.  It is unclear at this stage whether or not these elements play roles in the
evolutionary process. 
Dr. Tanda's research interests are directed at elucidating the roles that insertion elements (tom,
Om(1D),
and P-elements) play in the development of the adult compound eye of<i> Drosophila.</i><p>
<blockquote>Tanda,  S. and Corces, V.G.,  Retrotransposon-induced overexpression of a
homeobox gene causes defects in eye
morphogenesis in<i> Drosophila.  EMBO J.</i>  10:407-417 (1991).<br>
     Tanda, S., Leshko, L.A. and Corces, V.G.,  Genetic and molecular analysis of Optic
morphology mutants.  In: Y.N. Tobari
(ed.)<i>,  Genetical and Biological Aspects,</I> Japan Scientific Society Press, Tokyo and
KARGER, Basel, pp. 89-119
(1993). <a href ="#list">  Return to list</a></blockquote>
<a href ="research.html">Return to "Research Areas" page</a>

