<title>University of Maryland
Molecular & Cell Biology Program</title> </head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<h2>University of Maryland<br>
Molecular & Cell Biology Program </h2><a name="list">
<h2>Immunology Faculty</h2>
<a href="#b"><strong>Philip N. Bryan   </a></strong>  Protein folding and stability.<br>
<a href="#o"><strong>Keiko Ozato   </a></strong>  Gene regulation in the immune system.<br>
<a href="#p1"><strong>Carol Pontzer   </a></strong> Structure-function relations in
signalling molecules that regulate the immune response.<br>
<a href="#p2"><strong>Roberto J. Poljak  </a></strong> X-ray diffraction studies of
antigen-antibody and idiotope/anti-idiotope complexes.
<p>
<a href ="research.html">Return to "Research Areas" page</a>
<hr>
<a name = b><strong>Philip N. Bryan </strong> Assoc. Professor, Ph.D., U. Tennessee - Oak
Ridge National Laboratory, 1979.  Protein folding and stability.<p>
     Dr. Bryan's group employs genetic, biochemical and biophysical methods to study protein
folding and molecular recognition using the Bacillus protease, subtilisin, and streptococcal
Protein G.<br>
     <blockquote>Bryan, P., Alexander, P., Strausberg, S., Schwarz, F., Wang, L., Gilliland,
G. and Gallagher, D.T., Energetics of folding subtilisin BPN'. <cite> Biochemistry </cite>
31:4937-4945 (1992).<br>
     Strausberg, S., Alexander, P., Wang, L., Schwarz, F. and Bryan, P., Catalysis of the
subtilisin folding reaction: Thermodynamic and kinetic analysis of interactions of subtilisin BPN'
and its propeptide fragment.  <cite>Biochemistry </cite> 32:8112-8119 (1993).  </cite><a href
="#list">  Return to list</a><p></blockquote>
<a name = o><strong>Keiko Ozato</a></strong> Lab of Molecular Growth Regulation, Ph.D.,
Kyoto U., Japan, 1973.  Gene regulation in the immune system.<p>
     This laboratory is interested in gene regulation in the immune system.  Our current focus is to
analyze the mechanism of transcriptional regulation mediated by cytokines and by
retinoids/vitamins.  To this
end, activities of nuclear hormone receptors (particularly RXR) and interferon regulatory factors
that
associate with the basal transcription complex are being studied.  To analyze their interaction with
DNA and
functional activities in vivo and in vitro, we use transfection assays, cell free transcription systems
in
combination with a gene knock-out strategy in a mouse model.<p>
<blockquote>Martinez-Balbs, M.A., Dey, A., Rabindran, S.K., Ozato, K., and Wu, C., 
Displacement of sequence-specific
transcription factors from mitotic chromaton.  Cell 83:29-38 (1995).<br>
     Bovolenta, C., Lou, J., Kanno, Y., Park, B.-K., Thornton, A., Coligan, J., Schubert, M. and
Ozato, K.,  Vesicular stomatitis
virus infection induces a nuclear DNA binding factor specific for the interferon stimulated
response element.  J. Virol.  69:4173-4181
(1995).<a href ="#list">  Return to list</a><p></blockquote>

<a name = p1><strong>Carol H. Pontzer </a></strong> Asst. Professor, Ph.D., Marquette U.,
1985. 
Structure-function relations in signalling molecules that regulate the immune response.<p>
     Dr. Pontzer's studies deal with structure-function relations among several signalling molecules
that regulate the immune response.  She has been particularly interested in the production and in
the functional and structural characterizations of a unique interferon and its
mutants.  In addition, she is using synthetic peptides to examine interactions of microbial
superantigens with both class II major histocompatibility complex molecules and the T cell
antigen receptor.
 <blockquote>  Pontzer, C.H., Irwin, M.J., Gascoigne, N.R.J. and Johnson, H.M.,  T cell antigen
receptor
binding sites and the microbial superantigen SEA. <cite> Proc. Natl. Acad. Sci.</cite>, USA,
89:7727-7731
(1992).<br>
     Jarpe, M.J., Johnson, H.M., Bazer, F.W., Ott, T.L., Curto, E.V., Rama Krishna, N. and
Pontzer, C.H.,  Predicted structural motif of interferon tau. <cite> Protein Eng.. </cite>
 7:863-867 (1994). <a href ="#list">  Return
to list</a><p></blockquote>

<a name = p2><strong>Roberto J. Poljak  </strong>Professor, Ph.D., Universidad de La Plata
(Argentina),
1956.  X-ray diffraction studies of antigen-antibody and idiotope/anti-idiotope complexes.<p>
     The research conducted in Dr. Poljak's laboratory deals with the three-dimensional
structure and specificity in antigen-antibody reactions.  For these studies, hen-egg white
lysozyme (HEL) has been adopted as a model antigen.  BALB/c monoclonal antibodies directed
against HEL have been prepared and their Fab fragments, complexed to the antigen, have been
submitted to systematic crystallization trials.  X-ray diffraction studies of the crystalline
Fab-lysozyme complexes have permitted the three-dimensional structure of the antigenic
determinants as well as those of the combining sites of the specific antibodies to be defined. <p>
<blockquote>   Poljak, R. J.,  Structures of antibodies and their complexes with antigens. <i>
Molelc. Immunol.  </i>28:1341-1345 (1991).<br>
     Juy, M., Amit, A. G., Alzari, R. J., Poljak, R. J., Claeyssens, P., Beguin, P. and Aubert, J.
P.,  Three-dimensional structure of a thermostable bacterial cellulase.  <i>Nature</i>357:89-91
(1992).<a href ="#list">  Return to list</a><p></blockquote>
<a href ="research.html">Return to "Research Areas" page</a>

