<head>
<title>University of Maryland
Molecular & Cell Biology Program</title> </head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<h2>University of Maryland<br>
Molecular & Cell Biology Program </h2><a name="list">
<h2>Neurobiology Faculty</h2>
<a href="#k"><strong>Wayne J. Kuenzel</a> </strong> Neuroanatomy and neurobiology of
avian development.<br>
<a href="#o"><strong>Mary Ann Ottinger</a>  </strong>  Neuroendocrine regulation of
endocrine and behavioral aspects of reproduction.<br>
<a href="#p"><strong>Richard Payne</a>  </strong>  Mechanisms of visual excitation and
signal transduction in photoreceptors.<br>
<p>
<a href ="research.html">Return to "Research Areas" page</a>
<hr>
<a name ="k"><strong>Wayne J. Kuenzel</a> </strong> Professor, Ph.D., U. Georgia, 1969. 
Neuroanatomy and neurobiology of avian development.<br>
     The overall goal in Dr. Kuenzel's laboratory is to document functional neuroanatomical
pathways
throughout the avian brain.  Research being conducted involves exploring mechanisms that affect
the
neural regulation of food intake and early onset of gonadal development.  Two examples of
neuromodulators being studied include neuropeptide Y (NPY) and vasoactive intestinal
polypeptide (VIP). 
Immunocytochemistry is first used to map the distribution of perikarya and fibers throughout the
chick
brain.  In situ hybridization is then applied to determine gene expression during specific periods
of
development or experimental manipulation.  Sterotaxy and tract-tracing procedures are utilized to
ascertain
which groups of neurons significantly alter feeding behavior or onset of puberty.
<blockquote>   Fraley, G.S. and Kuenzel, W.J.,  Precocious puberty in chicks <i>(Gallus
domesticus)</i> induced by central
injections of neuropeptide Y. <i> Life Sciences</i>  (in press).<br>
     Kuenzel,W.J.,  Central neuroanatomical systems involved in the control of food intake in
birds.<i>  J. Nutr</i>.  (in press). 
<a href ="#list"> Return to list</a></blockquote><p>

<a name = "o"><strong>Mary Ann Ottinger</a> </strong>Professor, Ph.D., U. Maryland, 1977. 
Neuroendocrine regulation of endocrine and behavioral aspects of reproduction.<br>
     Research programs focus on neuroendocrine mechanisms regulating endocrine and behavioral
components of reproduction.  Areas of emphasis include alterations during aging and interactions
of
regulatory systems at the molecular endocrine level.  Studies consider both the fundamental
molecular and
cellular basis of neuroendocrine processes as well as the dynamics of endocrine and behavioral
responses
at the system level.
<blockquote>   Ottinger, M.A.,  Altered neuroendocrine mechanisms during reproduction aging.
<i> Poultry Sci. Rev.</i>  4:235-
248 (1992).<br>
     Li, Q., Paciotti, G.F., Tamarkin, L. and Ottinger, M.A.,  LHRH-I release from quail
hypothalamic slices measured by
specific EIA.<i>  Gen. Comp. Endocrinol. </i> 95:13-24 (1994).<a href ="#list"> Return to
list</blockquote><p></a>

<a name ="p"><strong>Richard Payne </a></strong> Associate Professor, Ph.D., Australian
National
U., 1982;  Mechanisms of visual excitation and signal transduction in photoreceptors.<br>
     Dr. Payne investigates mechanisms of visual excitation in photoreceptors.  The research
concentrates on messenger molecules released by light inside photoreceptor cells.  These
messengers
mediate and modulate the electrical response of the photoreceptor to light.  The messenger
currently under
investigation is inositol trisphosphate, which releases calcium from internal stores within a wide
range of
animal and plant cells. The research combines methods of micro-injecting messengers into cells
with
optical and electrophysiological techniques that monitor intracellular calcium release and the
activity of
ionic channels.
<blockquote>   Levitan, I., Hillman, P. and Payne, R., Fast desensitization of the response to
photoreceptors.<i>  Biophys. J.</i>
64:1354-1360 (1993).
     Peretz, A., Suss-Toby, E., Rom-Glas, A., Arnon, A., Payne, R., and Minke, B.  The light
response of drosophila
photoreceptors is accompanied by an increase in cellular calcium.<i>  Neuron </i> 12:1257-1267
(1994).<a href ="#list">  Return to list</a><br></blockquote>
<a href ="research.html#list">Return to "Research Areas" page</a>

