<head>
<title>University of Maryland
Molecular & Cell Biology Program</title> </head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<h2>University of Maryland<br>
Molecular & Cell Biology Program </h2><a name="list">
<h2>Oncology Faculty</h2>
<a href="#a"><strong>Ibrahim Z. Ades, Ph.D.</a> </strong> Second
messengers and signal transduction pathways.<br>
<a href="#h"><strong>Bruce Howard, M.D.</strong> </a>Regulation of cell growth with an
emphasis on the roles of anti-oncogenes.<br>
<a href="#m"><strong>Frederic Mushinski, M.D.  </strong></a>Oncogenes, anit-oncogines and
protein kinase C in proliferation, differentiation, and carcinogenesis.<br>
<a href="#p"><strong>Michael Potter, M.D.  </strong></a>  Mechanisms in malignant
development of lymphocytic cells<br><p>
<a href ="research.html#list">Go to MOCB research page </a>
<hr>
<a name ="a"><strong>Ibrahim Z. Ades</a></strong>  Assoc. Professor, Ph.D., UCLA, 1976. 
Second messengers
and signal transduction pathways.<br>
     The research activities of Dr. Ades have focused on two areas and deal with the regulatory
processes that govern the development of eukaryotic cells.  One group of studies aims to identify
the
enzymes responsible for modulating porphyrin production and to determine how the enzymes are
regulated.  Research in the second area is examining the signalling cascades triggered by
interleukin 6 in
lymphocytes and in cells of neural origin.<br>
<blockquote>   McKinney, C. E. and Ades, I. Z., Production of -aminolevulinic acid:
Characterization of murine liver 4,5-
dioxovaleric acid:L-alanine aminotransferase. <i> Int. J. Biochem.</i> 23:803-810 (1991).<br>
     Ryan, G. and Ades, I. Z., On the mechanism of induction of hepatic -aminolevulinate
synthase by translational blockers. 
<i>Biochem. J</i>. 272:619-621 (1991).</blockquote> <p>

<a name ="h"><strong>Bruce Howard  </strong> </a>Lab of Molecular Growth Regulation ,
NICHHD, M.D., U. California at San Francisco, 1972.  Mammalian cell cycle regulation and
chromatin-mediated gene silencing mechanisms.<p>
     Dr. Howard's research focuses on the molecular mechanisms that underlie immortalization and
senescence in mammalian cells.  His laboratory uses a variety of novel gene transfer techniques to
study the
function of tumor supporessor genes.  In addition, his group has recently sought to relate cell
cycle-linked
defects in the reassembly of repressive chromatin domains to checkpoint controls.  Interpersed
repeat
elements are studied as model systems for chromatin-mediated gene silencing.
<blockquote>   Ogryzko, V.V., Hirai, T.H., Shih, C.E., and Howard, B.H.,  Dissociation of
retinoblasoma gene protein
hyperphosphorylation and commitment to enter Sphase.  J. Virology, 68(6):3724-3732
(1994).<br>
     Englander, E.W. and Howard, B.H.,  Nucleosome positioning by human Alu elements in
chromatin.  J. Biol. Chem.
270(17):10091-10096 (1995). <br> <a href ="#list">  Return to list of oncology researchers</a> 
</blockquote><br>
<a name ="m"><strong>Frederic Mushinski</strong> </a> Lab of Genetics, M.D., Harvard U.,
1963. 
Oncogenes, anto-oncogenes and protein kinase C in proliferation, differentiation, and
carcinogenesis.<p>
     Dr. Mushinski's research is focused on the molecular genetics of cell growth and neoplastic
transformation, utilizing  lymphocytes as the principal model system.  These cells are
transformed by over-expression of proto-oncogenes or by mutations in anti-oncogenes.  He
studies the causes and effects of
chromosomal translocations that lead to over-expression of certain genes in -cell tumors.  In
addition,
retroviral and other vectors are used to induce over-expression of one or more genes in mouse
and other
mammalian cells to investigate the effects of these genes on growth, differentiation or
transformation.
<blockquote>Weissinger, E.M., Mischak, H., Goodnight, J., Davidson, W.F. and Mushinski, J.F., 
Addition of constitutive c-myc
expression to Abelson murine leukemia virus changes the phenotype of the cells transformed by
the virus from pre--cell lymphomas to
plasmacytomas.  Mol. Cell. Biol. 13:2578-2585 (1993).<br>
     Goodnight, J.A., Mischak, H., Kolch, W., Mushinski, J.F.,  Immunocytochemical localization
of eight protein kinase C
isozymes overexpressed in NIH 3T3 fibroblasts.  Isoform-specific association withmicrofilaments,
Golgi, endoplasmic reticulum, and
nuclear and cell membranes.  J. Biol. Chem. 270:9991-10001 (1995).
<br><a href ="#list">  Return to list of oncology researchers</a><br></blockquote>


<a name ="p"><strong>Michael Potter</strong> </a> Laboratory of Genetics, NCI, M.D., U.
Virginia, 1949.  Pathogenesis of peritoneal plasma cell tumor development in BALB/c mice.<p>
     Paraffin oils (pristane), silicone gels and plastic (Lucite) objects introduced peritoneally lead to
plasmacytoma induction in BALB/c mice but not in other strains.  Specific studies deal with
identifying genes
that determine susceptibility and resistance and the role of chronic inflammation.  Virtually all
plasmacytomas carry characteristic chromosomal translocations that deregulate transcription of
c-myc
oncogenes.  The molecular genetics of these illegitimate recombinations is currently being
intensively
pursued.
<blockquote>   Potter, M., Mushinski, E.B., Wax, J.S., Hartley, J., and Mock, B.A., 
Identification of two genes on chromosome 4
that determine resistance to plasmacytoma induction in mice.  Cancer Res. 54:969-975
(1994).<br>
     Mller, J.R., Janz, S., and Potter, M.,  Differences between Burkitt's lymphomas and mouse
plasmacytomas in the
immunoglobulin heavy chain/c-myc recombinations that occur in their chromosomal
translocations.  Cancer Res. 55:5012-5018 (1995). 
<br><a href ="#list">  Return to list of oncology researchers</a><br>
</blockquote>
