<head>
<title>University of Maryland
Molecular & Cell Biology Program</title> </head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<h2>University of Maryland<br>
Molecular & Cell Biology Program </h2><a name="list">
<h2>Plant Sciences</h2>
<a href ="#c"><strong>James N. Culver </a></strong> Molecular biology of plant viruses and
plant-virus interactions.<br>
<a href ="#d"><strong>Gerald F. Deitzer </a></strong> Molecular genetics of floral
induction.<br>
<a href ="#g"><strong>Elisabeth Gantt </a></strong>Assembly and
functional development of photosynthetic membranes.<br>
<a href ="#g2"><strong>Jane Glazebrook </a></strong>Genetic analysis of plant defenses
against pathogen attack.<br>
<a href ="#h"><strong>Steven W. Hutcheson   </a></strong>Molecular events in plant-microbe
interactions in bacterial pathogenesis and disease resistance.<br>
<a href ="#l"><strong>Zhongchi Liu </a></strong> Molecular genetics of flower development
in Arabidopsis.<br>
<a href ="#s1"><strong>Theo Solomos  </a></strong>Biochemistry of plant senescence.<br>
<a href ="#s2"><strong>David C. Straney  </a></strong>Molecular interactions between plants
and fungal pathogens.<br>
<a href ="#s3"><strong>Heven Sze </a></strong>  Biochemistry and molecular
biology of ion pumps, cotransporters and channels.<br>
<a href ="#w"><strong>Stephen M. Wolniak </a> </strong>Biology of cell motility, mitotic
mechanisms, and signal transduction.<br>

<a href ="research.html#list">Go to MOCB "research areas" page </a><hr>
<a name ="c"><strong>James N. Culver</a></strong>  Asst. Professor, Ph.D., U. Calif. at
Riverside,
1991. 
Molecular
biology of plant viruses and plant-virus interactions.<p>
     Research in Dr. Culver's laboratory is directed at understanding how plant viruses interact
with
their hosts to cause disease and induce resistance responses.  Specifically, his group is interested
in
identifying the viral and host components involved in these responses and determining how they
react. 
Tobacco mosaic virus (TMV) is being used as a model system for studying plant-virus
interactions.  Dr.
Culver's group is particularly interested in the role of the TMV coat protein in the induction of
both host
resistance and disease responses.<br>
<blockquote>   Culver, J.N., Lehto, K., Close, S.M., Hilf, M.E., and Dawson, W.O.,  Genomic
position affects the expression of
tobacco mosaic virus movement and coat protein genes. <i> Proc. Natl. Acad. Sci</i>. USA
90:2055-2059 (1993).<br>
     Culver, J.N., Stubbs, G. and Dawson, W.O.,  Structure-function relationship between tobacco
mosaic virus coat protein and
hypersensitivity in Nicotiana sylvestris. <i> J. Mol. Biol</i>.  242:130-138
(1994).<a href ="#list">  Return to list</a></blockquote>

<a name ="d"><strong>Gerald F. Deitzer</strong> </a>  Associate Professor, Ph.D., U.
Georgia,
1971. 
Molecular
genetics of floral induction.<br>
     Among the most important unanswered questions in plant biology is how the transition from
vegetative to reproductive development is mediated.  Dr. Deitzer's laboratory is currently
undertaking a
molecular genetic approach to answer this question.  He has recently obtained a number of single
gene
mutants in barley (Hordeum vulgare L.), pea (Pisum sativum L.) and Arabidopsis that have
altered
responses to photoperiod.  Attempts are being made with both the barley and the pea genotypes
to isolate
and clone the genes that encode these proteins.  The ultimate goal is to identify the components
of the
phytochrome mediated transduction chain leading to floral induction and to transgenically alter
photoperiodic response types in a wide variety of plants.
<blockquote>     Principe, J.M., Hruschka, W.R., Thomas, B. and Deitzer, G.F.,  Protein
differences between two isogenic cultivars of barley
(Hordeum vulgare L.) that differ in sensitivity to photoperiod and far-red light.  Plant Physiol.
98:1444-1450 (1992).<br>
     Deitzer, G.F.,  Molecular genetics of photoperiodic induction.  In M.G. Holmes, C. Johnson
(eds.), Plant Photoreceptors
and Photoperception, Cambridge University Press (1993, In press).<a href ="#list">  Return to
list</a></blockquote>

<a name ="g"><strong><a href="faculty/gantt.html"> Elisabeth Gantt</strong></a>Professor,
Ph.D., Northwestern U., 1963. 
Assembly and
functional development of photosynthetic membranes.<br>
     The objectives of Dr. Gantt's studies include elucidation of mechanisms by which plants
utilize
photosynthetically active energy, and the biosynthetic pathway of carotenoid synthesis in
microalgae. 
Cellular and physiological changes are being correlated, including determining topography,
functional
interactions, and regulation of the major complexes of photosynthetic membranes.  Microalgae
are being
used for enhanced productionof carotenoids (-carotene and astaxanthin) which are important for
the
aquaculture and food industry.<br>
<blockquote>   Cunningham, F.X., Chamovitz, D., Sun, Z., Hirschberg, J. and Gantt, E., 
Molecular structure and enzymatic
function of lycopene cyclase from an oxygenic photosynthetic organism. <i> The Plant Cell.</i> 
6:1107-1121 (1994).<br>
     Gantt, E., Supramolecular membrane organization.  In: D.A. Bryant (ed.),<i> The Molecular
Biology of Cyanobacteria. </i>
Kluwer Academic Publishers, pp. 117-136 (1994).<a href ="#list">  Return to
list</a></blockquote>

<a name ="g2"><strong>Jane Glazebrook </strong>  Center for Agricultural Biotechnology,
Ph.D.,
Massachusetts Institute of Technology, 1991. Genetic analysis of plant defenses against pathogen
attack.<p>
     Research in Dr. Glazebrook's laboratory is directed toward understanding the molecular
mechanisms
that plants use to defend themselves from pathogen attack, and how these responses are
regulated. 
<i>Arabidopsis thaliana </i>has been used as a model system to take a genetic approach to this
problem. 
Many mutants with defects in defense responses have been isolated, including mutants with
defects in
synthesis of a plant antibiotic, called camalexin, and mutants with defects in regulation of defense
responses. 
Current work includes cloning of genes identified by the mutations, and molecular analysis of their
roles in
disease resistance.<p>
<blockquote>   Glazebrook, J., and Ausubel, F.M., Isolation of phytoalexin-deficient mutants of
Arabidopsis thaliana and
characterization of their interactions with bacterial pathogens.<i>  Proc. Natl. Acad. Sci.</i> USA
91:8955-8959 (1994).<br>
     Glazebrook, J., Rogers, E.E., and Ausubel, F.M., Isolation of <i>Arabidopsis</i> mutants
with enhanced disease
susceptibility by direct screening. <i>Genetics</i> 143:973-982 (1996). <a href ="#list">  Return
to list</a>
</blockquote>


<a name ="h"><strong><a href="faculty/hutch.html"> Steven W. Hutcheson  </strong>
</a>Assoc. Professor, Ph.D., U. Calif.
at Berkeley,
1982. 
Molecular events in plant-microbe interactions in bacterial pathogenesis and disease
resistance.<p>
     Dr. Hutcheson's research aims at identifying some of the molecular mechanisms controlling
the
pathogenicity of the gram negative bacterium, Pseudomonassyringae.  His group studies the
<i>hrp</i>
gene cluster that encodes a secreted proteineceous pathogenicity factor, a protein secretion
system similar
to that used by several mammalian pathogens to secrete virulence factors and an apparently
dedicated
regulatory system involving several alternative sigma factors and novel regulatory components. 
The
studies are now attempting to determine the function for each of the<i> hrp </i>gene products
and their
integration into functional complexes necessary for pathogenesis.<br>
<blockquote>   Xiao, Y., Heu, S., Yi, J., Lu, Y. and Hutcheson, S.W.,  Identification of a
putative
alternate sigma factor and
characterization of a multicomponent regulatory cascade controlling the expression of
<i>Pseudomonas syringae</i> pv. syringae
Pss61 hrp and hrmA genes. <i> J. Bacteriol</i>. 176, 1025-1036 (1994).<br>
     Lidell, M. and Hutcheson, S.W.,  Characterization of the <i>hrpJ and hrp</i>U operons of
<i>Pseudomonas syringae</I>
pv. syringae Pss61: Similarity with components of enteric bacteria involved in flagellar
biogenesis and demonstration of their role in
harpin secretion.  <i>Mol. Plant-Microbe Interactions  </I>7:488-497 (1994).<a href ="#list"> 
Return to list</a> </blockquote>

<a name ="l"><strong>Zhongchi Liu</strong>  Dept. of Plant Biology, Ph.D., Harvard U., 1990. 
Molecular genetics of flower development in <i>Arabidopsis</i><p>
     The research activities in Dr. Liu's laboratory are aimed at understanding the molecular and
genetic
basis of pattern formation and organ morphogenesis in higher plant development.  Using
<i>Arabidopsis
</i>as a model system, genes that regulate both flower organ formation and cell division in
flowers have
been identified.  These genes will be cloned using methods of map-based cloning and transposon
tagging and
will be characterized at the molecular level.  Ultimately, by changing the regulation of these genes
in
transgenic plants, new types of flowers will be created.<br>
 <blockquote>Liu, Z. and Meyerowitz, E. M.  LEUNIG regulates AGAMOUS expression in
Arabidopsis flowers. <i> Development </i>
121: 975-991 (1995).<br>
        Liu, Z., Kirch, S., and Ambros, V.  The <i>C. elegans </i>heterochronic gene pathway
controls stage-specific transcription of
collagen genes. <i>Development </i>121:2471-2478 (1995).<a href ="#list"> Return to
list</a></blockquote>

<a name ="s1"><strong>Theo Solomos </strong> </a> Professor, Ph.D., Cambridge U.,
England, 1963. 
Biochemistry
of plant senescence.<br>
     The broad objective of the work is the investigation of plant senescence in detached plant
organs
at the biochemical and molecular levels and the factors which may alter the rate of senescence. 
C2H4 is a
plant growth regulator which induces a number of biological responses, including senescence. 
An
investigation of the mode of action of ethylene on the induction and development of senescence
is the
focus of the research.  Low O2 delays the onset and rate of senescence in a number of plant
tissues.  This
aspect of low O2 is used as a tool for identifying molecular events which are associated with the
induction
and action of C2H4.<br>
<blockquote>     Ronning, C.M., Bouwkamp, J. and Solomos, T.,  Observations on the
senescence of a mutant non-yellowing genotype of
Phaseolus L. <i> J. Expt. Bot.</i>  42:235-241 (1991).<br>
     Kanellis, A.K., Solomos, T. and Roubelakis-Angelakis, A.K.,  Suppression of cellulase and
polygalacturonase and induction
of alcohol dehydrogenase isoenzymes in avocado fruit mesocarp subjected to low oxygen stress. 
<i>Plant Physiol.  </i>96:269-274.<a href ="#list">  Return to list</a></blockquote><p >


<a name ="s2"><strong>David C. Straney </strong> </a> Asst. Professor, Ph.D., Yale U., 1987. 
Molecular
interactions between plants and fungal pathogens.<br>
     The objective of Dr. Straney's research is to understand how plants and their fungal pathogens
interact at the molecular level, particularly in how molecular signals from plants are used by
fungi to
regulate the expression of their virulence or pathogenicity genes. The plant-pathogen interaction
on which
his group is now focusing is that between garden pea (Pisum sativum) and the fungus Nectria
haematococca (Imperfect form: Fusarium solani fsp. pisi), the cause of pea stem and root
rot.<br>
<blockquote>     Wilhite, S.E., and  Straney, D.C.,  Mutational analysis of gliotoxin production
by the biocontrol fungus Gliocladium virens
in relation to suppression of Pythium dampiing-off.<i>  Phytopathology  </i>84:816-821
(1994).<br>
     Ruan, Y. and Straney, D.C.,  Analysis of the PDA1 promoter of the phytophathogenic fungus,
Nectria haematococca,
through In Vitro transcription. <i> Current Genetics.  </i>(1994, in press).<a href ="#list"> 
Return to list</a></blockquote>



<a name ="s3"><strong>Heven Sze</strong> </a>  Professor,  Ph.D., Purdue U., 1975. 
Biochemistry and
molecular
biology of ion pumps, cotransporters and channels.<br>
     The long-range goals of Dr. Sze's research are to understand the mechanisms of ion transport
across plant membranes, the factors that regulate them, and how membrane energization and
solute fluxes
are integrated into cell functions.  A combination of cell biology, biochemical and molecular
approaches
are being used to study H+ pumps, Ca2+ pumps, H+-coupled cotransporters and ion
channels.<br>
<blockquote>   Lai, S., Watson, J.C., Hansen, J.N. and Sze, H.,  Molecular cloning and
sequencing of cDNAs encoding the
proteolipid subunit of the vacuolar H+-ATPase from a higher plant. <i> J. Biol. Chem.</i> 
266:16078 (1991).<br>
     Ward, J. and Sze, H.,  Subunit composition and organization of the vacuolar H+-ATPase from
oat roots.  <i>Plant Physiol.
</i> 99:170 (1992).<a href ="#list">  Return to list</a></blockquote>

<a name ="w"><strong>Stephen M. Wolniak  </a></strong> Assoc. Professor, Ph.D., U. Calif.
at Berkeley,
1979. 
Biology of cell motility, mitotic mechanisms, and signal transduction.<br>
     The theme of Dr. Wolniak's research program centers on the roles of ions and other factors in
the
regulation of microtubule arrays that function in motility and development in plant and animal
cells. 
Work in his laboratory has focused on the possible involvement of calcium and protein
phosphorylation in
the regulation of mitotic events. His experiments on stamen hair cells of the spiderwort plant,
Tradescantia
virginiana have led to a working model for the regulatory cascade that culminates in anaphase
onset where
it appears that elevations in protein kinase activities early in prometaphase and again late in
metaphase are
punctuated by a period of high protein phosphatase activity that occurs in mid-metaphase.<br>
<blockquote>   Wolniak, S.M. and Larsen, P.M.,  Changes in the metaphase transit times and the
pattern of sister chromatid
separation in stamen hair cells of <i>Tradescantia</i> after treatment with protein phosphatase
inhibitors.<i> J. Cell Sci.</i>
102:691-715 (1992).<br>
     Larsen, P.M. and Wolniak, S.M.,  Asynchronous entry into anaphase induced by okadaic acid:
spindle microtubule
organization and microtubule/kinetochore attachments.<i>  Protoplasma </i> 177:53-65
(1993).<a href ="#list">  Return to list</a><p>
</blockquote>
<a href ="research.html#list">Return to "Research Areas" page</a>

