<head>
<title>University of Maryland
Molecular & Cell Biology Program</title> </head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<h2>University of Maryland<br>
Molecular & Cell Biology Program </h2><a name="list">
<h2>Prokaryotic Biology Faculty</h2>
<a href="#b"><strong>Spencer A. Benson </a></strong> Mechanisms of
bacterial evolution and genetic regulation of function of bacterial envelopes.<br>
<a href="#h"><strong>Steven W. Hutcheson  </a></strong> Molecular events in plant-microbe
interactions in bacterial pathogenesis and disease resistance. <br>
<a href="#s"><strong>Daniel C. Stein </a></strong> Modulation of
expression of prokaryotic antigens in pathogenesis.<br>
<a href="#st"><strong>Richard C. Stewart  </a></strong>   Signal transduction in
microorganisms.<br>
<a href="#w"><strong>Ronald M. Weiner</a></strong> Molecular
ecology of marine prokaryotes.<br>
<p>
<a href ="research.html">Return to "Research Areas" page</a><hr><p>
<a name ="b"><strong>Spencer A. Benson</strong>  Assoc. Professor, Ph.D., U. Chicago,
1978.  Mechanisms of bacterial evolution and genetic regulation of function of bacterial
envelopes.<p> 
     Research interests in Dr. Benson's laboratory are directed at several aspects of environmental
interactions and bacterial cell surfaces. Using<i> Escherichia coli</i> as a model system, his
group has
developed several novel genetic approaches for the isolation and characterization of mutations
that alter
cellular permeability.  The goal is to define at the molecular level how a specific class of
transmembrane
proteins (the porins) functions to allow small molecules to diffuse across the outer membrane
barrier. <br>
<blockquote>   Benson, S.A., DeCloux, A.M. and Munro, J.,  Mutant bias in non-lethal
selections results from selective recovery
of mutants. <i> Genetics </i> 129:647-658 (1991).<br>
     Gauthier, M.J., Benson, S.A., Flatau, G.N., Clement, R.L., Breittmayer, V.A. and Munro,
P.M.,  OmpC and OmpF porins
influence viability and culturability of<i> Escherichia coli </i>cells incubated in seawater. <i>
Microb. Releases  </i>1:47-50
(1992).<a href ="#list">  Return to
list</a></blockquote>

<a name ="h"><strong>Steven W. Hutcheson  </strong>Assoc. Professor, Ph.D., U. Calif. at
Berkeley, 1982. 
Molecular events in plant-microbe interactions in bacterial pathogenesis and disease
resistance.<p>
     Dr. Hutcheson's research aims at identifying some of the molecular mechanisms controlling
the
pathogenicity of the gram negative bacterium, Pseudomonassyringae.  His group studies the
<i>hrp</i>
gene cluster that encodes a secreted proteineceous pathogenicity factor, a protein secretion
system similar
to that used by several mammalian pathogens to secrete virulence factors and an apparently
dedicated
regulatory system involving several alternative sigma factors and novel regulatory components. 
The
studies are now attempting to determine the function for each of the<i> hrp </i>gene products
and their
integration into functional complexes necessary for pathogenesis.<br>
<blockquote>   Xiao, Y., Heu, S., Yi, J., Lu, Y. and Hutcheson, S.W.,  Identification of a
putative
alternate sigma factor and
characterization of a multicomponent regulatory cascade controlling the expression of
<i>Pseudomonas syringae</i> pv. syringae
Pss61 hrp and hrmA genes. <i> J. Bacteriol</i>. 176, 1025-1036 (1994).<br>
     Lidell, M. and Hutcheson, S.W.,  Characterization of the <i>hrpJ and hrp</i>U operons of
<i>Pseudomonas syringae</I>
pv. syringae Pss61: Similarity with components of enteric bacteria involved in flagellar
biogenesis and demonstration of their role in
harpin secretion.  <i>Mol. Plant-Microbe Interactions  </I>7:488-497 (1994).<a href ="#list"> 
Return to
list</a> </blockquote>

<a name ="s"><strong>Daniel C. Stein </strong> Assoc. Professor, Ph.D., U. Rochester, 1981. 
Modulation of
expression of prokaryotic antigens in pathogenesis.<p>
     Dr. Stein's research focuses on the mechanisms by which the human pathogen,<i> Neisseria
gonorrhoea</i>, is able to synthesize and regulate the expression of one of its principal outer
membrane
antigens, lipooligosaccharides (LOS).  This question is being addressed in two different ways. 
His lab has
cloned and is characterizing genes involved in LOS biosynthesis.  He has used these cloned
genes to
construct site-directed mutants in the gonococcus and is currently studying how these mutations
affect
LOS expression.<br>
<blockquote>   Sandlin, R.C. and Stein, D.C.,  Role of phosphoglucomutase in
lipooligosaccharide biosynthesis in <i>Neisseria
gonorrhoeae.  J. Bacteriol.  </i>176:2930-2937 (1994).<br>
     Danaher, R.J., Petricoin, E.F., III and Stein, D.C.,  Use of xylE fusions to demonstrate that
lsi-1, a Neisseria gonorrhoeae
lipooligosaccharide biosynthetic gene. and lsi-3 are not transcriptionally linked. <i> J. Bacteriol.
</i> 176:3428-3432
(1994).<a href ="#list">  Return to list</a></blockquote>

<a name ="st"><strong>Richard C. Stewart </a></strong>  Dept. of Microbiology, Ph.D., U. of
Michigan,1984.  Signal transduction in microorganisms.<p>
     Microorganisms are chock-full of fascinating sensory-response systems that enable them to
respond
to changes in their immediate environments.  Research activities in Dr Stewart's laboratory focus
on
identifying and characterizing the interactions among components in several such signal
transduction
systems.  For example, current work will lead to an understanding of how the activity of a protein
kinase
(CheA) in the E. coli  chemotaxis system is controlled at a molecular level.  This control enables
E. coli  to
modulate its swimming movements in response to changes in the cell's chemical environment. 
Also under
investigation is a second distinct system that directs the activity of Skn7, a transcription factor
that operates
in Saccharomyces cerevisiae (yeast) and that appears to be involved in regulating synthesis of the
yeast cell
wall.  The goal of current efforts is to identify the signaling circuitry that regulates Skn7.<p>
<blockquote>Brown, J.L., Bussey, H., and Stewart, R.C.,  Yeast Skn7p functions in a eukaryotic
two-component regulatory pathway. 
EMBO J. 13:5186-5194 (1994).<br>
     Tawa, P. and Stewart, R.C.,  Mutational activation of CheA, the protein kinase in the
chemotaxis system of Escherichia coli. 
J. Bacteriol. 176:4210-4218 (1994).<a href ="#list">  Return to list</a></blockquote>

<a name ="w"><strong>Ronald M. Weiner</strong>  Professor, Ph.D., Iowa State U., Ames,
1970.  Molecular
ecology of marine prokaryotes.<p>
     The work in Dr. Weiner's laboratory is directed at understanding the interface between marine
procaryotes and their environment.  It is now known that many species survive in low nutrient
environments by colonizing surfaces via the synthesis of complex exopolysaccharide (EPS). 
This EPS
adheres the bacteria to the surface and sequesters nutrients.  Current investigations include the
way that
periphytic bacteria signal invertebrates to colonize the surface.  Dr. Weiner's group has shown
that some
<i>Shewanella and Hyphomonas</i> species synthesize tyrosinase and that its primary product,
L-
dihydroxyphenyl alanine (L-Dopa), can cue invertebrate set.  They have cloned other genes for
melanization and found them to code for novel enzymes.<br>
<blockquote>   Fuqua, C. and Weiner, R., The mel A gene is essential for melanin biosynthesis
in <i>Shewanella colwelliana.  J.
Gen. Microbiol.</i>  139:1105-1114 (1993).<br>
     Coon, S., Kotob, S., Jarvis, B., Wan, S., Fuqua, W. and Weiner, R.,  Homogentisic acid is the
product of<u> Mel</u>A
which mediates melanogenesis.  <i>Appl. Environ. Microbiol. </i> 11:47-49 (1994).<a href
="#list">  Return to list</a></blockquote><br>
<a href ="research.html">Return to "Research Areas" page</a>

