<html>
<head>
<title>University of Maryland
Molecular & Cell Biology Program</title> </head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<h2>University of Maryland<br>
Molecular & Cell Biology Program </h2><a name="list">
<h2>Virology Faculty</h2>
<a href ="#c"><strong>James N. Culver </a></strong> Molecular biology of plant viruses and
plant-virus interactions.<br>
<a href ="#d"><strong>Jeffrey J. DeStefano </a> </strong>  Mechanisms of viral replication in
eukaryotes.<br>
<a href ="#d2"><strong>Sukanta K. Dutta </a> </strong> Molecular biology and immunology of
rickettsial pathogens of animals. <br>
<a href ="#s"><strong>Siba K. Samal </a></strong>  Molecular biology of pathogenic animal
viruses.<br>
<a href ="#v"><strong>Vikram N. Vakharia  </a></strong> Molecular virology and vaccine
development.<br>
<p>
<a href ="research.html#list">Return to "Research Areas" page</a><hr><p>
<a name ="c"><strong>James N. Culver</a></strong>  Asst. Professor, Ph.D., U. Calif. at
Riverside, 1991. 
Molecular biology of plant viruses and plant-virus interactions.<p>
     Research in Dr. Culver's laboratory is directed at understanding how plant viruses interact
with
their hosts to cause disease and induce resistance responses.  Specifically, his group is interested
in
identifying the viral and host components involved in these responses and determining how they
react. 
Tobacco mosaic virus (TMV) is being used as a model system for studying plant-virus
interactions.  Dr.
Culver's group is particularly interested in the role of the TMV coat protein in the induction of
both host
resistance and disease responses.<br>
<blockquote>   Culver, J.N., Lehto, K., Close, S.M., Hilf, M.E., and Dawson, W.O.,  Genomic
position affects the expression of
tobacco mosaic virus movement and coat protein genes. <i> Proc. Natl. Acad. Sci</i>. USA
90:2055-2059 (1993).<br>
     Culver, J.N., Stubbs, G. and Dawson, W.O.,  Structure-function relationship between tobacco
mosaic virus coat protein and
hypersensitivity in Nicotiana sylvestris. <i> J. Mol. Biol</i>.  242:130-138
(1994)..<a href ="#list">  Return to list</a></blockquote>

<a name ="d"><strong>Jeffrey J. DeStefano </a> </strong>Asst. Professor, Ph.D., U.
Connecticut, 1990. 
Mechanisms of viral replication in eukaryotes.<p>
     Dr. DeStefano's studies have dealt with the mechanisms of viral replication.  He has been
particularly interested in genome replication of the human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) and the
enzymology of that particle's reverse transcriptase.  Retroviruses like HIV undergo genomic
recombination
at a high rate.  This process contributes to the substantial genetic diversity among these viruses
by
allowing for the exchange of genetic material between viruses.  Dr. DeStefano's work focuses on
the role
the viral polymerase plays in recombination.<br>
<blockquote>   DeStefano, J.J., Bambara, R.A. and Fay, P.J.,  Affinity of human
immunodeficiency virus reverse transcriptase for
various nucleic acid structures that are present during replication.  <i>Biochemistry </i>
32:6908-6915 (1992).<br>
     DeStefano, J.J., Bambara, P.J. and Fay, P.J.,  The mechanism of human immunodeficiency
virus reverse transcriptase
catalyzed strand transfer between internal regions of heteropolymeric RNA templates. <i> J.
Biol. Chem</i>.  269:161-168
(1994)..<a href ="#list">  Return to list</a></blockquote>

<a name ="d2"><strong>Sukanta K. Dutta </a></strong>  Ph.D., U. Minnesota, 1962. 
Molecular
biology and immunology of rickettsial pathogens of animals.<p>
     The work at Dr. Dutta's laboratory is directed towards the molecular biology, pathogenesis
and
immunity of rickettsial/ehrlichia pathogens of domestic animals.  Major emphasis has been given
on
Ehrlichia risticii, an equine pathogen.  The work is focused on analysis of major antigens of the
organism
and the associated genes, aiming at identifying protective antigen(s) and developing recombinant
vaccine. 
Nucleic acid based diagnostic probe and PCR have been developed in the study of transmission
and
epidemiology of the disease.
<blockquote>Dutta, S.K., Shankarappa, B. and Mattingly-Napier, B.L.,  Molecular cloning and
analysis of recombinant major antigens of
Ehrlichia risticii.  Infect. Immun.  59:1162-1169 (1991).<br>
     Dutta, S.K., Shankarappa, B. and Mattingly-Napier, B.,  Antigneic analysis of Ehrlichia risticii
isolates.  Equine Infectious
Disease  6:61-65 (1992).<a href ="#list">  Return to list</a></blockquote>

<a name ="s"><strong>Siba K. Samal</a></strong>  Assoc. Professor, Ph.D., Texas A & M U.,
1985.  Molecular
biology of pathogenic animal viruses.<p>
     The research in Dr. Samal's laboratory is aimed at understanding the role of viral genes in
immune
recognition and pathogenesis.  The approach he has taken is to clone viral genes by
recombinant-DNA
technology and to express abundantly the hybrid gene product with an appropriate heterologous
expression system.  The role of the expressed protein in pathogenesis and immunity is studied in
the
natural host.  Dr. Samal's ultimate goals are: (1) develop reliable and cost effective vaccines by
recombinant-DNA technology; (2) develop highly sensitive, specific and economic diagnostic
tests for
viral infections; and (3) understand the molecular basis of pathogenesis.  The emphasis is placed
on
economically important viruses of bovine and aquatic animals.<br>
<blockquote>   Samal, S.K., Zamora, M., McPhillips, T.H. and Mohanty, S.B.,  Molecular
cloning and sequence analysis of
bovine respiratory syncytial virus MRNA encoding the major nucleocapsid protein.<i>  Virology 
</i>180:453-456 (1991).<br>
     Samal, S.K., Pastey, M.D., McPhillips, T.H. and Mohanty, S.B.,  Bovine respiratory syncytial
virus nucleocapsid protein
expressed in insect cells specifically interacts with the phosphoprotein and the M2 protein.<i> 
Virology</i>  193:470-474
(1993)..<a href ="#list">  Return to list</a></blockquote>
<a name ="v"><strong>Vikram N. Vakharia</a> </strong> Assoc. Professor, Ph.D., U. Kansas,
1983.  Molecular
virology and vaccine development.<P>
     The research goal of Dr. Vakharia's laboratory is to study the molecular biology of
economically
important avian pathogens.  Specifically, he would like to develop subunit or virus-directed
vaccines using
recombinant DNA technology and nucleic acid based diagnostic probes.  Currently, Dr. Vakharia
is
employing recombinant DNA techniques to study the molecular biology of two economically
important
avian viruses, namely infectious bursal disease virus (IBDV) and avian reovirus which causes
viral
arthritis.<br>
<blockquote>   Vakharia, V.N., Snyder, D.B., Ltticken, D., Mengel-Whereat, S.A., Savage,
P.K., Edwards, G.H. and Goodwin,
M.A.,  Active and passive protection against variant and classic infectious bursal disease virus
induced by baculovirus expressed
structural proteins.  <i>Vaccine.  </i>12:452-456 (1994).<br>
     Vakharia, V.N., He, J., Ahamed, B. and Snyder, D.B.,  Molecular basis of antigenic variation
in infectious bursal disease
virus.<i>  Virus Res. </i> 31:265-273 (1994)..<a href ="#list">  Return to list</a>
<p></blockquote>
<a href ="research.html#list">Return to "Research Areas" page</a>


