<TITLE>Zoology 211 - Lecture Schedule</TITLE>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<center>
<h3>POLICIES AND GRADING FOR DR. PAYNE'S AND DR. POLITIS' SECTIONS </h3>
POLICIES, TEXTS, LECTURE TIMES, EXAMS GRADING, HELP AND DISCUSSION SECTIONS
<br>Prerequisites: BIOL 105 & CHEM 103
</center>

<blockquote>
<p>All lectures will be taped and copies will be available for 
student use in the Non Print Media Center, Room 4210, Hornbake Library.  
Request a tape by the course (Zoology 211) and the date of the lecture.  
It usually takes two working days to copy a lecture tape for 
distribution.  History has shown that students relying on lecture tapes do not fare well! 
Use these tapes as a lecture supplement, not as a substitute!<p>
     Lecture notes obtained from note taking services are not produced 
by the course staff, which is hereby absolved from any responsibility for 
their accuracy.  Any error in these notes cannot be used as an argument 
for a grade change on an exam.  Naturally, whether you decide to buy 
these notes or not is totally up to you.<p>

<b>Work Missed Because of Absence:</b><br>
     Absences caused by religious observances or participation in a 
University activity at the request of University authorities may be 
excused if the TA (for laboratory matters only!) or Drs. 
Payne, Politis or Compton are notified of the conflict ahead of time.  Absences 
caused by illness may be excused if a verifiable letter from a physician 
indicating the nature of the illness and the necessity of absence is 
provided.  Refer to the Undergraduate Catalog for a complete description 
of University policy.<p>
     Students who miss a scheduled examination for any of the above 
reasons should request and will be given the opportunity to take a 
make-up examination covering the same material.  You must present a 
valid, documented excuse for missing a scheduled lecture examination.  
After contacting either Drs. Payne, Politis or Compton, presenting 
your documentation, and securing their approval, you should plan on 
taking the make-up examination at the date and  location announced in class.<p>

<b>Optional Discussion Sections:</b><br>
     Several former 211 students have graciously volunteered to 
conduct weekly 50 minute review sessions!  These sessions are OPTIONAL 
and may be taken without risk to your grade if you attend faithfully and 
make some effort to keep up with the material.  Students in these 
sessions will be graded on the basis of 750 total points (vs. 700 points; 
see below).  Simply by attending and participating, you have every chance 
of learning more and improving your grade.
Sign up forms will be available during the week of 3rd. Feb. in the 
teaching laboratory.  You will have a two week period to try out the 
session.  After signing up, you may drop out at any time during these two 
weeks by notifying Dr. Compton in writing.  If you remain in the 
discussion section, you will be graded on the basis of 750 points and 
expected to attend and participate.  Again, the only way to really mess 
this up is by not attending!<p>

<b>Examinations:</b><br>
     Three hourly examinations of 100 points and a final, two hour,
 cumulative, examination worth 200 points.  200 points total from lab work.<p>

<b>Regrade Policy:</b><br>
     You should first discuss your examination with your TA or Dr. Compton.
 This discussion must take place within one week of the return of graded 
examinations.  If your T/A or Dr. Compton deem that a regrade is likely, have them 
attach a note to the exam and then leave the exam and the note in the box 
provided in the laboratory so that Dr. Payne or Dr. Politis can endorse the change 
(or he may not). His judgement is final.<p>
 
<b>Grades:</b>
     Lecture - 71% - 500 points  ;  Laboratory - 29% - 200 points<br>
  <b>Total                700</b><br>
     Grade of<br>
               A = 620 points<br>
               B = 550 points<br>
               C = 480 points<br>
               D = 420 points<p>

     For those in Discussion Sections<br>
     (50 additional possible points = 750 total points)<br>
     Grade of<br>
               A = 665 points<br>
               B = 595 points<br>
               C = 520 points<br>
               D = 450 points

<p>This grading system is hereby agreed to by all course participants.  Thus 
there will be no competition among participants and final course grades 
will not be discussed/negotiated.  You either have the points or you 
don't!<p>

<b>Appointments:</b><br>
     Communication is essential:  we must hear your comments, 
criticisms, questions, etc.  We will make an effort to visit the 
laboratories.  We will try to be available in our offices for a few 
minutes after lecture to answer your questions.  Feel free to chat during 
these times.  Your GTA will also have time to discuss both lecture and laboratory material 
with you.  If the class shows sufficient interest, we are willing to schedule group 
discussions/reviews. <p>

     A listserve (CellNet ) will be set up on the campus e-mail 
network in order that students and course staff can communicate with one 
another.  All you will need to receive these important communications is 
an active e-mail account.  Details about the listserve are attached.  
This is NOT optional.<p>
     Directions for subscribing to cellnet and for retrieving 
information may be found below<p>

<hr width="75%">
<b>Laboratory Attendance:</b><br>
     Please note that one laboratory exercise/demonstration requires 
the use of animals.  We have reduced the number of animals used by 
modifying procedures and introducing computer simulations into the 
laboratory.  However, certain key objectives of the course cannot be 
accomplished without utilizing animal tissues.  We will adhere to Federal 
guidelines and insist upon humane treatment of animals at all times.  If 
you have a problem with this approach for religious, ethical, or personal 
reasons, please see a course coordinator immediately.  This sensitive 
issue must be addressed by all concerned parties.<p>

<b>Laboratory Attendance:</b><br>
     Attendance in the lab is mandatory; absences will be penalized by 
deducting 50% of the points from the laboratory assignment that was 
conducted during the missed lab period and additional points from the 
discretionary GTA-assigned points.  If you miss a lab due to an excused 
absence, you must attend another lab during that same week.  See your TA 
to have your excuse approved and to obtain permission <p>
to attend another laboratory during that same week.  (see procedure for 
attending a different lab section below).  Students who arrive more than 
20 minutes late to lab will not be admitted to lab, their absence counted 
as an unexcused absence, and 20 points deduced accordingly.  Any student 
missing three (3) laboratories will automatically fail the course!<p>


<b>Procedure for Switching Lab Sections:</b>
<p>     A written permission slip must be completed in order to attend a 
lab section other than that for which you are registered as a result of 
an excused absence.  Permission forms are available from Mr. Carpenter. 
Students must provide a valid excuse in order to be 
permitted to attend another lab section.  If you know in advance that you 
have a valid excuse for missing lab and wish to switch to another section 
that week, please notify Mr. Carpenter and your GTA early.
A Final Note:
<p>     The entire staff is dedicated to making this course an enjoyable, 
worthwhile learning experience.  We are very concerned about providing a 
comfortable atmosphere conducive to learning.  We expect you to work 
hard, but we also realize that you will learn best by asking questions.  
You, our audience and consumers, should have input into the course and 
should demand our best efforts.  Don't be intimidated or afraid, we are 
all on your side and stand ready to assist you.  Help us to help you by 
providing questions, criticisms, praise, etc.  Have fun and get your 
money's worth.
</blockquote>

</body>
</html>
