<HEAD>

<TITLE> Z422, f'94 Exam i answers</TITLE>
</HEAD>


<BODY BGCOLOR=FFFFFF>

<P><H2> Answers to Exam 1; Fall, 1994 <B>(page 74 of manual)</B> </H2>

<HR>

<OL TYPE=1 START=1>
 <LI><OL TYPE=a START=1>
 <LI><B>@ 37 <SUP>o</SUP>C</B> , V<SUB>m</SUB> (in mV) = - (61.5/z) log [K+ ]<SUB>in</SUB> / [K+ ]<SUB>out</SUB> = - 61.5 mV</P>

 <LI>Used K<sup>+</sup> since it is the permeable ion</P>

 <LI>Vm is slightly more posiotive since Na+  leaks into the cell, but at a much slower rate than K+  leaks out.</P>

 <LI>It approaches the equilibrium potential for Na+  which = + 61.5 mV (using the concentrations in the data table for this problem).</P>

 <LI>Cl<SUP>-</SUP> would not move since the Vm is equal to Cl-  equilibrium potential (- 61.5 mV)</P>

 <LI>Increased P of Na+  &amp; Ca++  and a decreased P of K+</P>
 </OL>

<li>Latent period increases (error in question) and velocity decreases because: to lift the heavy weight it takes more time to make and break more cross bridges.</P>

<li>Increased AP frequency ---&gt; increased calcium released from SR ---&gt; increased # of cross bridges ---&gt; increased tension.</P>

<li>Increased AP frequency ---&gt; increased neurotransmitter released from terminal ---&gt; increased receptors occuppied ---&gt; increasaed response</P>

<li>In order left to right, D, E, E, E, E, E</P>

<li>decreased blood P O2 ---&gt; decreased oxygen delivery to tissues, esp. kidneys---&gt; increased erythropoeitin from kidney ---&gt; increased production of RBCs in red bone marrow ---&gt; increased P O2 (note the closed loop!)</P>

<li>Refer to figure in book for intrinsic and extrinsic clotting mechanisms, knowing the steps from factor X through fibrin stabilizing factor and the ways both mechanisms are activated.</P>

<LI>
 <UL><LI><B>neutrophils:</B> phagocytosis, rapid entry to wound site by diapedesis, chemotaxis</P>
     <li><B>basophils:</B> release histamine and othe vasodilators and smooth muscle relaxants</P>
     <li><B>lymphocytes:</B> become plasma cells that produce antibodies in the humoral immune response moncytes: Become macrophages which are phagocytic, rapid entry to wound site by diapedesis, chemotaxis
 </UL></P>

<LI>Top to bottom:

<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=10>
    <TR>
        <TD ALIGN=LEFT> ACh & Epi</TD>
        <TD ALIGN=LEFT> muscarinic & beta 2</TD>
        <TD ALIGN=RIGHT> inhibit</TD> 
    <TR>
        <TD ALIGN=LEFT> Ne & Epi</TD>
        <TD ALIGN=LEFT> alpha 1</TD>
        <TD ALIGN=RIGHT> excite</TD>
   <TR>
        <TD ALIGN=LEFT> ACh</TD>
        <TD ALIGN=LEFT> muscarinic</TD>
        <TD ALIGN=RIGHT> excite</TD>
    </TR>
    <TR>
        <TD ALIGN=LEFT> NE, EPI</TD>
        <TD ALIGN=LEFT> alpha 2 &amp; beta 2</TD>
        <TD ALIGN=RIGHT> inhib</TD>
    </TR>
    <TR>
        <TD ALIGN=LEFT> Epi</TD>
        <TD ALIGN=LEFT> beta 2</TD>
        <TD ALIGN=RIGHT> inhib</TD>
    </TR>
    <TR>
        <TD ALIGN=LEFT> epi, NE</TD>
        <TD ALIGN=LEFT> alpha 1</TD>
        <TD ALIGN=RIGHT> excite</TD>
    </TR>
    <TR>
        <TD ALIGN=LEFT> ACh</TD>
        <TD ALIGN=LEFT> muscarinic</TD>
        <TD ALIGN=RIGHT> excite</TD>
    </TR>
    <TR>
        <TD ALIGN=LEFT> ACh</TD>
        <TD ALIGN=LEFT> nicotinic</TD>
        <TD ALIGN=RIGHT> excite</TD>
    </TR>
</TABLE>

<LI>Stimulate parasympathetic nerve and measure tissue response or amount of ACh released. Repeat in the presence of Epi and noticed diminished response and ACh release.</P>

<LI>Increased leakage of sodium and decreased leakage of potassium</P>

<LI>Two different receptors: H2 and H1 respectively</P>

<LI>Jaundice indicates liver problems as it is not being removed from the plasma and made into bile salts</P>

<LI>CO 2 + H 2O &lt;-------&gt; H 2CO 3 &lt;-----&gt; H+  + HCO 3- As exercise procedes, CO 2 goes up so reaction moves to right.</P>

<LI>
a = I<BR>
b = I<BR>
c = I<BR>
d = N/C<BR>
e = I<BR>
f = I<BR>
g = D<BR>
h = D<BR>
i = I<BR>
j = I<BR>
k = N/C<BR>
l = I</P>
</OL>

