<head>
<TITLE>Publication Abstracts</TITLE>
</head>
<body background="back4.gif">
<H1> Publication Abstracts </H1>
<HR>
<BR>
Kirby, D. A., S. V. Muse and W. Stephan. 1995.  Maintenance of pre-mRNA secondary structure by epistatic selection. Proc. Natl. Acad. Sci., USA, (in press).

<BR>
<BR>
<B>Abstract</B> - Linkage disequilibrium between polymorphisms in a natural population may result from various evolutionary forces, including random genetic drift due to sampling of gametes during reproduction, restricted migration between subpopulations in a subdivided population or epistatic selection. We present here evidence suggesting that the linkage disequilibria observed at the alcohol dehydrogenase locus (<I>Adh</I>) of<I> Drosophila pseudoobscura</I> are due to epistatic selection maintaining secondary structure of precursor messenger RNA (pre-mRNA). Based on phylogenetic-comparative analysis and a likelihood approach, we propose secondary structure models of <I>Adh</I> pre-mRNA for the regions of the adult intron and intron 2 where clustering of linkage disequilibria has been observed. Furthermore, we applied the likelihood ratio test to the phylogenetically predicted secondary structure in intron 1. In contrast to the other two structures, polymorphisms associated with the more conserved stem-loop structure of intron 1 are in low frequency and linkage disequilibria have not been observed. These findings are qualitatively consistent with a model of compensatory fitness interactions. This model assumes that mutations disrupting pairing in a secondary structural element are individually deleterious if they destabilize a functionally important structure; a second "compensatory" mutation, however, may restabilize the structure and restore fitness.

<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
Kirby, D. A. and W. Stephan. 1995.  Positive selection in the <I>white</I>  gene of <I>Drosophila melanogaster</I>. Genetics, submitted.

<BR>
<BR>
<B>Abstract </B>- Restriction map studies had previously revealed extensive linkage disequilibria in the transcriptional unit of the <I>white</I> locus in natural <I>Drosophila melanogaster</I> populations. To understand the causes of these disequilibria, we have sequenced a 4722 bp region of the <I>white</I> gene from 15 lines of <I>Drosophila melanogaster</I> and one line of<I> Drosophila simulans</I>. In <I>D. melanogaster</I> we have identified an 834 bp segment, encompassing the 3' end of the intron 1 to the 3' end of the intron 2, in which the polymorphisms form distinct high frequency haplotypes. Statistical tests applied to the entire 4722 bp region do not reject neutrality. In contrast, the observed pattern within the 834 bp segment deviates significantly from the predictions of a neutral equilibrium model. We propose that the high frequency haplotypes are due to positive selection on variants within the <I>white</I> gene, including a replacement polymorphism, Arg --> Leu, within this segment.
<BR>
<BR>

<A HREF="kirby.html"><img vspace=3 hspace=3 src="http://inform.umd.edu/Pictures/arrow.gif">
Return to David Kirby's page</A>
</DOC>
