<head>
<TITLE>Abstracts</TITLE>
</head>
<body background="back4.gif">
<H1> Abstracts </H1>
<HR>
<p>
W. Stephan, V. S. Rodriguez, B. Zhou, and J. Parsch (1994).
 Molecular evolution of the 	metallothionein gene <I>Mtn</i> in the <I>melanogaster</i> species group:
 Results from <i>Drosophila ananassae</I>.
 	Genetics 138: 135-143.
<p>
	Three distinctly different alleles of the metallothionein gene Mtn have been identified in natural Drosophila melanogaster populations: Mtn.3, Mtn1, and Dp(Mtn1), where the latter designates a tandem duplication of Mtn1.  In D. simulans, only Mtn.3-type alleles have been found. It has been suggested that Mtn.3 is the ancestral allele and demonstrated that a presumed two-step transition from Mtn.3 to Mtn1 to Dp(Mtn1) is accompanied by an approximate 5-fold increase in RNA levels. We analyzed the evolutionary genetics of the Mtn locus of D. ananassae, a distant relative of D. melanogaster and D. simulans within the melanogaster species group. The Mtn gene of D. ananassae is most similar to Mtn.3: (i) it is identical with Mtn.3 at the amino acid level, but differs from Mtn1 in its terminal codon; (ii) its 3' UTR contains a characteristic extra DNA segment of about 50 bp which is present in Mtn.3, but lacking in Mtn1; (iii) duplications of Mtn were not found in a worldwide sample of 110 wild D. ananassae chromosomes. However, the intron of the Mtn gene in D. ananassae is only 69 bp long, whereas the length of the Mtn.3 and Mtn1 introns is 265 bp; and it lacks a polypyrimidine stretch upstream of the 3' splice site in contrast to the much greater pyrimidine-richness found in the Mtn.3 and Mtn1 introns. A short intron (67 bp) was also identified in a D. pseudoobscura Mtn allele, suggesting that the short intron is the ancestral form and that the transition from the short to the long intron occurred within the melanogaster species group. We discuss the significance of this observation with regard to the recently proposed classification of D. melanogaster introns into two groups: short introns 
(< 90 bp) which tend to lack polypyrimidine stretches, and longer ones which have strong 3' splice signals similar to mammalian introns. A database search revealed that this length dimorphism is an evolutionarily conserved feature of Drosophila introns; transitions from one size class to the other appear to be rare between closely related species (e.g. within the melanogaster subgroup). 
<p>
<hr>
<br>
J. Parsch, S. Tanda, and W. Stephan. Use of site-directed mutagenesis to study the evolution of conserved, 
non-coding sequences at the <I>Adh</I> locus of <I>Drosophila melanogaster</I>.
 Poster presented July 1995 at the annual meeting of the Society for the Study of Evolution, McGill University, Montreal, Quebec, Canada.
<p>
Nucleotide sites in non-coding regions, such as the 3' untranslated region (UTR), are often considered neutral, because base substitutions in these sites have no effect on the amino acid sequence encoded by a gene.  Substitution patterns in the 3' UTR, however, suggest that there are some constraints on nucleotide substitutions in this region.  We used two different approaches in an attempt to identify functional significance in 3' UTR sequences.  First, we looked at a possible role of the 3' UTR in mRNA secondary structure.  We examined the long-range pairing potential of 138 <I>Drosophila</I> mRNA sequences.  This analysis revealed a strong tendency for pairing stems between the start of the protein coding region and the 3' UTR.  Second,   we tested the neutrality of several non-coding nucleotide sites in the alcohol dehydrogenase gene (<I>Adh</I>) of <I>Drosophila melanogaster</I>.  Site-directed mutations were made in a region of the 3' UTR that was conserved across five species of the subgenus <i>Sophophora</I>, but was not conserved in species from the subgenera <I>Drosophila</I> and <I>Scaptodrosophila</I>.  The mutant <I>Adh</I> gene was then re-introduced into the <I>D. melanogaster</I> genome using P-element mediated germ line transformation.  Transformants were spectrophotometrically assayed for their ADH enzymatic activity and compared to transformants containing the wild type <I>Adh</I> gene.  The mutant lines showed approximately 30% less ADH activity, which suggests that non-coding nucleotide sites may play an important role in gene expression and that selection may place constraints on nucleotide substitutions at these sites.
<p>
<hr>
<br>
J. Parsch, S. Tanda, and W. Stephan. The Role of the 3' Untranslated Region in Gene Expression. 
Poster presented October 1995 at 19th Annual Mid-Atlantic Chromosomal Elements Meeting, Virginia Beach, Virginia, USA.
<p>
Nucleotide sites in the 3' untranslated region (UTR) of a gene are often considered neutral, because base substitutions at these sites do not alter the amino acid sequence encoded by the gene.  Substitution patterns in the 3' UTR, however, suggest that there are some constraints on nucleotide changes in this region.  We used two different approaches in an attempt to identify functional significance in 3' UTR sequences.  First, we looked at a possible role of the 3' UTR in mRNA secondary structure.  We examined the long-range pairing potential of 137 Drosophila  mRNA sequences.  This analysis revealed a strong tendency for pairing stems between the start of the protein coding region and the 3' UTR.  Second, we used site-directed mutagenesis to test the neutrality of several nucleotide sites within the 3' UTR of the alcohol dehydrogenase gene (Adh ) of Drosophila  melanogaster.  Mutant Adh  genes were incorporated into the D. melanogaster genome using P-element mediated germ line transformation.  Transformants were spectrophotometrically assayed for their ADH enzymatic activity and compared to transformants containing the wild type Adh  gene.  The mutant lines showed a significant reduction in ADH activity relative to the wild type, which suggests that nucleotide sites in the 3' UTR may play an important role in gene expression.
<p>
<hr>
<br>
J. Parsch. The Effect of Site-Directed Mutations on Gene Expression. 
Talk to be given April 1996 at GRID (Graduate Reasearch Interaction Day), University of Maryland, College Park, Maryland, USA.
<p>
The goal of my research is to determine what effect, if any, single nucleotide substitutions have on gene expression.  I am particularly interested in mutations which do not alter the amino acid sequence encoded by a gene, because they are often considered to be 'neutral' mutations which have no effect on an organism.  For my experiments I have used the fruit fly, Drosophila melanogaster, because it is well suited for genetic study and manipulation.  The two major methods used in my research are site-directed mutagenesis and P-element mediated germ-line 
transformation.  These techniques allow me to make specific mutations in a DNA sequence in vitro, then re-introduce the altered gene back into living flies.  I have used this approach to make several mutations in the Drosophila alcohol dehydrogenase gene (Adh), which encodes an enzyme required for the detoxification of alcohol.  Mutant flies had a significant reduction in enzymatic activity relative to normal, wild-type flies.  This suggests that the altered nucleotide sites are not neutral and may be under selective constraints that limit substitutions at these sites during the course of molecular evolution. 
<p>
<br>

<A HREF="parsch.html"><img vspace=3 hspace=3 src="http://inform.umd.edu/Pictures/arrow.gif">
Return to John Parsch's page</A>
